window.METHODEN = [{"id":"agenda-design-mit-fragen","name":"Agenda Design with Questions","feld":"G","kurz":"Agenda items are formulated as questions to be answered instead of keywords. Each item comes with a purpose (inform / gather input / decide), a time slot, and a responsible person.","schritte":["Gather topics and check: does this concern everyone present?","Formulate each topic as a question (\"Under what conditions do we reschedule the appointment?\" instead of \"Scheduling question\").","Mark each question: information, input, or decision.","Assign a realistic time slot and a responsible person.","Send the agenda out in advance so everyone comes prepared.","In the meeting: question answered = item closed."],"zweck":"Meetings get a clear end-criterion per item and the right list of participants.","hinweise":"Most common mistake: an agenda as a topic list without a stated purpose – then the group discusses without a goal. If someone can't formulate the question, they haven't thought the topic through yet – that's already the diagnosis.","phasen":["planen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"How to Design an Agenda for an Effective Meeting – HBR","url":"https://hbr.org/2015/03/how-to-design-an-agenda-for-an-effective-meeting"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Roger Schwarz: Smart Leaders, Smarter Teams"}],"wann_passt":["A recurring team meeting that regularly runs too long or ends without a clear outcome – phrasing it as a question forces the person raising it to clarify in advance what they actually need (information, feedback, or a decision).","New team or new facilitation: the agenda as a visible planning document signals structure without control – everyone sees in advance what's coming.","Decision meeting with several items of varying weight – the purpose marker (inform / input / decide) helps to call up the right energy per item instead of discussing everything at the same intensity."],"wann_nicht":["Informal exchange rounds or community meetings without a fixed expectation of outcomes – the question structure feels bureaucratic there.","If the person raising the topic can't formulate the question – then the topic isn't ready for the agenda, and the format doesn't fix the missing preparation."],"fokusfragen":["\"What exactly do we want to know, have decided, or have done by the end of this item?\" (clarify purpose)","\"Who really needs to be there for this – and who could receive the results asynchronously?\" (the right invite list)","\"How much time do we realistically need – and what do we drop if it's too much?\""],"beispiel":"Instead of the agenda item \"Finances\" → \"Under what conditions do we approve the budget shift between line A and line B?\" – Purpose: decision. Outcome: clear yes/no plus reasoning. Time: 15 min. Responsible: treasurer. The question immediately makes visible that the bookkeeper needs to prepare figures beforehand – otherwise the group meets without a basis.","mini_form":"5-minute agenda audit before the meeting: reformulate existing agenda items as questions and mark each one: I (inform) / F (feedback) / D (decide). Cross out or postpone items with no answer.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","entscheidungstreffen","kickoff","krisensitzung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-15 people, suitable for any group size – effort scales with preparation time","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"check-in-check-out","name":"Check-in / Check-out (Short Meeting Form)","feld":"G","kurz":"A deliberate opening and closing of a meeting: each person briefly says how they're arriving or what they're leaving with. Makes every voice heard once before the substantive work begins.","schritte":["Ask a question (e.g. \"What's on your mind right now?\" / \"What do you need to be present?\").","Going around or popcorn-style, everyone answers in 1-2 sentences, uncommented.","Facilitation says thank you, no follow-up questions.","At the end, the same in reverse: check-out question (\"What are you taking with you?\", \"What's still open?\")."],"zweck":"Presence, visibility, and transition into shared work mode – especially for recurring meetings.","hinweise":"\"Why\" questions open things up more deeply, \"what\" questions stay closer to the surface – choose the question to fit the type of meeting. For large groups, use the one-word variant, otherwise the check-in eats the agenda.","phasen":["ankommen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":15,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Check-in / Check-out – SessionLab Library","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/check-in-check-out"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Jim & Michele McCarthy: The Core Protocols"}],"wann_passt":["A recurring team meeting where the group falls straight from email into substantive work with no transition – 2-3 minutes of check-in lower the mental scatter and increase actual presence.","A group reconvening after a longer break (after holidays, after a crisis week) – a short arrival makes the unspoken audible before it undermines the substantive work.","A workshop with new or mixed participants – having heard every voice once lowers the threshold for contributing later."],"wann_nicht":["Groups over 20 people with a spoken round – then the check-in eats the agenda; use a chat waterfall or one-word variant instead.","If the check-in has had the same question for months – then it's become a mandatory exercise and loses its meaning."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's on your mind right now outside this room that you might be bringing with you?\" (presence check)","\"What do you need to really be here today?\" (needs check for demanding content)","\"What are you taking from this meeting – and what's still open?\" (check-out)"],"beispiel":"Check-out at a planning retreat: \"In one sentence: what was your most important thought today – and what's still on your mind?\" Going around, uncommented. Often reveals that an unresolved question is on several people's minds – facilitation notes it visibly for the next day without discussing it further now.","mini_form":"One-word check-in: everyone names a word for their current mood simultaneously (or in a chat waterfall) – 90 seconds, gives an instant mood picture without unequal speaking time.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","teamtag","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-15 for a spoken round, up to 100 for the chat variant","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","muede","belastet","frisch"]},{"id":"lean-coffee","name":"Lean Coffee","feld":"G","kurz":"A structured meeting without a prepared agenda: participants propose topics, prioritize by vote, and work through them in timeboxes. A democratically generated agenda in real time.","schritte":["Set up a simple kanban board (to discuss / in discussion / discussed).","Everyone writes topic proposals on cards (2-3 min).","Present each card in one sentence, then dot-voting.","Discuss the top topic for 5-8 min.","Thumb vote: continue (thumbs up) or move to the next topic (thumbs down).","Repeat until time runs out; cards move across the board."],"zweck":"Exchange rounds, communities of practice, and team meetings where the group itself decides what matters.","hinweise":"Works very well online with a digital board. Pitfall: softening the timebox – then it slides into an unstructured discussion. Less suited when a concrete decision needs to be made.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Lean Coffee","url":"https://leancoffee.org/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Lean Coffee Facilitator's Guide – Medium (Agile Outside the Box)","url":"https://medium.com/agile-outside-the-box/lean-coffee-facilitator-s-guide-d79d9f13d0a9"}],"wann_passt":["A community of practice or network meeting without a fixed agenda, where no single person should set the agenda – the group prioritizes itself what counts today.","A regular team meeting where the same topics keep coming up but there's never time for what individuals actually care about – Lean Coffee dissolves the pre-set agenda and makes room for what's pressing right now.","A retrospective or informal knowledge exchange in a group that needs structure but doesn't want a conference feel."],"wann_nicht":["When a concrete decision needs to be made – the timebox format doesn't produce a decision process, only conversation time.","Under 5 or over 15 people without facilitation experience: for small groups the structure is overhead, for large groups the timebox discipline collapses.","If participants aren't willing to name topics openly (hierarchy pressure, lack of trust) – then only safe, inconsequential cards emerge."],"fokusfragen":["\"What topic is most on your mind right now – what do you really want to discuss today?\" (card prompt)","\"We have 5 minutes – what's the one thing we should clarify about this topic?\""],"beispiel":"Community of practice (10 people, monthly): everyone writes 2 cards. After dot-voting, the top 3 topics land on the board. First topic: \"What do we do if a sponsor pulls out?\" – 7 minutes of discussion, thumb check: 8 up, 2 down → continue. Result: agreement to sketch an emergency plan before the next meeting. Card moves to \"discussed\" with an action item.","mini_form":"\"Mini Lean\": just write cards + dot-vote (5 min), then discuss a single top topic for 10 min – enough as a kickoff for a regular team meeting to surface the group's most pressing concern.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","regeltermin","retro","krisensitzung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-12 ideal, possible from 4, over 15 only with subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"elmo","name":"ELMO (Enough, Let's Move On)","feld":"G","kurz":"An agreed-upon signal that anyone in the meeting can use to show that a discussion has passed its productive point – by calling out, hand signal, or card.","schritte":["At the start (once), agree: anyone may call ELMO or raise the card, regardless of role or hierarchy.","When a discussion is circling: give the signal.","Facilitation briefly asks: close the point, postpone it, or move it to the parking lot?","Continue with the agenda; review parked items at the end."],"zweck":"Ending sprawling detail and repetition discussions without devaluing the person speaking.","hinweise":"Needs a one-time shared agreement, otherwise it feels abrupt. Best combined with a parking lot, so \"ended\" doesn't mean \"lost\". Online as a chat signal or reaction emoji.","phasen":["vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["klaerung","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop"],"dauer_min":1,"dauer_max":2,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["spielerisch","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"What does the E.L.M.O acronym mean? – Facilitator School","url":"https://www.facilitator.school/glossary/elmo"}],"wann_passt":["An established work team with good trust that has noticed meetings regularly run too long – ELMO as a jointly agreed signal prevents one single person from always having to play the stop-sign role.","A workshop day with many agenda items, where the early ones would otherwise eat up the later ones – ELMO protects the time budget without drawing on the facilitator's authority."],"wann_nicht":["A new or not-yet-settled group – the signal can be experienced as being cut off if there's no shared understanding.","If there's no parking lot: then ELMO means to participants \"my contribution is being ignored\" – that produces withdrawal instead of focus."],"fokusfragen":["\"Are we far enough on this point to act or decide – or are we going in circles?\" (self-check before ELMO)","\"What would we need to close this point right now?\" (after the ELMO signal)"],"beispiel":"At the start, the team agrees: \"Anyone can signal ELMO – 'E' in chat, hand signal, or say it out loud. Then we decide together: close it, park it, or extend 3 minutes.\" In the session, a discussion circles for the third time. Person A types 'E' in the chat. Facilitation: \"ELMO – do we agree to park this?\" 5 of 6 nod. Parking lot card: \"Technical question – who clarifies this by Friday?\" → Person B.","mini_form":"As a 2-minute opening agreement: a card with 'ELMO' on the table or in the chat – done. Needs no explanation once the purpose is briefly stated.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","entscheidungstreffen"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-20, scalable as long as the agreement is clear","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"parkplatz","name":"Parking Lot","feld":"G","kurz":"A visible topic reservoir (flipchart, board area) for points that matter but don't belong to the current agenda. Honors the contribution and protects focus.","schritte":["Explain it at the start and set up a visible area.","An off-topic point comes up → write it on a card and park it (facilitation or participants themselves).","Plan 5 minutes before the end: go through the parking lot.","Decide per point: clarify briefly now, put on the next agenda, delegate to a person, or drop.","Put remaining points with responsible people into the minutes."],"zweck":"Keeping meetings on track without shutting down contributions.","hinweise":"Most common mistake: never revisiting the parking lot – then the group learns that parking means burying, and trust collapses. Schedule the closing review firmly.","phasen":["vertiefen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["uebergang","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Parking Lot – SessionLab Library","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/parking-lot"}],"wann_passt":["A workshop or retreat with a broad range of topics, where cross-connections and associations naturally arise – the parking lot signals appreciation of the contribution without losing focus.","A meeting culture where off-topic comments regularly lead to long tangents – the parking lot gives facilitation a legitimate, non-shutting-down steering tool.","A multi-day retreat: the parking lot at the end of day 1 can be used as an entry point into day 2."],"wann_nicht":["If no time is planned at the end to review the parking lot – then the group learns that parking equals burying, and trust breaks down.","Online without a visible board – invisible parking lots don't exist."],"fokusfragen":["\"Important topic – does that belong to today's focus, or do we park it for later?\" (parking decision)","\"What of this do we want to clarify now, what to delegate, what to drop?\" (review at the end)"],"mini_form":"A post-it or digital sticky visible at the edge of the board: enough as a parking lot. Announcement: \"Important points outside the agenda go there – we'll look at them in the last 5 minutes.\"","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","strategie","entscheidungstreffen"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"any size – a facilitation tool, independent of group size","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"wer-macht-was-bis-wann","name":"Who-Does-What-By-When (3W Decision Anchoring)","feld":"G","kurz":"Every agreement is captured before the meeting ends as a one-sentence action item: one responsible person (Who), one task with a verb (What), one concrete date (By When).","schritte":["During the meeting, note every commitment visibly right away.","Name exactly one person as responsible per item – \"we\" doesn't count.","Phrase the task with a verb (\"send the draft\", not \"draft\").","A concrete date instead of \"soon\".","Before closing, read the list out loud; everyone confirms their own points.","Record the list in the minutes/tool and bring it up first at the next meeting."],"zweck":"Decisions and commitments survive the meeting – accountability instead of a collective memory gap.","hinweise":"Reading it out loud at the end is the most effective step and the one most often skipped. Pitfall: too many action items per meeting – better to have few that actually happen.","phasen":["entscheiden","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"What is an Action Item? – Lucid Meetings Glossary","url":"https://www.lucidmeetings.com/glossary/action-item"}],"wann_passt":["Any meeting that produces decisions or commitments – 3W is the minimum standard to turn conversation into action.","Teams with a long history of decisions that don't get implemented – reading it out loud at the end creates a collective accountability that silent minutes don't achieve.","The retreat's final block: gather all action items, read them out loud, everyone confirms their own – this is the most effective close of a multi-day process."],"wann_nicht":["When too many action items arise – better to select: a maximum of 5 truly binding points instead of 20 wishes.","As a substitute for a missing decision culture – 3W documents decisions but can't fix the absence of clear mandates."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who takes this on – exactly one person, not 'we'?\" (accountability test)","\"What's the concrete action – with a verb?\" (phrasing check)","\"By when? Not 'soon' – which date?\""],"beispiel":"Meeting close: facilitation reads out: \"Maike sends the draft to everyone by Thursday noon. Tom asks the supplier about the deadline by Friday.\" Maike and Tom each confirm: \"Yes, I'll do it.\" The minutes contain only these two lines – no discussion record. At the next meeting, these two points are the first agenda item.","mini_form":"2-minute closing round: \"Before we go – everyone says in one sentence what they'll do next.\" No board needed, still creates accountability through public naming.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","entscheidungstreffen","strategie","krisensitzung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"any size – the smaller the group, the faster","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","muede","neugierig"]},{"id":"delegation-poker","name":"Delegation Poker","feld":"G","kurz":"A card game (Management 3.0) that helps team and leadership clarify, for each decision area, which of the seven delegation levels (Tell, Sell, Consult, Agree, Advise, Inquire, Delegate) a decision sits at.","schritte":["Gather concrete decision cases (\"Who decides on vacation planning / tool selection / budget X?\").","Read out a case.","Everyone picks a card 1-7 face down and reveals it at the same time.","The highest and lowest votes explain their choice.","Play again if needed, until a shared picture emerges.","Record the result on a delegation board (areas x levels)."],"zweck":"Making implicit expectations about decision authority explicit and building self-organization step by step.","hinweise":"It's about the conversation, not the score – discussing the outliers is the real value. Delegation isn't a switch but a ladder; update the board regularly.","phasen":["planen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","vertrauen"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","teamentwicklung","klausur"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":7,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["spielerisch","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Delegation Poker & Delegation Board – Management 3.0","url":"https://management30.com/practice/delegation-poker/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Jurgen Appelo: Management 3.0"}],"wann_passt":["A team in its founding phase or after restructuring: implicit expectations about decision authority (who decides on tool selection? On vacation? On a budget up to 500 EUR?) become explicit – this prevents later frustration over overstepping authority or a lack of decisions.","A growing team where leadership wants to delegate but it's unclear how far – the game reveals where leadership and team assess things differently and creates a shared picture instead of a one-sided announcement.","A retrospective after decision conflicts: instead of assigning blame, team and leadership play through the same cases and find the gap in their shared understanding."],"wann_nicht":["If leadership isn't ready to actually delegate – then the game creates expectations that are later disappointed.","Over 8 people without a subgroup structure – too many individual justifications for outliers wear the group down."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which level would make the work easiest for you here – and which would give you the most security?\" (take both perspectives)","\"What would the team need to delegate one level higher than before?\""],"beispiel":"Case: \"Who decides which software we use for project management?\" Team cards: 5, 6, 4. Leadership card: 3. Discussion: the person with 6 (full delegation) explains the team uses the tools daily, leadership never does. The person with 4 (Agree) adds they want a say in the choice. Leadership explains they want to be informed before a decision is made (=4, Consult/Agree). Result: level 4 recorded – the team develops a proposal and informs leadership a week before deciding.","mini_form":"Just 3 cases instead of a full delegation board: 20 min is enough to surface the most common misunderstandings – good as a team meeting element without workshop effort.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","entscheidungstreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-8 ideal (direct leadership relationship + team), up to 12 in subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"silent-start-6-pager","name":"Silent Start / 6-Pager (Memo Reading)","feld":"G","kurz":"The meeting begins with silent reading: instead of a presentation, the person raising the topic writes a narrative memo in advance (max. six pages); everyone reads silently for the first 10-30 minutes and takes notes.","schritte":["The responsible person writes the memo as running prose with full sentences and argumentation – no bullet-point slides.","The meeting starts with silent reading time, everyone comments in writing in the margin/document.","Facilitation goes through the memo section by section and calls up comments.","Discuss open questions, make the decision.","Anchor decisions as action items."],"zweck":"Decisions based on well-thought-out arguments instead of presentation charisma; everyone starts with the same information level.","hinweise":"Quality stands and falls with the memo – writing forces thinking but costs preparation time. Short form: a 1-2-page memo with 10 min of reading time. Strong online, because everyone comments in parallel in the same document.","phasen":["verstehen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["meeting","klausur"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["schriftlich","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"6 Page Memo – Async-First Method Stack","url":"https://www.asyncagile.org/method-stack/6-page-memo"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Colin Bryar & Bill Carr: Working Backwards"}],"wann_passt":["A decision meeting with a complex proposal where presentation charisma would otherwise dominate the discussion – the memo forces the author to sustain the argument in writing and gives everyone the same information level.","A remote team across time zones or with asynchronous preferences: the memo can be read in advance, synchronous time focuses on clarification and decision.","A group that regularly spends 20 minutes in meetings asking for context that could have been clear beforehand – the format disciplines the person raising the topic and relieves the group."],"wann_nicht":["Spontaneous or emergent questions that allow no preparation time.","If writing the memo costs more than the conversation is worth – it's overhead for small operational questions."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's still unclear after reading – and what's already decided?\" (end of reading phase)","\"Which assumption in the memo do you consider riskiest?\" (discussion opener)"],"beispiel":"Short form in a team meeting: a 1-page memo on a partnership inquiry. 10 minutes of silent reading, everyone comments in the document. Then: \"What surprises you?\" – 3 comments. \"What's missing to decide?\" – 2 additions. \"Are we ready to decide?\" – fist-to-five. Total duration: 35 minutes instead of a 60-minute presentation.","mini_form":"Just 1 page + 10 min reading: the full 6-pager logic also applies to short memos – even a well-written one-page text read for 10 minutes produces qualitatively better discussions.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-15, especially strong at 4-8","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"timeboxing","name":"Timeboxing","feld":"G","kurz":"Every agenda item gets a fixed time window that runs visibly and is held consistently. The time limit creates focus and protects later items.","schritte":["When designing the agenda, assign a realistic time to each item.","Make timeboxes transparent at the start and agree whether they're hard or soft.","Keep the timer visibly running (time timer, screen timer).","Give an early warning (e.g. \"2 minutes left\").","When time is up: close the item, deliberately extend it (at the expense of which item?), or move it to the parking lot."],"zweck":"Meetings end on time and important later agenda items aren't eaten up by early discussions.","hinweise":"Hard timeboxes for status formats, soft ones for creative work. Pitfall: setting a timer but never enforcing it – then the tool loses its effect. Extensions should always be an explicit group decision.","phasen":["planen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["klaerung","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop"],"dauer_min":0,"dauer_max":5,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Timeboxing: How to Work Faster and Stay Focused – Asana","url":"https://asana.com/resources/what-is-timeboxing"}],"wann_passt":["Meetings with several agenda items of varying importance – without timeboxes, early items eat up later ones, which are often strategically more important.","Workshop design: timeboxes as the skeleton of every session plan – without them there's no valid run sheet.","Creative phases prone to endless optimizing – a hard timebox creates productive pressure and prevents perfectionism."],"wann_nicht":["Deep clarifying conversations in conflicts or difficult interpersonal situations – strict timeboxes signal there: your topic isn't important enough.","If time is never enforced – a timer set but never followed through trains the group to ignore timeboxes."],"fokusfragen":["\"How much time do we really need for this item – and what do we drop if we plan too little time?\""],"beispiel":"Explicit extension decision: the timer runs out, the discussion isn't finished. Facilitation: \"Time's up – we could extend 5 minutes, which comes at the expense of the next item, or we decide now with what we have. What do we want?\" The group decides deliberately – this prevents silently running over.","mini_form":"Just the visible clock on the table or screen – no facilitation, no explanation. Already creates focus.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","entscheidungstreffen","strategie","krisensitzung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"any size – a room-design tool","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","muede","neugierig"]},{"id":"roti","name":"ROTI (Return on Time Invested)","feld":"G","kurz":"Instant feedback at the end of a meeting: everyone rates on a 1-5 scale whether the time invested was worth it. Makes meeting quality measurable and improvable.","schritte":["2-3 minutes before the end, explain the scale (1 = wasted time, 3 = balanced, 5 = very worthwhile).","Everyone votes simultaneously – raise fingers, stick a dot, or use an anonymous online tool.","Briefly look at the picture: where does the group stand?","Ask 1-2 low scores: \"What would have increased the value?\"","Record one concrete improvement for the next meeting."],"zweck":"Continuously improving recurring meetings instead of just enduring them.","hinweise":"Anonymous submission increases honesty, especially with hierarchy gaps. Only works if something visibly follows from the feedback – otherwise it's a ritual without consequence.","phasen":["reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["reflexion"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":5,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"What is ROTI? – Lucid Meetings Glossary","url":"https://www.lucidmeetings.com/glossary/roti"}],"wann_passt":["A recurring meeting that has crept in without ever being questioned about its usefulness – ROTI forces visible feedback and makes improvement the norm.","A team that never talks about meeting quality because 'it's always the same' – the scale gives dissatisfaction a number and facilitation a conversation opener.","A workshop at the end of each half-day as a learning loop for the facilitation team."],"wann_nicht":["If the feedback is never visibly acted on – then ROTI only signals that dissatisfaction is recorded and ignored.","A one-off workshop with no follow-up meeting – then the feedback is worthless for improvement."],"fokusfragen":["\"What would have increased the value of this meeting for you?\" (to 1-2 low scores)","\"What was the most valuable moment?\" (optional for 4-5 scores)"],"beispiel":"ROTI result: 2 x 5, 4 x 3, 1 x 2. Facilitation asks the person with 2: \"What could have been better today?\" Answer: \"We discussed the same point as last month – with no outcome.\" Concrete improvement: the next meeting starts with: What was the outcome from last time on this? → a one-minute reminder.","mini_form":"5-finger ROTI: everyone raises a hand with 1-5 fingers simultaneously. 30 seconds. No conversation needed if everyone shows >= 3.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-30, scalable to any size","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"konsent","name":"Consent (Sociocracy, Short Form)","feld":"G","kurz":"A sociocratic decision-making process: a proposal is considered accepted if no one has a serious, well-reasoned objection – the question asked is \"Does anything speak seriously against this?\" instead of \"Are you in favor?\"","schritte":["Present the proposal, clarify understanding questions (information round).","Opinion round: everyone speaks briefly in turn, proposal may be adjusted.","Consent round: each person says \"consent\" or names their objection.","Integrate objections: adjust the proposal so the objection is resolved.","Repeat the consent round until no serious objection remains.","Record the decision with a review date."],"zweck":"Workable team decisions without endless consensus-seeking and without majority overruling.","hinweise":"Consent isn't consensus: \"good enough for now, safe enough to try\" is sufficient. Objections are gifts but need reasoning tied to the shared goal. Facilitate rounds strictly one at a time, otherwise loud voices dominate.","phasen":["entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["entscheidung","klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"KonsenT-Moderation – Soziokratie.org","url":"https://www.soziokratie.org/konsentmoderation/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Consent Decision Making – Sociocracy For All","url":"https://www.sociocracyforall.org/consent-decision-making/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Christian Rüther: KonsenT-Moderation"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Konsens und Konsent – s3lf.org","url":"https://s3lf.org/erklaerungen/konsens-und-konsent/"}],"wann_passt":["A team with a sociocratic or self-organized way of working that wants to pass a concrete proposal – consent is faster than seeking consensus and more legitimate than a majority vote once the group knows the process.","A decision of medium significance (guideline, role allocation, project decision) where genuine objections are expected – the opinion round gives all objections space before a vote.","A group familiar with endless discussions looking for a structured way out – the question 'Does anything speak seriously against this?' is more precise and faster than 'Is everyone in favor?'."],"wann_nicht":["A group without prior experience of sociocratic processes in a high-pressure situation – the distinction between objection and opinion must be learned beforehand, otherwise frustration and endless integration rounds arise.","Very large groups (>20) without facilitation experience – the objection-integration loop isn't manageable in a large group without practice.","If the decision actually rests with a single person (leadership mandate) – consent in a hierarchical setting without a real mandate for the group is pseudo-participation."],"fokusfragen":["\"Does anyone have a serious objection – something that would harm our shared goal?\" (consent round)","\"What would the proposal need for your objection to be resolved?\" (after an objection)","\"Is this proposal good enough for now, safe enough to try?\" (decision phrasing)"],"beispiel":"A team of 6 decides on a new meeting structure. Proposal: \"From now on we meet Mondays 9-10am instead of Fridays 4pm.\" Information round: everyone understands the implications. Opinion round: Person A: \"I'd prefer Tuesday, but okay.\" Person B: \"Monday mornings are my childcare handovers – that doesn't work for me.\" That's an objection. Integration: proposal adjusted to Tuesdays 9am. Second consent round: no objection. Decided. Review date: in 3 months.","mini_form":"Fast consent for small decisions: name the proposal, one round of \"objection or not?\" – whoever says no briefly says why. Possible in under 5 minutes for uncritical operational questions.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","regeltermin","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-12 ideal, up to 20 with experience","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"systemisches-konsensieren","name":"Systemic Consensing (Resistance Polling)","feld":"G","kurz":"A decision process that measures resistance instead of approval: everyone rates each option with 0-10 resistance points; the option with the lowest total resistance is chosen – the least conflictual solution.","schritte":["Clarify the question and any unchangeable framework conditions.","Gather solution options (including the passive solution \"everything stays as it is\").","Resistance poll: each person gives 0 (no resistance) to 10 points (strong rejection) per option.","Sum the points per option.","Choose the option with the lowest total resistance; for high individual resistance scores, ask why and further develop the options."],"zweck":"Group decisions with many options where acceptance matters more than a majority – prevents narrow voting wins with a large, angry minority.","hinweise":"The passive solution should always be included as a benchmark for comparison. Fast variant: resistance via hand signal, 0-5 fingers. Pitfall: resistance points used as a tactical tool – counter this by asking about reasons.","phasen":["entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["entscheidung","konflikt"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":50,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Die Methode Systemisches Konsensieren – SK-Prinzip","url":"https://sk-prinzip.eu/methode/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Erich Visotschnig & Siegfried Schrotta: Systemisches Konsensieren"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Systemisches Konsensieren – Karl Hosang Anleitung","url":"https://karlhosang.de/systemisches-konsensieren/"}],"wann_passt":["A group with several competing options (3 or more proposals) and recognizable camps – the resistance poll prevents a narrow majority from overruling a large, angry minority.","Decisions in networks and loose cooperations where no majority logic applies but a result is needed – systemic consensing without hierarchy and without a consensus requirement.","A conflict-laden situation where a classic vote would produce winners and losers – focusing on resistance rather than approval lowers emotional escalation."],"wann_nicht":["If one option is strategically preset and facilitation already knows the outcome – then it's theater.","If participants vote tactically (high points on competing options to favor their own) with no basis for a duty to justify – anonymity helps, but asking about high individual resistance scores is mandatory.","For decisions that are legally or technically clear-cut – systemic consensing is a consensus-approximation process, not a substitute for expertise."],"fokusfragen":["\"On a scale of 0 (no resistance) to 10 (strong rejection): how high is your resistance to option X?\" (poll phrasing)","\"Who gave 8 or more points – what's behind that?\" (follow-up on high individual resistance)","\"Should the passive solution (everything stays as it is) also be on the board as a comparison point?\" (completeness)"],"beispiel":"4 options for the event venue. Resistance poll (0-10, per person, per option). Result: Option A: sum 12, Option B: sum 28, Option C: sum 7, Option D: sum 19. Option C wins. But: Person X gave 9 points to C. Follow-up: \"X, what bothers you so much about C?\" Answer: accessibility is missing. Option C adjusted: check accessibility, new vote. Adjusted Option C: sum 4. Decided – with a condition.","mini_form":"Hand-signal variant: resistance 0-5 fingers instead of 0-10 points. Once per option around the group: everyone shows at the same time. Visible result within 2 minutes per option.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","konfliktklaerung","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-30 ideal, up to 50 with digital voting","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","angespannt","frisch"]},{"id":"dot-voting","name":"Dot Voting (with Variants)","feld":"G","kurz":"Fast prioritization: each person gets a fixed number of sticky dots (or digital votes) and distributes them across the options on display; the density of dots shows the group's preference.","schritte":["Display the options visibly on a wall/board and briefly go through them.","Set the number of dots (rule of thumb: about a quarter of the number of options per person).","Vote silently and as simultaneously as possible – no discussion.","Count and mark the top options.","Discuss the result: prioritization, not automatically a decision."],"zweck":"Quickly filtering the most important items out of many ideas or topics (e.g. after a brainstorm, for a Lean Coffee agenda).","hinweise":"Variants: cumulative voting, color dots (green = important, red = risky), numbered dots for ranking, juniors-first to counter anchoring effects. Pitfall: mistaking dot voting for a decision process – it prioritizes, it doesn't legitimize.","phasen":["entscheiden","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["team","netzwerk"],"modi":["entscheidung","klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":15,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":50,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Dot Voting: A Simple Decision-Making and Prioritizing Technique – Nielsen Norman Group","url":"https://www.nngroup.com/articles/dot-voting/"}],"wann_passt":["After a brainstorm or idea collection with 8-25 options: dot voting quickly filters out the 3-5 most important ones for the group, without discussion or lost time.","A Lean Coffee agenda at the start: cards get dotted, and the order is set within 5 minutes.","Workshop design with a decision moment between topic clusters – dots give an instant visual picture of the group's energy."],"wann_nicht":["As a decision process for important resolutions – dot voting prioritizes but doesn't legitimize. A narrow point majority doesn't give any option a workable basis.","If the group is under hierarchy pressure – everyone waits for the leader before placing dots. Remedy: everyone votes first, then leadership.","With fewer than 4 options – a direct conversation is faster and more honest."],"fokusfragen":["\"You each have X dots – place them where you see the most energy or the greatest need.\" (voting announcement)","\"What surprises you about the result? Where did you expect more or fewer dots?\" (after voting)"],"beispiel":"A retrospective, 12 ideas for improvements on post-its. Everyone gets 3 dots. Everyone votes at the same time (leadership last). Result: 2 ideas each have 6+ dots, the rest 0-2 each. Facilitation: \"The group agrees on the top 2. Do we take both – or choose one?\" This sparks a conversation about prioritization, not a majority vote. Important: explicitly state that dots aren't decisions.","mini_form":"Digital emoji reaction vote in Zoom or Teams: everyone places reactions on the options in chat or presentation. Result visible immediately, no tool switch needed.","anlass_typen":["retro","strategie","beteiligung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-50, digital up to any size – warning: visually confusing above 20 people","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"fist-to-five","name":"Fist to Five","feld":"G","kurz":"A fast consensus check via hand signal: fist (veto/no) to five fingers (full enthusiasm) show everyone's level of agreement with a proposal at the same time.","schritte":["Formulate the proposal clearly and explain the scale (fist = no/block, 1-2 = concerns, 3 = can support it, 4-5 = agreement/enthusiasm).","On cue, everyone shows their hand at the same time – raised and visible.","Read the room: all >= 3 → accepted.","Ask people with 0-2: \"What would you need to get to a 3?\"","Adjust the proposal and poll again."],"zweck":"Making visible within minutes how workable a decision really is – instead of silent pretend agreement.","hinweise":"Showing simultaneously is crucial, otherwise everyone anchors on the first person shown. Online via reaction emojis, numbers in chat, or hand signals on camera. Clarify beforehand whether a fist is a genuine veto.","phasen":["entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["entscheidung","klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["koerperlich","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Fist to five – SessionLab Library","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/fist-to-five"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Fist to Five – Civic Canopy Tool Sheet","url":"https://www.civiccanopy.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/04/Dialogue_FisttoFive_En_2022_v1.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["A concrete proposal is on the table that should be accepted or further developed – fist to five shows within seconds how far the group is, without long discussion rounds.","At the end of a consent or discussion round: test whether the proposal is now workable or still needs to be integrated (0-2 = discuss again, 3-5 = accepted).","An energy check in long workshops: a quick mood poll on a proposal before time is invested."],"wann_nicht":["When choosing among many options – dot voting is better there (prioritization); fist to five is only for single proposals.","Online without a clear simultaneous show – if one person shows first, everyone else follows suit (anchoring effect). Solution: everyone shows on a count of 3.","As a decision process for questions with a strong minority and real consequences – consent (with objection integration) is better there."],"fokusfragen":["\"Fist means no and block, 1-2 means serious concerns, 3 means 'I can live with it', 4-5 means agreement – everyone shows on 3-2-1.\" (announcement)","\"Who's showing 1 or 2 – what would you need to get to 3?\" (after showing)"],"beispiel":"A team of 8 discusses whether annual planning switches to a quarterly rhythm. A proposal is on the table. Facilitation: \"I'll count 3-2-1 – everyone shows at the same time.\" Result: 3 x 5, 3 x 4, 1 x 3, 1 x 1. Facilitation to the person with 1: \"What worries you?\" Answer: \"I'm still missing a clear handover protocol between quarters.\" Facilitation: \"Can we accept the proposal and add the protocol by the end of November?\" New vote: 7 x 4-5, 1 x 3 → accepted.","mini_form":"As a quick mood test with no consequence: \"How do you feel about this proposal – show your fingers briefly.\" No decision character, just a sense of the room's mood.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","regeltermin","krisensitzung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-25, online with chat number or reaction","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"gradients-of-agreement","name":"Gradients of Agreement","feld":"G","kurz":"An eight-level agreement scale by Sam Kaner (from \"fully in favor\" to \"block\") that lets group members express their stance on a proposal in a differentiated way instead of just yes/no.","schritte":["Display the scale visibly (8 levels from enthusiastic agreement through \"abstain\" and \"serious concerns\" to veto).","Formulate the proposal.","Everyone positions themselves at the same time (card, dot, physical lineup).","Look at the distribution together: where's the center of gravity, where are the outliers?","Listen to the lower levels, refine the proposal.","Apply the decision rule (e.g. no one below level 5)."],"zweck":"Making the real landscape of support behind a \"yes\" visible – especially in the tough phase before closing (the \"groan zone\").","hinweise":"A mood-picture tool, not a voting process – the decision rule must be agreed separately. The scale may be simplified to 4-6 levels.","phasen":["entscheiden","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["entscheidung","klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":25,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Gradients of Agreement – SessionLab Library","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/gradients-of-agreement"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Sam Kaner: Facilitator's Guide to Participatory Decision-Making"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Gradients of Agreement – MSU Facilitation Tool","url":"https://www.canr.msu.edu/news/gradients_of_agreement_can_help_move_groups_forward"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Gradients of Agreement Scale – Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradients_of_agreement_scale"}],"wann_passt":["An important decision with a recognizable agreement landscape where 'yes/no' is too coarse: the scale makes visible whether the group is enthusiastic or only resignedly agreeing – both count as yes but have completely different implications for implementation.","Consensus-building in the 'groan zone' (Sam Kaner): the group is exhausted, the conversation is circling, no one is blocking but no one is really on board – gradients makes the picture explicit and gives facilitation a point of intervention.","When a narrow majority decision is looming and the minority is strong enough to sabotage implementation – the scale shows how deep the skepticism runs before a vote."],"wann_nicht":["As a standalone decision process without a previously agreed decision rule – the scale is a diagnostic tool, not a voting process.","For small operational decisions without strategic weight – the effort exceeds the benefit.","Online without a whiteboard or voting tool – without a visible picture, the scale loses its value."],"fokusfragen":["\"Position yourselves on the scale – from 'I block' to 'I'm fully on board': where do you stand on this proposal right now?\" (announcement)","\"Who's on the lower three levels – what would it take to move a step higher?\" (after the picture)","\"How much agreement do we need to decide now?\" (clarify the decision rule)"],"beispiel":"8 people, a decision on a new governance document. Scale from 1 (block) to 8 (full enthusiasm) on a whiteboard. Distribution: 1 x 3, 2 x 5, 4 x 6, 1 x 7. Facilitation: \"We have one person at 3 – what would you need?\" Answer: \"The liability clause is unclear.\" Clarification follows, a new document with an addition. New gradient: spread now 5-7. Decision rule (no one below 5) met – accepted.","mini_form":"4-level variant: A = fully in favor / B = can live with it / C = concerns / D = block. Via card or chat. Faster than 8 levels, almost as informative.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","strategie","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-25, with whiteboard or tool","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"advice-process","name":"Advice Process","feld":"G","kurz":"A decentralized decision principle (Frédéric Laloux): anyone may make any decision but must first seek advice – from those affected and from those with expertise. The advice flows in, but the decision is made by the individual.","schritte":["A person recognizes a problem/opportunity and takes the initiative.","They sketch a decision draft.","They actively seek advice: from those affected and from those with expertise (the bigger the decision, the wider the circle).","They seriously weigh the advice – with no obligation to follow it.","They decide and inform everyone who gave advice, including the reasoning."],"zweck":"Fast, self-responsible decisions in teams and organizations, without a consensus bottleneck and without top-down orders.","hinweise":"Common misunderstanding: it's neither consensus (no one has to agree) nor a solo act (seeking advice is mandatory). Needs a culture of trust and a clear agreement, otherwise it's experienced as ruling through with an alibi consultation.","phasen":["entscheiden","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["entscheidung","vertrauen"],"formate":["meeting","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Decision Making – Reinventing Organizations Wiki","url":"https://reinventingorganizationswiki.com/en/theory/decision-making/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Frédéric Laloux: Reinventing Organizations"}],"wann_passt":["A self-organized or teal-oriented organization dismantling formal hierarchical decisions – the advice process isn't a workshop element but an operating system for everyday decisions.","When a person in an organization should make decisions independently but it's unclear whom they need to ask first – the process gives structure without a requirement for agreement.","As an introductory element in a retreat on self-organization: the principle is explained and played through on a concrete case to establish shared understanding."],"wann_nicht":["Without prior cultural preparation – the advice process only works if the duty to seek advice is actually lived. Without this basis it's experienced as alibi participation.","For decisions with legal or safety-relevant consequences – a clear mandate structure (not an advice process) is required there.","As an immediate solution in a crisis – under acute time pressure, consulting those affected and those with expertise doesn't work."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who does this decision affect – who do you need to ask before you decide?\" (mapping the advisers)","\"How will you factor in the advice – and who will you inform after the decision, including the reasoning?\""],"beispiel":"Person A wants to introduce a new tool for team communication (budget: EUR 600/year). Advice process: A asks the IT team (expertise), three team members who use it daily (affected), and the treasurer (budget relevance). Advice: IT warns of a data protection issue with option 1. Team members prefer option 2. A decides on option 2, informs everyone with reasoning. No consensus needed, but a transparent process.","mini_form":"As a reflection question in a meeting: \"Who in this room is affected by this decision and hasn't been asked yet?\" – opens up the advice-process idea without the full procedure.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"one individual + a circle of 2-10 advisers, not a classic group format","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"online-energizer-scavenger-hunt","name":"Online Energizer: Scavenger Hunt","feld":"G","kurz":"A movement energizer for video calls: everyone quickly fetches an object matching a prompt (\"something blue\", \"something important to you\") and shows it on camera.","schritte":["Announcement: \"You have 60 seconds – go get something that ...\"","Everyone stands up and searches, camera stays on.","Back: everyone holds the object up to the camera at the same time.","2-3 people say in one sentence what they brought.","Optional second round with a more personal category."],"zweck":"Activating the body and lifting energy after long sitting phases; with a personal category it also builds connection.","hinweise":"The category determines the depth: \"something red\" = pure energy, \"something that describes your week\" = mini check-in. Watch for accessibility (not everyone can get up quickly) – offer an alternative task.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["energie","verbindung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":7,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["energizer"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"29 online energizers for more engaging meetings – SessionLab Blog","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/blog/online-energizers/"}],"wann_passt":["The opening of an online workshop where participants are at home or in the office and physically reachable – movement before a long sitting phase.","The middle of a long webinar as an activation break after 60+ minutes of quiet listening.","A get-to-know-you situation: with a personal category ('something that describes your week') the scavenger hunt becomes a mini check-in with a visual anchor."],"wann_nicht":["If participants are in open-plan offices or public spaces and can't stand up.","A group without cameras – the format lives from the simultaneous presentation of the object."],"fokusfragen":["\"You have 60 seconds – go get something that's [category]. Go on 3-2-1.\" (announcement)"],"mini_form":"One-round variant without a second round: 60 sec to fetch, 30 sec to show, 3 people tell in one sentence. 3 minutes total.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-25, online, cameras on","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch"]},{"id":"online-energizer-stretch-shake","name":"Online Energizer: Stretch & Shake","feld":"G","kurz":"A guided 2-3-minute movement break in a video call: standing up together, stretching, rolling shoulders, shaking out – facilitation demonstrates, everyone joins in.","schritte":["Announce: \"Everyone stand up, we're moving for 2 minutes.\"","Demonstrate a simple sequence: stretch upward, lean to the side, roll shoulders.","Shake out arms and legs, feel free to turn the sound on and groan/laugh together.","Breathe deeply in and out.","Sit back down and move straight into the next item."],"zweck":"Bringing back concentration when screen-staring and the afternoon slump set in – with no content overhead.","hinweise":"Works best done regularly (e.g. every 60-90 min) rather than once as a gimmick. Don't force anyone to keep their camera on – joining in without being on stage is fine.","phasen":["ankommen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":5,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["energizer"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"29 online energizers for more engaging meetings – SessionLab Blog","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/blog/online-energizers/"}],"wann_passt":["After 50-60 minutes of continuous screen work – a body break with no shift in content.","The afternoon slump (2-3pm): concentration drops, an energy interval before the next topic.","As a regular unit in long online training days: participants expect the break and calibrate their energy budget accordingly."],"wann_nicht":["As a one-off gimmick at the start of a session – without repetition the effect fizzles out.","In very formal settings with external guests and no advance notice."],"mini_form":"90-second variant: just roll shoulders + shake out + breathe deeply. No facilitation needed, just announce it and join in.","anlass_typen":["lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"any size, up to 100+","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","belastet"]},{"id":"online-energizer-virtual-wave","name":"Online Energizer: Virtual Wave / Row Impulse","feld":"G","kurz":"The group sends a \"wave\" through the video tiles: in an agreed order, everyone in turn makes the same short movement or gesture.","schritte":["Clarify the order (a name list in chat or \"everyone calls the next person\").","Agree on a movement (arms up, waving, a sound).","Start the wave and let it run once through everyone.","Ramp it up: faster, backwards, or with each person's own variation.","Close with an applause wave."],"zweck":"Creating attention and group feeling within seconds – each person gets a turn and is seen.","hinweise":"Only works with cameras on; for large groups, run parallel subgroup waves in breakouts. The name-calling variant also trains everyone to know each other's names along the way.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["energie","verbindung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":5,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["energizer"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"29 online energizers for more engaging meetings – SessionLab Blog","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/blog/online-energizers/"}],"wann_passt":["The opening of an online meeting with a group that doesn't yet know each other well – the wave creates group feeling within 3 minutes and makes everyone visible once.","A transition between two heavy content phases: the wave as a playful signal that a new chapter is starting."],"wann_nicht":["Without cameras – the format only works with visuals.","Groups over 25 people without a subgroup split – the wave otherwise takes 10 minutes and loses its energy."],"mini_form":"A clap wave instead of a movement wave: everyone claps once in turn in the agreed order – even faster, also works audio-only.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-20 with cameras, up to 50 in subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch"]},{"id":"breakout-design","name":"Breakout Design (small groups online)","feld":"G","kurz":"Methodical design of breakout rooms: clear task, appropriate group size, roles, and harvest format are set before the split – the small group is the most important place for real participation online.","schritte":["Define the goal of the small-group phase (brainstorm, deep dive, peer feedback, getting to know each other).","Choose group size: pairs for depth/trust, 3-4 for discussion, 5-6 only with a facilitation role.","Give the task in writing (slide, chat, or board): task, time, expected result, roles.","Announce the time including a 1-minute warning; facilitation drops into rooms for spot checks.","Design the plenary harvest deliberately: one sentence per group, board gallery, or chat collection – never let everyone report everything."],"zweck":"Increase speaking share and safety for everyone – otherwise only a few people speak in the large group online.","hinweise":"Most common mistake: announcing the task only verbally – once in the rooms, nobody remembers what to do. Second pitfall: harvest phase longer than the breakouts themselves; limit the reporting format radically in advance.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","netzwerk"],"modi":["verbindung","klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Virtual Breakout Room Best Practices – Facilitation First","url":"https://facilitationfirst.com/virtual-breakout-room-best-practices/"}],"wann_passt":["Online workshop with 8+ people, where only 3-4 people regularly speak in the large group – breakouts increase everyone's speaking share and sense of safety.","Learning format with in-depth peer conversations: pairs or trios work on the same case and bring back different perspectives.","Large-group conference (20-100): breakouts as the structured core, plenary only for opening and harvest."],"wann_nicht":["When the task can't be given in writing – a verbal announcement gets lost in breakouts.","When the harvest afterward needs more time than the breakouts themselves – then use fewer groups or radically shorter reports."],"fokusfragen":["\"What should be visible in the plenary at the end of the breakout phase – a sentence, a card, a result?\" (harvest design)","\"Who facilitates in the small group, who documents?\" (assigning roles in advance)"],"beispiel":"10-minute breakout in groups of 3: task visible as a slide: \"Discuss for 8 minutes: What is the biggest hurdle with X for your context? Note one sentence on a Miro sticky.\" Plenary: each group reads out their one sentence (3 x 30 sec). Facilitation clusters live. Result: 3 sentences in 3 minutes of harvest.","mini_form":"Pair-share in 5 minutes: 2 people, 1 question, 4 min conversation, 1 min result note. No breakout room needed – pair assigned in chat or formed spontaneously.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","lernformat","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"from 6 people, ideal 8-30 in plenary","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"digitales-whiteboard-arbeiten","name":"Digital Whiteboard Work (methodical)","feld":"G","kurz":"Methodical ground rules for collaborative work on digital whiteboards (Miro, Mural, FigJam, etc.): prepared structure, tech onboarding, silent parallel writing, and clear navigation instead of free-for-all chaos.","schritte":["Structure the board in advance: frames/areas per work step, goal visible at the top, example sticky as a template.","Share the board before the session and build in a 5-minute tech warm-up (write a sticky, move it, zoom).","Start work phases as silent parallel writing (one thought per sticky), only then talk and cluster.","Guide navigation: \"We are now in Frame X\" or bring participants to the frame.","Review the result together at the end and note what carries over into the minutes/next session."],"zweck":"Visible, equitable contribution online – writing instead of talking lowers the dominance of individual voices.","hinweise":"Pitfalls: overloaded boards (cognitive overload) and missing tech onboarding (a third silently drop out). With more than 15 people, plan for co-facilitation. Rule of thumb: one thought per sticky, readably large.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen","planen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["schriftlich","strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Tips for Creating Interactive Online Workshops – Miro Facilitation Guide","url":"https://miro.com/virtual-workshops/guide-to-workshop-facilitation/"}],"wann_passt":["Workshop with a simultaneously writing group: silent parallel writing on stickies gives quieter participants room without the loud ones dominating.","Remote team that wants to structure, cluster, or plan together – a digital whiteboard replaces the flipchart and archives the result instantly.","Trainings with many participants and several parallel group tasks – each group has its own frame, facilitation sees all of them at once."],"wann_nicht":["When a third of the group isn't tech-savvy and no tech onboarding is planned – then silent dropouts undermine participation.","For quick operational decisions – overhead outweighs the benefit."],"fokusfragen":["\"We're now in Frame X – please scroll there.\" (navigation)","\"One thought per sticky – and please write big enough for others to read.\" (writing rule)"],"mini_form":"5-minute tech warm-up: \"Write a sticky with your name and an emoji – move it to the yellow field.\" 5 minutes are enough for everyone to know the basic functions before the work phase begins.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","beteiligung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-30, co-facilitation from 15","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"online-check-in-varianten","name":"Online Check-in Variants","feld":"G","kurz":"Check-in formats adapted to the online space: chat waterfall (everyone types, sends simultaneously on cue), emoji/GIF mood picture, scale via reaction, photo check-in (\"show your desk object\").","schritte":["Choose the format for the group size: up to 8 people, verbal round; above that, chat waterfall or emoji.","Display the question clearly (slide/chat).","For the chat waterfall: everyone writes, but only sends on \"3-2-1-go\" – prevents anchoring effects.","Pick up 2-3 answers out loud so the chat doesn't go unheard.","Name the transition into the agenda."],"zweck":"Actively involve every person once within 5 minutes, even in large online sessions, and establish presence.","hinweise":"The chat waterfall is the most versatile format and scales up to webinar size. Match the personal depth of the question to the group's familiarity; when in doubt, start lighter.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["schriftlich","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Check-in Workshop Activities – SessionLab Library","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/library/check-in"}],"wann_passt":["Online workshop with 10-50 people: chat waterfall gives everyone a voice without spending 45 minutes on a verbal round.","Webinar format where participants don't speak (microphones off): emoji or scale check-in as the only low-threshold moment of participation.","First session of a learning series where the group doesn't yet know each other – photo check-in as a visual conversation opener."],"wann_nicht":["When the same question is used every week – then it's a duty exercise without any insight gained.","When answers in the chat aren't picked up – then the check-in signals that contributions go nowhere."],"fokusfragen":["\"Type your answer – everyone sends on my signal: 3-2-1-now.\" (chat waterfall announcement)"],"beispiel":"Chat waterfall, 20 people: question displayed: \"In one word or sentence: what are you bringing with you today?\" Everyone types. Facilitation: \"3-2-1-go.\" 20 answers appear simultaneously. Facilitation reads 3-4 aloud and comments briefly: \"I'm hearing a lot of energy, a bit of tiredness – fits a Monday. Thanks.\" Transition: \"Let's get started.\" Duration: 3 minutes.","mini_form":"Emoji check-in: question on screen, participants use meeting reactions or type an emoji. 60 seconds, no evaluation needed – the picture speaks for itself.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","lernformat"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-100, chat waterfall up to any size","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"kamera-energie-hygiene","name":"Camera & Energy Hygiene (long online meetings)","feld":"G","kurz":"Design rules against video-call exhaustion (\"Zoom fatigue\"), derived from Stanford research (Bailenson): hide self-view, audio-only phases, freedom of movement, and real breaks built in.","schritte":["Make agreements at the start: hiding self-view is allowed/recommended, camera-off phases are legitimate.","For meetings over 60 minutes: every 50-60 min a 5-10 min break away from the screen (turn body away from the screen).","Announce listening phases as audio-only (\"next 15 min: cameras off, feel free to move around\").","Shrink the window instead of full screen to bring faces to a natural size.","Sprinkle in movement elements (stretch break, standing up while thinking)."],"zweck":"Sustain concentration and quality of participation over long online meetings instead of burning them out through constant camera use.","hinweise":"Ask for the camera deliberately for connection moments (check-in, decision, closing), release it for listening phases. Bailenson's four stressors: constant eye contact, increased nonverbal effort, self-view, immobility.","phasen":["ankommen","vertiefen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":0,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Four causes for 'Zoom fatigue' and their solutions – Stanford Report","url":"https://news.stanford.edu/stories/2021/02/four-causes-zoom-fatigue-solutions"}],"wann_passt":["Full-day or multi-hour online workshops: structured camera breaks and movement interventions maintain quality of participation throughout the day.","Establishing a new online meeting culture in a team: explain the Bailenson findings once and agree on rules together (self-view off, camera breaks legitimate).","Large-group conferences online: plan Zoom-fatigue prevention from the start instead of fixing it in the afternoon."],"wann_nicht":["Short meetings under 30 minutes – overhead not justified.","As a rulebook without explanation – camera rules feel controlling without context."],"fokusfragen":["\"When do we need cameras – and when can we consciously release them?\" (team agreement)"],"mini_form":"One agreement at the start: \"Hiding self-view recommended – we don't watch ourselves. Camera break allowed in the next listening phase.\" 30-second announcement, immediate effect.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"any, especially relevant from 60 min duration","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","belastet"]},{"id":"smart-ziele","name":"SMART Goals","feld":"A","kurz":"Translate vague intentions into specific, measurable, attractive, realistic, and time-bound goals – the classic of goal clarification.","schritte":["Have a draft goal formulated: What do we want to achieve?","Check the draft against the five criteria: specific, measurable, attractive/achievable, realistic, time-bound.","Sharpen each criterion: How do we measure this? By when?","Formulate the final goal and record it visibly.","Optional: clarify responsibility and the first step."],"zweck":"Translate vague intentions into verifiable, time-bound goals.","hinweise":"Risk of false precision for complex undertakings – SMART fits results, less so emergent processes. Variant: SMARTER (+ evaluated, adjusted).","phasen":["planen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","coaching","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"SMART (Projektmanagement) – Wikipedia","url":"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/SMART_(Projektmanagement)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"}],"wann_passt":["Coaching setting or individual support, where a person wants to translate a vague intention into an actionable plan – the five criteria as a checklist work well as a 1:1 conversation structure.","Planning meeting of a team wanting to sharpen a concrete sub-goal for an ongoing project – not for the overall strategy, but for the next 4-week block.","Closing a brainstorming phase: translate the best idea into a SMART goal to mark the transition from creative phase to implementation planning."],"wann_nicht":["For complex societal change processes where the path is emergent – SMART creates false precision there and prevents willingness to adapt. A Theory of Change or Emergent Strategy is better here.","When the group actually needs to first clarify WHAT it wants before clarifying how measurable it is – then SMART is too early. Direction first, then precision.","As a permanent tool in every planning session – SMART formulations that are no longer questioned are empty ritual prose without steering value.","For goals that describe social relationships or cultural change – measurability there is either trivial or impossible."],"fokusfragen":["\"How would you recognize in 3 months that we've achieved this goal – very concretely?\" (measurability)","\"Is this in our hands – i.e. realistic under the conditions we control?\" (realism check)","\"By when exactly? A date, not 'soon.'\" (time-bound)"],"beispiel":"Vague intention: \"We want to improve member retention.\" SMART sharpening: \"By September 30, active participation in our monthly network meetings rises from an average of 12 to at least 20 people, measured via registration numbers of the next 3 meetings.\" The formulation immediately makes visible: Who's responsible for the invitation strategy? What data do we already have? What's missing?","mini_form":"SMART quick test: read the draft goal aloud, then three questions: \"How do we measure it? When? Who's responsible?\" – 5 minutes, no framework explanation.","anlass_typen":["coaching","strategie","kickoff"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1-6 people (coaching to small team), in large groups only as a group task","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"logframe","name":"LogFrame","feld":"A","kurz":"A planning matrix from activities through outputs and outcome to impact – with indicators, means of verification, and assumptions.","schritte":["Clarify the goal hierarchy: impact, outcome, outputs, activities.","Check the if-then logic between levels.","Define indicators per level: How do we recognize achievement?","Set means of verification.","Enter assumptions and risks per level.","Review the matrix together for plausibility."],"zweck":"Make project logic plannable, steerable, and reportable in a 4x4 matrix.","hinweise":"Easily becomes a duty exercise for funders instead of a thinking tool; don't skip the assumptions column, that's where the insight lies. In the session, best built backward from the impact.","phasen":["planen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"How to write a logical framework (logframe) – tools4dev","url":"https://tools4dev.org/resources/how-to-write-a-logical-framework-logframe/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Logframe – BetterEvaluation","url":"https://www.betterevaluation.org/methods-approaches/methods/logframe"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Logical Framework – INTRAC Guide","url":"https://www.intrac.org/app/uploads/2017/01/The-Logical-Framework.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["Proposal workshop with a project team that needs to convince a funder with a structured impact logic – build the LogFrame in the session backward from the impact (not from the activities).","Early project design with several partner organizations: filling it out together makes visible assumptions on which participants hold different views.","Monitoring review of an ongoing project: go through the assumptions column and check which have proven wrong."],"wann_nicht":["As a desk duty exercise after planning is already complete – then the matrix is bureaucracy, not a thinking tool.","For adaptive or emergent undertakings where the path is by definition open – LogFrame forces a linear if-then causality that doesn't fit there. Better: Theory of Change or Outcome Mapping.","When the team doesn't understand what the frame is for – without meaning behind the structure, empty boxes result."],"fokusfragen":["\"If we deliver these outputs – what actually changes then? And what assumptions lie behind that?\" (if-then check)","\"Which assumption in our impact logic is riskiest – and what do we do if it proves wrong?\""],"mini_form":"Results chain in 15 minutes: sketch only the vertical logic – activities to outputs to outcomes to impact – without indicators and verification. Enough as a planning basis for an early discussion.","anlass_typen":["strategie","kickoff"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-10, with a facilitator who knows the structure","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"theory-of-change","name":"Theory of Change","feld":"A","kurz":"A narrative model of the causal pathways and assumptions of an intervention – thought backward from the long-term goal.","schritte":["Formulate the long-term outcome together.","Map backward: which preconditions must be met? (outcomes pathway)","Make the assumptions behind each causal arrow explicit.","Assign interventions to the pathways.","Determine indicators for key outcomes.","Formulate the narrative: if we do X, then Y, because Z."],"zweck":"Make the causal pathways and assumptions of an intervention visible and discussable.","hinweise":"The strength lies in jointly negotiating the assumptions, not in the finished diagram; the Theory of Change is the thinking model behind the LogFrame. A living document, revise regularly.","phasen":["planen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"What is Theory of Change? – Center for Theory of Change","url":"https://www.theoryofchange.org/what-is-theory-of-change/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Theory of Change Workshop Guidance – EIF","url":"https://www.eif.org.uk/resource/running-a-theory-of-change-workshop-a-quick-reference-for-workshop-facilitators"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Station 3: Theory of Change"}],"wann_passt":["Project team (5-15 people) at the start of program planning, when it's unclear whether the planned activities really lead to the intended change – the method forces clarification of the causal logic: if we do X, then Y, because Z.","Strategy process of an organization that needs to distinguish between transformative goals (conditions must change) and interventional goals (what we concretely do) – the Theory of Change makes this distinction explicit and negotiable.","Evaluation preparation, when funders or clients want to know how the program is supposed to work – a fully formulated Theory of Change (max. 3 sentences in if-then-because format) is the basis for measurable outcomes.","Team clarification after conflicts over priorities: the question 'What actually needs to change for our goal to be achieved?' separates activism from strategic intervention."],"wann_nicht":["As a single workshop in one session: a Theory of Change needs iteration – a first draft, field test, revision. Whoever 'finishes' it in 90 minutes usually has a wish list, not a causal logic.","In early contact phases with partner organizations that don't yet share a common problem picture – then do conflict analysis/Connectors-Dividers first, Theory of Change afterward.","As a top-down control tool: if the Theory of Change is dictated by the funder and the team just 'fills it in,' no orientation knowledge is created."],"fokusfragen":["\"If we look back on this program in three years and it was successful – what actually changed, for whom?\" (opens the outcome space)","\"Why do we believe our activities trigger exactly this change – what assumption lies behind that?\" (tests the causal logic)","\"What changes need to happen in society/the system that we can't directly bring about ourselves, but depend on?\" (distinguishes transformative from interventional goals)"],"mini_form":"If-then-because in 10 minutes: everyone writes on three post-its 'If we... (activity)', 'then... (change for whom)', 'because... (assumption)'. Collect, cluster, mark the assumptions with a question mark – which is the most uncertain? That's the theory's risk point.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-12 people ideal, in subgroups for larger groups","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"],"beispiel":"Formulating a Theory of Change in if-then-because format: 'If we train local peace committees in conflict analysis (activity), then they will recognize early-warning signals sooner and open spaces for dialogue (outcome), because communities that understand their own conflict dynamics are more likely to act preventively than to wait for escalation (assumption/because-clause).' The because-clause is the most critical part – it makes the theory testable and falsifiable."},{"id":"outcome-mapping","name":"Outcome Mapping","feld":"A","kurz":"Plan and track impact as observable behavior change in direct partners (boundary partners) rather than as abstract impact.","schritte":["Formulate the program's vision and mission.","Identify boundary partners: actors the program interacts with directly.","Formulate outcome challenges per partner (desired behavior change).","Stage progress markers: expect to see / like to see / love to see.","Plan strategies per partner.","Agree on monitoring via outcome journals."],"zweck":"Plan and track impact as observable behavior change in direct partners.","hinweise":"Terminology (boundary partner, progress marker) needs introduction; use as a complement to funders' LogFrame requirements.","phasen":["planen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":120,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Outcome Mapping – BetterEvaluation","url":"https://www.betterevaluation.org/methods-approaches/approaches/outcome-mapping"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Sarah Earl, Fred Carden, Terry Smutylo: Outcome Mapping. Building Learning and Reflection into Development Programs (IDRC)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Station 4: Outcomes"}],"wann_passt":["Program planning for complex social change processes (8-20 people), where the direct causal link between activities and societal change is too long – Outcome Mapping focuses on behavior change in 'boundary partners' (key actors), not on societal end states.","When a program primarily targets behavior change in specific people or organizations (e.g. government representatives, local leaders): Outcome Mapping explicitly names these boundary partners and defines 'outcome challenges' – what should they do, think, feel differently?","Reflection with field teams (6-15 people) on the difference between what we can control (outputs) and what we can only influence (outcomes) – protects against unrealistic impact promises."],"wann_nicht":["When the team needs clear indicators and measurable targets for funders – Outcome Mapping is impact-oriented but not geared toward simple metrics.","As a replacement for conflict analysis: without understanding the relationships between boundary partners, the foundation is missing.","In single workshops without follow-up: Outcome Mapping lives on regular monitoring of behavior changes."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who are the three to five actors where something concretely needs to change for our goal to be achieved – and what relationship do we have with them?\" (identifying boundary partners)","\"What should these actors do differently, know more about, or think differently by the end of the program? Formulate that as observable behavior.\" (outcome challenge)","\"How will we recognize that something is changing in these actors – what can we observe, even without a questionnaire?\" (progress markers)"],"mini_form":"Boundary-partners mapping in 15 minutes: on a flipchart, the program itself in the middle, the actors that need to change around it. Arrows: who influences whom? Then: for the two most important boundary partners, one sentence each: 'By the end, we wish that [person/organization] ...' – that's the core of an outcome challenge.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-15 people, field team or program management","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"okr","name":"OKR","feld":"A","kurz":"A motivating objective plus 3-5 measurable key results – focus and alignment in short cycles.","schritte":["Formulate one qualitative, motivating objective: Where do we want to go?","Define 3-5 measurable key results: How do we recognize we've gotten there?","Check the ambition level: stretch goal, 70% achievement is good.","Make the OKRs transparent and visible to everyone.","Agree on weekly check-ins and a quarterly review/retro."],"zweck":"Create focus and alignment in short cycles without falling into detailed planning.","hinweise":"Most common mistake: key results as a to-do list instead of outcome metrics; don't tie OKRs to bonus payments. In NGOs, translate the term if needed, the logic stays the same.","phasen":["planen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"What is an OKR? Definition & Examples – What Matters","url":"https://www.whatmatters.com/faqs/okr-meaning-definition-example"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"John Doerr: Measure What Matters"},{"typ":"online","titel":"OKR für soziale Organisationen – IdeeQuadrat","url":"https://www.ideequadrat.org/objectives-and-key-results-in-sozialen-organisationen/"}],"wann_passt":["An organization or team that has a developed strategy and clear mission and wants to operationalize it in 90-day cycles – OKR without a strategic base is goal roulette.","Team retreat for quarterly planning: formulate a motivating objective together and determine 3-5 key results that let everyone recognize their progress.","When the team regularly doesn't know after a quarter what actually mattered – OKR forces focus through quantity limits (1 objective, max. 5 KRs)."],"wann_nicht":["Without a prior clear strategy, vision, or mission – OKR operationalizes direction but can't replace it.","When key results are tied to individual bonus payments – then goals are set tactically (too low, so they're achievable) instead of ambitiously.","In very small teams (2-3 people) – the coordination effort exceeds the benefit; direct alignment is more efficient.","For undertakings aiming at complex qualitative impact – mandatory measurability produces oversimplifications that miss the essence. Better: Theory of Change."],"fokusfragen":["\"If this quarter was great – what did we achieve? In one sentence.\" (formulating the objective)","\"How will we recognize in 3 months that we're on the right track – very concretely and measurably?\" (key results)","\"Is this goal a result – or an activity?\" (KR quality check)"],"beispiel":"OKR review, one team: objective: \"We're known as a credible point of contact for new partner organizations.\" KR 1: 3 new partner inquiries this quarter (currently: 1). KR 2: 2 co-created events (currently: 0). KR 3: network page with 5 new references (currently: 2). Check-in after 6 weeks: KR 3 on track, KR 1 and 2 stuck. Discussion: What's blocking KR 2? → lack of capacity in fall. Adjust the OKR or reallocate resources.","mini_form":"OKR quick draft in 20 minutes: everyone writes one objective in one sentence + 2-3 KR ideas. Check in pairs: Is this a result or an activity? Plenary: choose 1-2 drafts as a starting point.","anlass_typen":["strategie","kickoff","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-12, quarterly planning in team format","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"agiles-pm","name":"Agile PM (Scrum/iterative)","feld":"A","kurz":"Steer complex undertakings in short learning and delivery loops instead of full planning – with backlog, sprints, dailies, and retrospectives.","schritte":["Prioritize the product backlog: What creates value next?","Sprint planning: team chooses a realistic work package for 1-4 weeks.","Daily: 15-min sync (What's done? What's next? What's blocked?).","Sprint review: show the result to stakeholders, gather feedback.","Retrospective: improve collaboration.","Start the next cycle."],"zweck":"Steer complex undertakings in short learning and delivery loops instead of full planning.","hinweise":"Only works with a real mandate for self-organization; Scrum theater (rituals without a mindset) is the most common derailment. For non-software contexts, adapt roles and artifacts pragmatically.","phasen":["planen","verstetigen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["meeting","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":10,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The Scrum Guide – Schwaber & Sutherland","url":"https://scrumguides.org/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Ken Schwaber, Jeff Sutherland: The Scrum Guide (frei online)"}],"wann_passt":["Undertakings with complex, hard-to-predict requirements, where regular course correction matters more than full planning – Scrum sprints or Kanban cycles as a steering framework.","Workshop module in a retreat on the question 'How do we want to work going forward?': introduce basic principles (backlog, timebox, retro) and transfer them to your own context.","Team with high ownership and a clear mandate – then Agile PM delivers the rhythm without needing micromanagement."],"wann_nicht":["Without a real mandate for self-organization – Scrum theater (all the rituals, none of the mindset) demoralizes teams faster than classic leadership.","For clearly plannable, stable undertakings with little uncertainty – linear project management is more efficient there.","When 'agile' is used as a cost-cutting argument (no project manager needed) – without dedicated roles it tips into chaos."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's the smallest deliverable unit that gives us feedback today?\" (sprint selection)","\"What did we learn – and what do we change in the next cycle?\" (retro opening)"],"mini_form":"Kanban start in 20 minutes: fill a 3-column board (to do / in progress / done) with the team's current tasks. First question: What's currently in progress – and why is so much active at once?","anlass_typen":["kickoff","strategie"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-10 people (Scrum team size)","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"ecosystem-mapping","name":"Ecosystem Mapping","feld":"A","kurz":"Make the actors, relationships, and resource flows of a field visible on a shared map.","schritte":["Set the focus: around whom/what is the ecosystem being mapped?","Collect actors and entities (people, organizations, platforms, places) – on cards/stickies.","Arrange them on the surface, e.g. by proximity to the center.","Draw in relationships: information, money, resource, and support flows.","Read the patterns: gaps, dependencies, unused connections.","Derive consequences and next steps."],"zweck":"Make the actors, relationships, and flows of a field visible on a shared map.","hinweise":"The map quickly becomes cluttered – keep the focus question narrow and limit line types; works well online with Miro/Mural. A living artifact, not a final product.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Ecosystem Map – Service Design Tools","url":"https://servicedesigntools.org/tools/ecosystem-map"}],"wann_passt":["Strategy retreat of an organization in a complex environment: a shared picture of the ecosystem sharpens understanding of where one stands and which connections are missing or need strengthening.","Network meeting of several organizations at the start of a cooperation: the map makes visible who contributes what and where the overlaps and gaps are.","Preparation for a call for proposals or an application: understand actors and resource flows before writing the intervention strategy."],"wann_nicht":["When the focus question is too broad – 'the entire education ecosystem' doesn't fit on one board; narrow the scope in advance.","As solo work – the map lives on multiple perspectives; created alone it's blind to blind spots."],"fokusfragen":["\"Around whom or what are we drawing this map – what is our center?\" (scope clarification)","\"Which connections surprise you – what didn't you expect to see?\" (after drawing)"],"mini_form":"5-min actor brainstorm: everyone writes actors on stickies (1 actor per sticky), then roughly arrange them: close to the core / further away. Enough as a first shared picture without a complete mapping.","anlass_typen":["strategie","netzwerktreffen","kickoff"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-12, with whiteboard or Miro","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"social-network-analysis","name":"Social Network Analysis","feld":"A","kurz":"Measure and visualize a network's relationship structures: who is central, who is isolated, where are clusters and bridges?","schritte":["Define the network question: who works with whom / exchanges information?","Collect data: survey or joint mapping of relationships.","Visualize the network (nodes = actors, edges = relationships; tools: Kumu, Gephi, or paper).","Analyze: who is central, who is isolated, where are clusters and bridges?","Interpret the findings with the group and derive interventions, e.g. deliberately building bridges."],"zweck":"Make a network's relationship structures measurable and visible in order to work deliberately on connections.","hinweise":"Data collection is sensitive (who is \"isolated\"?) – frame results appreciatively and clarify data protection. In sessions, a participatory light version on paper is often enough.","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Social Network Analysis – BetterEvaluation","url":"https://www.betterevaluation.org/methods-approaches/methods/social-network-analysis"}],"wann_passt":["Organizational development aiming to understand information flows or collaboration patterns – SNA shows who is de facto the information hub (often not formal leadership).","Network intervention aiming to build bridges deliberately between isolated clusters – SNA makes visible where these bridges are missing.","Evaluation of a network program: did the program actually create new connections that weren't there before?"],"wann_nicht":["Without explicit clarification of data protection – network maps show who is isolated, which can be hurtful in trust-sensitive settings.","As a quick workshop exercise without data collection – without a survey or systematic mapping, the results are speculation.","When the team can't handle the findings (e.g. leadership is isolated) – then the SNA needs a culture of processing, not just a visualization."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who do you exchange information with on X in a typical week?\" (survey question)","\"What stands out to you – who is central, who did you surprisingly not find?\" (interpretation round)"],"mini_form":"Participatory quick mapping: everyone writes 3 names on stickies each ('I work closely with these people on X') and connects them on a poster. A first picture emerges in 15 minutes – not statistically valid, but a conversation opener.","anlass_typen":["strategie","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-30, with a tool (Kumu, Gephi) or paper light version","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"abcd","name":"Asset-Based Community Development (ABCD)","feld":"A","kurz":"Map a community's existing strengths instead of deficits – and spark self-organization from within.","schritte":["Introduce the shift in perspective: from deficits to strengths.","Inventory assets in five categories: individuals, associations, institutions, places, connections.","Make individual gifts visible: What can you contribute?","Build connections: who can move something with whom?","Agree on first self-organized undertakings.","Make successes visible and keep the momentum."],"zweck":"Map a community's existing strengths and spark self-organization from within.","hinweise":"Not a quick workshop method but a mindset and long-term process – asset mapping can be well started in a session. Pitfall: outsiders take over the lead again.","phasen":["planen","oeffnen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","grossgruppe","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":50,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Asset Based Community Development – Nurture Development","url":"https://www.nurturedevelopment.org/asset-based-community-development/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"John Kretzmann, John McKnight: Building Communities from the Inside Out"}],"wann_passt":["Kickoff of community work or a community initiative, where outside actors threaten to set the agenda – ABCD reverses the question: what's already here? What can we do ourselves?","Organizational or network development after a crisis phase in which deficit thinking dominates – asset mapping generates energy and agency before problems are discussed.","Workshop module in a longer participation process: a 90-minute asset-mapping block that produces a picture of existing strengths, which then becomes the basis for planning."],"wann_nicht":["As a quick workshop format with a result expectation in 2 hours – ABCD is a mindset and a long-term process; in one session only the asset mapping can be started.","When external facilitators leave the group after the session and there's no internal commitment to continue – then ABCD generates energy without follow-through.","In contexts with strong power imbalances, where certain voices are systematically not heard – then ABCD needs prior work on the power structures, otherwise only the strengths of the privileged get mapped."],"fokusfragen":["\"What can you contribute – not what do you need?\" (paradigm reversal)","\"Who in this group could work with whom – what would then become possible?\""],"mini_form":"Gifts round in 20 minutes: everyone names one skill or resource they could contribute. Facilitation clusters visibly. Closing question: \"Which combination of gifts surprises you?\"","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","kickoff","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"10-40, with room for movement; limited online","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","belastet","frisch"]},{"id":"stakeholder-mapping","name":"Stakeholder/Actor Mapping","feld":"A","kurz":"Reveal stakeholders' interests and influence on a matrix in order to plan participation and communication deliberately.","schritte":["Name the question/undertaking.","Brainstorm all relevant actors (internal/external).","Place them on a matrix: influence/power (y) x interest (x).","Derive a handling strategy per quadrant: engage closely, satisfy, inform, monitor.","Discuss relationships and coalitions.","Agree on concrete engagement steps and set a review date."],"zweck":"Reveal stakeholders' interests and influence in order to plan participation and communication deliberately.","hinweise":"Placements are hypotheses, not truths – update regularly; clarify confidentiality of the room for sensitive stakeholder assessments. Variants: influence/attitude matrix, stakeholder onion.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Power/Interest Grid – Improvement Service","url":"https://www.improvementservice.org.uk/business-analysis-framework/consider-perspectives/powerinterest-grid"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"}],"wann_passt":["Kickoff of a new project or initiative with several stakeholder groups – the matrix immediately shows who to engage, inform, win over, or monitor.","Preparing a difficult communication step: which actors have high interest and could block? Where are allies with high influence?","Cooperation design: who brings what in, who do we absolutely need at the table, who do we not invite – and why?"],"wann_nicht":["As a static one-off exercise – stakeholder positions shift over the course of a project; the map needs regular updating.","When the placement of individual actors is sensitive and representatives of exactly those actors are in the room – clarify confidentiality of the process in advance."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who has the greatest interest in the outcome – and who has the greatest influence to prevent it?\" (matrix starter)","\"Which actors have we forgotten? Who's missing who would be affected but isn't in the room?\""],"mini_form":"5-min brainstorm on actors, then quick placement: 4 sticky-note quadrants (influence high/low x interest high/low) on the table. Stick cards on, 1-min discussion per quadrant: What do these actors need from us?","anlass_typen":["kickoff","strategie","entscheidungstreffen"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"2-12, as team work at the whiteboard","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"community-canvas","name":"Community Canvas","feld":"A","kurz":"Develop a shared picture of a community across three areas (Identity, Experience, Structure) with 17 topic fields.","schritte":["Introduce the canvas: three areas (Identity, Experience, Structure) with 17 topic fields.","Start with Identity: answer purpose, values, member definition together.","Work on Experience: rituals, experiences, roles.","Work on Structure: governance, funding, organization.","Mark gaps and tensions.","Derive priorities for community development."],"zweck":"Develop a shared, complete picture of a community and find blind spots in community design.","hinweise":"17 fields are too many for one session – preselect 5-7 relevant fields or spread across several sessions. Good as diagnostics for both existing and planned communities.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The Community Canvas – community-canvas.org","url":"https://community-canvas.org/"}],"wann_passt":["Founding phase or fundamental reorientation of a community: the canvas uncovers blind spots in community design – with 17 fields, almost every group finds at least 5 they haven't thought about yet.","Diagnosis of an existing community with loss of energy or declining membership – systematically going through the fields shows where the foundation is missing.","Cooperation retreat of several organizations wanting to design a shared community – the canvas gives a common language."],"wann_nicht":["All 17 fields in one session – that takes a whole day and is overwhelming; better to select 5-7 fields by diagnostic priority.","As a quick workshop tool for a community that urgently needs to solve acute governance problems – a direct clarifying conversation is faster there."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's the purpose of this community – why does it exist, and what would be missing if it weren't there?\" (Identity starter)","\"Which fields have we never discussed together before? What surprises you when you look at it?\""],"mini_form":"Identity sprint in 30 minutes: work only the 3 Identity fields (purpose, values, member definition). These three alone often produce the most important clarifications.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","strategie","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-12 (core team or steering group of the community)","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"platform-design-toolkit","name":"Platform Design Toolkit","feld":"A","kurz":"Understand and design an ecosystem as a platform: who produces, who consumes, what value is exchanged?","schritte":["Map ecosystem actors (Ecosystem Canvas): who produces, who consumes, who orchestrates?","Capture potentials per actor (Entity Portrait): goals, gifts, pain points.","Design core transactions: what value is exchanged between whom?","Define the platform's supporting services (Enabling/Empowering Services).","Sketch a Minimum Viable Platform and agree on test steps."],"zweck":"Understand and design an ecosystem as a platform that enables value exchange between actors.","hinweise":"Vocabulary requires prerequisites – introduce with a familiar example (e.g. marketplace); the toolkit is freely available, a full run-through needs several sessions.","phasen":["planen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":120,"dauer_max":300,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Platform Design Toolkit – Boundaryless","url":"https://www.platformdesigntoolkit.com/"}],"wann_passt":["Organizations or networks that want to design a shared ecosystem in which value is exchanged between different actors – the toolkit gives a language for roles and transactions.","Design sprint for a new initiative or platform: the Entity Portrait forces thinking through each actor type from their own interest, not from your own.","Strategy retreat aiming to rethink a network's business model – who produces value, who consumes, who orchestrates?"],"wann_nicht":["Without an introduction to the terminology – the toolkit has its own vocabulary (Ecosystem Canvas, Entity Portrait, Enabling Service) that needs explaining beforehand.","As a tool for simple bilateral cooperations without platform logic."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who produces value in our ecosystem – and who consumes? Where does someone orchestrate this exchange?\" (opening question)","\"Which transaction is the core of our platform – what exactly is exchanged between whom?\""],"mini_form":"Ecosystem sketch in 20 minutes: three post-it colors: producers (yellow), consumers (blue), orchestrator (green). Lay them out on a surface, draw arrows. Opening question: what flows where?","anlass_typen":["strategie","kickoff"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-10, with a facilitator who knows the toolkit","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"strategic-doing","name":"Strategic Doing","feld":"A","kurz":"Bring loose networks without formal authority into joint action through small commitments and a 30/30 rhythm.","schritte":["Pose a framing question (\"What if...?\") and set the conversation's rules: equal footing, timeboxed.","Make all participants' assets visible: what could we contribute?","Link opportunities: where do combined assets create new possibilities?","Choose the \"Big Easy\": the most impactful, most feasible opportunity.","Define a pathfinder project with small commitments: who does what by when?","Agree on a 30/30 rhythm: meet again in 30 days, learn, adjust."],"zweck":"Bring loose networks without formal authority into joint action through lean loops.","hinweise":"Lives on the rhythm of follow-up meetings – without 30/30 discipline the start fizzles out; keep commitments small (\"small enough to do on the side\").","phasen":["planen","entscheiden","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","verbindung","entscheidung"],"formate":["workshop","grossgruppe","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Strategic Doing – strategicdoing.net","url":"https://strategicdoing.net/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Edward Morrison u. a.: Strategic Doing. Ten Skills for Agile Leadership"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Strategic Doing – SSIR Artikel","url":"https://ssir.org/articles/entry/accelerating_civic_innovation_through_strategic_doing"}],"wann_passt":["A loose network of several organizations without a shared hierarchy that wants to move into joint action – Strategic Doing is built for open networks without a formal decision-making framework.","Kickoff of a multi-organizational cooperation: the 'Big Easy' logic (impactful + feasible) prevents ambitious goals from getting stuck in paralyzing complexity.","When a group repeatedly has good strategy conversations but nothing happens – the 30/30 rhythm principle forces small, concrete commitments with a follow-up date."],"wann_nicht":["For established teams with clear hierarchy and existing decision-making structures – the decentralized logic creates friction there.","When the group has no willingness to actually keep small commitments – without follow-through, the kickoff workshop is a nice exercise without impact.","As a replacement for strategy development – Strategic Doing assumes direction is already given and then operationalizes it."],"fokusfragen":["\"What if...?\" (framing question for the Strategic Doing opening)","\"What's the most feasible and most impactful thing we could do together – with what we already have today?\""],"mini_form":"Asset round + Big Easy in 30 minutes: everyone names 2 resources/skills they could contribute. Then the question: \"What would be the one thing we could do together with these assets?\" Define the smallest possible version, name concrete next steps.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","kickoff","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-20, loose network constellation","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"emergent-strategy","name":"Emergent Strategy (adrienne maree brown)","feld":"A","kurz":"Strategy as an adaptive, relationship-based practice: fractal experiments amplify what is already emerging.","schritte":["Introduce the principles, e.g. \"small is all\", \"move at the speed of trust\", \"critical connections over critical mass\".","Read the present: which small patterns are already showing that we want to amplify?","Prioritize relationships over plans: where are our critical connections?","Agree on small, fractal experiments that mirror the large in the small.","Harvest regularly: what are we learning, what's adapting? (\"never a failure, always a lesson\")"],"zweck":"Shape strategy as an adaptive, relationship-based practice rather than a fixed plan.","hinweise":"More a mindset and framework of principles than a step-by-step method – works well as a reflective lens over existing undertakings; unfamiliar for planning-accustomed groups, needs translation.","phasen":["planen","verstetigen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["reflexion","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Emergent Strategy – adrienne maree brown","url":"https://adriennemareebrown.net/book/emergent-strategy/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"adrienne maree brown: Emergent Strategy. Shaping Change, Changing Worlds"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Emergent Strategy – Commons Library","url":"https://commonslibrary.org/emergent-strategy/"}],"wann_passt":["Social movements or networks acting in complex, non-linear contexts that notice classic strategy plans are outdated within 6 months – Emergent Strategy as a reflective lens to read and amplify what's emerging.","Retreat of an activist or civil-society organization wanting to reflect on its practice: the principles (small is all, move at the speed of trust) as an evaluation framework for existing work.","Strategy development with groups that experience planning-accustomed frameworks as foreign or alienating – Emergent Strategy gives an alternative language for adaptivity."],"wann_nicht":["As a step-by-step method with a clear output – Emergent Strategy delivers no plans, only principles. Whoever needs a strategy plan needs a different tool.","In planning-accustomed, funding-bound organizations that must present a result at the end of a session – the format doesn't relieve that pressure.","As a one-time workshop experience without follow-up – the principles are easy to state and hard to live; a workshop creates interest, not practice."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which small patterns are showing up in our work right now that we want to amplify?\" (reading patterns)","\"What would 'move at the speed of trust' concretely mean – in our next step?\""],"mini_form":"Principles check in 20 minutes: three principles from adrienne maree brown on cards. Small groups: which one describes our work right now the most – and what would we change if we took it seriously?","anlass_typen":["strategie","retro","dialograum"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-20 for a reflection format, larger groups possible in breakouts","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"backcasting","name":"Backcasting","feld":"A","kurz":"Plan backward from a concretely described future picture to milestones and first steps – frees thinking from the status quo.","schritte":["Set a time horizon (e.g. 10 years) and describe the desired future concretely: present tense, sensory, together.","Capture the present honestly: where do we stand today?","Go backward: what must have happened immediately before for this future to have been possible? Milestones from the target picture to the present.","Choose the path and arrange it on a timeline.","Derive first concrete steps for the next 6-12 months."],"zweck":"Plan backward from the future picture in order to break free from status-quo thinking.","hinweise":"Only works if the future picture is richly developed beforehand (possibly combine with visioning); pitfall: the group slips back into forward planning – keep asking backward consistently.","phasen":["planen"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","energie"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Backcasting – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/backcasting"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Backcasting from principles vs. Scenario planning – OERu","url":"https://course.oeru.org/csf103/learning-pathways/backcasting-from-sustainability-principles/backcasting-from-principles-vs-scenario-planning/"}],"wann_passt":["Strategy retreat where status-quo thinking is blocking planning – the future picture in the present tense allows thinking from a desired goal without immediately answering 'that's not possible.'","Vision development with a group that is short-term oriented and struggles to think beyond 2 years – backcasting with a 10-year horizon stretches the horizon and creates a logic for action.","Difference from scenario planning: backcasting starts with a desired future picture and asks backward for the path; scenario planning develops several possible (including undesired) futures. Backcasting suits motivation, scenario planning suits risk robustness."],"wann_nicht":["When the future picture isn't sufficiently developed – backcasting is only as strong as the quality of the group's imagination. Superficial visions produce superficial paths.","For a very short time horizon (under 2 years) – normal forward planning is more efficient then.","When the group keeps slipping into forward thinking during backward planning – consistent facilitation is needed, otherwise it becomes normal planning in reverse order."],"fokusfragen":["\"It's the year 2035 – describe your everyday life in this organization/network as if you were there.\" (future picture starter)","\"What must already have happened by 2033 for 2035 to be possible? And before that?\" (backward step)","\"What's the first concrete step in the next 6 months that lies on this path?\""],"mini_form":"3-horizons sketch in 20 minutes: choose a time horizon (e.g. 5 years). The group describes the desired picture in 5 min. Then: what must have happened in 2.5 years? What by next year? Stickies on a timeline. Not full backcasting, but a sense of direction.","anlass_typen":["strategie","kickoff"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-25, with whiteboard or timeline on the floor","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"szenario-planung","name":"Scenario Planning","feld":"A","kurz":"Play through several plausible futures along two critical uncertainties, to make strategies robust against uncertainty.","schritte":["Clarify the key question and the time horizon.","Brainstorm driving forces: social, technological, economic, ecological, political.","Choose two critical uncertainties (high impact, high uncertainty) and cross them as axes.","Develop four scenarios: in small groups, as vivid future narratives in the present tense.","Check implications: What does each scenario mean for us?","Identify robust strategies that hold up across several scenarios."],"zweck":"Play through several plausible futures to make strategies robust against uncertainty.","hinweise":"Scenarios are not forecasts – clear up this expectation early; quality depends on the choice of the two uncertainties, so take enough time for that.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":120,"dauer_max":360,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"How to facilitate scenario planning workshops – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/blog/scenario-planning/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peter Schwartz: The Art of the Long View"}],"wann_passt":["An organization's strategy process in a highly uncertain environment: crossing two critical uncertainties and playing through four scenarios makes the strategy robust instead of betting on a single picture.","When an organization wants to know whether its strategy holds up across different futures or only works for one particular course of events.","Difference from backcasting: scenario planning develops several possible futures (including undesirable ones) and derives robust strategies from them; backcasting starts with a desired picture and searches for the path there. Scenario planning fits better for risk awareness, backcasting for motivation and clarity of direction."],"wann_nicht":["As a one-day workshop – four fully developed scenarios need at least a day and a half to two days; otherwise you get flat caricatures instead of vivid future narratives.","When the group understands the scenarios as forecasts – scenarios are thinking tools, not predictions. This expectation must be cleared up early.","With groups that have a very short time horizon (under 3 years) – then planning thinking dominates, and scenarios feel contrived."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which two uncertainties have the greatest impact on us – and are at the same time the least predictable?\" (axis selection)","\"Imagine you're living in the year 2030 in scenario A – what are you doing right now, what news are you reading?\" (scenario development)","\"Which strategy would work in at least 3 of 4 scenarios?\" (robustness test)"],"mini_form":"2-scenario short version in 45 minutes: work out only one axis (e.g. resources: abundant vs. scarce) and two scenarios. Not four scenarios, but already a different perspective than a single future.","anlass_typen":["strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–20, in small groups each working on one scenario","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"systemische-organisationsberatung","name":"Systemic Organizational Consulting","feld":"B","kurz":"Understand organizations as social systems and accompany them through self-directed change – via hypotheses, questions, and settings.","schritte":["Contact and contract: clarify the assignment, roles, and expectations with the client system.","Observe the system: focus on communication patterns, rules, and interactions rather than individuals.","Form hypotheses about the system's functional logic: What is the problem good for?","Set interventions that enable self-reflection and pattern shifts: questions, feedback, settings.","Observe the effect and run through the loop again.","Evaluate and close the process together."],"zweck":"Understand organizations as social systems and accompany them through self-directed change.","hinweise":"A consulting approach, not a single tool – in a session you work with its elements (hypotheses, systemic questions, the loop). Pitfall: falling back into expert consulting and delivering solutions.","phasen":["ankommen","verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung","coaching"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Systemische Organisationsberatung – Wikipedia","url":"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systemische_Organisationsberatung"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Roswita Königswieser, Martin Hillebrand: Einführung in die systemische Organisationsberatung"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["A team or organization has a recurring problem that doesn't improve with more effort or new techniques – the systemic frame shifts the focus away from individuals toward patterns and interactions.","External support is commissioned that is not meant to act as a content expert, but instead shapes the system's own change process.","At the start of a retreat or clarification conversation, a systemic view is introduced: Who belongs here, what patterns are recognizable, what is the problem useful for?"],"wann_nicht":["When the group expects and needs a concrete expert answer (technical problem, legal question) – here, systemic work leads to frustration.","In acute crises under time pressure: the model needs observation time and reflection loops.","When the consultant is not clear about their own role – systemic consulting without a clarified contract quickly slips into unclear expectations."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who is all part of the system at work here – including those who aren't in the room?\"","\"What could this problem be useful for within the system – what would be missing if it were gone?\"","\"What patterns do you see recurring – regardless of who currently occupies the roles?\""],"beispiel":"In a coaching conversation, a manager complains about her team's lack of engagement. Systemic question: 'What do you think your team would say about your engagement?' (circular – forcing a change of perspective). The answer reveals that the manager herself seems ambivalent. Follow-up question: 'How does the team notice that you stand behind this initiative?' This makes the pattern visible: the leadership's ambivalence is mirrored in the team – the real field for intervention lies in the leadership stance, not in the team.","mini_form":"'What is this good for' question in 5 minutes: in an ongoing meeting, throw in a single systemic hypothesis question – 'What if this problem is currently serving an important function for the system?' – and observe the reactions. Not a complete format, but a starting point for the loop.","anlass_typen":["coaching","konfliktklaerung","strategie"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–6 people ideal, up to 20 possible in structured workshop settings","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"prozessberatung-schein","name":"Process Consultation (Schein)","feld":"B","kurz":"Shape the client's working and relationship process instead of delivering content – with humble inquiry and a helping relationship.","schritte":["Build a helping relationship: the client retains ownership of the problem and the solution.","Jointly explore current reality (\"Never lose sight of current reality\").","Ask humbly instead of answering (Humble Inquiry): What is actually happening right now in this process?","Reflect observations about the work process back to the client.","Let the client system develop its own diagnosis and next steps.","Agree on how progress will be recognized."],"zweck":"Shape the client's working and relationship process so they solve their own problems.","hinweise":"Biggest trap: delivering content expertise under pressure after all – this undermines the system's self-efficacy; Schein's 10 principles work well as a checklist for your own consulting stance.","phasen":["ankommen","verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung","coaching"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Die 10 Prinzipien der Prozessberatung nach Edgar Schein – kantelbergs.de","url":"https://www.kantelbergs.de/prinzipien-prozessberatung-schein/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Edgar H. Schein: Prozessberatung für die Organisation der Zukunft"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["An individual or team wants to solve a problem but already holds the answers within – the consulting consists of accompanying the thinking process, not delivering solutions.","A new consulting relationship is starting: Schein's 'Humble Inquiry' gives the first session a clear stance – asking with curiosity, not judging.","The consultant comes under pressure to give advice – then the process-consultation stance serves as a corrective: let current reality be described instead of delivering analysis."],"wann_nicht":["When genuine subject-matter expertise is needed (legal, technical, medical) – pure process consultation would then amount to a refusal to help.","In groups that need leadership impulses and structure – too much humble inquiry can be perceived as weak leadership.","As a rigid method corset: Schein describes a stance that can be mixed with content contributions."],"fokusfragen":["\"What is actually happening in this process right now – not what you wish for, but what is actually happening?\"","\"How would you know that the consulting was successful – concretely, observably?\"","\"What do I need to understand about your situation that I haven't asked about yet?\""],"beispiel":"A client describes a conflict with a colleague. Instead of advice: 'Describe to me what happens in a typical encounter between the two of you – from beginning to end.' (Humble Inquiry: exploring reality, not interpreting it). The client describes it. Follow-up question: 'What do you do the moment you notice the mood shifting?' This makes their own contribution visible – without the consultant naming it.","mini_form":"'Describe to me…' as an opening technique: instead of an analytical question, let the client narrate the current situation in their own words (3–5 min). No comments, only follow-up questions: 'What else?' Sets the process-consultation stance for the rest of the session.","anlass_typen":["coaching","konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"haltung","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–3 people; possible with teams up to 6 with an explicitly clarified role","stimmung_geeignet":["belastet","angespannt","skeptisch"]},{"id":"lewin","name":"Lewin (3 Phases)","feld":"B","kurz":"Structure change in three phases – unfreeze, change, refreeze – with force-field analysis as a practical building block.","schritte":["Introduce the model: Unfreeze – Change – Refreeze.","Determine location: Which phase is our change initiative currently in?","Work on Unfreeze: force-field analysis – which forces drive the change, which restrain it?","Plan Change: which new behaviors/processes are being tried out, who needs what support?","Secure Refreeze: how do we anchor the new state (routines, structures, recognition)?","Record measures for each phase."],"zweck":"Structure change processes in three phases and choose fitting interventions for each phase.","hinweise":"\"Refreeze\" is often criticized as too static in dynamic environments – better framed as \"stabilize\"; force-field analysis is the most practical session building block of the model.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Das 3-Phasen-Modell nach Lewin – projekte-leicht-gemacht.de","url":"https://projekte-leicht-gemacht.de/blog/business-wissen/das-3-phasen-modell-lewin/"}],"wann_passt":["An organization starts a change project and the leadership team disagrees on why previous attempts failed – Lewin's force-field analysis makes driving and restraining forces visible and creates a shared diagnostic frame.","In a retreat where a change initiative needs to be structured: the three phases serve as a planning grid (What does Unfreeze need? What is Change? What anchors Refreeze?).","A training module on change management: the model is easy to grasp, has a clear sequence, and delivers immediately applicable tools."],"wann_nicht":["In very agile, iterative environments: the Refreeze concept seems static and creates resistance among people who experience change as a permanent state.","When the change initiative has already been decided and communicated – then Unfreeze diagnosis no longer helps, it's about implementation planning.","As a full model for short meetings – here, only use force-field analysis as a building block."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which of the three phases are we currently in – and how do we concretely recognize that?\"","\"Which forces are driving the change forward, which are restraining it – what is the strongest brake?\"","\"What would need to happen so the new state doesn't fall back into old patterns (Refreeze)?\""],"beispiel":"Force-field analysis in 20 minutes: two columns on the flipchart – 'What is driving the change?' and 'What is holding it back?'. The group collects in silence (sticky notes, 5 min), then clusters. Question: 'Which brake carries the most weight?' Follow-up question: 'What would it take to reduce exactly this brake by 20%?' – turning diagnosis into a field for action.","mini_form":"Force-field analysis only, as a 20-minute building block: skip introducing the whole phase model and go straight into the analysis – gather driving and restraining forces, identify the heaviest brake, note one concrete idea for action.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–20 people; force-field analysis also works well for two people","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"glasl-org-phasen","name":"Glasl (Organizational Phases & Escalation)","feld":"B","kurz":"Determine an organization's stage of maturity (pioneer, differentiation, integration, association phase) and interpret crises as normal developmental steps.","schritte":["Introduce the four developmental phases: pioneer, differentiation, integration, association phase.","Gather symptoms: How do we recognize our organization? (leadership, structures, culture)","Locate together: Which phase – or phase crisis – are we in?","Name typical crises of the phase, e.g. the maturity crisis of the pioneer phase, bureaucratization in the differentiation phase.","Derive a direction for development: What would be the next healthy step?","In conflicts, additionally use the escalation stages as a diagnostic overlay."],"zweck":"Determine an organization's stage of maturity to interpret crises as normal developmental steps.","hinweise":"Locating the organization often triggers aha-moments and relief (\"our crisis is typical\") – leave room for that; don't communicate the phases as a value judgment (\"further along = better\").","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Entwicklungsphasen einer Organisation nach Friedrich Glasl – fritz.tips","url":"https://www.fritz.tips/entwicklungsphasen-einer-organisation-nach-friedrich-glasl"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Friedrich Glasl, Bernard Lievegoed: Dynamische Unternehmensentwicklung"}],"wann_passt":["A leadership team notices the organization is under stress but can't name why – Glasl's phase model provides relief through classification: 'Our pioneer-phase crisis is normal.'","An organization has just gone through a major change (mergers, growth, leadership change) and wonders where it stands – phase location provides orientation and a direction for development.","In a training module on organizational development: the model makes OD processes tangible without being too abstract."],"wann_nicht":["When the group misunderstands the phases as a value ladder ('further along = better') – then better use another OD model or adjust the framing.","In an acute crisis session: the model needs reflection time, it is not a crisis-intervention tool.","With very small teams (under 5): the phases are designed at the organizational level and often don't apply at the team level."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which symptoms do we recognize – what from the pioneer phase is still alive, what has differentiated?\"","\"What would it mean for our leadership structure if we really are in phase X?\"","\"What would be the next healthy developmental step – not the fastest, but the one that fits?\""],"beispiel":"In a retreat: the phase model on a slide (briefly introduce 4 phases + typical crises, 10 min). Then small-group work: 'Which symptoms from which phase do you recognize in us?' (15 min). In plenary: 'Where do most of you land?' – often a conversation emerges about different perceptions that is more valuable than the phase location itself. Follow-up question: 'What exactly is missing for us to use the current crisis as a normal developmental step?'","mini_form":"Location question in 10 minutes: 'If you had to describe our organization with one of these four images – which fits best?' (pioneer business/family enterprise, growing bureaucracy, integrated network organization, learning association). Then why – without introducing the whole model.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–20 people; most effective with a leadership team","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"kotter-8-stufen","name":"Kotter (8 Steps)","feld":"B","kurz":"Plan large-scale organizational change along eight steps – from urgency through guiding coalition to anchoring.","schritte":["Introduce the eight steps: urgency, guiding coalition, vision, communication, removing obstacles, quick wins, not letting up, anchoring.","Locate your own change initiative on the steps: What has been done, what has been skipped?","Discuss skipped steps as a risk (often: lack of urgency or coalition).","Work out concrete measures for the current step.","Identify quick wins that will be visible within 90 days.","Assign responsibilities."],"zweck":"Plan large-scale organizational change along a proven sequence of steps and find gaps in the change process.","hinweise":"The model has a top-down bias – in participatory contexts, use the steps as a checklist rather than a strict order; Kotter himself now recommends thinking of the steps as parallel and continuous.","phasen":["planen"],"ebenen":["organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":150,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The 8 Steps for Leading Change – Kotter Inc.","url":"https://www.kotterinc.com/methodology/8-steps/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"John P. Kotter: Leading Change"}],"wann_passt":["A larger change project is coming up and the leadership team wonders what it has already done and what's missing – the 8 steps serve as a checklist for gap diagnosis.","In a retreat on strategy and change: the model structures the planning and makes concrete sequencing logic discussable.","After a failed change attempt: a retrospective analysis of which steps were skipped (often: urgency wasn't established, coalition wasn't formed)."],"wann_nicht":["In participatory, agile organizations: the model has a top-down bias and feels out of place in self-organized contexts.","As a rigid sequence: the steps overlap, and Kotter himself emphasizes this in his updated version.","For small teams or short projects: the model's overhead is disproportionate to the benefit."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which of the 8 steps have we skipped or only addressed superficially?\"","\"Who is in our guiding coalition – and who is missing whose absence would put us at risk?\"","\"Which quick win can we make visible within 90 days – concretely, not vaguely?\""],"beispiel":"Leadership retreat: the 8 steps as a checklist (handout). The group rates each step on a scale of 1–5: 'How well have we done this?' (10 min individually, 10 min discussion). Evaluation: Where are the biggest gaps? Follow-up question on step 1 (urgency): 'What would be a concrete moment where we make urgency tangible instead of just claiming it?' – turning model work into a planning impulse.","mini_form":"Step diagnosis in 15 minutes: focus on only the three most common gaps (urgency, coalition, quick wins) – the group assesses where they stand and names one concrete measure each.","anlass_typen":["strategie","kickoff","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–20 people; especially effective with a leadership team","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"theory-u-laloux","name":"Theory U / Laloux","feld":"B","kurz":"Lead profound change from the emerging future potential (presencing) – complemented by Laloux's images of evolutionary, self-organized organizations.","schritte":["Introduce the U-movement: interrupt downloading, perceive with an open mind, open heart, and open will.","Co-sensing: explore the system from multiple perspectives – interviews, empathy walks, stakeholder voices.","Presencing: silence/reflection at the \"bottom of the U\" – what wants to emerge here?","Crystallizing: distill vision and intention.","Prototyping: build small experiments that make the new tangible.","Institutionalize learning; through the Laloux lens ask: which practices of self-organization, wholeness, evolutionary purpose fit us?"],"zweck":"Lead profound change from the emerging future potential rather than from patterns of the past.","hinweise":"High level of abstraction – without concrete practices (interviews, prototypes) it remains vulnerable to being seen as esoteric; Laloux supplies the organizational images (teal/evolutionary), Theory U the process path – keep them cleanly separate.","phasen":["verstehen","oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["organisation","feld"],"modi":["selbstzugang","reflexion","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":360,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":40,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Theory U – Presencing Institute","url":"https://www.presencing.org/theoryu"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"C. Otto Scharmer: Theory U. Leading from the Future as It Emerges"}],"wann_passt":["A transformation process is meant to change not only structures but also thinking and perception patterns – Theory U gives the deeper change a frame and a language.","A retreat or multi-day gathering where something truly new is meant to emerge (not just optimizing what exists) – presencing at the bottom of the U needs time and space.","Laloux's organizational images are used to develop a shared vision: 'Which practices of wholeness and evolutionary purpose do we want to try?'"],"wann_nicht":["In results-driven settings with a tight time window: without genuine presencing phases, the model remains an abstract promise.","When the group has strong reservations about anything esoteric: without concrete grounding in practices (interviews, prototypes) it quickly tips into rejection.","As a single method within one meeting: it is a process frame for development initiatives spanning weeks or months."],"fokusfragen":["\"What are we currently loading into our perception – what are we systematically overlooking?\"","\"What wants to emerge here – not what we're planning, but what is announcing itself?\"","\"Which practices would concretely allow us to live wholeness in our work?\""],"beispiel":"A co-sensing round in a multi-day process: participants conduct empathy interviews with stakeholders (2 h), come back, sit in silence (5 min), then: 'What really touched you – what did you perceive that you didn't know before?' (presencing entry point). Follow-up question: 'What would this person need that we don't yet offer?' – turning perception into direction.","mini_form":"\"Interrupt downloading\" in 10 minutes: before a strategic conversation, ask the group: 'What ready-made judgments and patterns are we bringing in right now – what would we rather hear?' (write silently for 3 min, then share openly). Opens up the difference between downloading and genuine perceiving.","anlass_typen":["strategie","dialograum","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–40 people; as a full process, multi-day; individual elements also work in smaller groups","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"auftragsklaerung-kontrakt","name":"Contracting & Clarifying the Assignment","feld":"B","kurz":"Before starting work, clarify who wants what from whom – occasion, concern, and assignment together form the contract. The foundation of every consulting and facilitation process.","schritte":["Clarify the occasion: What led to this conversation, who initiated it?","Work out the concern: What is supposed to be different? How would you know it was worth it?","Clarify who's involved: Who wants what from whom here? With multiple clients: triangular contract.","Formulate the assignment: What exactly is my role, and what is not?","Agree on the frame: scope, confidentiality, boundaries.","Have the contract explicitly confirmed (mnemonic: occasion + concern + assignment = contract)."],"zweck":"Before starting work, clarify who wants what from whom – as the foundation of every consulting and facilitation process.","hinweise":"Most common mistake: working with the \"problem\" that was brought along instead of with the actual assignment; actively ask about hidden third-party assignments. Contracting is recurring, not a one-off.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","coaching","prozessbegleitung","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":10,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Systemischer Spickzettel – Auftragsklärung – istob-Zentrum","url":"https://istob-zentrum.de/systemischer-spickzettel-auftragsklaerung/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["At the start of every consulting or facilitation relationship: without a clarified contract you work on the wrong assignment – especially when several clients with different expectations are involved.","When a person or group arrives with a 'problem' that, after a bit of questioning, turns out to be a different concern – contracting questions help find the real topic.","After entering a longer process: contract revisions are normal and should happen explicitly, not implicitly."],"wann_nicht":["As a rigid ritual that bores the group – the clarification needs to flow smoothly into the first part of the conversation.","When it has already been clarified several times and the setting is clear – then a short 'Am I still positioned correctly for today?' is enough.","Without genuine willingness to also decline or reformulate the assignment – if the clarification is only pro forma, it loses its protective function."],"fokusfragen":["\"What led to us sitting together today – who initiated this conversation and why now?\"","\"How would you know in six months that this conversation / this process was worth it?\"","\"What do you want from me – what should my role be, and explicitly what not?\""],"beispiel":"Initial contact with a team: 'Who initiated this meeting?' (occasion). 'What should be different at the end compared to today?' (concern). 'What exactly do you expect from me – facilitation, consulting, decision-making?' (assignment). When it turns out that the manager and team members hold different assignments in mind: 'I'm hearing two different expectations – it's important to clarify this before we start on content. Would it be okay if we looked at this together first?' – making the triangular contract explicit.","mini_form":"Three-question clarification in 10 minutes: occasion / concern / assignment each as one direct question, note the answers briefly. Enough for a regular check-in or a 1:1 accompaniment.","anlass_typen":["coaching","kickoff","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–8 people ideal; with larger groups, clarify the contract with leadership beforehand","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","skeptisch","angespannt"]},{"id":"kundentypen-de-shazer","name":"Client Types (de Shazer)","feld":"B","kurz":"Recognize the client's relationship stance – visitor, complainant, or customer – and dose interventions accordingly.","schritte":["Listen for it during initial contact: Does the person see a problem? Do they see themselves as part of the solution?","Classify the type: visitor (sent, no concern of their own), complainant (sees the problem, but expects others to change), customer (own concern + willingness to change).","Choose the fitting response: appreciate visitors without giving them a task; give complainants observation tasks; work on solutions with customers.","Observe during the process how the type shifts, and adapt your approach."],"zweck":"Recognize the client's relationship stance and dose interventions accordingly.","hinweise":"The types are relationship patterns, not personality diagnoses – they can change within a single session; pitfall: overwhelming complainants with change tasks and creating resistance.","phasen":["ankommen","verstehen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["coaching","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":5,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Die drei Kliententypen in der Beratung nach Steve de Shazer – Consiglio","url":"https://consiglio.at/die-drei-kliententypen-in-der-beratung-nach-steve-de-shazer/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["In the early phase of consulting or coaching, when it's unclear whether the person really wants to change something or was just sent – the classification prevents working on solutions with complainants.","When an intervention falls flat: the question 'What client type is this person in right now?' often explains why homework isn't done or resistance arises.","In supervising your own consulting processes: 'Did I work with this person as a customer or as a complainant – and what would have fit?'"],"wann_nicht":["As a diagnostic label attached to the person – types are relationship patterns, not character traits.","When you rationalize your own impatience with the type ('She's just a complainant, nothing can be done') – then it's a defense, not a tool.","In group consulting with mixed types without differentiation – interventions must be dosed type-sensitively."],"fokusfragen":["\"Does the person see a concern of their own – or is the problem exclusively with others?\"","\"What would I need from this person so we can work on a solution together?\"","\"How can I appreciate visitors without simulating a task that doesn't exist?\""],"beispiel":"A manager is sent to coaching by the board. In the first session, she describes at length what her staff are doing wrong. Diagnosis: probably a complainant. Fitting intervention instead of solution work: 'What do you notice about yourself in these situations – what do you do in that moment?' (observation task, not a solution assignment). Follow-up question at the next session: 'What did you observe – what surprises you about it?' – opening the way toward customer mode.","mini_form":"Type check in 5 minutes (internal, for the consultant): before the next session, ask three questions: 'Does the person see a concern of their own? Have they signaled willingness to change? Who initiated the assignment?' This yields the type and the fitting intervention dose.","anlass_typen":["coaching","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–3 people; primarily an individual setting","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","belastet"]},{"id":"systemische-fragetechniken","name":"Systemic Questioning Techniques","feld":"B","kurz":"Use circular, scaling, and hypothetical questions to generate new perspectives, distinctions, and solution images within the system.","schritte":["Clarify the direction: What should the question open up – a change of perspective, distinctions, the future?","Choose the question type: circular, scaling, hypothetical, miracle question, paradoxical.","Ask the question and let the answer take effect – don't immediately follow up.","Deepen distinctions with follow-up questions: What would be different at 6 compared to 5?","Have the insights summarized."],"zweck":"Use questions to generate new perspectives, distinctions, and solution images within the system.","hinweise":"The effect comes from slowness and genuine interest – avoid a barrage of questions; circular questions take a bit of practice for those being asked, explain briefly if needed.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["coaching","prozessbegleitung","workshop","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Systemische Fragen: 8 Fragearten + 100 Beispiel-Fragen – Karrierebibel","url":"https://karrierebibel.de/systemisches-fragen/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["In a team clarification session dominated by loops of justification – circular questions interrupt the pattern by forcing a change of perspective without confronting anyone.","In a coaching session where the person is stuck in problem focus – scaling questions and miracle questions open the solution space without direct advice.","In a workshop where a group jumps to solutions too quickly – hypothetical and circular questions slow things down and deepen them."],"wann_nicht":["As a barrage of techniques in a short time – systemic questions need slowness and genuine interest, otherwise they feel manipulative.","In a group that knows the questioning techniques and perceives them as technique – then use them transparently or work more directly.","When quick fact clarification is needed – then use closed, direct questions."],"fokusfragen":["\"[Circular] If I asked your colleague what burdens her most about this situation – what would she say?\"","\"[Scaling] On a scale of 1–10: How satisfied are you with the collaboration? What would be different at a 7 compared to a 5?\"","\"[Hypothetical] Suppose the problem were solved overnight – what would be the first sign the next morning that something is different?\""],"beispiel":"Question classes and their distinctions: **Circular** – creates a change of perspective: 'Ms. A, if I asked your colleague B what costs him the most energy about the collaboration – what would he say?' Purpose: A has to construct B's perspective, which interrupts justification loops. Next: let B answer, make the difference productive: 'What surprises you about what B said?' **Scaling** – makes distinctions visible: 'On a scale of 1–10, how close was A's guess to your reality?' and 'What would need to change to move from 5 to 6?' Purpose: concrete steps instead of vague wishes. **Hypothetical/miracle question** – opens the solution space: 'Imagine you wake up tomorrow and the problem is gone – what is the first thing you notice, and who notices it second?' Purpose: target images without assigning blame. **Exception question** – dissolves problem fixation: 'Was there ever a time when it went better – what was different then?' Purpose: distill resources from exceptions. **Paradoxical question** – for stuck systems: 'What would you have to do to make the problem even worse?' Purpose: reversal makes the space for action visible. Important: stay silent after each question – the effect lies in the pause.","mini_form":"One circular question as a perspective opener: in any clarification conversation, throw in a single circular question – 'What would X say in this moment if they were here?' – and wait 30 seconds. No need for the full repertoire of questioning techniques.","anlass_typen":["coaching","konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech","teamtag"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–8 people ideal; in larger groups, use only individual questioning techniques selectively","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","neugierig"]},{"id":"systemische-schleife","name":"Systemic Loop","feld":"B","kurz":"An internal navigation aid for consultants: observe, form hypotheses, intervene, observe again – in a cycle.","schritte":["Gather information/observe: use all senses, without premature interpretation.","Form hypotheses: tentative thinking offers about the patterns and function of what was observed.","Plan the intervention: which impulse might fit based on the hypotheses?","Intervene: set the impulse.","Observe again: How does the system react? Confirm, discard, or refine hypotheses – run the loop again."],"zweck":"Structure the consultant's own thinking so interventions arise from observation rather than reflex.","hinweise":"More a stance than a scheme – can also be used as an internal navigation aid in the middle of facilitation; pitfall: clinging to your favorite hypothesis instead of testing it against new observations.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung","coaching","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":10,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Die Systemische Schleife als Navigationshilfe – Systemisches Netzwerk","url":"https://systemischesnetzwerk.de/die-systemische-schleife-als-navigationshilfe/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Roswita Königswieser, Alexander Exner: Systemische Intervention"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["As an internal navigation aid during facilitation or consulting: when you notice you're intervening out of reflex rather than observation – the loop slows down your own actions.","In supervising your own consulting processes: 'What did I observe, what hypotheses did I have, what did I intervene – and what did the system report back?'","In a training on consulting competence: the loop makes your own thought movement explicit and teachable."],"wann_nicht":["As an external scheme shown to the group – the loop belongs in the consultant's head, not on the flipchart.","In very fast crisis moments where there is no time for reflection – here experience and instinct take over.","As a substitute for hypothesis-building within the group – the loop is a self-tool, not a group format."],"fokusfragen":["\"What am I observing right now – without interpretation?\"","\"Which hypothesis best explains what I see – and which counter-hypothesis could also be true?\"","\"Which impulse would fit now – and what response from the system do I want to see, to test whether the hypothesis holds?\""],"beispiel":"In the middle of team facilitation, the atmosphere grows heavier without anyone saying anything. Loop: observation: 'Body language more closed, less eye contact.' Hypothesis: 'The topic touches something unspoken – maybe hierarchy.' Intervention: 'I notice the room feels a bit heavier – may I ask what's in the way right now?' Observe again: Does someone react with relief? Is the unspoken thing named? Test counter-hypothesis: 'Maybe it's simply exhaustion – then a break would be the right intervention.'","mini_form":"Internal stop-question in 1 minute: before setting an intervention, run through internally once: 'What am I observing? What is my hypothesis? Does my planned step fit it?' – these three seconds change the quality of the intervention.","anlass_typen":["coaching","konfliktklaerung","lernformat"],"typ":"haltung","gruppen_sweetspot":"Not a group format – an internal tool for the accompanying person","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","neugierig"]},{"id":"hypothesenbildung","name":"Hypothesis Formation (Milan School)","feld":"B","kurz":"Develop tentative circular explanatory offers about the function of behavior – usefulness counts, not truth.","schritte":["Gather information about the client system: genogram, concern, interactions.","Form circular hypotheses, alone or as a team: what function could the behavior serve for the system? Who benefits how from the status quo?","Mark hypotheses as tentative – usefulness counts, not truth.","Ask hypothesis-guided circular questions and observe reactions.","Revise or discard hypotheses; maintain neutrality/multipartiality."],"zweck":"Develop tentative explanatory offers about the function of behavior that preserve curiosity and neutrality.","hinweise":"Hypotheses belong in the toolbox, not unfiltered in the client system; danger of \"falling in love\" with your own hypothesis – deliberately form counter-hypotheses.","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["person","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","coaching"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":8,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Hypothetisieren – Lexikon des systemischen Arbeitens, Carl-Auer","url":"https://www.carl-auer.de/magazin/systemisches-lexikon/hypothetisieren"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Mara Selvini Palazzoli u. a.: Paradoxon und Gegenparadoxon"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["As preparation before a consulting session: form circular hypotheses from the information available about the system so far, preserving curiosity and neutrality.","In a team debrief after a difficult intervention: 'What could be the function of this behavior for the system?' – several hypotheses prevent premature judgments.","In a training on systemic consulting: hypothesis formation as an explicit exercise makes the difference between linear cause-and-effect and systemic functional logic tangible."],"wann_nicht":["When hypotheses are introduced unfiltered into the client system – they belong in the consultant's head or the consulting team.","When you fall in love with a favorite hypothesis – then actively form counter-hypotheses.","As an analysis tool searching for truth – hypotheses are thinking offers, not diagnoses."],"fokusfragen":["\"What could this behavior be useful for within the system – what would be missing if it disappeared?\"","\"Who benefits how from the status quo – who has an interest in it staying that way?\"","\"Which hypothesis is the boldest – what would we rather not think?\""],"beispiel":"Consulting team before a session: 'The team complains about the boss, but the boss complains about the team.' First hypothesis: 'The leader's leadership style unconsciously sustains the complaining because it secures her central role.' Counter-hypothesis: 'The team signals through complaining that it wants to take on more responsibility, but doesn't dare to.' Neutrality check: 'Which hypothesis do I prefer – and why?' Then ask hypothesis-guided: 'What happens in your team when the boss isn't there?' (circular) – to test which hypothesis has more explanatory power.","mini_form":"Three-hypothesis exercise in 10 minutes (in a consultant tandem): quickly form three hypotheses about a client case – first: obvious, second: systemic (function), third: bold (what we'd rather not think). Then formulate one question for each.","anlass_typen":["coaching","konfliktklaerung","lernformat"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–4 people (consulting team); not a group format with clients","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"neun-felder-puma","name":"9-Field Model & PUMA","feld":"B","kurz":"Sharpen the concern and steer where a conversation stands between problem, resource, and solution space across three time perspectives.","schritte":["Set up the matrix: three time perspectives (past, present, future) × three spaces (problem, resource, solution/wish).","Start with the present-problem field: have the concern described concretely.","Systematically ask through the fields: \"When was it better before?\" (resource/past), \"What should be there instead?\" (solution/future).","Mark the location: which field is the person currently moving in?","Choose a direction of movement: deliberately shift into resource and solution fields.","Secure insights and the next step."],"zweck":"Sharpen the concern and steer where a conversation stands between problem, resource, and solution space.","hinweise":"Quickly feels technical if you \"work through\" the fields – better used as an internal map, dosing the shifts; combines well with scaling questions.","phasen":["ankommen","verstehen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["coaching","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":6,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Das 9-Felder-Modell nach Prof. Joseph Rieforth – mediator.sweti.de","url":"https://mediator.sweti.de/post/9-felder-modell/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"}],"wann_passt":["In a coaching session where the person is circling in problem focus – the matrix makes visible which field the conversation is stuck in and enables a deliberate shift into resource or solution fields.","With concerns that have a temporal dimension ('It's always been like this') – resources from the past ('When did it go better?') become directly addressable through the matrix.","As a facilitation compass in a clarification conversation: the facilitator can internally check 'Which field are we in?' and steer deliberately."],"wann_nicht":["As a form that is visibly filled out – that makes the conversation technical and the client feels analyzed.","With people who don't yet have enough trust: shifting too early into solution fields feels like being brushed off.","In group formats without individual accompaniment – the model is primarily for 1:1 clarification conversations."],"fokusfragen":["\"[Present/problem] What exactly is the problem – what concretely happens when it occurs?\"","\"[Past/resource] Was there ever a time when this was better – what was different back then?\"","\"[Future/solution] What should be there instead – what would your everyday life look like once the problem is gone?\""],"beispiel":"Coaching conversation: the person has been describing the problem for 10 minutes (present/problem field). Deliberate field shift: 'I notice we're deep in the problem. May I briefly shift perspective? – Was there ever a phase when what you're describing was better?' (past/resource). The person names an exception. Follow-up question: 'What did you do back then – what was different about the situation or about you?' (activating resources). Then future: 'What would be the first sign you'd notice that things are moving in that direction again?' – combine with scaling: 'And on a scale of 1–10, where would you be then?'","mini_form":"Field-shift question in 3 minutes: a single targeted question that shifts from the problem field into resources or solution – without introducing the whole model. Sufficient in many conversations.","anlass_typen":["coaching","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–3 people; primarily an individual setting","stimmung_geeignet":["belastet","angespannt","muede"]},{"id":"tuckman","name":"Tuckman (Team Phases)","feld":"C","kurz":"Interpret team dynamics as normal developmental phases – forming, storming, norming, performing, adjourning – and choose fitting support.","schritte":["Introduce the model: Forming – Storming – Norming – Performing – Adjourning.","Let the team locate itself, e.g. via dot-voting or a physical lineup: Where are we?","Discuss differences in assessment – they are themselves diagnostic material.","Derive phase-typical needs: Forming needs orientation, Storming needs conflict clarification, Norming needs agreements, Performing needs freedom.","Agree on 1–2 concrete measures for the current phase."],"zweck":"Interpret team dynamics as normal developmental phases and choose fitting support for each phase.","hinweise":"In reality, phases run cyclically and overlapping, not linearly – introduce the model as a map, not a schedule; the normalization of storming is what provides the most relief.","phasen":["verstehen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Teamentwicklung nach Tuckman – 5 Phasen im Überblick – mychange.solutions","url":"https://mychange.solutions/toolbox/teamwork/phasen-der-teamentwicklung"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Working with Teams and Groups"}],"wann_passt":["A new team after 4–8 weeks of working together, when first frictions arise and members interpret it as personal failure – the model normalizes storming as an unavoidable phase.","A team retreat after a change in leadership or a reorg: the team has to relocate itself; Tuckman provides language for the collective disorientation (relapse into forming).","A training context (OD, leadership, team coaching) when basics of group development are to be conveyed – the model is well-known enough to immediately spark follow-up conversations."],"wann_nicht":["In an acute conflict as a tranquilizer – 'you're just in storming' comes across as condescending when the group has a genuine need for clarification right now.","As the sole diagnosis in established teams: mature teams no longer go through linear phases, the model doesn't fit then and undermines itself.","When hierarchical gaps in the room prevent honest self-location – the location exercise needs psychological safety."],"fokusfragen":["\"If you locate yourselves on the curve from Forming to Performing – where do you stand as a team today, and where do you stand individually?\" (the difference between individual and group assessment is often more fruitful than the assessment itself)","\"What do you need as a team in this phase from leadership, from structure, from each other?\" (concretize the phase-specific need)","\"Has there already been a relapse into an earlier phase in your team's history – what triggered it, and what helped?\""],"mini_form":"A lineup along an imaginary Forming-to-Performing line in the room (5 min): everyone positions themselves, 2–3 people say a sentence about it. Enough as a conversation opener without introducing the model.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","retro","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"5–15 people ideal; with larger groups, evaluate self-location in small groups","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","muede","neugierig"]},{"id":"eisbergmodell","name":"Iceberg Model","feld":"C","kurz":"Make visible that hidden relationship and emotional dynamics (~80%) drive the visible behavior on the content level.","schritte":["Introduce the model: ~20% visible content level, ~80% hidden relationship and emotional level.","Have the current situation/conflict described at the content level.","Look below the waterline: which feelings, needs, relationship experiences are at play? (individual reflection or paired conversation)","Share insights, as far as the group can carry it.","Derive: what does the relationship level need so the content level can work again?"],"zweck":"Make visible that hidden relationship and emotional dynamics drive the visible behavior.","hinweise":"The model invites self-disclosure – emphasize voluntariness and avoid sliding into depth psychology; the 80/20 figures are a rule of thumb, not a research finding.","phasen":["verstehen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["klaerung","konflikt"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Das Eisbergmodell: Beispiele für sichtbare + unsichtbare Kommunikation – projekte-leicht-gemacht.de","url":"https://projekte-leicht-gemacht.de/blog/softskills/kommunikation/das-eisbergmodell/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Working with Teams and Groups"}],"wann_passt":["When a team keeps arguing about the same content-level issue without resolving it – the model makes it discussable that the energy comes from the relationship level, not the content itself.","Training on communication or conflict: the model is low-threshold enough for groups unfamiliar with methods and produces immediate recognition effects from everyday life.","Before a clarification conversation in a dyad or small group: introduced as a frame, it gives those involved language for what they couldn't say before."],"wann_nicht":["When the group hasn't yet built basic trust – the model invites self-disclosure, which isn't safe among strangers or in a hierarchical constellation.","As a therapeutic deep-diving device: the model shows the water's surface, it is not an invitation to slide into psychodynamics.","In time-critical sessions with a concrete need for decisions – it slows down and opens up, which is sometimes counterproductive."],"fokusfragen":["\"What does everyone in the room see – and what do you suspect is resonating beneath the surface without being said?\" (name the content level, then open the relationship level)","\"If you apply the iceberg model to our current situation: What lies below the waterline that is blocking the content level?\" (transfer to the concrete context)","\"What would the relationship level need so the content level can flow again?\""],"mini_form":"Silent individual reflection (3 min): everyone notes, for a current tension, what's visible above and what's suspected below – then exchange in pairs. No need to speak in plenary.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"2–15 people; from 16 on, only usable as a teaching model, not for group diagnosis","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","neugierig"]},{"id":"rangdynamik-schindler","name":"Rank Dynamics (Schindler)","feld":"C","kurz":"Make informal leadership and resistance roles in groups (alpha, beta, gamma, omega) visible and discussable.","schritte":["Introduce the four positions: alpha (leads), beta (expertise, alongside), gamma (carries along), omega (counter-position, critique).","Emphasize: positions are situational, not personality traits.","Have the group reflect: who takes which position in which situations? (individual reflection, then exchange)","Acknowledge omega: what important information is contained in the resistance?","Foster flexibility: what would it take for positions to be able to shift?","Make agreements on how to handle the roles."],"zweck":"Make informal leadership and resistance roles in groups visible and discussable.","hinweise":"Delicate when people are publicly labeled as \"omega\" – work with anonymized or situational examples; frame the omega position as a function for the group, not as a problem case.","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":16,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Rangdynamik (Schindler) – wirtrainieren.de","url":"https://wirtrainieren.de/werkzeugkoffer/rangdynamik-schindler/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Working with Teams and Groups"}],"wann_passt":["A team retreat where the same person always dominates all decisions, or silent resistance paralyzes the work – rank dynamics gives language for these patterns without pathologizing individuals.","Training for leaders or OD practitioners: the model is well-known in these circles and immediately sparks transfer discussions about one's own organization.","Supervising a group that has just experienced an omega person (someone who left or was marginalized) – the model helps acknowledge the function of this position instead of dismissing it."],"wann_nicht":["In the group itself, when individuals could be publicly identified as 'the omega' – that creates stigmatization instead of reflection.","As an explanatory model for personal conflicts: rank dynamics explains structural patterns, not individual motivations.","In front of a plenary without prior knowledge of group dynamics – the term 'omega' is easily misunderstood."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which positions do you take in this group – and which would you like to take if the group allowed it?\" (self-reflection without public labeling)","\"What does the resistance in our group signal to us – what important information is contained in the omega?\" (reframe the omega function)","\"When have your positions in the group shifted – what triggered that?\""],"mini_form":"Individual writing (5 min): 'Which position do I take situationally, which would I prefer?' Then exchange in pairs – no plenary speaking. Enough for initial awareness without group exposure.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"6–14 people ideal; below 4 the diversity of roles collapses","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"teamrollen-belbin","name":"Team Roles (Belbin)","feld":"C","kurz":"Make functional role diversity in the team visible – nine roles in the clusters thinking, doing, relating – and balance out gaps.","schritte":["Introduce the nine Belbin roles (e.g. Plant, Coordinator, Shaper, Teamworker, Completer Finisher) in the clusters thinking/doing/relating.","Self-assessment: which 2–3 roles do I prefer to fill? (questionnaire or card selection)","Add outside perspective: brief feedback from the team.","Lay out the team profile: which roles are over-, which under-represented?","Derive consequences: task allocation, deliberate role-taking, tolerance for \"allowable weaknesses\".","Record agreements."],"zweck":"Make functional role diversity in the team visible and balance out gaps or overlaps.","hinweise":"Roles are behavioral preferences, not typology boxes – choose language carefully (\"prefers\", \"situationally\"); the official Belbin test is paid, for workshops the card-selection variant is often enough.","phasen":["verstehen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":150,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The Nine Belbin Team Roles – belbin.com","url":"https://www.belbin.com/about/belbin-team-roles"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"R. Meredith Belbin: Management Teams. Why They Succeed or Fail"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Working with Teams and Groups"}],"wann_passt":["A new project team at the start of a longer collaboration (kickoff or first team day): make roles visible before gaps become a problem.","A team with recurring friction over division of labor – Belbin makes it discussable that all roles are needed and 'allowable weaknesses' are part of it.","Leadership training with a focus on team composition: the model is well known in German-speaking contexts, transfer conversations arise easily."],"wann_nicht":["As a justification for rigid task allocation – roles are preferences, not boxes; the model becomes harmful when it restricts flexibility.","When no official Belbin test is available and self-assessment turns into identity statements: 'I am a Plant' is different from 'I'm currently acting like a Plant'.","In teams under strong performance pressure with little time for reflection – the process needs leisure and willingness for self-feedback."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which roles are over-represented in our team – and which are missing or genuinely enjoyed by no one?\" (read the team profile)","\"Where have you recently filled a role that doesn't match your preference – what did it cost, what did it bring?\" (discuss allowable weaknesses)","\"Which role would you like to bring in more strongly if the context allowed it?\""],"mini_form":"Card selection (10 min): everyone chooses their top-2 roles from cards without a questionnaire, lays them out, brief partner interview – 'does that match what you perceive in me?' Quick diagnosis without test overhead.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–12 people; above 15 the evaluation becomes unwieldy","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"prozesskurven","name":"Process Curves","feld":"C","kurz":"Make the energetic course of a group process visible as a curve and de-dramatize dips as normal working phases.","schritte":["Introduce the concept: group and seminar energy runs in curves – highs, lows, and dips are part of it.","Have a shared curve drawn: the course of energy/mood over the process so far (on a wall or whiteboard).","Have individuals draw in their personal curve.","Discuss notable points: where were the dips, what preceded them?","Normalize: interpret lows as necessary working phases, not as failure.","Derive what the group needs for the next phase."],"zweck":"Make the energetic course of a group process visible and de-dramatize dips as a normal phase.","hinweise":"Works best right in the middle of a low point – apply it exactly then; not a single canonical model but a practical tool of group dynamics (related: phase models of group development).","phasen":["vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["reflexion","energie"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","klausur","fortbildung","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["schriftlich","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["reflexion","uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Wissensbaustein Gruppendynamik – Deutsches Institut für Erwachsenenbildung (DIE)","url":"https://www.die-bonn.de/wb/2015-gruppendynamik-01.pdf"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Worksheet: Process Curves"}],"wann_passt":["In the middle of an energy low during a multi-day format or a training series: the model normalizes the low and makes it discussable together instead of ignoring it.","After a difficult session phase (intense conflict, tough decision): drawing the curve together gives the exhaustion a place and opens up what the group needs now.","As a reflection tool in supervision or intervision groups that share a longer joint process."],"wann_nicht":["As an entry point into a new process – the curve needs shared history, otherwise it stays abstract.","When the mood is so good that there is no dip – then the model feels contrived.","When the group is under heavy time pressure and has no time for reflection."],"fokusfragen":["\"Draw your personal energy curve over today – and note: what was the low point, what triggered it?\" (diagnosing the pattern)","\"If we compare our curves: where are they similar, where different – what does that say about our shared process?\" (reading the collective pattern)","\"What do you need – individually and as a group – to draw energy again out of the current low?\""],"mini_form":"Quick version (5 min): everyone draws just the curve (without labels), shows it briefly, says one word about it. No plenary conversation – just making visible that everyone knows it.","anlass_typen":["retro","teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–20 people; above 25 only with small-group evaluation","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","belastet","angespannt"]},{"id":"faktoren-teamarbeit","name":"Factors of Successful Teamwork","feld":"C","kurz":"Diagnose team quality using the five factors from Google's Project Aristotle – psychological safety, dependability, structure & clarity, meaning, impact.","schritte":["Introduce the five factors from Google's Project Aristotle: psychological safety, dependability, structure & clarity, meaning, impact.","Team self-assessment: rate each factor on a scale of 1–10 (anonymous or open).","Visualize results and discuss differences.","Dig deeper into the weakest factor: What do we base that on? Gather concrete situations.","Agree on 2–3 improvement experiments.","Set a follow-up date to review."],"zweck":"Diagnose team quality using evidence-based factors and improve it in a targeted way.","hinweise":"According to the study, psychological safety is the most important factor – the assessment itself already requires safety, so consider starting anonymously; the factors concern the \"how\" of collaboration, not team composition.","phasen":["verstehen","verstetigen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Guide: Understand team effectiveness – Google re:Work","url":"https://rework.withgoogle.com/intl/en/guides/understand-team-effectiveness"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Amy C. Edmondson: The Fearless Organization"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Working with Teams and Groups"}],"wann_passt":["A team with underlying dissatisfaction but no concrete, nameable conflict: the five factors give structure to the diagnosis and make the diffuse measurable.","A team day after an exhausting year – as a self-diagnosis with concrete agreements afterward; the evidence-based source (Google Project Aristotle) gives the diagnosis weight.","A new leader who wants to understand the team: the factor assessment quickly gives an honest picture if collected anonymously."],"wann_nicht":["When the team doesn't trust the leader – anonymous assessment is then necessary, but the result still won't be shared honestly.","As a one-off action without follow-up: the effect lies in the improvement experiments and the follow-up check, not in the measurement itself.","In a crisis situation that requires immediate action – the model is diagnosis, not intervention."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which of the five factors feels weakest in your team – and what do you base that on concretely?\" (from abstract to concrete)","\"What would change if psychological safety in your team rose by one point – what could you say then that you can't say now?\" (make impact tangible)","\"What is a small experiment you could try in the next two weeks to strengthen the weakest factor?\""],"mini_form":"Quick diagnosis (10 min): everyone rates the five factors on slips of paper 1–5, slips are collected, the facilitator reads out the averages. Only dig deeper together into the weakest factor.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","retro","kickoff"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–15 people ideal; larger teams need anonymous data collection","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"open-space","name":"Open Space","feld":"C","kurz":"Large-group format in which participants set their own agenda – with marketplace, the Law of Two Feet, and self-organized sessions.","schritte":["Formulate an inviting guiding question and set up the circle.","Opening: explain the principles and the \"Law of Two Feet\"; open the marketplace.","Participants offer sessions: whoever has a concern writes it up and picks a time/room.","Session rounds run self-organized; hosts document the results.","News wall/harvest: collect results so everyone can see them.","Closing circle: resonances and next steps."],"zweck":"Enable large groups to set their own agenda and work on what matters to them.","hinweise":"Stands or falls with a genuine, open guiding question and the facilitators' willingness to let go of control; needs at least half a day, otherwise it stays topic speed-dating. Doable online with breakouts, though the marketplace needs good tooling.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","verbindung","energie"],"formate":["grossgruppe","klausur"],"dauer_min":180,"dauer_max":480,"gruppe_min":15,"gruppe_max":500,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"What is Open Space Technology? – OpenSpaceWorld","url":"https://openspaceworld.org/wp2/what-is/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Harrison Owen: Open Space Technology. A User's Guide"}],"wann_passt":["An organization of 30–200 people where many different issues are burning at once and no leadership level knows what really matters – Open Space lets the topics with real energy emerge.","A strategy day or annual congress where the usual plenary presentations kill the energy: Open Space activates everyone and produces more real conversations in half a day than three conference days with fixed agendas.","A network gathering without a shared mandate but with a shared concern – the Law of Two Feet ensures only the conversations that truly matter get held."],"wann_nicht":["When leadership has already set the topics and is only seeking agreement – a genuinely open guiding question is a basic condition; without it, Open Space becomes an alibi process and breeds cynicism.","Under 15 people: the mechanism of parallel sessions collapses, and a direct conversation is more honest.","When the outcome must be minuted and binding – Open Space produces conversations and impulses, but no binding decisions without an explicit harvest structure.","As a full online substitute: physical simultaneity and the Law of Two Feet can only partially be rebuilt digitally; quality drops noticeably."],"fokusfragen":["\"What is the most pressing topic you want to bring in – one you couldn't discuss anywhere else?\" (marketplace opening)","\"What are you taking away from your sessions – and what concrete next step do you want to hold onto?\" (harvest after the sessions)"],"mini_form":"Topic marketplace without sessions (20 min): everyone writes their burning questions on cards, clusters them together, votes with dots – without any follow-up session rounds. Shows what's moving the group without the full time investment.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","strategie","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"30–150 ideal; under 20 not worthwhile, over 200 needs a lot of room logistics","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"world-cafe","name":"World Café","feld":"C","kurz":"Connect the perspectives of many people through rotating table conversations and surface collective patterns.","schritte":["Create a café atmosphere: tables of 4–5 people, paper tablecloths, pens.","Introduce context and etiquette: listen, connect ideas, doodling welcome.","Round 1: conversation on the first question (~20 min).","Switch: the host stays, everyone else redistributes; 2–3 more rounds with questions that build on each other.","Hosts link the threads of conversation.","Harvest in plenary: gather patterns and insights."],"zweck":"Connect the perspectives of many people through rotating table conversations and surface collective patterns.","hinweise":"Quality depends almost entirely on the strength of the questions – invest time in \"questions that matter\"; plan for a harvest, otherwise the insights evaporate. Works well online via breakouts plus a shared board.","phasen":["oeffnen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":12,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"World Café Method – The World Café","url":"https://theworldcafe.com/key-concepts-resources/world-cafe-method/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Juanita Brown, David Isaacs: The World Café. Shaping Our Futures Through Conversations That Matter"}],"wann_passt":["A strategy or development process where 3–4 different questions need to be worked on at once and cross-pollination between perspectives is desired – the rotating tables let ideas grow across conversation groups.","A large group (20–100) where not everyone can speak at once but all voices should feed into the results – World Café is the format when Fishbowl is too selective and Open Space too unstructured.","A network kick-off with participants from different organizations who barely know each other: the relaxed café atmosphere and forced rotation mix better than any icebreaker."],"wann_nicht":["When a single, deep question needs to be worked on – World Café needs multiple questions; for one question, Fishbowl or 1-2-4-All works better.","Under 12 people: the rotation makes no sense if only 2–3 tables form.","When there are no genuine \"questions that matter\" – shallow questions produce shallow conversations, and the method won't fix that.","As a purely networking format without a harvest step: without a structured harvest, the insights evaporate."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's the one insight from this table conversation that you absolutely need to carry to the next table?\" (host briefing)","\"What patterns keep showing up, no matter which table you sat at?\" (harvest opening in plenary)"],"mini_form":"Single-table variant with one question and two rounds (30 min, from 8 people): round 1 (12 min) everyone at the table, then half switch to a new table, host summarizes. Enough for one intensive question without table infrastructure.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","strategie","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"16–80 ideal; under 12 not worthwhile","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"appreciative-inquiry","name":"Appreciative Inquiry","feld":"C","kurz":"Develop change from a system's strengths and best experiences – in the 4-D cycle Discovery, Dream, Design, Destiny.","schritte":["Choose an affirmative topic: what the organization wants more of.","Discovery: paired interviews about peak experiences – \"Tell me about a moment when things really went well.\"","Dream: develop a vivid future image from those strengths.","Design: formulate statements about how the organization should be (provocative propositions).","Destiny: agree on initiatives and commitments for implementation."],"zweck":"Develop change from a system's strengths and best experiences, rather than from problem analysis.","hinweise":"Focusing on strengths means acknowledging and reframing problems – otherwise it can feel like imposed optimism; the Discovery interview is the heart of the method and works as a stand-alone element too.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen","planen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["verbindung","energie","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","grossgruppe","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":480,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":300,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"4D Appreciative Inquiry Model – AI Commons","url":"https://aicommons.champlain.edu/educational-material/4d-appreciative-inquiry-model/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"David Cooperrider, Diana Whitney: Appreciative Inquiry. A Positive Revolution in Change"}],"wann_passt":["An organization that needs a fresh start after a difficult year (crisis, restructuring, losses) and is looking for energy and direction rather than more problem analysis – AI starts from what already works.","A strategy workshop where the group is stuck in deficit thinking and the facilitator needs a focus shift: the Discovery interview alone as an opener changes the tone of the whole day.","A large group (50–300) with heterogeneous stakeholders who need to develop a shared future image – the 4-D cycle works at any size and can run over one day or several weeks."],"wann_nicht":["When real structural problems (lack of resources, leadership misconduct, systematic discrimination) get made invisible by a strengths focus – AI can come across as imposed optimism and destroy trust.","As a substitute for necessary conflict clarification – AI works alongside conflicts, not through them.","When the group has already worked with AI approaches several times and knows the patterns – then it needs variation."],"fokusfragen":["\"Tell me about a moment when our collaboration or project really went well – what was different than usual, who was involved, what did you do?\" (Discovery interview opener)","\"If this pattern – what was present in your best moment – became the norm: how would your work feel then?\" (Dream transition)","\"What's the smallest first step you could take right now to make this future image a bit more real?\" (Destiny closing)"],"beispiel":"Discovery interview in a team retreat: 'Tell me about a moment in our collaboration when you thought: this is exactly how teamwork should be. What happened, who was involved and how, what did you specifically do?' – Purpose: the memory activates existing resources and creates a vocabulary for the conditions of success. Next: the interview partner retells the story in a group of four, the group notes recurring themes. Follow-up question: 'What from the stories you heard could be applied right away?'","mini_form":"Discovery interview in pairs (10 min): one question, 5 min per direction. On its own it works as an energy booster and gesture of trust – without Dream/Design/Destiny. Works as an opener for any session.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","strategie","teamtag","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–150 ideal; scalable through small groups","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"future-search","name":"Future Search","feld":"C","kurz":"Bring all stakeholders of a system to a shared future image and common action on common ground – a large-scale format over several days.","schritte":["Invite the \"whole system\": people with authority, resources, expertise, information, and those affected.","Past: build and evaluate a shared timeline of the past.","Present: map external trends as a mind map, reflect on pride/regret.","Future: stakeholder groups design ideal future scenarios.","Common Ground: identify shared foundations – only what everyone truly stands behind.","Action: plan measures and commitments on the common ground."],"zweck":"Bring all stakeholders of a system to a shared future image and common action on common ground.","hinweise":"Conflicts are treated as information, not worked through – make that transparent beforehand; the original format needs about 20 hours over 3 days, and shortened variants lose considerable depth.","phasen":["oeffnen","planen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["verbindung","klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["grossgruppe","klausur"],"dauer_min":480,"dauer_max":1200,"gruppe_min":40,"gruppe_max":80,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Methodology – Future Search Network","url":"https://futuresearch.net/about/methodology/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marvin Weisbord, Sandra Janoff: Future Search. An Action Guide to Finding Common Ground"}],"wann_passt":["A systemic turning point: an organization or network must clarify a fundamental question where all relevant stakeholders (those affected, decision-makers, expertise, resources) need to be at one table – Future Search is the only format that genuinely invites the \"whole system\".","When a topic has been discussed in dead ends for years and new perspectives need to come in before decisions are made – the timeline work creates a shared historical memory as a foundation.","Urban development, education reform, network strategy: contexts where 40–80 people can and may invest three days – and leadership is ready to actually implement the common ground."],"wann_nicht":["When the actual decision has already been made and the format is only meant to provide legitimacy – Future Search recognizes this, and the resulting frustration is massive.","Without binding implementation commitments from leadership: the format raises hope; if nothing happens afterward, the damage to trust is greater than before.","When less than 2.5 days are available: the timeline work and stakeholder-group phase need their time, and shortcuts undermine the impact.","For internal team issues: the effort is disproportionate; World Café or Open Space are enough."],"fokusfragen":["\"What are the most important moments in our shared history – pride and regret – that brought us here?\" (timeline opening)","\"What is the common ground – what everyone can truly stand behind, without a compromise that satisfies no one?\" (common ground search, what distinguishes Future Search from consensus formats)"],"mini_form":"Stakeholder perspectives round (20 min): name different stakeholder positions, have one person speak from each perspective – without voting and without the full Future Search format. Shows system complexity without a 3-day investment.","anlass_typen":["strategie","beteiligung","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"40–80 ideal; under 30 the stakeholder mix isn't credible","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"liberating-structures","name":"Liberating Structures","feld":"C","kurz":"33 precise micro-structures (e.g. 1-2-4-All, TRIZ, Troika Consulting) that include all voices and replace conventional meeting patterns.","schritte":["Clarify the purpose of the sequence: what should the group achieve – open up, analyze, decide?","Choose the fitting micro-structures from the 33, e.g. 1-2-4-All, TRIZ, Troika Consulting, 25/10 Crowd Sourcing.","Guide the structure exactly: invitation, room setup, participation distribution, time boxes.","Run it – the structure carries itself, the facilitator holds back.","Chain structures (\"strings\") for longer sessions.","Debrief briefly: what did we see?"],"zweck":"Include all voices with precise micro-structures and replace conventional meeting patterns.","hinweise":"The strength lies in following the micro-rules exactly – \"roughly like this\" dilutes the effect; the easiest entry point is 1-2-4-All or Impromptu Networking.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","verbindung","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","grossgruppe","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern","einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Liberating Structures – Including and Unleashing Everyone","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Henri Lipmanowicz, Keith McCandless: The Surprising Power of Liberating Structures"}],"wann_passt":["A facilitator who wants to break up repetitive meeting patterns without much explanation – individual LS like Impromptu Networking or 1-2-4-All can be introduced in 5 minutes and used right away.","A training context (OD, facilitation, leadership) where the repertoire of participation formats should be expanded – LS as a collection of 33 clearly coded micro-structures is the best-known open-source method system.","A longer workshop sequence where several phases (opening, deepening, deciding) need to be modeled – LS \"strings\" enable curated sequences instead of random programs."],"wann_nicht":["When only a single structure is used half-heartedly – the strength lies in following the micro-rules exactly and in sequencing; \"roughly like 1-2-4-All\" dilutes the effect.","With groups suffering from severe method fatigue who expect \"another workshop game\" – better to use the structure without labeling it.","As a substitute for content preparation: LS structure participation but don't solve content problems."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which of the 33 structures fits this moment – opening up, clarifying, or deciding?\" (meta-question for the facilitation team)","\"What's the one invitation question for this structure – precise enough that everyone knows what to talk about?\""],"mini_form":"Impromptu Networking as an LS opener (15 min): three 4-minute conversations on a double question – connects the whole group's network and immediately makes the effect of LS tangible. The best entry point into LS overall.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","lernformat","regeltermin"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–200; varies greatly depending on the specific structure chosen","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","neugierig","muede","frisch"]},{"id":"fishbowl","name":"Fishbowl","feld":"C","kurz":"Inner and outer circle: a focused, in-depth discussion in large groups that anyone can join via the empty chair.","schritte":["Set up an inner circle (4–6 chairs) and outer circle; leave one chair in the inner circle empty.","Introduce the topic and rules: only the inner circle speaks, the outer circle actively listens.","The starting line-up discusses; anyone from the outer circle who wants to contribute takes the empty chair.","When the empty chair is taken, one person voluntarily leaves the inner circle.","Facilitation watches speaking time and topic focus.","Closing: capture observations from the outer circle and key essences."],"zweck":"Hold a focused, in-depth discussion in large groups that everyone can, in principle, join.","hinweise":"The empty chair is the mechanism that makes it work – without it, it becomes a panel; quiet groups may need a warmed-up starting line-up. Only conditionally effective as a rebuilt online variant.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","grossgruppe","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":12,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Fishbowl Diskussion – Methodenkartei Uni Oldenburg","url":"https://www.methodenkartei.uni-oldenburg.de/methode/fishbowl-diskussion/"}],"wann_passt":["A large group (20–100) where a controversial topic with different perspectives needs an in-depth discussion without everyone talking at once – the inner circle focuses the conversation, the outer circle really listens.","When a group consists of frequent talkers who dominate speaking time in plenary – the empty chair forces selection and creates real access for more reserved voices.","A learning format where a topic should be viewed from different roles (e.g. leaders vs. staff, different disciplines) – the composition of the inner circle makes the perspectives visible."],"wann_nicht":["When the group has too little trust to volunteer for the inner circle – without enough \"volunteers\" for the empty chair, Fishbowl tips into a panel with a disengaged outer circle.","Online: the spatial dynamic (empty chair, sitting in a circle, outer-circle observation) is hard to reproduce digitally; digital variants lose the central mechanism.","For operational decisions – Fishbowl deepens and clarifies, but doesn't make decisions."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's the most important thing you're taking from the inner-circle conversation – and what do you as the outer circle still want to add?\" (transition to closing)","\"What perspective is still missing from the inner circle?\" (empty-chair invitation, when the outer circle is hesitant)"],"mini_form":"Fishbowl with a fixed inner circle (no empty chair, 20 min): 4 people with different perspectives discuss, outer circle observes with an observation task. Easier to facilitate but less participatory.","anlass_typen":["dialograum","beteiligung","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"12–60 ideal; under 12 a direct discussion works better","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"barcamp","name":"Barcamp/Unconference","feld":"C","kurz":"Participants design the conference program themselves in the morning and share knowledge as equals – with a session board and the Law of Two Feet.","schritte":["Open with the frame and rules: anyone can offer sessions, Law of Two Feet.","Short round of introductions, e.g. three hashtags per person.","Session planning: participants pitch topics, interest is checked by show of hands, a session board with times and rooms emerges.","Session rounds of ~45 min run self-organized: talk, discussion, workshop.","Document each session (pad/Etherpad/photos).","Closing round with feedback."],"zweck":"Participants design the conference program themselves and share knowledge as equals.","hinweise":"First-time participants need encouragement to offer sessions – emphasize \"one question is enough for a session\"; facilitate session planning tightly, it's the critical moment. Well-tested digitally.","phasen":["oeffnen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["verbindung","klaerung","energie"],"formate":["grossgruppe","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":240,"dauer_max":480,"gruppe_min":20,"gruppe_max":300,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Barcamp planen und durchführen – wb-web","url":"https://wb-web.de/material/interaktion/barcamp-planen-und-durchfuehren.html"}],"wann_passt":["A specialist community or network with a shared knowledge horizon that wants to share knowledge as equals – Barcamp only works if participants genuinely have topics they want to bring.","An association, NGO, or community of practice with an annual gathering: Barcamp is the most convincing argument against frontal conferences, because participants choose what to talk about themselves.","A training format with practitioners who see their own experience as equal to expert knowledge – the format makes the implicit democratization of knowledge explicit."],"wann_nicht":["When participants have no topics of their own – Barcamp with forced sessions is a worse conference.","With groups who have no experience with self-organization and expect clear leadership – morning session planning needs encouragement and a safe facilitation setting.","When binding decisions are needed – Barcamp produces knowledge and connections, but no decisions."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's the question or topic you absolutely want to talk about today – whether you're an expert or just have questions?\" (session-planning invitation)","\"What are you taking from this session – and who else do you want to connect with because of it?\" (session closing)"],"mini_form":"Mini-Barcamp (90 min, 20–40 people): only 2 session rounds with 3–4 parallel rooms. Enough for a first Barcamp experience when a full day isn't possible.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","lernformat","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"25–150 ideal; under 20 parallelization barely makes sense","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"buergerrat-planungszelle","name":"Citizens' Assembly/Planning Cell","feld":"C","kurz":"Randomly selected citizens deliberate on a political question with informed input and give recommendations as a citizens' report.","schritte":["Clarify the mandate and question with the commissioning body (municipality, state), and secure a commitment to implement.","Recruit participants through random selection (drawing lots), attending to diversity.","Information phase: experts and interest groups give balanced input.","Deliberation phase: facilitated small groups (~5 people each) weigh options, plenary consolidates.","Formulate and prioritize recommendations.","Hand over the citizens' report; the commissioning body publicly responds on implementation."],"zweck":"Randomly selected citizens deliberate on a political question with informed input and give recommendations.","hinweise":"Credibility rests on random selection, balanced input, and a binding response from policymakers – without the latter, frustration looms; the original format takes 2–4 days and can only be simulated in a single session.","phasen":["oeffnen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["feld"],"modi":["klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":480,"dauer_max":2400,"gruppe_min":25,"gruppe_max":160,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Planungszelle/Bürgergutachten – Methodenbeschreibung – Wegweiser Bürgergesellschaft","url":"https://www.buergergesellschaft.de/mitentscheiden/methoden-verfahren/methoden-und-verfahren-der-buergerbeteiligung-von-a-bis-z/planungszelle-buergergutachten/methodenbeschreibung"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peter C. Dienel: Die Planungszelle"}],"wann_passt":["A municipal or regional decision with high conflict potential between organized interests – random selection breaks up lobbying dynamics and legitimizes the result as \"what ordinary citizens want after good information\".","When expert knowledge and citizen perspective need to be brought together without experts dominating the outcome – the format guarantees that lay judgment counts.","An education format (political science, democracy education): simulating the method as a learning format makes deliberative democracy tangible."],"wann_nicht":["Without a genuine political mandate and implementation promise: a citizens' assembly with no consequence creates more cynicism than no assembly at all.","When the outcome is already decided – the method needs genuine openness at the decision-making level.","As a one-day format: it needs at least 2 days for the information phase and deliberation; compressed variants lose deliberative quality."],"fokusfragen":["\"What recommendation would you give the city/state/organization – and what was the decisive argument that convinced you?\" (closing of the deliberation phase)","\"What piece of information surprised you the most – and what did you believe before that now looks different?\""],"mini_form":"Deliberative mini-panel (45 min): 6–8 randomly selected people each hear 2 min of expert input on a question, deliberate for 15 min, give a recommendation. Not a real planning cell, but experiential.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","entscheidungstreffen","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"25–100 participants; core group 15–30 council members","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"palodium","name":"Palodium (IPG)","feld":"C","kurz":"Interweave panel discussion and small-group palaver (\"Greek coffeehouse\") so large groups are actively involved rather than just listening.","schritte":["Short panel: 2–4 speakers respond briefly to the guiding question (no long talks).","Switch to the \"Greek coffeehouse\": participants discuss the input at small-group tables.","Collect questions and theses from the tables (cards or shout-out).","Second panel round: speakers respond to the table questions.","Further switches between panel and tables as needed.","Closing: capture the key insights and open questions."],"zweck":"Interweave panel discussion and small-group palaver so large groups are actively involved rather than just listening.","hinweise":"Lives from the rhythm of the switches – keep panel rounds short (10–15 min); brief speakers in advance on the dialogue format, otherwise it tips into classic panel monologues.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","verbindung"],"formate":["grossgruppe","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":20,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Arbeitsanweisung Palodium (Handbuch-Material) – Gemeinsam Digital Berlin","url":"https://gemeinsamdigital.berlin.de/documents/48/GDB_Materialien_fur_das_Handbuch_-_Arbeitsanweisung_A3___Palodium.pdf"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"IPG Method Library: Palodium (MTB 0022)"}],"wann_passt":["A large-group conference (40–200) where a panel is unavoidable – e.g. due to external experts, decision-makers, or prestige logic – but real participation should still emerge: Palodium is the structured answer to the classic panel dilemma.","When a topic is controversial with opposing positions – the switches between panel and small-group palaver prevent one side from dominating the plenary.","A network's annual gathering with keynote logic: Palodium turns a keynote into a dialogue."],"wann_nicht":["When speakers aren't willing to engage in dialogue – Palodium needs panel guests who give short answers and want real questions.","Online as a full substitute: the room logistics (tables, switching) are hard to replicate digitally; only works with very good tooling.","When the topic has no real controversy – then a normal Q&A is more efficient."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's the one question you want to ask the panel – write it down before we switch.\" (table-to-panel transition)","\"What did the panel's answer give you – and what's still open?\" (after panel round 2)"],"mini_form":"Panel-palaver switch (40 min): short input (10 min), table conversation on a question (10 min), questions to the panel (10 min), closing palaver (10 min). Enough for one focused question.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","lernformat","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"25–150; under 20 a direct discussion works better","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"new-games","name":"New Games","feld":"C","kurz":"Movement games with no winners or losers – \"play hard, play fair, nobody hurt\" – build contact and a sense of community.","schritte":["Introduce the game idea and principle: \"Play hard, play fair, nobody hurt\" – no winners or losers.","Start with a low-threshold movement game, e.g. everyone keeps a balloon in the air together.","Increase intensity: games with more contact or coordination, while preserving voluntariness.","Let the group vary the rules together in between.","Debrief briefly: how did playing together instead of competitively feel?"],"zweck":"Build contact, trust, and a sense of community through movement games with no losers.","hinweise":"Always make physical contact optional and respect cultural/physical boundaries; works best in small doses as an opener or energy shift, not as a continuous program.","phasen":["ankommen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung","energie"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","klausur","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"nein","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","energizer"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"New Games – Kooperative Spiele ohne Gewinner und Verlierer – wirkstatt.com","url":"https://wirkstatt.com/newgames"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Andrew Fluegelman (Hrsg.): The New Games Book"}],"wann_passt":["A new team that doesn't know each other well yet, at the start of a team day or training series – New Games build more physical-emotional contact in 15–20 minutes than two hours of get-to-know-you conversation.","A group that needs to be physically activated after intense mental work – a simple movement game changes the mode entirely.","Children's and youth seminars or mixed-age groups: New Games work regardless of fitness level, because cooperation counts, not competition."],"wann_nicht":["Online – New Games are physical and cannot be translated digitally.","With groups who have physical limitations or a trauma-sensitive background, without explicit preparation – physical contact must always be an opt-out.","As the sole element in a long process – powerful in small doses as an energizer, but too little depth of reflection as a main format."],"fokusfragen":["\"How did playing together with no winners feel – what's different from everyday life?","\"Which moments in the game remind you of good collaboration?\""],"mini_form":"Balloon in the air (5 min): one balloon, everyone must keep it up together – no hands twice in a row. Almost always succeeds, creates a sense of achievement without pressure for physical contact.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–30 ideal; over 40 only in subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"initiativaufgaben","name":"Initiative Tasks","feld":"C","kurz":"Tasks like the spider web, acid pond, or tower building that can only be solved through everyone's cooperation – making team processes tangible.","schritte":["Give clear instructions for the task and rules, e.g. spider web: each opening only once, no touching the net; acid pond: retrieve an object without touching the ground.","Make safety rules explicit (lifting, spotting).","Planning phase: the group develops its own strategy – facilitators stay out of it.","Execution; on a rule violation, a defined consequence, e.g. restart.","Thorough debrief: how did we decide, who was heard, what do we carry into everyday life?"],"zweck":"Set a task that can only be solved through everyone's cooperation, and make team processes tangible through it.","hinweise":"The learning gain lies in the debrief, not in solving the task – reserve at least a third of the time for it; consider the group's physical abilities and offer roles for those who can't climb.","phasen":["vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung","reflexion"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","klausur","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":16,"online":"nein","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","spielerisch","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Probleme lösen, Initiative ergreifen – erlebnispädagogische Übungen (PDF) – Uni Wuppertal","url":"https://itps.uni-wuppertal.de/fileadmin/itps/Wastl/EP-Aktiv-04.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["A team that wants to talk about collaboration but doesn't want to – the task creates a safe observation level: people talk about the spider web, not about each other.","Training with teamwork as the learning subject: decision-making processes and communication patterns become visible live and can then be analyzed in the debrief.","A team retreat in the middle of a phase of paralysis – the physical challenge with a clear task and end creates agency as an experience."],"wann_nicht":["Without enough time for the debrief – the task itself is worthless; the learning gain lies entirely in the following conversation.","With physical limitations and no adapted variants – climbing and lifting must be feasible for everyone, or replaceable by observer roles.","Online – not transferable."],"fokusfragen":["\"How was it decided in your group – who brought in ideas, who listened, who had doubts?\" (debrief opener)","\"What do you carry from this process into your real collaboration – what do you want to keep, what do you want to change?\""],"mini_form":"Paper tower (15 min, indoor): each group builds the tallest free-standing tower from 10 sheets of paper and tape. No physical contact, low effort, same dynamic. Good as a debrief task without safety requirements.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","kickoff","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–16 ideal; over 20 in subgroups with a shared debrief","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","muede","neugierig"]},{"id":"trust-uebungen","name":"Trust Exercises","feld":"C","kurz":"Let go of control and experience trust physically – from blind leading to the trust fall in a tight circle.","schritte":["Establish voluntariness and safety rules: body tension, spotting, stop signal.","Start with low intensity: blind leading in pairs through the room.","Increase: trust fall in a tight circle – a person falls back, the group catches them gently.","Swap roles so everyone leads and trusts.","Debrief: what was it like to let go of control? What made trust possible?"],"zweck":"Let go of control and experience trust physically.","hinweise":"Never use early in a group process or under social pressure – failed trust exercises damage more than they build; supervision and mats depending on the exercise.","phasen":["vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung","selbstzugang"],"formate":["teamentwicklung","workshop","klausur","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"nein","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Vertrauensspiele – praxis-jugendarbeit.de","url":"https://www.praxis-jugendarbeit.de/spielesammlung/spiele-vertrauen.html"}],"wann_passt":["A group with trust built up over several shared days that wants to take a next deepening step – trust exercises are then a powerful expression of what's already there.","Training with body/trust/leadership as the learning topic – the debrief after the exercise is the real learning format.","An experiential education program that specifically targets trust – here trust exercises belong in the repertoire."],"wann_nicht":["Early in a process or with unfamiliar groups – failed trust exercises create more distrust than was there before.","When there's a strong hierarchy gap: a manager who lets themselves be caught by staff doesn't create a trust exercise but a power demonstration.","Online – not feasible.","In trauma-sensitive contexts without an explicit clearing phase and therapeutically trained support."],"fokusfragen":["\"What was it like to let go of control – what did that enable, what did it cost?\" (debrief after blind leading)","\"What happened between you that made trust possible or impossible?\""],"mini_form":"Back-to-back sitting (5 min): two people sit back to back, feel the contact, and settle into it. No falling, no loss of control – the gentlest form of physical contact and reciprocity.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–20; in pairs or small groups","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"betzavta-dilemmata","name":"Betzavta Dilemmas","feld":"C","kurz":"Make democratic principles tangible through experienced dilemmas instead of instruction – both claims, my freedom and that of others, also exist within me.","schritte":["Guide an exercise with a built-in dilemma (e.g. limited resources, a majority decision with consequences for the minority), without giving away the learning goal.","Let the group act – the conflict arises from the task itself.","Stop the process and reflect: how was the decision made? Whose freedom was restricted?","Work on the core question: both claims – my freedom and that of others – also exist within me.","Transfer: where do we experience such negotiations in everyday life/the organization?","Gather democratic courses of action."],"zweck":"Make democratic principles tangible through experienced dilemmas instead of instruction.","hinweise":"Needs trained facilitation – the reflection phase is demanding and can trigger frustration that must be held; never resolve the exercises before the group has really felt the dilemma.","phasen":["vertiefen","konflikt","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team","feld"],"modi":["konflikt","reflexion"],"formate":["fortbildung","workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["spielerisch","beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Betzavta / Mehr als eine Demokratie – Akademie Führung & Kompetenz, C·A·P München","url":"https://www.cap-lmu.de/akademie/schwerpunkte/betzavta-miteinander/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Uki Maroshek-Klarman: Miteinander – Erfahrungen mit Betzavta"}],"wann_passt":["A democracy-education training where principles like majority decision-making and minority protection should be experienced rather than explained – the exercises make the tension tangible before it's conceptualized.","A group working with power dynamics and experiences of exclusion (NGO, civic education, school) – Betzavta offers a tried-and-tested, protected form for this.","With trained facilitation assumed: as a building block in multi-day trainings, where the demanding reflection phase sits within a safe overall frame."],"wann_nicht":["Without trained facilitation: the reflection phase can trigger intense emotions and frustrations that must be held.","In groups with acute conflicts or traumatic experiences related to exclusion – the format can be triggering.","As a stand-alone exercise without embedding in an educational process – the exercises need a conceptual frame."],"fokusfragen":["\"What did you decide for yourself in the exercise – and what did that mean for others?\" (securing results after the action phase)","\"Where do you experience this tension between your freedom and the freedom of others in everyday life – and how do you deal with it?\""],"mini_form":"Resource dilemma (20 min): the group gets too few materials for everyone (chairs, cards, etc.). Don't prescribe a solution – observe how it's decided. Brief debrief: 'How was it decided, who lost out?' Enough for a first dilemma moment.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","dialograum","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"10–20 ideal; over 25 needs a small-group structure","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"gefangenendilemma","name":"(Iterated) Prisoner's Dilemma","feld":"C","kurz":"Make the tension between self-interest and cooperation tangible through game theory and derive conditions for trust.","schritte":["Explain the payoff matrix: cooperate or defect, the payoff depends on both decisions.","Pairs or teams play several rounds (iterated), decisions hidden, points recorded.","Show the running score and keep playing – strategies may adapt.","Debrief: which strategies emerged? (Tit for Tat, retaliation, forgiveness)","Transfer: where do self-interest and trust stand in tension in our context? What favors cooperation?"],"zweck":"Make the tension between self-interest and cooperation tangible through game theory and derive conditions for trust.","hinweise":"Team-versus-team variants can produce real annoyance – plan time to resolve it; the learning effect lies in the iteration (shadow of the future), single rounds fall too short.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["reflexion","vertrauen"],"formate":["fortbildung","workshop","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":40,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["spielerisch","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Prisoner's Dilemma – Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy","url":"https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/prisoner-dilemma/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Robert Axelrod: The Evolution of Cooperation"}],"wann_passt":["A training on cooperation, trust, or game theory: the iterated dilemma makes abstract concepts like \"shadow of the future\", \"Tit for Tat\", and \"forgiveness\" tangible and connectable.","A team implicitly or explicitly struggling with competition between units (departments, teams, sites) – the game externalizes the dynamic and makes it analyzable.","A workshop on negotiation strategies or organizational development: the debrief on the cooperate-vs-defect decision transfers directly."],"wann_nicht":["Single rounds without iteration – the decisive learning effect (cooperation arising from expectations about the future) gets lost.","When real annoyance arises between groups and can't be resolved – plan enough time to resolve it.","With groups that react very rationally-skeptically to games – then explain the concept first, then play."],"fokusfragen":["\"When did you decide to cooperate – and what motivated you? When did you defect?\" (strategy analysis in the debrief)","\"What would it take in your real collaboration for the 'Tit for Tat' logic to emerge – that is: cooperation as the first choice, a response to betrayal, but also forgiveness?\""],"beispiel":"Iterated game (5 rounds, 2 min each): Team A and B choose 'C' or 'D' in secret. Outcome: CC = 3 points each; CD = A 0, B 5; DD = 1 each. After round 3, a short strategy huddle is allowed. Debrief: 'Which strategy was smarter in the long run?' – Punchline: Tit for Tat (start with C, then mirror the other side) is, according to studies, superior in the long run. Follow-up question: 'What is the first step that makes cooperation possible again even after a betrayal?'","mini_form":"Individual decision without a team (10 min): everyone anonymously chooses C or D on a concrete dilemma from their own work. Debrief the distribution in plenary. Not a game, but a direct transfer.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","teamtag","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–24 ideal; split larger groups into parallel pairings","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","skeptisch","frisch"]},{"id":"wetterbericht-check-in","name":"Weather Report (Check-in)","feld":"C","kurz":"Describe your inner state as a weather forecast – a quick check-in without pressure to explain, the metaphor protects.","schritte":["Give the invitation: \"Describe your inner state as a weather forecast.\"","Give brief examples: sunny, cloudy with sunny spells, thunderstorm front.","Share in turn or freely in popcorn order, without commentary.","Optionally acknowledge briefly (\"Thank you\") and transition into the agenda."],"zweck":"Quickly make everyone's inner state visible at the start of a session, without pressure to explain.","hinweise":"The weather metaphor protects – no one has to give reasons; for large groups use the chat or picture-card variant. Don't comment on it or turn it into therapy.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","selbstzugang"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":15,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Weather Check-in – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/weather-check-in-obyout"}],"wann_passt":["A regular team meeting where mood varies a lot and isn't addressed – the weather report gives everyone a chance to signal in one word, without having to explain.","A group that has rejected check-ins as \"too personal\" – the weather metaphor protects and feels more playful than \"How are you?\"","At the start of a difficult conversation: briefly make visible what inner state everyone is coming into the room with, before the content starts."],"wann_nicht":["In very large groups (>25) without adaptation – going around the room takes too long; the chat or picture-card variant works better then.","When direct matter-of-factness is needed and the group generally rejects check-ins – then a mood scale of 1–10 is better.","As a permanent solution without variation – it wears thin after a few weeks."],"fokusfragen":["\"Describe your inner state as a weather forecast – one sentence is enough.\" (invitation formula)","\"What do you need for things to get better over the next few hours?\" (optional deepening for burdened groups)"],"mini_form":"Weather bar in chat (2 min): everyone writes their weather report in the chat at the same time, no reaction. Gives a picture of the group in 2 minutes without the round-robin logic.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","teamtag","coaching"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3–20 ideal; over 25 use chat or picture-card variant","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","muede","belastet","neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"ein-wort-check-in","name":"One-Word Check-in","feld":"C","kurz":"Arrive with a single word – make all voices heard in the shortest time and get a mood picture.","schritte":["Ask the question: \"What one word describes how you're arriving today?\"","Give a short moment to think.","Go around, one word each, without commentary.","Optionally: briefly pick up or leave standing any striking words at the end."],"zweck":"Make all voices heard in the shortest time and get a mood picture.","hinweise":"Stick consistently to one word – the constraint creates the precision; works equally well as a one-word check-out.","phasen":["ankommen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":40,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"One Word Method – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/one-word-method"}],"wann_passt":["A time-pressed context (regular meeting, short work session) where a long check-in isn't possible – one word per person takes 30 seconds and still gives a mood picture.","A large group (20–40): going around with one word each is done in 5 minutes, without anyone rambling.","As a check-out at the end: 'What word are you leaving with?' – a compact closing that condenses the essence."],"wann_nicht":["When the group needs clarification and one word doesn't give enough room – then use Weather Report or Blitzlicht (quick round).","In a tense group where one-word answers like \"exhausted\" or \"frustrated\" would be left uncommented – that needs room for follow-up."],"fokusfragen":["\"What one word describes how you're arriving here today?\" (arrival variant)","\"What word are you leaving this room with?\" (closing variant)"],"mini_form":"Already a minimal format itself – no further reduction possible.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","teamtag","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3–40; over 40 in writing","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","skeptisch","neugierig","frisch","angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"stimmungsskala","name":"Mood Scale 1–10","feld":"C","kurz":"Quickly quantify the group's energy or agreement – by show of hands, card, spatial line-up, or chat – and make it actionable.","schritte":["Define the question: \"What's your energy/clarity on this topic – 1 to 10?\"","Poll: show of hands, hold up a card, line up along an imaginary line, or type a number in chat.","Read the picture briefly: where does the group sit, where are the outliers?","Optionally hear 1–2 voices: \"What would you need to be one point higher?\"","Draw a consequence: break, pace change, topic change."],"zweck":"Quickly quantify the group's energy or agreement and make it actionable.","hinweise":"Don't judge the numbers (\"only a 4?\") – they're information, not a verdict; asking about \"+1 point\" turns the measurement into an intervention.","phasen":["ankommen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","uebergang","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Soziometrische Aufstellung und Skalenabfrage beim Online-Lernen – selbstlernen.net","url":"https://www.selbstlernen.net/aufstellung-und-skalenabfrage/"}],"wann_passt":["A transition between agenda items, when facilitators don't know how the energy stands – the scale gives an objective picture in 2 minutes and legitimizes course corrections.","Decision preparation: before a group votes, take a quick clarity scale ('How clear are you on this topic, 1–10?') – it shows whether more information is needed.","Online meetings where camera absence makes the mood invisible – numbers in chat give instant orientation."],"wann_nicht":["When numbers could be misread as a performance rating – in hierarchical contexts, low numbers can feel like public weakness.","As a substitute for a real conversation: the scale measures but solves nothing – 'What would you need for +1 point?' is the crucial follow-up question.","When the group has already been polled several times in the same session – measurement fatigue sets in quickly."],"fokusfragen":["\"On a scale of 1–10: how clear/energized/satisfied are you right now – type a number in chat, please.\" (invitation formula)","\"What would you need to get one point higher?\" (the crucial follow-up question, turns measurement into intervention)"],"beispiel":"Before a vote on a strategy option: 'On a scale of 1–10: how well do you understand the implications of this option?' – The facilitator reads out: 'I'm seeing a lot of 4–6s. Before we vote: what's still missing for you?' Two people name concrete information gaps. Second question after 5 min of clarification: the scale rises to 7–8. The vote now happens on a real information basis.","mini_form":"Show-of-hands variant (2 min): everyone shows 1–5 fingers at the same time – no chat needed, no tool. Instantly visible in the room.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","entscheidungstreffen","teamtag","krisensitzung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3–100; from 30 upward use chat or show of hands instead of individual polling","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","angespannt","neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"1-2-4-all","name":"1-2-4-All","feld":"C","kurz":"Activate everyone at once: think alone in silence, then in pairs, then in fours – and carry only the best ideas to the plenary (Liberating Structures).","schritte":["Pose a clear invitation/question.","1 min of silent individual reflection.","2 min of exchange in pairs, developing ideas further.","4 min of comparing in groups of four: mark commonalities and best ideas.","5 min \"All\": each group of four shares one important idea in plenary; repeat the cycle if needed."],"zweck":"Activate everyone at once and condense ideas from individuals through pairs into group essences.","hinweise":"Keep the time boxes strictly – the brevity creates focus; in plenary don't collect everything, only the most important idea per group (otherwise the energy dies).","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","grossgruppe","fortbildung","klausur"],"dauer_min":12,"dauer_max":25,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern","einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"1-2-4-All – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/1-1-2-4-all/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Henri Lipmanowicz, Keith McCandless: The Surprising Power of Liberating Structures"}],"wann_passt":["A workshop of ~8 people or more, where 2–3 frequent talkers would otherwise fill the room and quieter voices get lost – the silent work at the start gives everyone their own thought before the loud ones speak.","A skeptical or method-fatigued group: barely feels like a \"method\" because it's just structured conversation – a good opener when \"workshop games\" have burned out their welcome.","When real diversity of opinion is suspected on an open question but wouldn't become visible in the large group (hierarchy in the room, a boss present)."],"wann_nicht":["Under 6 people: the stages collapse, and a direct facilitated conversation is more honest.","When the question is actually already decided – then the participation creates cynicism.","As a permanent solution in every meeting: it wears out quickly and then feels mechanical."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's the most important lever, from your point of view, to achieve X?\" (one question, not three – the quality of 1-2-4-All stands or falls with a precise opening question)","\"What would Y change from the perspective of the people we work for?\""],"mini_form":"Just '1-2-All' in 10 minutes: 1 minute of silent notes, 4 minutes in pairs, then a quick round – plenty for small groups (6–10).","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","strategie","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"12–40 ideal, from 8 worthwhile, under 6 not","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"think-pair-share","name":"Think-Pair-Share","feld":"C","kurz":"Individual thinking, pair exchange, plenary: secure everyone's participation and raise contribution quality through forethought.","schritte":["Pose a question or task.","Think: 1–3 min of silent individual thinking, notes optional.","Pair: exchange in pairs, compare and sharpen thoughts.","Share: bring results to the plenary – at random or voluntarily.","Facilitation pulls together the patterns."],"zweck":"Secure everyone's participation and raise the quality of contributions through forethought and a pair check.","hinweise":"Really keep the think phase silent – it protects introverted and slower thinkers; the difference from 1-2-4-All: it stays at the pair level, making it even more low-threshold.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":20,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Think-Pair-Share – Methodenkartei Uni Oldenburg","url":"https://www.methodenkartei.uni-oldenburg.de/methode/think-pair-share/"}],"wann_passt":["A learning format or workshop with a single content-heavy question, where forethought clearly raises the quality of answers – Think-Pair-Share is the simplest structure for that.","A group with very different levels of prior knowledge: the pair conversation levels things out before everything goes to plenary – results are more consistent.","As a lighter entry point than 1-2-4-All: when no group of four should be formed, or the question is too close for 4 people."],"wann_nicht":["For questions that require individual opinion and don't benefit from pair discussion (e.g. personal reflection, self-assessment).","When the think phase isn't really kept silent – then it's just a slightly delayed plenary conversation.","For complex topics that need more than 2 perspectives – then 1-2-4-All is better."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's your personal answer to this question – even before you talk to anyone?\" (think-phase invitation)","\"What did your pair conversation change or sharpen about your first answer?\" (share-phase introduction)"],"mini_form":"Already a short format itself (5–10 min). Shortest version: 1 min silent – 2 min in pairs – one statement per pair to the plenary.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","regeltermin","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–100; for large groups, share in subgroups instead of plenary","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","skeptisch","frisch"]},{"id":"blitzlicht","name":"Lightning Round (Blitzlicht)","feld":"C","kurz":"Going around the circle, one sentence per person, no comments – a quick, unfiltered snapshot of the whole group's mood or opinion.","schritte":["Pose the focus question: \"How are you feeling about where we are?\" / \"What are you taking away?\"","Explain the rule: one sentence per person, going around, no comments, no discussion.","Run the round; passing is allowed.","Facilitator thanks the group and, at most, summarizes patterns – without evaluating individual contributions."],"zweck":"Quickly gather an unfiltered snapshot of the whole group's mood or opinion.","hinweise":"The no-comment rule is the protective boundary – the facilitator holds it too; from ~15 people it gets long, so switch to a one-word variant.","phasen":["reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["reflexion"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":15,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["abschluss","reflexion"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Blitzlicht – Methodenkartei Uni Oldenburg","url":"https://www.methodenkartei.uni-oldenburg.de/methode/blitzlicht/"}],"wann_passt":["Closing a session phase or the whole day: one sentence per person gives the facilitator a quick diagnosis of whether the group is ready for the next step or needs clarification.","Groups under 12 people, where a scale check-in would be too coarse – Lightning Round gives verbal nuance without taking much time.","When you want the mood to become visible after a demanding block, without working it through therapeutically."],"wann_nicht":["From ~16 people on: Lightning Round becomes too long; a one-word check-in or mood scale is more efficient.","When discussion or commenting on contributions is expected – the no-comment rule is a protection, but also a limitation.","As the only feedback format for an entire day – it lacks the depth needed for important evaluations."],"fokusfragen":["\"In one sentence: how are you feeling right now about what we've worked out?\" (mid-point check)","\"What are you taking away from this session – one sentence, no discussion.\" (closing)"],"mini_form":"Is already a minimal form itself. Even shorter: word lightning round (1 word instead of 1 sentence) for groups > 12.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","retro","teamtag","krisensitzung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-14 ideal; over 15 too long","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","angespannt","neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"paarinterview","name":"Pair Interview (Icebreaker)","feld":"C","kurz":"Interview each other and introduce your partner to the plenary – contact through stories instead of self-presentation.","schritte":["Form pairs, ideally people who don't know each other well.","Give guiding questions: name, relation to the topic, one surprising thing.","Interview each other, 3-5 min per direction.","In the plenary, each person introduces their partner – not themselves.","Optional: collect commonalities in the room."],"zweck":"Foster contact and getting to know each other through stories rather than self-presentation.","hinweise":"Being introduced by someone else lowers stage fright and increases listening quality; in large groups, introduce in groups of four instead of the plenary.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":40,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":40,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Partnerinterview – Methodenkartei Uni Oldenburg","url":"https://www.methodenkartei.uni-oldenburg.de/methode/partnerinterview/"}],"wann_passt":["A new team or training group on day one: being introduced by someone else massively lowers stage fright and immediately creates real listening quality.","Network meetings where people don't yet know each other and the classic plenary round of introductions bores everyone – pair interviews create more real contact in 15 minutes.","As a warm-up before an intense process: the interview setting builds bilateral trust that then benefits the overall process."],"wann_nicht":["When there's no time for the plenary introductions – then the appreciation of listening is missing.","In very large groups (>40) without adjustment: plenary introductions become too long; better to introduce in groups of four.","When the group already knows each other well – the format then feels forced."],"fokusfragen":["\"Interview your counterpart – three questions: name and relation to the topic, a project that's currently moving you, one thing about you that isn't obvious.\" (guiding questions for the interview)","\"What surprised you most about your interview partner?\" (plenary opener after the introductions)"],"mini_form":"Interview flash (10 min): 3 min per direction, one question ('What brings you here?'), plenary introduction in one sentence. Enough for a first contact network.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","netzwerktreffen","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-30 ideal; from 40 on, introduce in small groups instead of plenary","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"warp-speed","name":"Warp Speed (Energizer)","feld":"C","kurz":"Complete the ball-passing order in a circle faster and faster – activates the group in minutes and makes creative problem-solving beyond habitual assumptions tangible.","schritte":["Form a circle; the ball is thrown so that each person receives it exactly once and it returns to the first person – memorize the order.","Repeat the order and time it.","Issue the challenge: \"Can you do it faster?\" – the group is free to change formation and method.","Several attempts with brief strategy discussions.","Brief debrief: which assumptions slowed us down at the start?"],"zweck":"Activate the group in minutes and, along the way, make creative problem-solving beyond habitual assumptions tangible.","hinweise":"The aha moment comes when the group abandons the circle pattern (under 1 second is possible) – don't give it away; use soft balls.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["energie"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":15,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"nein","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["energizer"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Warp Speed – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/warp-speed"}],"wann_passt":["After a long lecture or work block, when energy has visibly dropped – Warp Speed fully activates in 10 minutes without needing any content connection.","Workshop on creative thinking or innovation: the debrief ('Which assumptions slowed us down?') transfers directly to the day's content.","A group that's skeptical of warm-up games but needs a shared success – the aha moment of abandoning the circle pattern creates real energy."],"wann_nicht":["Online – physical presence and a ball are required.","When no debrief follows – then it's just a game; the transfer happens in the conversation afterward.","With groups that don't want to or can't move."],"fokusfragen":["\"What assumption did you make at the start that slowed you down – and when did you let go of it?\" (core debrief question)","\"What thinking block from your own work operates in a similar way?\""],"mini_form":"Is already a short format (5-15 min) – no further reduction needed.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat","kickoff"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-25; over 25, run two parallel circles","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","skeptisch","frisch"]},{"id":"zaehlkreis","name":"Counting Circle (Energizer)","feld":"C","kurz":"Count together to 20 with no agreed order – sharpens attention, listening, and shared timing.","schritte":["Form a circle, close eyes or look at the floor.","Explain the task: count together to 20, one person per number, with no agreed order.","If two people speak at once, the group restarts at 1.","Keep playing until 20 is reached or time runs out.","Briefly reflect: what helped – pace, pauses, listening?"],"zweck":"Sharpen attention, listening, and shared timing, and create focused silence.","hinweise":"Failure is part of the game – frame it lightly, otherwise frustration builds; variants: counting backwards, alphabet, with eyes open facing outward.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["energie"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["energizer","uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Count To 20 – Drama Resource","url":"https://dramaresource.com/count-to-20/"}],"wann_passt":["A group that needs to find a shared rhythm again after intense discussion or conflict – the counting circle creates focused silence without exposing content.","As a transition ritual in recurring groups (supervision groups, training series): failing is part of it and is handled lightly – relieving.","Shortly after lunch or in the early afternoon when energy is low – creates attention without physical exertion."],"wann_nicht":["With very large groups (>25) – the likelihood of two people speaking at once rises, which frustrates rather than relaxes.","When under time pressure and 5-10 min aren't available – better nothing than an aborted game.","Synchronous online: the shared timing is barely tangible without physical presence."],"fokusfragen":["\"What helped – pace, pauses, listening to others?\" (quick debrief after the game)","\"What of that do we need in our work together?\""],"mini_form":"Is already a minimal format. Variant without failure: alphabet instead of numbers, evenly in turn – less risk, less dynamic.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-20; over 20 too unreliable","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","angespannt","neugierig"]},{"id":"gefuehls-beduerfnis-karten","name":"Feelings & Needs Cards (NVC mini)","feld":"C","kurz":"Cards with feelings and needs words lower the threshold for talking about one's own situation – naming without having to justify.","schritte":["Lay out cards with feelings and needs words, or hand out lists.","Invitation: \"Choose 1-2 cards that match your current situation.\"","Silent selection time.","Share in pairs or a round – only naming, no need to justify.","Optional deepening: \"What need is behind that feeling?\""],"zweck":"Open up emotional language and make feelings/needs nameable without conversational pressure.","hinweise":"Cards significantly lower the threshold compared to speaking freely about feelings; the CNVC lists (Feelings/Needs Inventory) are freely available and can also be shared digitally.","phasen":["ankommen","vertiefen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung","coaching","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["schriftlich","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Feelings and Needs Inventory – Center for Nonviolent Communication","url":"https://www.cnvc.org/store/feelings-and-needs-inventory"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall B. Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation"}],"wann_passt":["A team after a difficult event (a dismissal, criticism, failure) that needs to talk about the situation, but where a direct call to self-disclosure would be too much – cards provide language and lower the threshold of shame.","As an opening for conflict clarification: before positions are exchanged, everyone clarifies for themselves what they feel and need – NVC cards structure this without introducing NVC as a method.","Coaching or individual support: as an opener for a difficult conversation, when the person struggles to get in touch with their own situation."],"wann_nicht":["In very task-focused groups without prior framing – 'feelings cards' without context feel alienating.","When there's no time to hold what surfaces – no emotional opening without a container to close it.","Online without good digital card material – choosing from physical cards has a different quality than word lists on a screen."],"fokusfragen":["\"Choose 1-2 cards that best describe your current situation – you don't need to explain anything, just name it.\" (invitation formula)","\"What need is behind the feeling you chose – and is it currently met or not?\" (optional deepening)"],"beispiel":"In a team clarification after a failed project: cards are laid out, everyone chooses silently. Person A chooses 'exhausted' and 'frustrated' – says only that. Person B chooses 'disappointed' and 'sad'. Facilitator: 'I hear exhaustion and sadness in the room – what do you need right now?' Step to needs: recognition, clarity, a break. This opens the conversation without blame.","mini_form":"Word selection without cards (5 min): facilitator reads out 10 feeling words, everyone says or writes the two that fit best. No materials needed.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","teamtag","coaching"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"2-20; over 25 in small groups","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"selbstempathie-pause","name":"Self-Empathy Pause (NVC mini)","feld":"C","kurz":"Clarify inwardly in 2-3 minutes what I feel and need – self-regulation in the middle of a heated session.","schritte":["Briefly interrupt and go quiet – possible even in the middle of a heated session.","Clarify the observation: what actually happened – without judgment?","Ask inwardly: \"What am I feeling right now?\"","Continue asking: \"What need is (not) being met?\"","Optionally formulate a request to yourself or others; then consciously return to the conversation."],"zweck":"Self-regulate in 2-3 minutes by inwardly clarifying feelings and needs.","hinweise":"Introduce as a facilitation offer before it's needed – instructions are hard to take in in the heat of the moment; can also be done as a silent writing minute.","phasen":["konflikt","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["selbstzugang","reflexion"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","coaching","teamentwicklung","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":10,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Der Prozess der Selbstempathie – Fachverband Gewaltfreie Kommunikation","url":"https://www.fachverband-gfk.org/der-prozess-der-selbstempathie"}],"wann_passt":["In the middle of a heated discussion, when a person has visibly lost regulation – the pause gives them space without breaking off the conversation.","As a facilitation tool before escalating statements are made: 'Let's take a brief self-empathy pause – 2 minutes of silence, everyone asks themselves: what do I feel, what do I need?'","In coaching or individual support as a personal practice: self-empathy before a difficult intervention or conversation."],"wann_nicht":["As a permanent solution for recurring escalations – then there's a structural problem that a pause won't solve.","When the group doesn't know the tool and the moment is too charged to take in instructions – better a simple pause instruction.","As an alibi pause, without any actual inner clarification happening."],"fokusfragen":["\"What am I observing right now – without judgment?\" (NVC self-empathy step 1)","\"What am I feeling right now – and what need is (not) being met?\" (NVC steps 2 and 3)"],"beispiel":"In a team clarification, the exchange gets loud. Facilitator: 'Short pause – 2 minutes for all of us. Ask yourself inwardly: what's happening in me right now? What do I feel, what do I need now?' – Silence. Then: 'Whoever wants to, say one sentence about it – without justifying yourself.' Person A: 'I notice I'm irritated – I need to feel that my contribution is heard.' This opens the next step of the conversation at the level of needs instead of positions.","mini_form":"Is already a minimal format (2-5 min). Even shorter: 30-second breathing pause without guidance as a facilitation signal.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech","coaching"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1-30; as a group intervention useful up to 20","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"erdung-bodyscan","name":"Grounding / Short Body Scan (Embodiment)","feld":"C","kurz":"Bring the group from the head into body awareness: attention travels through the body, feeling contact surfaces, arriving.","schritte":["Invite people to find a comfortable position (sitting, feet on the ground); closing eyes is optional.","Guide attention to the breath, 2-3 conscious breaths.","Let attention slowly travel through the body: feet - legs - pelvis - back - shoulders - head; notice without changing anything.","Feel contact surfaces: floor, chair.","Return with one deep breath, open eyes; let people briefly notice how they feel."],"zweck":"Bring the group out of their heads into body awareness and the here and now.","hinweise":"Keep the language inviting and secular (\"perception exercise\", not \"meditation\"), participation voluntary; in trauma-sensitive contexts, keep eyes open and choose a short duration.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","coaching","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":15,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"A Beginner's Body Scan Meditation – Mindful.org","url":"https://www.mindful.org/beginners-body-scan-meditation/"}],"wann_passt":["Start of a session after an intense arrival, stress, or a difficult previous day – grounding brings the group out of their heads and creates presence as a foundation for everything that follows.","Transition between a content-heavy block and a new topic – the body scan signals: we're now arriving somewhere else.","Online meetings where everyone is coming straight from other calls and is still cognitively elsewhere – 3 minutes of grounding actually raises the quality of conversation."],"wann_nicht":["In groups that categorically reject body exercises or 'meditation' – then better a one-word check-in or brief silence.","Trauma-sensitive without preparation: closing eyes and feeling the body can trigger – with vulnerable groups, keep eyes open, keep it short (2 min), and announce it in advance.","When under time pressure and the group has no willingness to pause."],"fokusfragen":["\"Feel where you have contact right now – with the floor, the chair. You don't need to change anything, just notice.\" (guiding formula)","\"What are you taking into the next hour – one word for your state right now?\" (optional closing)"],"mini_form":"30-second breathing pause: 'Three conscious breaths – breathe in counting to 4, breathe out counting to 6. Go.' No body scan, no need to close eyes. Works in any group, even skeptical ones.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat","coaching"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1-100; scales freely","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"systems-mapping-causal-loops","name":"Systems Mapping / Causal Loops","feld":"D","kurz":"Visualize feedback loops and system dynamics that linear cause-effect thinking misses.","schritte":["Define the focus question: why does X remain stable despite all efforts?","Collect key variables – things that can increase or decrease","Draw causal links (same direction/opposite direction)","Identify loops: reinforcing (R) or balancing (B)","Name the loops and have them told as a story","Mark entry points for intervention"],"zweck":"Make visible the feedback loops and system dynamics that linear cause-effect thinking misses.","hinweise":"Keep the map small (max. 10-15 variables), otherwise it becomes a spaghetti map. Formulate variables neutrally (level, not event). The discussion while building is more valuable than the finished diagram.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The Systems Thinker – Causal Loop Construction: The Basics","url":"https://thesystemsthinker.com/causal-loop-construction-the-basics/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Donella Meadows: Thinking in Systems (2008)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Omidyar Group – Systems Practice Workbook (free PDF)","url":"https://www.omidyar.com/sites/default/files/file_archive/Systems%20Practice%20Workbook.pdf"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Academy for Systems Change – Tools & Resources","url":"https://academyforchange.org/resources/"}],"wann_passt":["A group of 4-12 people is working on a problem that remains stable despite repeated interventions (e.g. chronic underfunding, recurring conflicts, a stagnant learning culture) – causal loops make visible which feedback loops stabilize the problem, and where interventions could target loops instead of symptoms.","Kick-off of a systems change initiative: stakeholders from different areas bring partial knowledge – jointly building the map makes system knowledge collectively accessible and creates shared understanding that individual conversations can't produce.","In a strategy retreat where the group has been planning linearly so far (cause → measure → effect): the mapping session interrupts this reflex and opens the discussion to interactions and unintended effects.","As an evaluation element at the end of a phase: 'What has changed – which loops have weakened, which did we overlook?'"],"wann_nicht":["The group is under acute pressure to act and needs a decision in 30 minutes – mapping costs time and openness that can't emerge under pressure.","More than 15 people without a subgroup structure: the map turns into a spaghetti catastrophe, no one understands the result.","The topic is actually linear and well understood – then causal loops is overengineering and irritates the group."],"fokusfragen":["'Why does [specific situation] remain stable despite everything – what holds it in place?' (opening question; forces a search for loops instead of jumping to measures)","'Which variable would need to change for the reinforcing loop R1 to turn more slowly?' (leverage question after the analysis)","'What is reinforcing itself here – and who benefits from it staying this way?' (power and interest question; opens the political dimension of the system)","'If we intervene at lever X – what happens in loop B2 as a reaction?' (intervention test before the decision)'"],"beispiel":"Topic: why do marginalized groups in our network never really gain decision-making power? Opening question: 'Which variables increase or decrease when power stays concentrated?' The group's answers: visibility, access barriers, informal networks, trust. Causal link: more trust → more visibility → more invitations → more trust (reinforcing loop R1). Counter-link: more access barriers → less visibility (balancing B1). Follow-up question: 'Where in B1 could we lower the barrier most cheaply?' – this produces a well-founded intervention instead of a gut-feeling measure.","mini_form":"15-minute quick map: a single question ('What holds X in place?'), 3 minutes of silently writing variables on post-its, then 10 minutes drawing arrows together – not a complete model, but a first look at loops that tips the conversation into depth.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","netzwerktreffen","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-12 ideal, possible from 3, over 15 only with parallel subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"leverage-points","name":"Leverage Points (Meadows)","feld":"D","kurz":"Sort interventions by depth of impact – from parameters to paradigm.","schritte":["Lay out the existing system analysis","Introduce the 12 levers in 4 clusters: parameters → structures → rules/information → goals/paradigms","Collect existing and possible interventions","Assign interventions to the lever levels","Discuss: where are we only working on shallow levers?","Concretize 1-2 deeper interventions"],"zweck":"Sort interventions by depth of impact – from parameters to paradigm.","hinweise":"Deep levers (paradigms) are powerful but hardest to access – plan for frustration. Don't read the hierarchy dogmatically; Meadows herself called it provisional.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Donella Meadows – Leverage Points: Places to Intervene in a System","url":"https://donellameadows.org/archives/leverage-points-places-to-intervene-in-a-system/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Donella Meadows: Thinking in Systems (2008)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"FSG / Kania, Kramer, Senge – The Water of Systems Change","url":"https://www.fsg.org/resource/water_of_systems_change/"}],"wann_passt":["A strategy group has a list of interventions and is arguing about what should really be prioritized – Leverage Points gives a shared language for depth of impact (parameter vs. paradigm) and makes visible that many measures work on shallow levers.","A program review of an organization that runs many activities but sees little systemic impact: mapping interventions onto the 12 lever levels shows the structural problem without blaming anyone personally.","Training context (systems change literacy): as a learning format to intuitively train participants on the question 'shallow or deep lever?' – Meadows' framework is easy to tell as a story and the paradigm argument sticks.","In a coalition where different actors work at different points in the system: Leverage Points makes visible who is pulling which lever and whether the approaches complement or neutralize each other."],"wann_nicht":["As a decision tool for concrete operational measures – the 12 levers are a thinking structure, not a decision matrix.","When the group hasn't yet done the system analysis (causal loops, iceberg): without a basic understanding of the system, the lever classification remains speculative.","In a group that uses deepening as procrastination – Leverage Points can endlessly prolong 'we need to understand more first'."],"fokusfragen":["'Which of our current interventions work at the level of parameters (flow variables, metrics) – and what would the equivalent be one level deeper?' (upgrade question)","'Who benefits from the current mental models in our field staying in place – and how are they maintained?' (paradigm question, political)","'If we had unlimited resources: which lever would we really want to intervene on?' (hypothetical serious case, opens strategic imagination)"],"beispiel":"An NGO coalition reviews its advocacy strategy. Interventions on cards: 'public campaign', 'change the law', 'funding rules', 'build a network of changemakers', 'shift the narrative in media'. Classification onto lever levels: campaign = lever 3 (information flows), law = lever 5 (rules), funding rule = lever 6 (structure), changemaker network = lever 2 (touches goals/paradigms). Follow-up question: 'We invest 80% of our time in levers 3-6 – who's taking care of the mental models behind the policy?' This reframes the resource discussion.","mini_form":"Quick mapping in 15 minutes: each person writes down their two most important current interventions. Sort together into just three clusters: 'levers', 'rules of the game', 'paradigms'. Then one question: 'What's missing in the paradigms column?'","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-15 ideal, possible from 3, over 20 only with subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"six-conditions","name":"Six Conditions of Systems Change (FSG)","feld":"D","kurz":"Check whether an initiative only changes what's visible or also relationships, power, and mental models.","schritte":["Introduce the model: three levels (structural/relational/transformative) with six conditions","Map your own system against all six conditions","Mark which conditions the initiative has addressed so far","Deepen mental models and power dynamics specifically","Derive and prioritize interventions per condition"],"zweck":"Check an initiative for whether it only changes what's visible or also relationships, power, and mental models.","hinweise":"Risk of just ticking off the grid as a checklist – demand concrete examples per condition. Discussing power dynamics honestly requires trust in the room.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"FSG – The Water of Systems Change (PDF)","url":"https://www.fsg.org/resource/water_of_systems_change/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Omidyar Group – Systems Practice Workbook","url":"https://www.omidyar.com/sites/default/files/file_archive/Systems%20Practice%20Workbook.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["An initiative wants to know whether it's really doing systems change or just treating symptoms – the 6 conditions (Policies, Practices, Resource Flows, Relationships, Power Dynamics, Mental Models) as a diagnostic grid show which levels are being worked on and which are missing.","Strategy development in a coalition: different organizations with different approaches map which conditions they each address – this makes gaps and synergy potential visible, without hierarchy.","Program evaluation after 2-3 years: which of the 6 conditions have changed, which haven't? The framework gives the evaluation a systems-informed language.","Systems change training: as a learning format to make the structural/relational/transformative distinction intuitively tangible."],"wann_nicht":["As the sole basis for a budget decision – the 6 conditions are diagnosis, not a prioritization matrix.","When there's no psychological safety in the room to discuss power dynamics: the transformative level (mental models, power relations) then stays on the surface.","In early phases of a coalition that doesn't yet know each other – honestly mapping power dynamics requires trust that has to be built first."],"fokusfragen":["'Which of the six conditions are we currently working on – and which are we systematically leaving out?' (diagnostic question)","'Whose mental models in the field would need to change for our intervention to hold long-term – and who is currently upholding these models?' (transformation level)","'Which power dynamic in the system makes it hard to work on condition X – and who has an interest in keeping it that way?' (power dynamics question)"],"beispiel":"An education initiative maps its work: Policies (curriculum change ✓), Practices (new teaching methods ✓), Resource Flows (new funding ✓), Relationships (school-community partnerships ✓), Power Dynamics (who decides on the curriculum? – blank), Mental Models (what teachers believe about 'good learning' – blank). Insight: the initiative works exclusively on the three structural conditions. Follow-up question: 'What would it take to also address the school leadership's mental models?'","mini_form":"10-minute scan: the group silently names one activity per condition (or 'blank'). Show the result. Ask just one question: 'Which level have we never explicitly worked on?'","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-20 ideal, possible from 4","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"iceberg-systeme","name":"Iceberg (Systems)","feld":"D","kurz":"Go from reacting to events to understanding structure in a single guided descent.","schritte":["Choose a specific event: what happened?","Collect patterns/trends underneath: what keeps happening?","Identify structures: what generates these patterns – rules, incentives, relationships?","Uncover mental models: which assumptions keep the structures alive?","Discuss levers at each level – the deeper, the more effective"],"zweck":"Move from reacting to events to understanding structure, in a single guided descent.","hinweise":"Works best with a real, emotionally charged event from the group. Stay appreciative at the mental models level – that's where it gets personal.","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Ecochallenge.org – A Systems Thinking Model: The Iceberg","url":"https://ecochallenge.org/iceberg-model/"}],"wann_passt":["A team keeps reacting to the same event (crisis, conflict, mistake) without understanding what generates it – the iceberg model guides the group from reacting to events to structural analysis in 30-45 minutes, without needing to explain systems theory.","Workshop opener on a difficult topic: instead of jumping straight to solutions, the model helps the group feel the depth of the problem – especially if the group has so far only discussed it at the symptom level.","Learning format for leaders who don't yet know systems thinking: the iceberg image is intuitively accessible and works even without prior knowledge.","Conflict preparation: before a mediation begins, the iceberg model helps understand the mental models and structures behind the conflict – not as a group exercise with the conflict parties, but as an analysis tool for the facilitator."],"wann_nicht":["When there's a concrete, uncontested operational problem that's known and solvable – the model deepens where sometimes only action is needed.","As a substitute for a real system analysis: the iceberg model opens the depth level but doesn't map feedback loops – as a standalone it's not enough for complex systems.","With a group that's too exhausted or too tense to go into abstraction – then stabilize the room first."],"fokusfragen":["'What has kept happening over the last few months – what pattern do you recognize?' (step from event to pattern)","'Which structures – rules, roles, incentives, resource flows – generate these patterns?' (step from pattern to structure)","'What image of the world, what belief, what conviction keeps these structures in place – and who shares it?' (step to mental models; this gets personal, facilitate appreciatively)"],"beispiel":"Event: the team keeps proposing short-term emergency solutions in crisis meetings, without lasting effect. Pattern: the same crisis has resurfaced every 6 months for 3 years. Structures: funding cycles reward activity, not impact; no budget for structural prevention; leadership changes every 2 years. Mental model: 'We have to show that we're acting – otherwise we'll lose trust.' Follow-up question: 'What would it take to change this image in the field – and who would need to hear it?'","mini_form":"Quick iceberg in 15 minutes: only two levels – event (what happened?) and pattern (what keeps happening?). Three post-its per person, then cluster. Entry into the structure question as homework.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro","krisensitzung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-15 ideal, up to 25 possible with subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"conflict-map-onion-tree-wheel","name":"Conflict Map/Onion/Tree/Wheel","feld":"D","kurz":"Break down a conflict in a structured way – make actors, causes, and needs behind positions visible.","schritte":["Name the conflict and the analysis goal","Choose ONE tool per session: Map (actors/relationships/alliances), Onion (positions → interests → needs), Tree (roots/trunk/branches), Wheel (six conflict dimensions)","Fill it in together on a large format","Make differences in perspective within the group visible, and let them stand","Derive entry points for working on the conflict"],"zweck":"Break down a conflict in a structured way – make actors, causes, and needs behind positions visible.","hinweise":"The analysis is always perspectival – compare several maps from different subgroups rather than forcing one true map. When NOT to use: with highly escalated conflict parties together without experienced facilitation – the analysis itself then becomes a battleground.","phasen":["verstehen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","konflikt"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Mason/Rychard (CSS ETH Zürich) – Conflict Analysis Tools (PDF)","url":"https://css.ethz.ch/content/dam/ethz/special-interest/gess/cis/center-for-securities-studies/pdfs/Conflict-Analysis-Tools.pdf"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"SCA Training Manual (Cambodia)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Simon Fisher et al.: Working with Conflict (Zed Books, 2000)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Station 1: Conflict Analysis"}],"wann_passt":["Conflict clarification or strategy process (6-20 people), when a complex conflict needs to be visualized: the Onion model separates positions (what we demand) from interests (what we really need) from needs (what we won't negotiate) – decisive for breakthroughs in stuck situations.","Training context (learning format): distinguishing between causes, driving factors, and actors in a conflict (conflict tree/wheel model) makes complexity manageable and creates shared understanding in the team.","Before negotiation processes: conflict map as preparation – who are the actors, what are their positions and interests, where is there overlap?"],"wann_nicht":["In acute escalation without a de-escalation step first: visualization only works if those involved are willing to look at the conflict analytically instead of being emotionally stuck in it.","As an end product instead of a working tool: the map is never 'finished' – it must be updated as the context changes."],"fokusfragen":["\"If we peel the onion: what is each party's official position – and what real interest lies underneath?\" (Onion logic)","\"What are the driving factors keeping the conflict alive – and which of them can we influence?\" (Conflict tree: causes vs. symptoms)","\"Who benefits from this conflict continuing – and who suffers the most?\" (actor analysis)"],"beispiel":"Onion in a team clarification session: two departments are arguing over budget. Position A: 'We need 30% more.' Position B: 'That's not justified.' Onion question to department A: 'What do you really need behind the extra budget?' Interest: planning security for next year. Need: recognition of the strategic importance of the work. Follow-up question: 'How could planning security arise even without 30% more?' – this opens options beyond the original position.","mini_form":"Quick actor map in 15 minutes: a circle in the middle of the flipchart (= the conflict/topic). Then enter all actors around it, arrows depending on the relationship. Three colors: supports / blocks / neutral. Enough as orientation for the next negotiation phase.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","strategie","lernformat"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-20 people","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","angespannt","skeptisch"]},{"id":"cynefin","name":"Cynefin","feld":"D","kurz":"Recognize what kind of problem you're facing – and which mode of action fits it.","schritte":["Introduce the domains: clear, complicated, complex, chaotic, plus confusion","Collect the group's current challenges on cards","Assign the cards to domains together – discuss contested cases","Derive the fitting mode of action per domain","Check consequences: where are we treating something complex as something complicated?"],"zweck":"Recognize what kind of problem you're facing – and which mode of action fits it.","hinweise":"Domains are context-dependent, not fixed labels. Most common mistake: confusing complex with complicated (expert plan instead of experiment). Not a personality grid.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The Cynefin Co – About the Cynefin Framework","url":"https://thecynefin.co/about-us/about-cynefin-framework/"}],"wann_passt":["A leadership team treats different challenges with the same mode of action (best practice for everything) – Cynefin as a diagnostic lens makes visible that complex is not the same as complicated, and what that means for steering.","Strategic planning process in an organization with many different kinds of topics: Cynefin as a sorting heuristic helps allocate resources to the right mode of action (planning, experiment, triage).","Team day or retreat after a crisis: 'What actually was that – chaotic, complex, or complicated?' as a reflection question in hindsight.","Training for leaders or facilitators who want to work in complexity: the framework is easy to learn and sticks as a mental heuristic."],"wann_nicht":["As a personality typology or to categorize people – Cynefin describes situations, not people.","When the decision has factually already been made and the framework would only serve to rationalize it.","As the sole basis for a strategic decision without system analysis – Cynefin classifies, but doesn't analyze."],"fokusfragen":["'Which domain does this problem actually belong to – and how do we justify this classification?' (core question; the classification should be justified, not just felt)","'Where are we currently treating something complex as complicated – i.e. looking for best practice where experiments would be needed?' (error diagnosis)","'What would be the fitting next action for the domain – sense-categorize-respond, probe-sense-respond, or act-sense-respond?' (consequence question)"],"beispiel":"Strategy retreat of an NGO. Topic cards on the table: 'IT migration', 'reach a new target group', 'acute communication conflict with a funder'. Classification: IT migration = complicated (experts can solve it), new target group = complex (unknown, experiments needed), conflict = chaotic (acute need to act, stabilize first). Follow-up question: 'We've only had one mode so far – which of the three needs a different mode of action?'","mini_form":"10-minute Cynefin check: each person assigns their currently most important challenge to a domain and justifies it in one sentence. Discuss only contested cases – these are especially valuable.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","entscheidungstreffen","krisensitzung"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-15 ideal, up to 20 possible","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"fuenf-cs","name":"The 5 Cs","feld":"D","kurz":"Audit and develop an impact network on its five core activities.","schritte":["Introduce the five activities: Clarify · Convene · Cultivate trust · Coordinate · Collaborate","Assess your own network on each C (scale + examples)","Identify gaps: which C is under-resourced?","Develop 1-2 concrete next activities per gap","Agree on responsibilities and rhythm"],"zweck":"Systematically audit and develop an impact network on its five core activities.","hinweise":"The 5 Cs are cyclical, not a stage model – networks keep falling back to Clarify and Cultivate. Don't mistake it for a project plan.","phasen":["planen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"SSIR – Five Steps to Building an Effective Impact Network","url":"https://ssir.org/articles/entry/five_steps_to_building_an_effective_impact_network"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"David Ehrlichman: Impact Networks (Berrett-Koehler, 2021)"}],"wann_passt":["Network review after the first or second year: the 5-Cs grid (Clarify, Convene, Cultivate Trust, Coordinate, Collaborate) gives the network a shared language to assess where it's strong and where it's stuck – without external judgment from outside.","Kick-off of a new network initiative: introduce the 5 Cs as a planning framework and name a minimum activity for each C from the start – this prevents the network from getting stuck in pure convening.","Retreat of a steering group that notices the network is losing strength: which C is under-resourced? Often: Clarify (shared direction has become diluted) or Cultivate Trust (hasn't grown along with growth).","Training on impact networks as a learning format – the 5 Cs are intuitively accessible and immediately applicable to participants' real networks."],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for a project plan – the 5 Cs are cyclical, not sequential; reading them as stages means planning a process that won't work that way.","In an organization that isn't a network – the grid is tailored to loosely coupled multi-actor constellations, not to teams or hierarchies.","As the sole basis for planning without reference to the network's specific history and dynamics – the 5 Cs are a heuristic, not a roadmap."],"fokusfragen":["'On a scale of 1-10: where are we on each C – and what's missing on the weakest one?' (diagnostic opener)","'On Cultivate Trust: when did we last consciously invest time in trust – and what did that trigger?' (concretizing the often-neglected C)","'On Clarify: would all network members phrase our shared purpose identically – or is it quietly diverging?' (check question)"],"beispiel":"Network review: the group rates the 5 Cs on cards (1-5 stars). Result: Convene ★★★★, Coordinate ★★★, Collaborate ★★, Clarify ★★, Cultivate Trust ★. Discussion: 'We meet a lot, but without a clear shared purpose – and we've never explicitly worked on trust.' Next step: a session dedicated just to Clarify (shared purpose workshop) and a network gathering with a personal storytelling format for trust.","mini_form":"5-C quick check in 10 minutes: each C on a flipchart, everyone gives points (sticky dots or tally). Show the result, name one gap, agree on one concrete next activity.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","strategie","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-20 ideal, possible from 3","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"network-weaving","name":"Network Weaving (Holley)","feld":"D","kurz":"Deliberately create connections across silos, instead of hoping for random networking.","schritte":["Sketch your own relationship network: who do I know, who knows whom?","Read the patterns: clusters, bridges, isolated nodes","Closing triangles: identify specific pairs who should know each other","Make connection commitments (who introduces whom to whom, by when)","Set a follow-up date to harvest the new connections"],"zweck":"Deliberately create connections across silos, instead of hoping for random networking.","hinweise":"Weaving is an ongoing task, not a one-off action – name the role of the weavers explicitly. Quality over quantity: a few well-prepared introductions have more impact than address lists.","phasen":["verstetigen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Krebs/Holley – Building Smart Communities through Network Weaving (PDF)","url":"http://www.orgnet.com/BuildingNetworks.pdf"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"June Holley: Network Weaver Handbook (2012)"}],"wann_passt":["Network gatherings with participants who barely know each other or operate in separate clusters – Network Weaving as an explicit exercise: who should know whom here, and why? Concrete introduction commitments with follow-up.","Individual support for a network coordinator who wants to reflect on their weaving practice: sketch their own relationship network, read clusters and bridges, name the next 'closing triangles'.","Strategic phase of a network where new actors need to be brought into the field – Network Weaving as a structured expansion process instead of chance encounters.","Network retreat after growth: 'We have more members, but the old silos have remained' – a weaving exercise to deliberately connect clusters."],"wann_nicht":["In groups where trust is so low that introducing someone to another person feels like an imposition – establish common ground first.","As a one-off event without follow-up: the weaving effect only shows after the second and third connection – without follow-through, the exercise fizzles out.","When the group is too large and there's no clear weaving role or coordination: Network Weaving without a weaver becomes loose networking without direction."],"fokusfragen":["'Who do I know well – and who should these people know each other, but don't yet?' (closing-triangles opener)","'Which connection between two people or organizations in this network would have the biggest multiplier effect?' (strategic weaving question)","'Who is isolated or on the margin of the network – and why? What keeps them there?' (edge-node diagnosis)"],"beispiel":"Network gathering, 15 people from different organizations. Exercise: each person sketches their two most important connections in the room on a card. Then the question: 'Who in the room do you barely know, even though your work overlaps?' Form pairs, 5 minutes to get to know each other. Then: who takes on weaving responsibility for this new connection until the next gathering?","mini_form":"Closing triangles in 10 minutes: each person writes down two names – 'I know both this person and that person well, but they don't know each other.' Brief introduction in the plenary, contact promise.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","kickoff","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-20 ideal; also usable as a coaching tool for individuals","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"trust-building","name":"Trust Building","feld":"D","kurz":"Deliberately and quickly build trust as a network's working infrastructure.","schritte":["Choose a format that combines shared experience with personal sharing","Pair interviews on background and motivation: why are you engaged with this topic?","Harvest commonalities – name the shared ground","Work on a small, real task together","Briefly reflect: how was the collaboration, what built or eroded trust?"],"zweck":"Deliberately and quickly build trust as a network's working infrastructure.","hinweise":"Trust arises from repeated experience, not from a single exercise – rhythm matters more than intensity. Dose personal sharing carefully, overload creates withdrawal.","phasen":["ankommen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team","netzwerk"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern","einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"SSIR – The Tactics of Trust (Ehrlichman/Sawyer)","url":"https://ssir.org/articles/entry/the_tactics_of_trust"}],"wann_passt":["Kick-off of a new coalition or network: before content work begins, half an hour for pair interviews (background, motivation) – this speeds up trust more than any team exercise, because real stories emerge.","After a setback or loss of trust in the team: a small, real shared task (not an exercise!) combined with a follow-up reflection on the collaboration – trust is rebuilt through action, not talk.","Network gatherings with changing participants: don't assume trust, but plan a brief encounter sequence (pair conversation, finding shared commonalities) that turns strangers into acquaintances.","Team development for a distributed, digital team: build an explicit trust-building structure into onsites – design informal time deliberately instead of leaving it to chance."],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for talking about concrete breaches of trust – Trust Building builds infrastructure, but doesn't repair a rupture that needs to be addressed.","When participation isn't voluntary or asymmetries are too great (a supervisor with real authority in the room) – dosed personal sharing then creates pressure instead of safety.","As a one-off action: trust arises from repetition, a single trust-building session without a follow-up rhythm fizzles out."],"fokusfragen":["'What brought you to this topic – what's behind it for you personally?' (motivation question; opens real encounter)","'What did you experience as easy in the task we just did together, what as difficult – and what does that say about our collaboration?' (reflection after a shared task)","'What would you need from this group to really be able to contribute?' (needs question; makes unspoken expectations explicit)"],"beispiel":"Network kick-off, 12 people from 8 organizations. Pair interview (8 minutes): 'Tell me about a moment when you realized this topic really mattered to you.' Then each person introduces their conversation partner. Then a joint mini-task (10 minutes): 'Agree on three words that describe how we want to work together.' Closing: brief reflection on what built trust.","mini_form":"8-minute pair interview as an opener: one question, both speak, then a brief introduction. No further format needed – listening alone builds trust.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","netzwerktreffen","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-20 ideal, up to 30 with parallel pairs/small groups","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"convening","name":"Convening","feld":"D","kurz":"Design encounter spaces so relationships emerge – not just a program running its course.","schritte":["Clarify the precise purpose of the gathering: what should emerge between the people?","Design the participant mix: who must be in the room, which voices are missing?","Plan format and space as relational architecture (seating, small groups, informal time)","Maximize encounter density: long breaks, meals, changing constellations","Plan follow-through: how do the connections that emerged stay alive?"],"zweck":"Design encounter spaces so relationships emerge – not just a program running its course.","hinweise":"Most common mistake: too much program, encounter withers. Convening power is power – whoever invites shapes the field, make the selection transparent.","phasen":["planen","ankommen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["workshop","grossgruppe","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":10,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Rockefeller Foundation – Gather: The Art and Science of Effective Convening (PDF)","url":"https://www.rockefellerfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/Gather-The-Art-and-Science-of-Effective-Convening.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["Planning a network gathering or a professional conference: convening as an explicit design task – who must be in the room? How much program, how much encounter time? What spatial design fosters conversation across silos?","An organization wants to bring together actors from different camps for the first time who otherwise avoid each other – convening as a carefully prepared invitation architecture, where status differences are buffered and common ground is marked.","Network coordination: the recurring host role as an impact strategy – whoever convenes shapes fields. Anchor this meta-awareness in the strategy.","Evaluation question after a gathering: 'Did relationships emerge or did information just flow?' – convening as a quality criterion for events."],"wann_nicht":["When the gathering is primarily about information transfer, not relationship building – then a different format will do.","When the power to invite remains opaque: who invites whom shapes the field politically. Without transparency about this, mistrust arises.","As a hastily thrown-together format without preparing the question and the participant mix – the result is a random meeting, not convening."],"fokusfragen":["'Which relationships should exist after this gathering that didn't exist before – and how do we design the space for that?' (outcome question for convening design)","'Whose voice is missing in the room – and what would it contribute that we don't have without it?' (participant-mix question)","'How much informal time is planned – and is that enough for real encounter?' (time architecture question)"],"beispiel":"Preparing a two-day professional conference. Convening design question: 'Which two people in this field absolutely need to talk to each other?' List of 5 strategic pairs. Design consequence: dinner seating deliberately arranged around these pairs, coffee breaks with changing small-group formats, an open-space block so energy can be followed. Evaluation question at the end: 'Who did you meet today that you urgently want to meet again?'","mini_form":"Convening review in 10 minutes after a gathering: 'Which encounter was most valuable for you – and what made it possible?' Learn from it for next time.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","kickoff","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"No fixed sweet spot – convening is a planning method, not a group-size-bound exercise; relevant from 2 parties to be invited","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"self-organization","name":"Self-Organization","feld":"D","kurz":"Create just enough structure so order emerges from the system itself instead of from above.","schritte":["Define minimal specs: purpose, a few principles, clear boundaries – no more","Give responsibility to self-selected circles/initiatives (whoever has energy, acts)","Set up transparency infrastructure (visible initiatives, open communication)","Regular sense-making rounds: what's emerging, what does the whole need?","Add structure only where friction keeps recurring"],"zweck":"Create just enough structure so order emerges from the system itself instead of from above.","hinweise":"Self-organization doesn't mean structureless – without clear purpose and boundaries it tips into informal power structures (tyranny of structurelessness). The leadership role transforms, it doesn't disappear.","phasen":["planen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Margaret Wheatley – Self-Organization: The Irresistible Future of Organizing","url":"https://margaretwheatley.com/articles/irresistiblefuture.html"}],"wann_passt":["An organization is considering whether and how to reduce hierarchy and introduce decentralized steering – Self-Organization as a framework helps think through the consequences: what do minimal specs need to accomplish? How does leadership change?","Diagnostic moment after growth: 'Our old steering mechanisms no longer fit' – the framework helps ask the right question: what structure is enough for what's supposed to emerge?","Training or strategy input for leaders who want to introduce self-organization: the distinction between structureless and minimally structured is the central learning insight.","Network governance design: how much coordination does a loose network need without killing its energy? Self-Organization as a lens for the design decision."],"wann_nicht":["As a justification for having no structure at all – 'we're self-organized' can become an excuse; the framework actually shows that clear purpose and boundaries are necessary.","In crises that need immediate decisions – self-organization is a slower, distributed process; a crisis needs clear leadership.","When the group has no shared basis for decisions – self-organization presupposes a shared purpose that must be explicitly developed."],"fokusfragen":["'What are the minimal specs for our system – which three to five principles would be enough for the right decisions to emerge?' (governance design question)","'Who currently holds informal power in our system that we haven't made explicit – and how does that play out?' (tyranny-of-structurelessness check)","'Which part of the system currently needs more structure because friction keeps recurring – and why isn't it there yet?' (readjustment question)"],"beispiel":"Workshop with the leadership team of a growing social organization. Question: 'Which decisions should be made decentrally – and what minimal specs need to apply?' Result: three principles (transparency about resources, tying back to purpose, informing the whole system about decisions over X€). Follow-up question: 'What happens if someone violates this – and who notices?' – this opens the governance discussion concretely.","mini_form":"Minimal-specs brainstorm in 15 minutes: 'Which three principles would need to apply for this system to make good decisions without us?' Note silently, then bring together.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","entscheidungstreffen"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-20 as a planning framework; not a group exercise per se","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"netzwerk-vs-hierarchie","name":"Network vs. Hierarchy","feld":"D","kurz":"Gain clarity on when network logic is the right organizational form.","schritte":["Contrast the two logics: hierarchy (control, efficiency) vs. network (emergence, adaptation)","Classify your own initiative: complicated-plannable or complex-distributed?","Check: where are we treating a network problem with hierarchy tools?","Derive consequences for governance, roles, and decision pathways"],"zweck":"Gain clarity on when network logic is the right organizational form – for problems no one can solve alone.","hinweise":"Don't turn this into an either-or debate – most initiatives need both in different zones. Avoid network romanticism: networks are slower at operational decisions.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Converge – Resources on Impact Networks","url":"https://www.converge.net/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"David Ehrlichman: Impact Networks (Berrett-Koehler, 2021)"}],"wann_passt":["An organization or coalition discusses governance questions and wants to know which steering logic fits which part of its work – the framework gives a structured comparison without ideological judgment.","Kick-off of a new cooperation project with several organizations: clarify early on which decisions are made hierarchically (internally) and which network-style (jointly).","Training for leaders working in hybrid structures – the model helps locate one's own organization and consciously work with both logics.","Diagnosis after frustration: 'We're not functioning as a network, even though we aren't one' – the model clarifies the category error."],"wann_nicht":["As a normative argument for or against hierarchy – the model is analytical, not an ideology.","As a substitute for concrete governance decisions: the model shows logics, it doesn't decide.","When the group is too tired or too burdened for conceptual work – then clarify the concrete occasion first."],"fokusfragen":["'Which of our current challenges is plannable-complicated – and which is emergent-distributed?' (classification question)","'Where are we currently applying hierarchy logic to a network problem – or vice versa?' (category-error diagnosis)","'What would concretely differ in decision-making, communication, and steering if we applied network logic to this part?' (consequence question)"],"beispiel":"Strategy retreat of a coalition. Question: 'Which decisions need hierarchy – and which need network?' Card sorting: 'budget decision' → hierarchy (clear accountability), 'develop the technical concept' → network (distributed knowledge), 'public relations' → hierarchy (speed), 'invite new partner organizations' → network (emergence). Insight: we've decided everything through hierarchy so far – that blocks emergence for technical concepts.","mini_form":"10-minute sort: current decisions on cards, two columns (hierarchy/network). Cluster, name one surprise.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","entscheidungstreffen"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-15 ideal","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"systems-oriented-design","name":"Systemic / Systems Oriented Design (Sevaldson)","feld":"D","kurz":"Externalize the complexity of a field together and derive design entry points from it.","schritte":["Define the topic and system boundary","Gigamapping: bring all knowledge onto a very large surface — actors, processes, material flows, history","Draw in relationships, zoom between the detail level and the big picture","ZIP analysis: mark points for Zoom (deepen), Innovation (potential), and Pain (problem)","Derive design tasks from the marked points"],"zweck":"Externalize the complexity of a field together and derive design entry points from it.","hinweise":"The map is allowed to be chaotic — completeness before beauty. Physical (paper, several meters) works considerably better than digital. A major time-eater, so plan generously.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Systems Oriented Design (Birger Sevaldson)","url":"https://systemsorienteddesign.net/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Systems Oriented Design – Gigamapping Introduction (Sevaldson)","url":"https://systemsorienteddesign.net/index.php/giga-mapping/giga-mapping-descriptions/introduction-to-gigamapping"}],"wann_passt":["A design or innovation team wants to visualize the complexity of a social or organizational field before designing solutions — Gigamapping as a radical externalization of all involved factors onto a very large surface.","Retreat of an interdisciplinary team (design, social science, practice) that wants to develop a shared systems language — the mapping process itself generates collective knowledge.","Undertakings with many actors, long time series, and several system levels: SOD is the only format physically large enough to keep everything visible at once.","Research or evaluation context in which qualitative complexity needs to be visualized — ZIP analysis marks areas for deepening (Zoom), potential (Innovation), and pain points (Pain) directly from the map."],"wann_nicht":["Online context: SOD needs a very large paper or whiteboard surface and physical movement in the room — digital boards are a poor substitute.","When time is under 3 hours: Gigamapping needs 3–6 hours for a usable result; in less time a superficial version emerges that frustrates people.","When a clear decision is needed within a short timeframe — SOD is deep analysis, not a decision-making format."],"fokusfragen":["'What belongs to this system altogether — who are the actors, what resources flow, what history is behind it?' (opening expansion question for the gigamap)","'Where on the map does everyone feel pulled deeper — what needs a zoom?' (ZIP analysis: Z)","'Which connections on the map surprise us — what have we never thought together before?' (innovation question, ZIP: I)","'Where is the pain greatest — where does it chafe the most?' (ZIP: P)"],"beispiel":"Retreat on an urban development project. Gigamap on 3×2 meters of paper: actors (city administration, citizens, investors, NGOs), processes (planning procedures, funding applications), material flows (land, building materials, money), history (last 20 years). After 3 hours: ZIP analysis. Zoom on 'informal decision-making channels in the administration.' Innovation: 'Citizens don't know the investors — a direct connection is missing.' Pain: 'Funding applications take 18 months — that kills initiative.' Design task: how do we speed up applications without losing quality?","mini_form":"Quick system map in 20 minutes: only actors and the three most important connections, on A1 paper. Then ask one ZIP question. Not a full gigamapping — but an entry point into systems thinking.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","kickoff"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"3–10 ideal; above 12 the map becomes unmanageable","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"participatory-co-design","name":"Participatory / Co-Design","feld":"D","kurz":"Develop solutions with rather than for those affected — placing lived expertise on equal footing with professional expertise.","schritte":["Win over those affected as equal design partners (not just as interviewees)","Share experiences: make stories, journeys, and lived expertise visible","Develop solution ideas together — everyone designs, no one merely supplies input","Build quick prototypes (paper, role play, mock-up)","Test and iterate with further affected people","Explicitly share decision-making power over the result"],"zweck":"Develop solutions with rather than for those affected — placing expertise from lived experience on equal footing with professional expertise.","hinweise":"The biggest pitfall is tokenism: participation without real decision-making power damages trust lastingly. Keep accessibility, language, and payment of co-designers in mind.","phasen":["planen","oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["verbindung","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"KA McKercher (Beyond Sticky Notes) – What is Co-Design?","url":"https://www.beyondstickynotes.com/what-is-codesign"}],"wann_passt":["Product development or policy design where the solution is intended for groups rarely present in planning processes — co-design brings lived expertise into the room and changes not just the product but the relationship between developer and user.","When existing solutions aren't being adopted even though they seemed well thought out — the likely reason is missing engagement with the actual needs and contexts of those affected.","Community projects in an NGO context: not 'we know what you need' but designing together — as a stance and structural question for the whole process.","Training context: learning co-design as a methodology — showing iterative prototyping with real users in a fast cycle."],"wann_nicht":["When the decision has effectively already been made and co-design is only meant to create legitimacy — tokenism damages trust lastingly and is worse than no co-design at all.","When there are no resources for real field phases: without contact with those affected, co-design stays internal and loses its core.","Without clarity about real decision-making power: when those affected participate but others decide in the end without explanation — that's a violation of the co-design promise."],"fokusfragen":["'Whose experiential knowledge belongs in this question — and who is not yet in the room?' (invitation question before the start)","'What do people experience when they come into contact with our offer — what is easy, what is hard, what is missing?' (journey question from the perspective of those affected)","'What would you build differently if you had the decision-making power — and what would you need for that?' (empowerment question; tests whether co-design is meant seriously)"],"beispiel":"An NGO develops a counseling service for refugees. Co-design session with 6 affected people and 3 staff members. Opening: 'Tell us about a moment when you sought support — what helped, what didn't?' 15 minutes of stories, then cluster insights together. Derive 'How might we…' questions. Build paper prototypes for two ideas. Follow-up question: 'What's still missing — what did we overlook?' — the gaps in the prototype are the most valuable feedback.","mini_form":"How-might-we in 15 minutes: select three insights from conversations with those affected, translate each into an HMW question, generate ideas for 5 minutes. Not a full co-design cycle, but the core of the stance.","anlass_typen":["strategie","kickoff","lernformat","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6–16 ideal (balanced between those affected and designers)","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"service-design","name":"Service Design","feld":"D","kurz":"Examine a service rigorously from the user's perspective and find the breaks between experience and organization.","schritte":["Choose a user persona","Map the journey: all steps and touchpoints of the service from the user's perspective","Add the service blueprint: overlay frontstage (visible) and backstage (processes, systems, roles)","Mark pain points and breaks","Prioritize improvements and sketch them as a prototype"],"zweck":"Examine a service rigorously from the perspective of users and find the breaks between experience and organization.","hinweise":"Build the journey on real data/observations, not on the team's assumptions. Don't leave out backstage — that's usually where the causes of frontstage problems live.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Nielsen Norman Group – Service Design 101","url":"https://www.nngroup.com/articles/service-design-101/"}],"wann_passt":["An organization notices that users drop off or are dissatisfied but doesn't know where — customer/user journey mapping makes visible the breaks that are invisible internally because no one has the end-to-end experience in view.","Optimization workshop: examine an existing offer before redesigning it — journey plus blueprint show what should be optimized rather than replaced.","Interdisciplinary team of frontstage and backstage roles: the service blueprint makes explicit what users see and what happens behind it — builds understanding for the other side's work.","Social-sector context: what experience does an applicant NGO have with a funding program? Service design brings the user perspective into program development."],"wann_nicht":["When the journey map is built from assumptions rather than observations and interviews — then it's a wish map, not service design.","As a purely visual result without consequence: the map only has value if prioritized improvements follow from it.","For very early concept phases where no service yet exists — co-design or human-centered design is the more suitable approach there."],"fokusfragen":["'Which step in the process do users experience as especially draining — and why does that happen?' (pain-point question from the journey)","'What happens backstage at this moment — and does that explain the frontstage pain?' (blueprint connection question)","'Which touchpoint costs us the most resources while creating the least user value?' (optimization priority)"],"beispiel":"Service design workshop for a counseling service. Persona: 'Ayşe, 34, single parent, seeking education counseling.' Journey: search (unclear where to start), phone call (on hold), first meeting (good), waiting for a response (2 weeks, no status update), closure (no follow-up). Blueprint: the wait time backstage = a capacity problem in the booking system. Priority: set up a status-update system, costs little, eliminates the biggest frustration. Follow-up question: 'What would be the cheapest first step toward improvement?'","mini_form":"Journey scan in 15 minutes: only 5 steps (awareness, first contact, use, problem, end). Per step: what do users actually experience? Mark pain points. No blueprint — but the perspective shift happens.","anlass_typen":["strategie","retro","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–12 ideal","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"human-centered-social-design","name":"Human-Centered / Social Design","feld":"D","kurz":"Think design rigorously from human needs — for products as well as for social impact.","schritte":["Inspiration: interviews and observations with the people the design is for","Synthesis: cluster insights, formulate insight statements","Derive 'How might we…?' questions","Ideation: generate a broad range of ideas","Build a quick prototype","Test with users and learn"],"zweck":"Think design rigorously from human needs — for products as well as for social impact.","hinweise":"In a single session the cycle can only be practiced in a fast pass — plan real field phases for actual projects. Danger of extraction: those being researched should benefit from the result.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["person","organisation","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"IDEO.org – Design Kit: Methods","url":"https://www.designkit.org/methods"},{"typ":"online","titel":"IDEO.org – Design Kit: The Field Guide to Human-Centered Design","url":"https://www.designkit.org/resources/1"}],"wann_passt":["Workshop or training session in which participants are meant to experience the design-thinking principle ('starting from the human') — the fast pass (empathize–define–ideate–prototype–test) in 2–3 hours makes the stance tangible.","Early phase of a social innovation initiative where the team doesn't yet know who it's designing for or which problem it's solving — HCD/social design as an exploration process before the solution.","NGO context where offers have historically been defined top-down: HCD as a cultural break that opens the development process toward the community.","Training for social workers or community developers: practicing the stance 'understand first, then design' as a professional principle."],"wann_nicht":["Without a real field/empathy phase: if there's no time for interviews with those affected, HCD stays internal and loses its distinction from ordinary brainstorming.","For politically charged topics without reflecting on the research relationship: who is questioning whom, who benefits from the result? The risk of extraction must be discussed explicitly.","When quick operational decisions are needed — HCD is exploratory and iterative, not a decision-making format."],"fokusfragen":["'What do people confronted with this problem experience — what do they see, feel, do, say?' (empathy-map question)","'How would we formulate the problem from this person's perspective — \"How might we…\"?' (how-might-we focusing question)","'What is the simplest prototype we can use today to learn whether our idea holds up?' (prototyping question — bias towards action)"],"beispiel":"Training workshop for staff of a youth welfare organization. Task: run through the HCD cycle once in 2 hours. Empathize: paired interview within the group ('Tell me about a moment when you felt misunderstood as a teenager'). Define: 'The person needs …, because …, but …' — formulate an insight statement. Ideate: 5 ideas in 5 minutes. Prototype: role play as a prototype for a new way of conducting conversations. Test: feedback in the group. Insight: the cycle works even in miniature — the stance remains.","mini_form":"How-might-we plus 3 ideas in 10 minutes: translate an insight into an HMW question, generate three ideas, select one. No interview needed if a real insight is already available.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","kickoff","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–12 ideal","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"theory-u-presencing","name":"Theory U / Presencing","feld":"D","kurz":"Move from repeating the known toward action guided by the emerging future.","schritte":["Name the topic and explain downloading: recognizing habitual thought patterns","Sensing exercise: empathy interview or perspective shift with an affected person","Moment of silence / guided journaling: what wants to emerge here? What is my part?","Crystallizing: formulate the core intention in one sentence","Define a small prototype step for the next 72 hours"],"zweck":"Move from repeating the known toward action guided by the emerging future.","hinweise":"Presencing phases need trust and voluntariness — don't force silence. Keep the language sober, otherwise pragmatic groups will resist it as esoteric. The full U is a process over weeks, not a single session.","phasen":["vertiefen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["selbstzugang","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"u-school for Transformation – Theory U","url":"https://www.u-school.org/theory-u"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"C. Otto Scharmer: Theory U (2009)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"u.lab – Leading From the Emerging Future (MITx MOOC)","url":"https://www.edx.org/course/u-lab-leading-from-the-emerging-future"}],"wann_passt":["Retreat of a leadership team that is stuck in routines and needs a real shift in perspective — Theory U as a one-day process frame (sensing + presencing + crystallizing), not a multi-day academy.","One-on-one accompaniment or coaching where someone wants to break out of old patterns: the journaling phase ('What wants to emerge here?') as a guided route to self-access.","Network gathering with a future question: when a group stops planning from the past and starts planning from the emerging future — as an entry stance for strategic work.","Training context for facilitators who want to learn to work with depth: understanding the U as a meta-structure, not a rigid format."],"wann_nicht":["In pragmatic, operational groups without warning — silence, presencing, and journaling feel esoteric if not explained and voluntary.","As a single 90-minute session without preparation: the U is a process over weeks; what's possible in one session is a fragment that must be treated as such.","When the group is in acute crisis mode — presencing needs an inner stillness that doesn't arise during a crisis."],"fokusfragen":["'What is the most urgent topic you're currently pushing away — and what would happen if you opened up to it?' (sensing question; opens the downloading pattern)","'What wants to emerge here — not what should, but what wants to?' (presencing question; future perfect instead of planning)","'What is your part in making sure the future that wants to emerge actually emerges — one action in the next 72 hours?' (crystallizing question; anchors presencing in everyday life)"],"beispiel":"Evening retreat with a leadership team. Sensing: 30 minutes of empathy interviews with two people from the target group (brought in person or by video). Presencing: 10 minutes of guided journaling, question: 'What wants to emerge here that isn't here yet?' Respecting silence. Crystallizing: each person formulates one sentence about their personal contribution to the emerging future. Follow-up question: 'What's the smallest step you can take tomorrow?' — not a big action plan, but a concrete starting point.","mini_form":"Presencing moment in 10 minutes: silence (2 min), journaling question 'What wants to emerge here?' (5 min), reading the sentence aloud (3 min). Can close a strategy session and gives the day a different tone.","anlass_typen":["strategie","dialograum","teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6–20 ideal; also works 1:1 as a coaching sequence","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"art-of-hosting","name":"Art of Hosting","feld":"D","kurz":"Create a held space where collective intelligence can work on real questions.","schritte":["Carefully formulate the invitation and the calling question","Open the container: check-in, agreements, presence of the hosts","Choose and run the suitable core structure (circle, world café, open space, pro action café)","Harvesting: make insights visible and take-away-able","Check-out and next steps"],"zweck":"Create a held space where collective intelligence can work on real questions.","hinweise":"The stance (hosting rather than steering) carries the method — tools without the stance feel hollow. Preparing the question is half the work.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["verbindung","klaerung"],"formate":["grossgruppe","workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Art of Hosting – What is the Art of Hosting?","url":"https://artofhosting.org/what-is-aoh/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Peer Canvas – Art of Hosting overview","url":"https://www.peercanvas.com/methodology/art-of-hosting/"}],"wann_passt":["A large network group (20–100 people) with a real open question that requires collective intelligence — Art of Hosting as a meta-frame in which world café, open space, or circle are embedded.","Community processes with distributed expertise and a flat hierarchy: the AoH stance (host rather than steerer) fits these contexts especially well.","Multi-year process accompaniment: AoH as the underlying philosophy for recurring large-format gatherings in a community of practice or network.","Facilitator training: AoH as a school of hosting — the language and stance are themselves the subject, not just the format."],"wann_nicht":["As a full online format: presence in the room, the body, informal encounters, and room design are integral parts — online AoH is significantly weakened.","When fixed outcomes are expected in fixed time slots — AoH follows the energy, not the agenda. Wrong format for decision-making meetings.","As a stand-alone method for inexperienced facilitators: AoH assumes familiarity with the embedded formats (world café, circle, open space)."],"fokusfragen":["'What is the question this group needs to be called for — a question big enough that showing up is worth it?' (calling-question development question; central to AoH design)","'How do I build a container in which people feel safe enough to say the things that really matter?' (host's question; stance, not technique)","'How do we harvest what has emerged — and how do we make it visible and usable for the group?' (harvesting question)"],"beispiel":"Annual network gathering, 60 people. Design: check-in in a circle (25 min), then world café on three calling questions (90 min), then an open-space marketplace for self-organized deep-dive groups (120 min), harvesting in plenary (30 min), check-out. The host group of 4 people developed the questions 4 weeks in advance. Follow-up question during harvesting: 'What is the one thing we want to remember — what do we take home?' — a harvest drawn from the day's energy, not set in advance.","mini_form":"Circle opening in 15 minutes as an AoH mini: everyone in a circle, check-in question, calm facilitation, no comments. Enough to set the hosting stance.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","dialograum","beteiligung","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"20–80 ideal; possible from 8 with a format like circle","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"dynamic-facilitation","name":"Dynamic Facilitation","feld":"D","kurz":"Enable creative breakthroughs on stuck issues by having facilitation follow the energy instead of an agenda.","schritte":["Set up four visible lists: challenges / solution ideas / concerns / information","Follow the group's energy — let whatever is pressing be spoken","Acknowledge every contribution and record it on the matching list","Don't facilitate concerns away — note them; they become new challenges","Wait for and name shifts (breakthroughs) as the group converges","Secure the results and any open threads"],"zweck":"Enable creative breakthroughs on stuck issues by having facilitation follow the energy instead of an agenda.","hinweise":"Requires practiced, fast facilitation (a lot of writing). Don't force an agenda — anyone who needs fixed results in a fixed time should choose a different format.","phasen":["vertiefen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","konflikt"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Co-Intelligence Institute – Dynamic Facilitation","url":"https://www.co-intelligence.org/P-dynamicfacilitation.html"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"IPG Method Library: Dynamic Facilitation (MTB 0043)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Rosa Zubizarreta: From Conflict to Creative Collaboration (2014)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Rosa Zubizarreta – Dynamic Facilitation Associates","url":"http://www.dynamicfacilitation.com/"}],"wann_passt":["A group has been stuck on a topic for months that conventional facilitation can't move forward — dynamic facilitation follows the energy instead of an agenda and enables creative breakthroughs precisely where structured methods create resistance.","A tense team meeting where different positions sit loudly and unheard side by side — the four-list structure (challenges, solutions, concerns, information) makes all contributions equally visible without winners.","A retreat with a complex topic and enough time (at least 3 hours): when the shift (breakthrough) comes, it needs room — dynamic facilitation doesn't work in 60 minutes.","Facilitator training: DF as a school for facilitating without an agenda — practicing following the energy instead of steering it fundamentally changes one's stance."],"wann_nicht":["When a fixed result is expected within a fixed timeframe — dynamic facilitation can deliver breakthroughs at best, but not on a plannable schedule.","For inexperienced facilitators: writing simultaneously across four lists, acknowledging every contribution, and following the energy is technically demanding — experience is a prerequisite.","For very large groups (over 20) without a small-group structure: the energy gets lost, facilitation becomes overwhelmed.","When a party in the room is actively sabotaging, or the group is traumatized — DF needs at least a minimal baseline of mutual trust."],"fokusfragen":["'What is it about this topic that moves you the most — the most urgent thing you want to say right now?' (energy opener; open to any list)","'What is the concern behind your concern — what are you really afraid of?' (deepening question for an objection; turns a blockage into a new challenge)","'What would have to be true for this solution to work — what conditions are behind it?' (solution deepening; opens the information list)"],"beispiel":"Team retreat after an internal conflict. Four lists on flipcharts. Someone says: 'We can't keep working like this.' Facilitation notes it on the challenges list: 'We can't keep working like this.' Acknowledgment: 'I hear that — that's important.' The next person offers a solution ('We need clear rules'). Noted on the solutions list. Someone responds with a concern ('Rules don't help if we don't trust each other'). Noted on the concerns list as a new challenge: 'Trust is missing as a foundation.' No debating, no judging — all four lists fill up. After 60 minutes, often the first shift: the group notices it has been looking at the same problem from different angles.","mini_form":"Four-list quick start in 20 minutes: set up four flipcharts, name the topic, 15 minutes of free association (noted according to energy). Not waiting for a breakthrough — but the energy becomes visible. Can serve as an opener for a longer session.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","dialograum","krisensitzung","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5–15 ideal; useful from 5, above 20 only with very experienced facilitation","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"sociocracy-3","name":"Sociocracy 3.0","feld":"D","kurz":"Make sound decisions that are good enough for now and safe enough to try.","schritte":["Present the proposal (driver: which need of the organization?)","Round of clarifying questions","Reaction round: short assessments, no debate","Gather objections — only reasoned ones: does it harm the purpose, or is it not safe enough to try?","Integrate objections, adjust the proposal","Establish consent and set a review date"],"zweck":"Make sound decisions that are good enough for now and safe enough to try.","hinweise":"Consent is not consensus — it's about the absence of reasoned objections, not everyone's enthusiasm. Hold the round format strictly, otherwise it tips into open discussion.","phasen":["entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["entscheidung","klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Sociocracy 3.0 – Patterns (frei zugänglich)","url":"https://patterns.sociocracy30.org/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Sociocracy 3.0 – free handbook (CC license)","url":"https://patterns.sociocracy30.org/the-handbook.html"}],"wann_passt":["A team or organization makes decisions either by majority vote (creating losers) or by informal consensus (a few decide, others stay silent) — Sociocracy 3.0 / consent round as a third option: objections are integrated instead of overruled.","Governance design in a self-organized or network organization that needs a decision-making structure not requiring central authority — S3 as a full governance system or as an individual pattern like consent decision-making.","Classic recurring meeting where decision points linger in the minutes because no agreement can be reached — consent as a method for these agenda items.","Onboarding new team members into a self-organized structure: practicing consent decision-making as the first S3 pattern, because it's intuitive and shows visible effect."],"wann_nicht":["For routine operational decisions that wouldn't produce objections — avoid overhead, not every decision needs a consent round.","When there are major power imbalances in the room and weaker parties won't voice objections — consent is only as good as the psychological safety in the room.","Without explaining the difference between consent and consensus: if the group thinks it's about everyone's enthusiasm, the format loses its meaning."],"fokusfragen":["'Is there a reasoned objection — that is: does this proposal harm the purpose of our organization, or is it not safe enough to try?' (core consent question; the difference from \"I don't like this\" must be learned)","'What would need to change about the proposal to resolve your objection — what condition must be met?' (objection integration; the objection becomes improvement information)","'Is this proposal good enough for now — and safe enough to try?' (closing question; grants permission for imperfection)"],"beispiel":"Consent decision in an NGO meeting. Proposal: 'Starting next month we'll introduce weekly check-ins.' Clarifying question: 'Does that apply to volunteers too?' Answer: 'No, only paid positions.' Reaction round (30 seconds each): 'Good,' 'I'm unsure if that's enough,' 'Makes sense to me.' Objection: 'Tuesday doesn't work for everyone — that excludes some people.' Integration: 'We'll set the day together.' Consent: 'Is there still a reasoned objection?' — Silence. 'We are in consent.' Review date set for 6 weeks out.","mini_form":"Quick consent in 10 minutes: proposal in one sentence, one round for objections (only reasoned ones, 30 seconds per person), integration if needed, establish consent. Without the clarifying and reaction rounds, for simple decisions.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","regeltermin","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–12 ideal; up to 20 with practiced facilitation","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"schreibgespraech","name":"Written Conversation (IPG)","feld":"D","kurz":"Hold a conversation without speaking — give quiet voices equal weight and enable simultaneity.","schritte":["Distribute posters with questions or statements around the room","Silent writing: everyone writes their thoughts directly onto the posters","Respond in writing to others' contributions — arrows, comments, questions","Rotate between posters","Joint walk-through and verbal review of the discussion threads"],"zweck":"Hold a conversation without speaking — give quiet voices equal weight and enable simultaneity.","hinweise":"Hold the silence consistently, otherwise the method loses its core. Good questions determine the depth. Works well online with a collaborative document/board.","phasen":["vertiefen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["schriftlich","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Methodenkartei Uni Oldenburg – Schreibgespräch","url":"https://www.methodenkartei.uni-oldenburg.de/methode/schreibgespraech/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"IPG Method Library: Written Conversation / Schreibgespräch (MTB 0043)"}],"wann_passt":["A workshop with a group in which typically 2–3 people dominate and the rest stay silent — the written conversation forces simultaneity and makes quiet voices visible without slowing down the loud ones.","A hierarchical environment (a department with leadership in the room): writing lowers the perceived social risk — critical or contradictory points appear on posters before they have to be spoken aloud.","Training or a workshop where many questions need to be addressed at once: 4–6 posters, everyone rotates — more coverage in 30 minutes than in a 60-minute plenary discussion.","Online setting with a collaborative board (Miro, Mural): the written conversation works very well digitally, because simultaneity and silence are preserved in the digital space too."],"wann_nicht":["When silence can't be maintained (moderated exceptions become the rule) — then the method loses its core.","For a group with very low willingness to write, or language barriers: writing can exclude.","As an opening format for a group that doesn't know each other yet and needs orientation — start with a short verbal encounter first, then the written conversation."],"fokusfragen":["'What is your most honest assessment of this topic — what would you say if you were sure it had no consequences?' (poster question; opens up what wouldn't be said in conversation)","'What do we as a group overlook on this topic — which aspect never comes up?' (blind-spot question)","'What would I answer my colleague who just left this comment on the poster?' (response impulse; creates a real dialogue on paper)"],"beispiel":"Workshop on improvement ideas in a team (12 people, leadership in the room). Four posters with questions: 'What's going well?', 'What bothers us?', 'What haven't we dared to say yet?', 'What would we change if we could?' 10 minutes of silent writing, rotating. Then 5 minutes: comment on others' contributions (arrows, exclamation marks, additions). Review: joint walk-through, leadership reads first without commenting. Follow-up question: 'What surprised us?' — the surprise is usually the most honest part.","mini_form":"One-poster written conversation in 10 minutes: one poster, one question, 5 minutes writing, 3 minutes responding to others' contributions. A mini version is enough as an opener for a plenary discussion.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","retro","teamtag","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6–25 ideal; up to 30 with enough posters","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","muede","angespannt","neugierig"]},{"id":"psychologische-sicherheit","name":"Psychological Safety (Edmondson)","feld":"D","kurz":"Create the condition under which teams learn, report mistakes, and dare to try new things.","schritte":["Introduce the concept: safety to take interpersonal risks (questions, mistakes, disagreement) without punishment","Anonymous quick diagnosis using the 7 Edmondson items","Review the results together — without a blame hunt","Collect situations: when did I stay silent here even though I wanted to say something?","Make team agreements for safer practice","Leadership goes first: share their own mistakes/uncertainty first"],"zweck":"Create the condition under which teams learn, report mistakes, and dare to try new things.","hinweise":"Psychological safety is not a cuddly norm — it belongs together with high performance standards. Don't force anyone into openness, that produces the opposite effect.","phasen":["verstehen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["vertrauen","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"McKinsey Explainers – What is psychological safety?","url":"https://www.mckinsey.com/featured-insights/mckinsey-explainers/what-is-psychological-safety"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Amy Edmondson: The Fearless Organization (2018)"}],"wann_passt":["A team diagnostic moment: why don't we learn from mistakes, why do concerns never come up in meetings — Edmondson's framework gives the diagnosis a language and makes the invisible phenomenon discussable.","Leadership training: introduce psychological safety as a concept and work through its connection to the learning curve and error culture — especially effective because it makes leadership visible as an influencing variable.","Team development after a setback or public criticism: the diagnosis (how safe does the team really feel?) as a structured entry into a conversation about team climate.","Organizational development: as a diagnostic lens in a culture analysis — in which teams and under which leaders is psychological safety high, and in which is it not?"],"wann_nicht":["As instructions for a one-off exercise: psychological safety is not a format but a condition — it emerges through behavior over time, not through a single session.","When the leader in the room isn't ready to share their own uncertainty: without this act of going first, the concept stays academic and the diagnosis superficial.","As an excuse concept for lacking performance: safety without challenge (Edmondson's learning zone) doesn't produce a learning culture, but a comfort zone."],"fokusfragen":["'When did you recently not say something you thought was important — and what held you back?' (behavioral diagnosis; concrete, not abstract)","'As a leader: what mistake have I made that I believe would be important for the team to hear?' (going-first question; leadership opens the space)","'On a scale of 1–10: how safe does it feel to share an unfinished idea in this team — and why?' (scale question; makes the perception explicit and discussable)"],"beispiel":"Team development after a crisis situation in which a problem escalated that the team had seen coming for a long time. Opening: brief explanation of the framework (10 min). Anonymous quick diagnosis with three items: 'I can admit mistakes,' 'I can criticize leadership,' 'I can bring up an idea that might sound stupid.' Show the results. Then the question: 'What did we not say during the crisis — and why?' Follow-up question: 'What would leadership need to do differently first so it gets said next time?' — leadership takes notes and responds concretely.","mini_form":"Quick psychological-safety check in 10 minutes: three items on sticky dots (1–5), anonymous on a flipchart. Show the result, make one observation, name one consequence. No full diagnostic format needed.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","retro","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–15 ideal as a full diagnostic; up to 30 as a concept input","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"trust-equation","name":"Trust Equation (Maister)","feld":"D","kurz":"Translate trust from a feeling into four influenceable behavioral dimensions.","schritte":["Introduce the formula: trust = (credibility + reliability + intimacy) ÷ self-orientation","Self-assessment: each person rates themselves on the four dimensions","Exchange in pairs with examples: how would someone notice this about me…?","Derive 1–2 concrete behavior changes per person (often: lower self-orientation, increase intimacy)","Record commitments"],"zweck":"Translate trust from a feeling into four influenceable behavioral dimensions.","hinweise":"The denominator (self-orientation) has the strongest effect and is the most reluctantly discussed. Use it as a self-reflection tool, not to judge others.","phasen":["verstehen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["vertrauen","selbstzugang"],"formate":["workshop","coaching","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Trusted Advisor Associates – Understanding the Trust Equation","url":"https://trustedadvisor.com/why-trust-matters/understanding-trust/understanding-the-trust-equation"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Maister/Green/Galford: The Trusted Advisor (2000)"}],"wann_passt":["Coaching or individual reflection: someone is perceived as 'untrustworthy' and doesn't understand why — the four dimensions (credibility, reliability, intimacy, self-orientation) as a diagnostic tool to find one's own blind spot.","Leadership development: treating trust as an influenceable behavioral variable rather than a personality trait — the tool demystifies trust and gives concrete entry points.","Pair reflection in a team development process: two people in tension with each other each reflect on their own trust equation — not evaluating the other person, but themselves.","Training for consultants and coaches: the trust equation as an orientation for professional relationships — especially self-orientation (the denominator) as the main lever for professional service providers."],"wann_nicht":["As a tool to judge others — 'I'm analyzing your trust equation' breaks a relationship, it doesn't build trust.","As a first intervention in highly escalated conflicts — the reflection is a calm tool and needs a stable frame.","When the group doesn't yet have enough trust to talk about self-orientation — the denominator is sensitive and needs psychological safety."],"fokusfragen":["'On which of the four dimensions are you weakest in your own view — and what would be a concrete behavior you could change there?' (self-reflection question after the self-assessment)","'What would someone need to see from you to experience your reliability — what is a promise you could keep in the next two weeks?' (behavioral question for reliability)","'If you're honest: in which situations does your own interest come before that of the other person — and what drives that?' (self-orientation question; the most productive and most uncomfortable point)"],"beispiel":"Coaching session. Leader X is perceived by the team as unreliable, even though X feels very competent professionally. Introduce the trust equation. Self-assessment: credibility high (competence), reliability medium (sometimes forgets commitments), intimacy low (never shows uncertainty), self-orientation high (talks a lot about their own projects). Diagnosis: the denominator is large. Follow-up question: 'What would happen if you shared something that's really hard for you in the next team meeting — and asked for advice instead of informing?' A week later: feedback that the meeting felt different.","mini_form":"Trust equation in 5 minutes: show the formula, self-score on the four dimensions (1–10), formulate one sentence about the consequence. Built in as an impulse in a leadership training.","anlass_typen":["coaching","lernformat","teamtag"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1:1 ideal; up to 8 possible as a group reflection","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","belastet"]},{"id":"grit-reziprozitaet","name":"GRIT / Graduated Reciprocity (Osgood)","feld":"D","kurz":"Reverse a downward spiral of mistrust through calculated unilateral concessions.","schritte":["Present the logic: announced, unilateral, verifiable de-escalation steps invite reciprocation","Brainstorm small, low-risk first steps that don't endanger one's own core interests","Formulate the first step plus a public announcement","Set criteria: how do we recognize reciprocation, how do we verify it?","Agree on a continuation and abort plan"],"zweck":"Reverse a downward spiral of mistrust through calculated unilateral concessions.","hinweise":"Steps must be verifiable and costly enough to be taken seriously. When NOT: during acute violence, or when the other side systematically exploits concessions without ever reciprocating.","phasen":["konflikt","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["vertrauen","konflikt"],"formate":["coaching","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"International Online Training Program on Intractable Conflict – Step-by-Step De-escalation (GRIT)","url":"https://www.intractableconflict.org/www_colorado_edu_conflict/peace/treatment/grit.htm"}],"wann_passt":["A conflict dyad in an organization or network is stuck in a mistrust spiral where neither side wants to make the first move because it believes it would be exploited — GRIT as a structured de-escalation logic for exactly this stalemate.","Conflict accompaniment after long escalation: when mediation isn't yet possible because trust for direct conversations is missing — GRIT as a preliminary stage that restores the capacity to act without immediate contact.","Strategic conflict analysis in a coalition with feuding camps: GRIT as a conceptual input to enable the group to create movement through calculated small gestures.","International contexts: GRIT originates in arms control (Osgood, Cold War) and is especially robust with institutionalized conflict parties."],"wann_nicht":["During acute violence or threat — GRIT assumes both sides are safe enough to make concessions.","When one side systematically exploits concessions without ever reciprocating — then GRIT stabilizes the mistrust system instead of resolving it.","As a first intervention in a freshly escalating conflict without analysis — understand the dynamic first, then plan calculated steps."],"fokusfragen":["'What would be a small, costly but low-risk step we could take unilaterally — verifiable, publicly announceable, without endangering our core interests?' (GRIT core question; the step must satisfy all three conditions)","'How would we recognize that the other side is reciprocating our step — and what timeframe do we accept?' (verification and patience question)","'What is our plan B if there's no reciprocation after three steps?' (abort criterion; without this GRIT is unilateralism without a strategy)"],"beispiel":"Two departments in an organization have been fighting over jurisdiction for a year. No more direct conversations. GRIT strategy: department A publicly announces (in an all-hands) that it will hand over a contested resource to the other department for 3 months without demanding anything in return. Announcement: 'We believe trust also has to come from us.' Verification: visible in the next quarterly report. Expectation: department B responds with its own small gesture. If not: offer a conversation after three months rather than escalating.","mini_form":"GRIT planning in 20 minutes: step 1 — what is a first step? Step 2 — is it verifiable and public? Step 3 — when and how to announce it? Three questions as a checklist, not a full process.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"Conflict coaching for 1–2 parties; up to 12 as an analysis session","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"confidence-building-measures","name":"Confidence Building Measures","feld":"D","kurz":"Create a baseline of security between mistrustful parties through institutionalized transparency and reliability.","schritte":["Gather the sources of mistrust between the parties (lack of transparency, misinterpretations, incidents)","Introduce types of measures: communication, transparency, verification, behavioral rules","Brainstorm concrete measures for one's own context","Sequence the low-threshold ones first — plan a series, not a single measure","Agree on monitoring and a review rhythm"],"zweck":"Create a baseline of security between mistrustful parties through institutionalized transparency and reliability.","hinweise":"A single CBM achieves little — the effect lies in the series. CBMs don't replace working on the core conflict, they make it possible.","phasen":["konflikt","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["vertrauen","konflikt"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Beyond Intractability – Confidence-Building Measures","url":"https://www.beyondintractability.org/essay/confidence_building_measures"}],"wann_passt":["The start of cooperation between actors who mistrust each other and must begin formal collaboration (mergers, new coalitions, post-conflict structures) — CBMs as a structured build-up of baseline security before the substantive work.","Network governance design in a field with historically mistrustful organizations: which transparency and communication measures does it take to make cooperation possible?","Organizational development after a breach of trust (e.g., restructuring, layoffs): CBMs as a formal plan that shows what leadership is doing to regain reliability.","International or interorganizational project cooperation with unequal partners: CBMs as an explicit agreement on information flow, decision transparency, and reporting obligations."],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for working through the core conflict — CBMs create conditions but don't resolve causes.","When one side isn't willing to show transparency — then the measure is one-sided and stabilizes mistrust instead of reducing it.","As a one-off action: CBMs work as a series of building steps, not as a single gesture."],"fokusfragen":["'What are the three sources of mistrust between us — lack of transparency, past injuries, misinterpretations? Which is the strongest?' (diagnostic opener)","'Which piece of information, if shared regularly and reliably, would reduce mistrust the most?' (core CBM question; targets communication measures)","'How do we build a sequence — what comes first because it costs the least and shows the most?' (sequencing question; order matters)"],"beispiel":"Two organizations in a coalition mistrust each other after a resource conflict. CBM planning: measure 1 (immediate): a weekly 30-minute update conversation between coordinators. Measure 2 (month 2): open budget reporting for coalition funds. Measure 3 (month 4): a joint meeting with partners from the field that shows both roles. Review after 6 months: has mistrust decreased? Follow-up question: 'What has changed — and what still needs more transparency?'","mini_form":"CBM brainstorm in 15 minutes: name one measure per source of mistrust. Agree only on the first — cheapest and most visible — as a commitment. Review in 4 weeks.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","kickoff","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2–15 (representatives of mistrustful parties)","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","belastet"]},{"id":"contact-hypothesis","name":"Contact Hypothesis (Allport)","feld":"D","kurz":"Reduce prejudice between groups through well-designed, equal-status contact.","schritte":["Check Allport's four conditions: equal status in the situation, a common goal, cooperation instead of competition, institutional support","Choose a real cooperative task (building something together, not debating)","Establish equal status in the situation (roles, speaking time, setting)","Enable personal encounters (pairs/small groups instead of blocs)","Debrief: reflect on the experience and plan follow-up contacts"],"zweck":"Reduce prejudice between groups through well-designed, equal-status contact.","hinweise":"Poorly designed contact can reinforce prejudice — the four conditions are the mechanism of effect, not decoration. When NOT: with a large, unbalanced power imbalance or an acute threat situation without a protective frame.","phasen":["oeffnen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","grossgruppe","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":40,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Simply Psychology – Contact Hypothesis (Intergroup Contact Theory)","url":"https://www.simplypsychology.org/contact-hypothesis.html"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Gordon Allport: The Nature of Prejudice (1954)"}],"wann_passt":["Designing encounter formats between polarized groups (interreligious, interethnic, pro/con): Allport's four conditions as a quality checklist for any encounter architecture — not what's planned, but whether the conditions are really met.","Evaluation lens for existing formats: 'Our exchange program barely has an effect' — the contact hypothesis explains why, if status wasn't equal or no common goal was set.","Training for conflict facilitators and community developers: the framework is the theoretical foundation for encounter design and essential for anyone working between groups.","Policy consulting for integration or exchange programs: the four conditions as an analytical frame to evaluate and improve existing programs."],"wann_nicht":["Poorly designed contact (without Allport's conditions) can reinforce prejudice instead of reducing it — that's the central warning of the framework. Any encounter format without checking the conditions is potentially counterproductive.","With a large structural power imbalance and no protective frame: if one group has historically dominated the other, encounter alone isn't enough — structural questions must be addressed.","As an immediate solution in an acute conflict: contact works as a medium- to long-term approach, not as crisis intervention."],"fokusfragen":["'Do all those involved have equal status in this situation — and what specifically is planned to neutralize status inequality in the encounter?' (condition-1 check)","'What is the common goal that all groups share and that requires cooperation — and is it really shared or merely assigned?' (condition-2 check)","'What institutional support signals that this encounter is legitimate and desired — and if it's missing, what would be the consequence?' (condition-4 check)"],"beispiel":"Evaluation of an intercultural youth dialogue. Contact hypothesis as an analysis grid: equal status? Partly — the host group had more resources and proficiency in the lingua franca. Common goal? Vaguely formulated ('experiencing exchange' is not a cooperative goal). Cooperation instead of competition? A joint task was included, but there wasn't enough time. Institutional support? Present. Diagnosis: conditions 1 and 2 weren't sufficiently met — the contact effect was therefore weak. Consequence for next year: a clear joint task, language adaptation, mixed roles.","mini_form":"Allport checklist in 10 minutes: go through four questions (one per condition) for a planned format. Rate each condition: met / partly / not met. Formulate the gaps as a design task.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","konfliktklaerung","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"Not a group exercise — a diagnostic tool for designers and facilitators; as a learning format up to 20","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"vulnerabilitaet","name":"Vulnerability (Brown/Lencioni)","feld":"D","kurz":"Lower the perceived risk in a team through dosed displays of weakness and enable trust-based collaboration.","schritte":["Leadership/facilitation goes first: share a real learning experience or weakness","Personal histories exercise: each person shares their background, a formative challenge, and a source of pride","Listen without comment, then a short acknowledgment","Connect it to the collaboration: what helps us understand each other better?","Agree on how the team handles what has been shared (confidentiality)"],"zweck":"Lower the perceived risk in a team through dosed displays of weakness and enable trust-based collaboration.","hinweise":"Strictly voluntary — forced intimacy destroys trust. Adjust the depth of questions to the group's maturity level; not a substitute for therapy. When NOT: as an opener in freshly feuding or highly politicized groups.","phasen":["ankommen","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["vertrauen","selbstzugang"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung","coaching"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Brené Brown – The Power of Vulnerability (TED Talk)","url":"https://www.ted.com/talks/brene_brown_the_power_of_vulnerability"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Patrick Lencioni: The Five Dysfunctions of a Team (2002); Brené Brown: Daring Greatly (2012)"}],"wann_passt":["A team day or retreat where relationship depth is meant to be built explicitly — introducing vulnerability as an impulse: leadership or facilitation goes first, sharing something real. That's the mini form that moves the most.","Onboarding or team development in a new group: the personal histories exercise (Lencioni) as a structured frame in which vulnerability is practiced in doses — questions about background, challenges, and pride.","Leadership training: understanding vulnerability as a professional strength — the opposite of weakness, rather a condition for trust. Brown's research as a learning impulse.","Coaching: which moments in everyday work could be used for self-disclosure — without turning into therapy?"],"wann_nicht":["As an opener in freshly feuding or politicized groups — forced or involuntary intimacy creates mistrust, not trust.","As a mandatory exercise without voluntariness — those who don't want to open up don't have to. Pressure is the opposite of the stance.","When the depth of the questions doesn't match the group's maturity level — better to start low-threshold and increase than to go too deep too soon."],"fokusfragen":["'As a leader or facilitator: what is something that's really hard for me — and that I'm willing to share today?' (going-first question; only for the person opening the space)","'What is a situation that was hard for you — and what did you learn from it?' (low-threshold invitation; not too personal, but real)","'What would it mean for you to be more vulnerable in this group — what would need to be there for that?' (conditions question; respects that vulnerability needs safety)"],"beispiel":"Team day, a new leader on the team. Instead of a get-to-know-you round, the leader shares something real first: 'When I stepped into this role, my biggest doubt was whether I could win the team's trust — and I'm still not sure about that.' Pause. Then an invitation: 'Whoever wants to can also share something that's on their mind right now.' Voluntary. What happens: almost everyone shares something. The room has changed — in 5 minutes. The rest of the day has a different quality.","mini_form":"Going first in 3 minutes: leadership or facilitation shares a real uncertainty. No invitation to the group needed — this act alone opens the space.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","kickoff","coaching"],"typ":"haltung","gruppen_sweetspot":"3–12 ideal; above 15 the intimacy becomes too thin","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"check-in-rituale","name":"Check-in Rituals","feld":"D","kurz":"Establish presence and visibility for everyone and open and close a reliable container.","schritte":["Choose a fixed opening question (from light: How are you arriving? to deeper: What's really on your mind right now?)","Answer briefly in turn — every voice sounds once in the room","No commenting, no dialogue","At the end of the session, close with a check-out as a mirror (insight, feeling, next step)","Establish it as a recurring ritual — the repetition creates the effect"],"zweck":"Establish presence and visibility for everyone and open and close a reliable container for the collaboration.","hinweise":"Adjust the depth of the question to the context and time budget. In large groups, use small groups or a one-word round. Gently time-box people who talk a lot.","phasen":["ankommen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["vertrauen","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":20,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Hyper Island Toolbox – Check-in / Check-out","url":"https://toolbox.hyperisland.com/check-in-check-out"}],"wann_passt":["The start of any meeting or workshop lasting more than 20 minutes: a check-in establishes presence and gives everyone an initial voice in the room — prevents only 2–3 people from talking for the first 10 minutes.","A tired or exhausted group in the afternoon: a short check-in ('What are you bringing with you right now?') pulls people out of autopilot and makes energy visible — better than a coffee break with no contact.","Online meetings: a check-in is even more important in the digital space, because nonverbal presence is missing — a short round gives the room a body.","Regular team meetings as a ritual: check-in plus check-out as a reliable bracket that gives orientation — over weeks, trust arises through repetition, not through a single exercise."],"wann_nicht":["In very large groups (30+) without a subgroup format: a full round takes too long then and drains energy instead of opening it.","When the question is too deep or too personal for the context — a one-hour project meeting with 'What's really moving you today?' overwhelms and feels inauthentic.","As a mandatory ritual experienced as such — better to leave it out or simplify the question."],"fokusfragen":["'What are you bringing into this room right now — in one word or one sentence?' (standard check-in; low-threshold, works for any context)","'What is one thing on your mind today — outside of this meeting?' (deeper check-in; makes the person visible, not just the role)","'What do you need from this meeting for it to be worthwhile for you?' (outcome-open check-in; makes expectations explicit and allows for adjustment)"],"beispiel":"Online recurring meeting, 8 people, 45 minutes. Check-in question: 'In one word: how are you right now?' Round goes through, 30 seconds per person, no comments. Result: 3 people say 'tired,' 2 say 'stressed.' Facilitation decision: shorten the agenda, put the most important topic first. Check-out at the end: 'What are you taking with you?' — in one sentence. Result: the meeting has a quality it would otherwise lack, because people briefly became visible.","mini_form":"One-word check-in in 3 minutes: ask the question ('One word for how you're arriving'), go around, no comments, move on. Can't get shorter — and it still works.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","teamtag","kickoff","lernformat"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"2–25 ideal; for larger groups only as subgroups or as the one-word variant","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","angespannt","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"cultivate-trust","name":"Cultivate Trust (Ehrlichman)","feld":"D","kurz":"Tend to trust as a permanent core activity of a network — the third C of the 5 Cs.","schritte":["Build regular personal encounters into the network's rhythm (not just working sessions)","Create space for stories and motivations — why is everyone here?","Practice reliability: make small commitments and visibly keep them","Address tensions early and directly instead of letting them fester","Regularly reflect together on the state of trust"],"zweck":"Tend to trust as a permanent core activity of a network — the third C of the 5 Cs.","hinweise":"Trust in networks is infrastructure, not a byproduct — budget explicit time for it. In distributed networks, prioritize in-person meetings; they carry for months.","phasen":["verstetigen","ankommen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Chief Executive – How To Cultivate An Impact Network: 5 Core Activities","url":"https://chiefexecutive.net/how-to-cultivate-an-impact-network-5-core-activities/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"David Ehrlichman: Impact Networks (Berrett-Koehler, 2021)"}],"wann_passt":["Network design: as a planning stance that reminds people trust needs explicit time — every network meeting design asks, 'Where is the space for encounter, not just for the program?'","Network review: as a diagnostic question — 'How much of our shared time goes toward trust? Is that enough?' The third C of the 5 Cs as a checkpoint.","Training for network coordinators: introducing cultivate trust as a permanent core task, not a one-off action — the rhythm is the method.","As a pre-check before an intensive network phase: 'Is trust strong enough for what we're about to do — or do we need to invest in trust first?'"],"wann_nicht":["As a stand-alone format alongside the 5 Cs: cultivate trust is the third C and has its place as a stance within the 5 Cs system — as an isolated standalone format it loses its distinctiveness from general trust-building.","As a justification for endless relationship management without substantive progress — trust is infrastructure, not an end in itself.","In a group that already has high trust and now wants to deliver — prioritizing trust activities then becomes an energy drain."],"fokusfragen":["'How much time in our last three network meetings was explicitly for trust and relationship — and what was the result?' (audit question for an existing network)","'Which simple recurring structure would strengthen trust in our network the most — and cost little?' (rhythm question; aimed at sustainability)","'What is the trust problem in our network — too little time for each other, too little reliability, or too little directness with tensions?' (differentiation question; not all trust problems are the same)"],"beispiel":"Network annual review. Question: 'How did we live cultivate trust as the third C this year?' Result: we had 4 joint content meetings, but not a single meeting focused on relationship. Consequence: build an in-person meeting with an explicit trust design into next year's plan (dinner, personal stories, no program after 6 pm). Follow-up question: 'Who takes responsibility for that?'","mini_form":"Trust audit in 10 minutes: look at the last three meetings — how much time was there for trust? Enough, too little, or none at all? Formulate one consequence for the next meeting.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","retro","strategie"],"typ":"haltung","gruppen_sweetspot":"As a stance: no group needed; as an audit: 3–15 people from the network","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"conflict-transformation","name":"Conflict Transformation (Lederach)","feld":"E","kurz":"Understand conflict as an opportunity for lasting change in relationships and structures rather than just a problem to shut down.","schritte":["Describe the current conflict situation — lens 1: the immediate episode","Lens 2: the epicenter — which relationship patterns and structures keep producing such episodes?","Lens 3: the future picture — which relationships and structures do we want instead?","Connect the answers: short-term resolution of the episode plus long-term work on the epicenter","Set first steps on both time horizons"],"zweck":"Understand conflict as an opportunity for lasting change in relationships and structures rather than just a problem to shut down.","hinweise":"Don't frame it as a quick fix — transformation thinks in years. Still take the episode seriously, otherwise the acute distress feels dismissed. When NOT: when immediate protection from violence takes priority.","phasen":["verstehen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["konflikt","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Beyond Intractability – Conflict Transformation (Lederach)","url":"https://www.beyondintractability.org/essay/transformation"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"John Paul Lederach: The Little Book of Conflict Transformation (2003)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peacebuilding Practice (Woman PeaceMaker Program, 2023) – Chapter 2: Conflict Transformation"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"John Paul Lederach: The Moral Imagination – The Art and Soul of Building Peace – Kapitel 5: On Peace Accords"}],"wann_passt":["An introductory or orientation format (learning format, 10–30 people), when a group needs to understand the difference between conflict resolution (short-term, symptom-focused) and conflict transformation (long-term, relationship-focused) and apply it to their own work.","A reflection round after a negotiation or mediation that was formally 'successful' but built no trust — conflict transformation asks about the relational foundation, not just the outcome.","A strategy conversation in organizations working in complex conflict contexts: when is it worth investing more deeply in relationship work instead of pursuing quick fixes?"],"wann_nicht":["In acute crisis situations where the capacity to act is what's needed — conflict transformation is a long-term frame, not a crisis protocol.","As a substitute for concrete methodological know-how: the concept alone doesn't replace competence in mediation, dialogue, or community processes.","When the group is only looking for quick fixes and brings no willingness to think about systemic causes."],"fokusfragen":["\"What would change if this conflict were really transformed — not just resolved, but processed in a way that strengthened the relationships?\" (transformation horizon)","\"Where in this conflict is the real injury — and who carries it?\" (uncovering the relational level)","\"What would be a first concrete sign that a transformation is beginning — which behavior, which gesture?\" (entry point into practice)"],"mini_form":"Quick reflection 'resolution vs. transformation' in 10 minutes: two columns. The team names differences: what would a 'resolution' of this conflict look like? What would a 'transformation' look like? The contrast alone creates orientation.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","dialograum","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"6–25 people","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"glasl-eskalation","name":"Glasl's Escalation Stages","feld":"E","kurz":"Diagnose the escalation level of a conflict and align the form of intervention with it.","schritte":["Introduce the nine stages in three levels: win-win (1–3), win-lose (4–6), lose-lose (7–9)","Rate your own conflict based on concrete behavioral observations","Estimate at which stage the other side experiences the conflict (often higher)","Derive the suitable form of intervention: facilitation (1–3), process accompaniment/mediation (4–6), power intervention (7–9)","Determine next steps and, if needed, external support"],"zweck":"Diagnose the escalation level of a conflict and align the form of intervention with it.","hinweise":"A diagnostic tool, not a working process. Self-rating is systematically biased (milder toward one's own side). When NOT: don't have highly escalated parties rate the conflict together — that turns immediately into mutual blame; from stage 6–7 on, no more self-help.","phasen":["verstehen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["konflikt","klaerung"],"formate":["coaching","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Thomas Jordan (Mediate.com) – Glasl's Nine-Stage Model Of Conflict Escalation","url":"https://mediate.com/glasls-nine-stage-model-of-conflict-escalation/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Friedrich Glasl: Konfliktmanagement (1980, laufend aktualisiert)"}],"wann_passt":["Coaching with a leader before a planned conflict intervention: the model gives them a realistic picture of the escalation stage and prevents them from approaching a situation with facilitation offers that actually needs external power intervention (stage 7+).","Training for HR staff or mediators: the nine stages as a teaching unit — with case vignettes that the group rates. Very effective for learning, because everyone has an opinion and the differences carry the conversation.","Consulting conversation with a team that has an ongoing conflict and wants to know what support it needs: Glasl gives a shared language for the severity."],"wann_nicht":["Having both conflict parties apply the model together — from stage 4 on, the joint rating immediately turns into the next round of escalation (mutual blame over who rates higher).","Using it as a self-help tool from stage 6-7 on — that requires external power intervention or escalation-stopping measures, not reflection.","As the sole basis for intervention decisions: the model diagnoses but doesn't replace a context analysis of the specific constellation."],"fokusfragen":["At which stage would you place the conflict — and at which stage do you see the other party? (surfacing self- vs. other-perception)","What is happening in this constellation that leads you to place it at stage X — which behavior, which escalation dynamic? (gathering concrete observations)","What kind of support would realistically be needed at this stage? (deriving the intervention)"],"beispiel":"Coaching opener: picture the nine stages as a staircase — stage 1 is a difference of opinion, stage 9 is the point where both sides accept their own destruction in order to harm the other side. Where on this staircase do you stand? The person answers: maybe stage 4 or 5. Coach: what do you observe concretely that places it there? The person describes coalition-building and communication breakdown. Coach: where do you think the other side would place itself? — Often the other side is higher. Then: at stage 4-5 facilitation alone won't be enough anymore — have you considered whether professional process accompaniment would make sense? Purpose: the model creates a shared language and realistically shows which form of intervention is needed.","mini_form":"Stage self-assessment: each person anonymously enters (e.g. via Mentimeter) their estimate of the escalation stage. Show the distribution and discuss the differences — 10 minutes, very revealing in groups.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","coaching","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"Individual coaching or small group (3-8) for diagnosis; training groups up to 20 for learning purposes","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"do-no-harm","name":"Do No Harm","feld":"E","kurz":"Make sure an intervention weakens conflict lines instead of unintentionally deepening them.","schritte":["Analyze the conflict context: collect Dividers and Connectors","Hold your own initiative up against it: resource transfers and implicit ethical messages","Check the effect: does the initiative strengthen dividers or connectors?","Adjust program options where they reinforce dividers","Agree on monitoring — context and effect keep changing"],"zweck":"Make sure an intervention weakens conflict lines instead of unintentionally deepening them.","hinweise":"Not a one-off exercise but a recurring reflection cycle. Get honest about the effects of your own resource flows — that's where the most common harm happens.","phasen":["verstehen","planen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Conflict Sensitivity Community Hub – Ressourcen zu Do No Harm / Conflict Sensitivity","url":"https://www.conflictsensitivityhub.net/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection (PME Guidelines GIZ Civil Peace Service)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Mary B. Anderson: Do No Harm – How Aid Can Support Peace or War (1999)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Station 1: Conflict Analysis / Do No Harm"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peacebuilding Practice (Woman PeaceMaker Program, 2023) – Chapter 4: Conflict Sensitivity & DNH"}],"wann_passt":["Program planning in conflict-sensitive contexts (5-20 people): before activities are set, analyzing which connectors and dividers exist in the context — so program design doesn't unintentionally reinforce dividing lines.","Reviewing ongoing programs in contexts where the conflict situation has shifted: the four DNH analysis components (context, actor behavior, program, options) systematically show where the program is producing unwanted effects.","Training and awareness-raising for field teams (8-20 people) working in fragile contexts: the six implicit ethical messages (e.g. 'whose safety counts') make invisible assumptions visible.","Strategic decision-making with multiple options: DNH analysis filters which option activates the fewest dividers."],"wann_nicht":["As a pure compliance form: DNH fizzles out if it's only filled in to tick a box — it needs honest engagement with what the program might be causing.","In acute crisis situations under extreme time pressure: secure the ability to act first, DNH reflection comes afterward.","Without context knowledge: connectors and dividers can't be identified from an office — they require local perspectives from the target community."],"fokusfragen":["\"What factors connect people in this context despite the conflict — and do our activities touch these connectors?\" (connector analysis)","\"What about how we work — not just what we do — could be deepening tensions between groups?\" (implicit ethical messages)","\"If we changed our program to weaken dividers, what would we concretely need to do differently?\" (options analysis)"],"mini_form":"Connectors-dividers in 15 minutes: two columns on a sheet, the team identifies 3-5 connectors and 3-5 dividers in the context. Then one single question: 'Which divider might our current approach be reinforcing?' — enough as an early warning signal.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-15 people, with local context knowledge in the room","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","skeptisch"],"beispiel":"Connectors-dividers scan in a team reflection: two flipcharts — 'Connecting' and 'Dividing'. The team collects, for their context: shared markets, shared religious festivals, shared history (connectors) vs. unequal access to land, conflicting memories, ethnic identification (dividers). Then: 'Which of our activities strengthen connectors? Which might unintentionally activate dividers?' Example: a training format that only reaches one group can be read as favoritism — even if the selection was purely capacity-based. Follow-up question: 'What would we need to change so both groups experience the program as made for them?'"},{"id":"transitional-justice","name":"Transitional Justice / Reconciliation","feld":"E","kurz":"Understand how societies organize truth-telling, justice, and reconciliation after mass violence.","schritte":["Introduce the four pillars: truth-seeking, prosecution, reparations, guarantees of non-recurrence","Map a concrete case context onto the pillars: what's happening, what's missing?","Discuss areas of tension: peace vs. justice, amnesty vs. prosecution","Check victim-centeredness: who defines what justice is?","Draw out implications for your own initiative"],"zweck":"Understand how societies organize truth-telling, justice, and reconciliation after mass violence.","hinweise":"Highly sensitive as soon as affected people are in the room — then trauma-sensitive facilitation and voluntary participation must be secured. When NOT to use: as an abstract desk exercise when participants have experienced violence themselves and haven't been prepared for it.","phasen":["verstehen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["feld"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"International Center for Transitional Justice – What is Transitional Justice?","url":"https://www.ictj.org/what-transitional-justice"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"}],"wann_passt":["Training for professionals in post-conflict contexts: the four pillars (truth, prosecution, reparation, guarantees of non-recurrence) as an analytical framework for concrete country cases — Rwanda, South Africa, Colombia.","Policy workshop with people working on reconciliation programs: which pillar is especially weak in our context? Where are the tensions (amnesty vs. prosecution)?","Reflection session in programs working with survivors of mass violence: transitional justice as a conceptual frame that explains why individual conversations and the societal level are connected."],"wann_nicht":["As an abstract desk exercise when affected people are in the room and there's no trauma-sensitive support structure in place.","When participants are survivors themselves and the session wasn't explicitly designed as a processing space — then specialized psychosocial support is needed.","In contexts where the conflict is still active — transitional justice presupposes at least a formal transition (ceasefire, change of government)."],"fokusfragen":["Which of the four pillars is strongest in this context — which is almost entirely missing? (analysis starting point)","Who defines what justice means in this process — and whose voice is missing? (checking victim-centeredness)","Where is the greatest tension: between peace and justice, amnesty and prosecution? (dilemma discussion)"],"mini_form":"Four-pillars mapping: 15 minutes, four flipcharts (truth / prosecution / reparation / non-recurrence), the group places dots by existing elements, gaps become visible.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","strategie","dialograum"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-20 people; smaller (8-12) if affected people are present","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"multi-track-diplomacy","name":"Multi-Track Diplomacy","feld":"E","kurz":"See peacework as an interplay of many societal levels and locate your own work within it.","schritte":["Introduce the nine tracks (government, professional conflict resolution, business, citizens, education/research, activism, religion, funding, media)","Collect actors in your own conflict context by track","Mark activities and gaps: which tracks are active, which are dormant?","Identify entry points for your own initiative","Plan cross-track connections"],"zweck":"See peacework as an interplay of many societal levels and locate your own work within it.","hinweise":"No track works alone — read the map for connections, not for jurisdictions. Risk of arbitrariness if no prioritization follows.","phasen":["verstehen","planen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Institute for Multi-Track Diplomacy – What Is Multi-Track Diplomacy?","url":"https://imtdsite.wordpress.com/about/what-is-multi-track-diplomacy/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Louise Diamond / John McDonald: Multi-Track Diplomacy – A Systems Approach to Peace (1996)"}],"wann_passt":["Strategy workshop for a peace organization trying to find its place in the wider ecosystem: the nine tracks as a map to see which levels are already active and where gaps or entry points lie.","Training for multipliers in conflict contexts: the model conveys that the government level and civil society don't act separately but together form a peace system.","Network planning in multi-sector settings (e.g. NGO + business + religion): which tracks are represented, which aren't — and how can we close that gap?"],"wann_nicht":["When the group has no connection to the peace context — the model then feels too abstract and academic.","As a standalone tool without prioritization: knowing the nine tracks doesn't help if no concrete entry points and next steps are drawn from it.","As a substitute for context analysis: the model structures but gives no picture of power relations and dynamics between the tracks."],"fokusfragen":["Which of the nine tracks are active in our context — and which are dormant? (gap analysis)","Where does our organization sit on the track map — and which other tracks are we connected to? (positioning)","Where would the biggest lever be to build cross-track connections? (strategic prioritization)"],"mini_form":"Track mapping: everyone places a dot on the track where their own organization primarily works — make the distribution visible, draw in connections (5-10 minutes).","anlass_typen":["strategie","netzwerktreffen","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-20 people; ideal for multi-sector networks","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"bohm-dialogue","name":"Bohm Dialogue","feld":"E","kurz":"Let shared thinking and shared meaning emerge, beyond debate and defending positions.","schritte":["Open the circle without agenda and without a decision goal","Agree on principles: suspend your own judgments, speak to the center rather than to individuals, listen radically","Sit through a long opening phase with silence — the group finds its topic","Observe your own reactions and share them as observations where useful","Close without summary or pressure for an outcome"],"zweck":"Let shared thinking and shared meaning emerge, beyond debate and defending positions.","hinweise":"Results-oriented groups find this format frustrating — clarify expectations in advance. Allow at least 60 minutes. When NOT to use: when a decision is needed.","phasen":["vertiefen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":40,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"David Bohm / Donald Factor / Peter Garrett – Dialogue: A Proposal","url":"http://www.david-bohm.net/dialogue/dialogue_proposal.html"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"David Bohm: On Dialogue (1996)"}],"wann_passt":["A group of 10-20 people who work together regularly and notice their meetings keep getting stuck on the same positions: Bohm Dialogue creates a space beyond agenda and decision-pressure where collective thinking can emerge.","A learning community (community of practice, training cohort) that meets at least monthly: the format needs continuity — the same people over several sessions. Over time, formal facilitation dissolves.","Closing an intensive strategy process: Bohm Dialogue as a space before a group moves into implementation mode — not to decide, but to pause and deepen together."],"wann_nicht":["When a decision or an outcome is expected — Bohm Dialogue by design has no product and frustrates results-oriented groups considerably.","As a one-off format without continuity: a single Bohm Dialogue is little more than an unfamiliar conversation form; its effect unfolds over many sessions.","With strongly hierarchical groups where free suspension of judgment is structurally blocked by the presence of superiors.","Online: the format loses essential qualities (silence, bodily presence in the circle, nonverbal signals)."],"fokusfragen":["What assumption are you bringing into this conversation that you'd be willing to suspend — not give up, but pause and look at? (entry into suspension of judgment)","What moved you in what someone just said — not as an opinion, but as an inner reaction? (sharing your own reaction as observation)"],"mini_form":"20-minute Bohm excerpt: circle, no table, no topic other than 'What's occupying us right now?', one person speaks, everyone listens, a minimum silence of 30 seconds between contributions. No closing poster, no outcome. Afterward, a brief reflection: 'What was different from usual?'","anlass_typen":["dialograum","teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-20 ideal; under 6 lacks diversity, over 30 only with very experienced facilitation","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","müde","belastet"]},{"id":"sustained-dialogue","name":"Sustained Dialogue (Saunders)","feld":"E","kurz":"Gradually transform broken relationships between groups through repeated, facilitated conversations.","schritte":["Clarify the frame: this is about changing the relationship, not negotiation","Exchange experiences on the topic — each person tells their story, everyone listens","Jointly name patterns in the relationship between the groups","Develop scenarios: what would deepen or change the relationship?","Agree on the next round — continuity of the same group is the active ingredient"],"zweck":"Gradually transform broken relationships between groups through repeated, facilitated conversations.","hinweise":"A single session is only the kickoff — the method works over months in five phases. Participants must commit to coming back, or it stays a flash in the pan.","phasen":["konflikt","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["konflikt","verbindung"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Sustained Dialogue Institute – Our Approach","url":"https://sustaineddialogue.org/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Harold Saunders: A Public Peace Process (1999)"}],"wann_passt":["Two community groups (e.g. different ethnic, religious, or political groups in a city) who barely speak to each other but have to live together long-term: Sustained Dialogue builds shared relational capital over 5 phases and many months, which is what first makes political negotiations possible.","A university program or youth exchange where a one-off encounter isn't enough: the same young people meet every 2-3 weeks over a semester — continuity is the active ingredient.","A broken cooperative relationship between two organizations that are structurally dependent on each other: when the relationship itself needs to change, not just be negotiated."],"wann_nicht":["When participants can't or won't commit to coming back — a single session is more honest then.","When a fast, visible solution is needed: Sustained Dialogue is designed for 6-18 months; as a short format it would be false advertising.","During acute violence: safety first, then dialogue."],"fokusfragen":["Why are we sitting here today — what is the state of our relationship that we want to change? (Phase 1: framing)","What have you experienced — concretely, from your perspective — that led to this relationship? (Phase 2: exchanging experiences)","What patterns do you see in our relationship as groups — not between us as individuals, but structurally? (Phase 3: naming patterns)"],"mini_form":"Phase-1 entry (30 minutes): each person describes in 3 minutes why they're in the room today and what they hope for from this series — no discussion. Creates awareness that this is about the relationship, not a single session.","anlass_typen":["dialograum","konfliktklaerung","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-15 ideal; too small lacks diversity, too large loses depth","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","belastet"]},{"id":"deep-democracy","name":"Deep Democracy (Lewis)","feld":"E","kurz":"Make minority voices heard and integrate them into decisions before they go underground as sabotage.","schritte":["Collect all viewpoints on the topic — including the quiet ones","Actively fish for the no: who sees this differently? What is nobody saying out loud?","Vote","Ask the outvoted minority: what do you need to go along with this?","Fold that condition into the majority decision","Vote again — the decision now carries the minority's wisdom within it"],"zweck":"Make minority voices heard and integrate them into decisions before they go underground as sabotage.","hinweise":"Facilitation must stay neutral and actively protect the minority; the no is information, not a disruption. When NOT to use: with massive power asymmetry and no protective frame.","phasen":["entscheiden","konflikt"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["entscheidung","konflikt"],"formate":["workshop","meeting"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Lewis Deep Democracy","url":"https://www.lewisdeepdemocracy.com/"}],"wann_passt":["A team decision where a minority opposes the consensus and the no isn't being heard: Deep Democracy turns the energy of the no into a carrier of information — it asks what the minority knows that the majority doesn't see.","A group that keeps sabotaging a seemingly settled matter: the tool shows that the resistance carries information, not blockage — and surfaces the underground knowledge.","Conflict work where one side is structurally weaker and isn't heard in normal formats: Deep Democracy actively protects the minority voice."],"wann_nicht":["With massive power asymmetry and no protected frame: if the manager is in the room and the no has real consequences, the format doesn't work — there's only a performed no.","When facilitation can't stay neutral (e.g. has a personal opinion on the topic or belongs to a party involved).","Without sufficient facilitator training: the Lewis model needs trained meta-skills (neutrality, handling strong emotions, protecting the minority).","In purely informational meetings without real decision openness — taking the no seriously must be genuinely possible."],"fokusfragen":["What does the part of us that says no know — what information does this resistance carry? (introducing no as a carrier of information)","What does the minority need so it doesn't have to work against the majority decision? (seeking a path to integration)","If the minority voice were right — what would we then need to know or do differently? (taking the perspective seriously)"],"mini_form":"No-round (10 minutes): once a decision is pending, explicitly open space for the no: who still has concerns or resistance? Please put it into words. Everyone listens. Then: what would need to change for your no to get smaller? — no voting, just listening and developing further.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","konfliktklaerung","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-20 ideal; over 25 people work in subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","müde"]},{"id":"circle-council","name":"Circle / Council","feld":"E","kurz":"Structurally secure speaking as equals and deep listening — every voice gets the same space.","schritte":["Shape the center and name the round's intention","Make agreements: listen without judgment, speak from the heart, say what's essential, confidentiality","Check-in round with the talking piece — only the holder speaks","Topic rounds (going around or popcorn-style), the keeper may call a pause at any time","Check-out: every voice closes the round"],"zweck":"Structurally secure speaking as equals and deep listening — every voice gets the same space.","hinweise":"The talking piece deliberately slows things down — that's exactly its function. Rounds need time; keep group size limited. When NOT to use: for fast operational meetings — there it feels artificial.","phasen":["ankommen","vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["verbindung","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","reflexionsrunde","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The Circle Way – Basic Guidelines","url":"https://www.thecircleway.net/circle-way-guidelines"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Christina Baldwin / Ann Linnea: The Circle Way (2010)"}],"wann_passt":["A clarifying round in a team after a hurtful incident: the circle creates a frame where every person knows they will speak and be heard — that alone lowers defensiveness.","Opening a sensitive or significant session (strategy process, closing, conflict clarification): the circle as a deliberate space-holder sets a different tone than a normal meeting.","Regular team check-ins where real voices should be heard instead of performative feedback — especially when hierarchy is in the room, because the talking piece structurally equalizes everyone."],"wann_nicht":["For operational decision meetings with a tight agenda: the format deliberately slows things down — in a status meeting with 12 items it feels artificial and creates frustration.","When the group finds the talking piece infantile (some corporate cultures): explain it beforehand or switch to a culturally fitting object.","Over 20 people without subgroups: the circle then gets too long and concentration breaks down."],"fokusfragen":["What are you bringing into this circle — what's on your heart about this topic? (opening round)","What are you taking from what you've heard — what moved or surprised you? (closing round)","If you could leave the circle with a question that stays with all of us — what would it be? (deepening round)"],"mini_form":"Flash circle (8-12 minutes): talking piece in the center, one question, each person 1 minute, no comment, no applause. Enough as an entry point into difficult sessions, to gather the mood in the room.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","teamtag","dialograum","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-18 ideal; possible from 4, over 20 only with subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","müde","skeptisch"]},{"id":"reflecting-team","name":"Reflecting Team (Andersen)","feld":"E","kurz":"Gain new perspectives on your own concern by listening to a conversation about yourself.","schritte":["The presenter describes their concern, the facilitator interviews them — the team only listens","Switch: the team talks among themselves appreciatively and hypothetically about what they heard — the presenter listens without reacting","Switch back: the presenter picks up what resonated","Optionally a second reflection loop","Closing: the presenter names what they're taking away"],"zweck":"Gain new perspectives on your own concern by listening to a conversation about yourself.","hinweise":"The team's language must be appreciative, questioning, and possibility-oriented — evaluations or advice destroy the mechanism. Keep the separation of conversation spaces strict.","phasen":["vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["reflexion","klaerung"],"formate":["coaching","teamentwicklung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":10,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"socialnet Lexikon – Reflecting Team","url":"https://www.socialnet.de/lexikon/Reflecting-Team"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Tom Andersen: Das Reflektierende Team (1990)"}],"wann_passt":["Supervision or peer case consultation: one person describes a case, a small team reflects on it out loud, the narrator listens and can respond afterward — they receive outside perspectives without direct advice.","Training context (coaching, therapy, mediation): a trainee holds a conversation, an observing team reflects openly — this is more effective for learning than after-the-fact feedback, because the context is still present.","A clarification process in a group where a subgroup has made a decision and the whole group is meant to give feedback: the Reflecting Team prevents feedback from turning into defense or justification."],"wann_nicht":["When the team slips into evaluative or advice-giving language — then the mechanism collapses (observers must speak exclusively in possibility-oriented, conditional terms).","When the narrating person experiences the listening as demeaning (e.g. a lower-status employee listens to the team reflecting about her) — clarify protection beforehand.","In highly escalated conflicts without neutral facilitation: the format presupposes basic safety."],"fokusfragen":["What moved us in what we heard — not as evaluation, but as an inner reaction? (team's entry into the reflecting round)","What possibilities do we see that the person may not have seen yet — as an invitation, not advice? (opening a space of possibility)","What are you taking with you — what of what you heard touches something in you? (return to the narrating person)"],"mini_form":"Mini reflecting (10 minutes): someone describes a dilemma (3 min), two people reflect out loud without addressing the person (5 min), the person responds with what they heard (2 min). No more elaborate format needed.","anlass_typen":["coaching","lernformat","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1 narrator + 2-5 in the reflecting team; max. 20 people total","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","müde"]},{"id":"betzavta","name":"Betzavta","feld":"E","kurz":"Don't teach democratic principles — make them experiential through your own behavior in a dilemma.","schritte":["Choose a Betzavta exercise with a built-in dilemma","Run the exercise — the decision is real, the conflict arises on its own","Interrupt the process once the dilemma is visible","Reflect: how did we handle freedom, majority, minority?","Transfer: what does this mean for democratic coexistence in everyday life?"],"zweck":"Don't teach democratic principles — make them experiential through your own behavior in a dilemma.","hinweise":"The effect lies almost entirely in the debrief — without thorough reflection, only frustration remains. Requires trained facilitation. When NOT to use: without enough time for the debrief, or mistaken for an energizer.","phasen":["vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["konflikt","reflexion"],"formate":["fortbildung","workshop"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["beteiligend","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Akademie Führung & Kompetenz – Betzavta / Mehr als eine Demokratie","url":"https://www.cap-lmu.de/akademie/schwerpunkte/betzavta-miteinander/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Uki Maroshek-Klarman: Mehr als eine Demokratie (Bertelsmann Stiftung)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Adam Institute - Betzavta Method","url":"https://www.adaminstitute.org.il/language/en/betzavta_method-2/"}],"wann_passt":["Civic or democracy education with adults or young people: Betzavta makes tangible what it costs to share rights — through a dilemma game that triggers real emotions, which are then analyzed.","Training for multipliers (teachers, youth workers, social workers) who want to convey democratic coexistence: the format gives them a concrete tool they can keep using.","Groups dealing with polarization: Betzavta shows that conflicts between rights and interests are worked out not through persuasion but through shared procedures."],"wann_nicht":["Without enough debrief time: the effect lies almost entirely in the reflection after the dilemma game — without it, the experience turns into frustration.","Mistaken for an energizer or warm-up: the format is not a game but a serious learning experience that needs time to process.","With untrained facilitators in highly conflictual groups: Betzavta needs trained facilitation because the game generates real emotions."],"fokusfragen":["What did you feel in the dilemma — which impulses, which conflicts? (debrief opening)","Where did you weigh your own interest against another's right — and how did you decide? (connecting to democratic principles)","What does this mean for situations in your everyday life where rights collide? (transfer)"],"mini_form":"No meaningful mini format: Betzavta needs the full dilemma experience and the debrief — partial forms would destroy the mechanism.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","dialograum","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"12-24 ideal; under 8 lacks dynamics","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"nvc-4-schritte","name":"NVC – 4 Steps","feld":"E","kurz":"Translate conflict-prone communication into language that triggers connection instead of defensiveness.","schritte":["Formulate an observation — concrete, without evaluation","Name the feeling","Voice the need behind it","Formulate a request — concrete, positive, negotiable","Practice with real examples in pairs","Feedback: where did evaluations slip in?"],"zweck":"Translate conflict-prone communication into language that triggers connection instead of defensiveness.","hinweise":"The biggest risk is mechanical NVC-speak — attitude (empathy) before technique. Observation without evaluation is the hardest step; plan plenty of practice time for it.","phasen":["vertiefen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung","konflikt"],"formate":["workshop","coaching","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"PuddleDancer Press – 4-Part Nonviolent Communication (NVC)","url":"https://nonviolentcommunication.com/learn-nonviolent-communication/4-part-nvc/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation (2001)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peacebuilding Practice (Woman PeaceMaker Program, 2023) – Chapter 11: Nonviolent Communication"}],"wann_passt":["A difficult 1:1 conversation where one person needs to express a complaint or criticism without damaging the relationship — the four steps (observation, feeling, need, request) give structure to precise, non-attacking speech.","A team stuck in destructive communication patterns (mutual accusations, blame): a 60-90 minute NVC training with concrete examples from everyday team life breaks the cycle.","A context with a power gap, where the weaker party learns to set boundaries (protective use of force, per Rosenberg): 'If you do X, I will do Y to protect my need for Z.'"],"wann_nicht":["In strongly asymmetrical conflicts with physical violence or real powerlessness: NVC presupposes that the other person is able and willing to listen empathically — that's not given in abusive relationships.","As a quick technique without practice: the difference between observation and interpretation ('you're arrogant' vs. 'I noticed you took the floor in three meetings in a row without asking') has to be practiced — otherwise NVC sounds artificial.","When the group has no emotional access or emotional self-disclosure is culturally unusual — then systemic questioning techniques or mediation are a better fit."],"fokusfragen":["\"What did I concretely see/hear — without judgment?\" (observation, not evaluation: 'I noticed that...' instead of 'You always...')","\"What feeling does this trigger in me — and is it really a feeling or a thought about the other person?\" (feeling vs. pseudo-feeling like 'I feel manipulated')","\"What need is behind this feeling — what do I need that isn't being met right now?\" (need as a bridge to the other person)"],"beispiel":"NVC formulation in a team tension: instead of 'You never listen when I speak' (accusation) → 'In our last meeting I noticed you checked your phone three times while I was speaking [observation]. That frustrated me [feeling], because being heard matters to me [need]. I'd like to ask you to put your phone away when I'm speaking in our next meeting [request].' Facilitator's follow-up question: 'What does that trigger in you — what do you need right now?' — opens dialogue instead of a justification loop.","mini_form":"NVC sentence frame in 5 minutes: everyone writes the four sentences for a current tension: 'I observe... / I feel... / Because I need... / I ask you...' Write it down alone, not necessarily said out loud — just formulating it brings clarity.","anlass_typen":["schwieriges_gespraech","konfliktklaerung","lernformat","coaching"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"ideal 1:1 to 8, groups up to 15 with role plays","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","neugierig"]},{"id":"selbstempathie","name":"Self-Empathy","feld":"E","kurz":"Clarify your own inner state before speaking or acting — a precondition for any empathic contact.","schritte":["Choose a situation that's stirring you up inside","Note down inner judgments unfiltered","Name the feeling behind each judgment","Find the need behind each feeling","Stay with the need and notice what shifts","Optionally formulate a request to yourself"],"zweck":"Clarify your own inner state before speaking or acting — a precondition for any empathic contact.","hinweise":"Also works silently in the middle of a session (2-3 minutes). Don't skip past judgments — they're the raw material that leads to the needs.","phasen":["reflektieren","ankommen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["selbstzugang","reflexion"],"formate":["coaching","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["schriftlich","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern","reflexion"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"PositivePsychology.com – Your Complete Nonviolent Communication Guide","url":"https://positivepsychology.com/non-violent-communication/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation (2001)"}],"wann_passt":["Preparing for a difficult conversation: before going into a clarifying talk, a confrontation, or a negotiation, self-empathy helps translate your own judgments (he's impossible) into the underlying feelings and needs — this makes your own communication clearer and less reactive.","In the middle of an ongoing conversation, when a person notices they're shutting down or getting heated: self-empathy as a brief inner pause (30-60 seconds) before continuing to speak.","Coaching opening with someone who arrives with strong anger or blame: clarify the inner state first, before talking about strategies or the other person."],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for legitimate protest or setting boundaries: self-empathy should establish contact with your own needs, not regulate needs away.","During acute dissociation or severe trauma: then professional psychological support is needed, not an NVC technique.","As a mandatory exercise in groups: self-empathy only works if the person genuinely wants it — forced inwardness creates resistance."],"fokusfragen":["What am I telling myself right now — which judgments are coming up? (name judgments, don't skip them)","What am I feeling — what feeling is there once I set these judgments aside? (reach the layer underneath)","What do I need right now — which need is unmet? (identify the need)","What do I want to do next — coming from this need? (clarify the impulse to act)"],"beispiel":"A person arrives at coaching agitated, saying their colleague embarrassed them in front of everyone today — she's just inconsiderate. Coach: I hear there's a lot going on right now. What do you feel when you say that? Person: I'm angry. Coach: Angry — and what's underneath the anger? What mattered to you in that moment that wasn't there? Person thinks: Respect. I want to be treated respectfully, especially in front of others. Coach: And knowing that — what would you like to do next with this anger and this need? Purpose: the person doesn't need to get rid of the judgments; they become material that leads to feeling and need. Then a capable response emerges instead of a reaction.","mini_form":"Silent self-empathy minute: sit silently for 60 seconds before a difficult conversation, answer three questions: What am I experiencing inside right now? What do I feel? What do I need? No need to write down an answer — running through it inwardly is enough.","anlass_typen":["coaching","schwieriges_gespraech","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"individual; can be done as guided silence in groups up to 20 people","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","müde"]},{"id":"empathisches-zuhoeren","name":"Empathic Listening","feld":"E","kurz":"Give a person the experience of being fully heard in their feeling and need.","schritte":["Form pairs, A tells a distressing situation","B only listens — full presence, no advice, no comfort, no own story","B reflects back as a guess: are you ... (feeling), because ... (need) matters to you?","A corrects or deepens — B stays in reflecting until A feels understood","Switch roles","Debrief: what was it like to be heard this way?"],"zweck":"Give a person the experience of being fully heard in their feeling and need.","hinweise":"The advice reflex is the most common stumbling block — explicitly rule it out beforehand. Offer guesses, don't diagnose. When NOT to use: with acute trauma in a lay setting.","phasen":["vertiefen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","coaching","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"PuddleDancer Press – NVC Empathy","url":"https://nonviolentcommunication.com/learn-nonviolent-communication/nvc-empathy/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation (2001)"}],"wann_passt":["Someone is emotionally shaken, hurt, or in a crisis and first needs to be heard — before any problem-solving, strategy, or perspective is offered. Empathic listening creates the connection that makes factual dialogue possible afterward.","Peer-support context (a colleague after a hard day, a friend after a conflict experience): no therapy, no advice, just full presence and occasional guesses as an offering.","Pre-mediation conversation with each party separately: before the parties come together, each needs to feel fully heard. Empathic listening in the pre-circle carries the whole mediation process."],"wann_nicht":["With acute trauma or a psychological crisis in a lay setting: then the person needs professional psychological support — empathic listening by an unqualified person can cause harm.","When the listening person is themselves emotionally activated: do self-empathy first, otherwise the listening becomes inauthentic or your own reaction interferes.","When the person is explicitly seeking advice or information: then empathic listening as a response would be a form of disregard."],"fokusfragen":["Am I guessing right that you're feeling [feeling] right now, because [need] matters to you? (offer a guess, don't assert it)","Is there more I should understand? (hold space before closing prematurely)","What would be helpful for you right now — keep talking, or something else? (actively ask what's needed)"],"beispiel":"A colleague says: I'm so frustrated, the workshop today was a total disaster. Empathic listening: That sounds like a hard day. Are you frustrated because it matters to you to deliver good work, and today didn't go the way you'd imagined? Colleague: Yes exactly, and I felt like the participants weren't engaged at all. Follow-up: You would have wanted more connection and resonance — and that didn't happen today? Purpose: the guess opens without pinning down. If it's wrong, the person corrects it. The second guess goes deeper. No advice follows — only once the person signals: Do you have an idea what I could do differently?","mini_form":"3-minute empathy: a person talks for 2 minutes about something moving them. The listener responds only with a guess (feeling + need) — no advice, no contribution of their own. The person confirms or corrects.","anlass_typen":["schwieriges_gespraech","coaching","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"dyads (2 people); in training formats up to 20 as a paired exercise","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","müde"]},{"id":"wolfs-giraffensprache","name":"Wolf / Giraffe Language","feld":"E","kurz":"Make the difference between dividing and connecting language tangible using your own speech material.","schritte":["Collect typical judgmental and accusatory sentences from the group's everyday life","Show the anatomy of wolf language: judgment, generalization, demand, blame","Translate each sentence into the four steps","Practice in pairs: one person speaks wolf, the other translates into giraffe","Compare: how does the same message land in each version?"],"zweck":"Make the difference between dividing and connecting language tangible using your own speech material.","hinweise":"Don't morally devalue wolf language — it's an expression of unmet needs. Humor helps; don't impose the animal metaphors on every audience (alternative: dividing/connecting language).","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Wikipedia – Nonviolent Communication (Abschnitt Jackal/Giraffe Language)","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonviolent_Communication"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation (2001)"}],"wann_passt":["Introductory NVC workshop: the animal metaphors make the difference between dividing and connecting language tangible quickly and with humor — good as an entry point before working out the four steps.","Training session for managers or facilitators: translating your own speech material — what sounds wolfish, what sounds giraffish? Very concrete and practical.","Youth work or school settings: the animal images are low-threshold and memorable, requiring no prior NVC knowledge."],"wann_nicht":["With audiences who find the animal metaphors infantile or off-putting (some corporate contexts, certain cultural contexts): better to use dividing / connecting language without the animals.","As a standalone format: practicing wolf and giraffe language needs the four NVC steps as a foundation, otherwise it stays superficial.","When wolf language is morally devalued: wolf language is an expression of unmet needs, not malice — anyone who doesn't frame this clearly creates shame instead of learning."],"fokusfragen":["Which sentence do you know from your everyday life that sounds typically wolfish — and what's behind it? (collect your own examples)","How would the same sentence sound coming from the giraffe — with observation, feeling, need, request? (practice translating)"],"beispiel":"Wolf sentence: You never listen. Giraffe translation: I was just telling you something that matters to me, and you were looking at your phone (observation). I felt disappointed (feeling), because contact and real listening mattered to me in that moment (need). Would you put your phone away when I'm telling you something that moves me (request)? Purpose: the wolf sentence triggers justification. The giraffe sentence invites a response. Follow-up question: How does the giraffe version sound — what changes when you hear it?","mini_form":"Translation duel (5 minutes): one person says a wolf sentence, their partner spontaneously translates it into giraffe language. Then switch. Can the same thing be expressed without accusatory language?","anlass_typen":["lernformat","konfliktklaerung","teamtag"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"any size for demonstration; practice in pairs or small groups (4-6)","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"bitte-vs-forderung","name":"Request vs. Demand","feld":"E","kurz":"Take the power dynamic out of a concern — be able to welcome a no without giving up the concern.","schritte":["Explain the difference: the reaction to a no reveals whether it was a request or a demand","Collect and test your own typical requests: what happens inside me if the answer is no?","Recognize hidden demands (guilt, pressure, withdrawal after the no)","Reformulate into genuine requests: concrete, positive, fulfillable in the here and now","Get to know connection requests"],"zweck":"Take the power dynamic out of a concern — be able to welcome a no without giving up the concern.","hinweise":"Especially tricky in hierarchies: a manager's request is often structurally a demand — name that honestly instead of glossing over it.","phasen":["vertiefen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung","konflikt"],"formate":["workshop","coaching","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"PuddleDancer Press – Learn Nonviolent Communication","url":"https://nonviolentcommunication.com/learn-nonviolent-communication/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation (2001)"}],"wann_passt":["When someone has a concern that the other side experiences as pressure: the request-vs-demand distinction helps check whether your own concern is really open to a no — and if not, what that says about your own need.","Leadership development: managers learn to recognize that their requests are often structurally demands — and how to deal with that honestly instead of staging pseudo-participation.","Mediation preparation: when one party disguises demands as requests, the distinction can help establish more honest communication."],"wann_nicht":["As a technique to frame your own concern as a request when it's actually a demand: that's manipulative and undermines trust.","In emergency situations where real action requirements apply: not everything has to be framed as a request — some safety instructions are demands and should remain so."],"fokusfragen":["If the other person says no — what would happen inside me? Would I really be open to that, or would I apply pressure? (checking request vs. demand)","If it's a demand — what do I actually need to protect? Can I address that directly instead of disguising it as a request? (honesty about your own need)"],"beispiel":"Team lead to employee: Would you be willing to take the minutes? — sounds like a request but is structurally a demand. Request check: would a no really be welcome? If not: a more honest version: I need someone to take the minutes — you're up today. Is there a reason that would be difficult for you today? This is open, without simulating a request that isn't one. Purpose: honest demands respect dignity more than disguised demands. Follow-up question: what would you need for this to be distributed fairly?","mini_form":"Request test (3 minutes): someone formulates a concern. Question: if the other person says no — how do you react inside? If the answer is pressure or disappointment: it's a demand. What does that mean for how you phrase it next time?","anlass_typen":["schwieriges_gespraech","coaching","lernformat"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"dyads or small groups (4-8); also as an impulse in a large group with self-reflection","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","angespannt"]},{"id":"aergerprozess","name":"Anger Process","feld":"E","kurz":"Take anger fully seriously and use it as a signpost to the need behind it.","schritte":["Choose a real anger situation","Pause and breathe — don't act","Identify the judgmental thoughts generating the anger","Find the unmet need behind the judgments","Notice how the anger shifts once the need comes into focus","Optionally formulate an expression or a request"],"zweck":"Take anger fully seriously and use it as a signpost to the need behind it.","hinweise":"Don't try to make the anger go away — it carries the energy for the need. Don't guide this during acute rage; regulate first. When NOT to use: as a substitute for legitimate protest against real violations.","phasen":["reflektieren","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["selbstzugang","reflexion"],"formate":["coaching","workshop"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"PuddleDancer Press – Nonviolent Communication for Anger","url":"https://nonviolentcommunication.com/learn-nonviolent-communication/nvc-anger/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: The Surprising Purpose of Anger (2005)"}],"wann_passt":["Coaching or individual support when someone arrives at a conflict with strong anger: the anger process invites finding the unmet need underneath the anger — turning reactivity into a starting point for action.","A supervision group where one team member is angry at someone else: work with the anger as a group topic without condemning the absent person.","A reflection round after a difficult event (session, intervention, conflict): what made me angry — and what does that say about what matters to me?"],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for legitimate protest against real violations or structural injustice: reframing anger as merely a need, when it's pointing to real wrongdoing, is politically and ethically problematic.","During acute emotional escalation (hot rage): regulate first (breathing exercise, pause), then address the anger process.","In a group, when the person the anger is about is present and there's no safe frame — then the anger process turns into unstructured accusation."],"fokusfragen":["What judgments do I formulate about the other person when I think of the situation? (take judgments seriously, don't skip them)","What should the person have done or not done for me not to be angry — what was my expectation? (making the demand behind the anger visible)","What need in me was unmet — what mattered to me in that moment? (finding the core of the anger)","What do I want to do with this need now — how can I make sure it gets met? (impulse to act)"],"beispiel":"Coaching: a person is angry at a colleague who interrupted their presentation in a meeting. Anger process: What are you saying about the colleague? — She's arrogant and doesn't respect me. — If the colleague had behaved differently — what would she have done? — She would have let me finish. — And what mattered to you in that moment that wasn't there? — Person pauses: I wanted to be heard. It mattered to me that my work was seen. — Coach: So the anger shows us: being heard and recognized is an unmet need right now. What do you want to make of that — do you want to talk to your colleague? Purpose: from 'she's arrogant' to 'I need recognition' — that creates the capacity to act.","mini_form":"Two-question flash (5 minutes): who or what is bothering you right now — and what does that say about what matters to you? Run through it in pairs — 2 minutes per person.","anlass_typen":["coaching","konfliktklaerung","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"individual to small group (6-10) in supervision/reflection","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"trauer-feiern","name":"Mourning & Celebrating","feld":"E","kurz":"Learn from mistakes without self-punishment, and honor successes in a way that gives energy.","schritte":["Choose a situation: something that failed/was lost (mourning) or something that succeeded (celebrating)","Mourning: name the unmet needs and the feelings around them — without self-blame","Celebrating: name the met needs and honor them concretely","Share in pairs or in a round","Notice: both movements deepen awareness of needs"],"zweck":"Learn from mistakes without self-punishment, and honor successes in a way that gives energy.","hinweise":"Mourning in NVC is not a substitute for therapy — introduce the terms carefully. Celebrating is often skipped, yet it carries the motivation.","phasen":["reflektieren","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["reflexion","selbstzugang"],"formate":["workshop","coaching","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["reflexion","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"PuddleDancer Press – NVC Mourning","url":"https://nonviolentcommunication.com/learn-nonviolent-communication/nvc-mourning/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation (2001)"}],"wann_passt":["A retro after a failed project or a difficult period: mourning and celebrating gives failure dignity without falling into self-punishment — and gives success a genuine place.","Closing a long collaboration or program: mourning what's ending — and celebrating the path. Making both explicit instead of neutralizing the ending.","A team after a loss (a colleague leaves the team, a project loses funding): emotional processing as a group format — gives feeling space before the group moves on."],"wann_nicht":["As a short format: mourning needs time and safety; a 5-minute round only produces superficiality.","When the term mourning feels too therapeutic or foreign to the group: adapt the framing instead (What cost us energy — and what was good?).","As a mandatory exercise without real feeling: forced celebrating of failures creates cynicism."],"fokusfragen":["What cost us energy during this time — what didn't succeed or was lost? (mourning round)","What was really good — what worked, what made you proud, what do you not want to forget? (celebration round)","What are you taking with you — from both? (integration)"],"mini_form":"Two-round flash (10 minutes): first round: what didn't work, what are we letting go of? — each person one sentence. Brief silence. Second round: what was good, what are we taking with us? — each person one sentence. No comments in between.","anlass_typen":["retro","teamtag","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-15 ideal; also works solo as a writing exercise","stimmung_geeignet":["belastet","müde","angespannt"]},{"id":"restorative-circles","name":"Restorative Circles (Barter)","feld":"E","kurz":"Work through community conflicts so that understanding, responsibility, and repair are carried by the community itself.","schritte":["Pre-circle: clarify with each person involved individually what happened, who belongs, secure voluntariness","Circle phase 1 — mutual understanding: each person speaks, the other reflects it back, until the speaker feels understood","Phase 2 — self-responsibility: what did each person contribute, what was the intention behind the action?","Phase 3 — agreed action: concrete, verifiable agreements","Follow-up circle: review the agreements"],"zweck":"Work through community conflicts so that understanding, responsibility, and repair are carried by the community itself.","hinweise":"Lives from building the system in the community, not from a one-off application. When NOT to use: for acute crimes or risk of violence without a professional frame; never without pre-circles.","phasen":["konflikt","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["konflikt","klaerung"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Restorative Circles (Dominic Barter)","url":"https://www.restorativecircles.org/"}],"wann_passt":["Schools, communities, or organizations that want to build their own system for working with conflict: Restorative Circles is not a one-off format but a system-building process — it works when the community itself trains facilitators and embeds the procedure.","Following up on a serious incident (dispute, property damage, breach of trust) in a community that has to keep living together: the three circles (pre-circle / main circle / follow-up circle) ensure that all three sides are heard.","Organizations with an NVC culture that want to handle conflicts internally and according to shared principles rather than through external mediation."],"wann_nicht":["For acute crimes or risk of violence without a professional legal frame: Restorative Circles doesn't replace legal protective measures.","As an ad-hoc one-off application without building the system in the community: the main circle without pre-circles is like surgery without preparation — the pre-circles aren't optional.","When the acting person takes no responsibility and also isn't willing to take part in the circle: then other procedures are needed."],"fokusfragen":["What happened — from your point of view? (pre-circle with each party individually)","What did what happened mean for you — what was the impact? (main circle: affected person)","What do you need now to feel safe and connected in this community again? (main circle: community needs)"],"mini_form":"No meaningful mini format: Restorative Circles needs all three circles and the system-building process. A shortened version without pre-circle and community presence is a different format.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","teamtag","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-party groups (acting person + affected person + community); main circle 5-20 people","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"gfk-mediation","name":"NVC Mediation by a Third Party","feld":"E","kurz":"Bring conflict parties back into contact through mutual empathy before talking about solutions.","schritte":["Listen empathically to both parties one after another — the mediator reflects each side's feeling and need","Place both sides' needs visibly next to each other (flipchart)","Guide mutual reflection back until both feel heard","Only then: collect solution ideas that address both sets of needs","Formulate the agreement as concrete, negotiable requests"],"zweck":"Bring conflict parties back into contact through mutual empathy before talking about solutions.","hinweise":"The mediator gives empathy, no judgments and no own solutions. The parties' urge to jump to solutions early is the main stumbling block. When NOT to use: with risk of violence or a strong power gap without protective measures.","phasen":["konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["konflikt","klaerung"],"formate":["coaching","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":8,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Center for Nonviolent Communication","url":"https://www.cnvc.org/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Marshall Rosenberg: Gewaltfreie Kommunikation (2001), Kap. Mediation"}],"wann_passt":["Two parties in a team conflict who can no longer talk to each other directly: NVC mediation by a third party creates a space where each side first receives empathy before negotiating solutions.","A couple or partnership conflict (professional or private) where both sides fundamentally want to keep working or living together: the empathy phase makes contact possible again as a foundation.","When classic mediation hasn't produced a breakthrough because the parties jump straight into negotiation mode: NVC mediation deliberately slows down and asks first about the inner experience."],"wann_nicht":["With violence in the relationship or a strong power gap without protective measures: empathy can blur responsibility; safety measures are needed first.","When one party isn't willing to take part in the process or rejects the basis of the procedure.","When the mediator is themselves involved in the conflict or has a personal opinion: NVC mediation requires genuine impartiality.","From Glasl stage 6+ onward: then professional conflict intervention is needed, not just a mediation offer."],"fokusfragen":["What's going on in you when you think of the situation — what do you feel? (empathy opening with party A)","What did you need in that situation that wasn't there? (opening the level of needs)","What do you hear when party B says that — what do you notice from what they just expressed? (mutual empathy offering)"],"mini_form":"Empathy round (15 minutes): the mediator gives both parties empathy in turn (reflecting feeling + need), without pressure for a solution. Only once both signal they feel heard is the question asked: what's needed now? — the solution space opens on its own.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech","coaching"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2 parties + 1 mediator; rarely more than 3-4 people","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"tanz-der-beduerfnisse","name":"Dance of Needs","feld":"E","kurz":"Make the NVC process physically tangible — movement in the room deepens the inner movement.","schritte":["Lay out floor markers: fields for observation, feeling, need, request (two tracks: self-empathy / empathy)","One person brings a real concern and physically moves from field to field","On each field, articulate out loud what's alive there — the guide asks supportive questions","Switch between the self and empathy tracks when the process stalls","Closing: what changed through the movement?"],"zweck":"Make the NVC process physically tangible — movement in the room deepens the inner movement.","hinweise":"Developed by Bridget Belgrave and Gina Lawrie (NVC Dance Floors). Needs space and willingness to show yourself in front of others. Works well as a demonstration with one person and an observing group.","phasen":["vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["selbstzugang","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"NVC Dance Floors (Belgrave/Lawrie)","url":"https://nvcdancefloors.com/"}],"wann_passt":["An NVC training that wants more than cognitive transmission: the Dance of Needs (NVC Dance Floors, developed by Bridget Belgrave and Gina Lawrie) makes the inner process physically tangible.","A demonstration with one volunteer in front of a group: one person walks their own conflict through the dance floor — the group observes and learns through witnessing.","An integration exercise after several NVC units: when the four steps are known cognitively but don't yet flow — the physical walk through the fields anchors them."],"wann_nicht":["When participants don't feel ready to expose themselves physically: the format presupposes willingness to show yourself to others in a process.","Online: without physical space and bodily movement, the format loses its central mechanism.","As an introductory format without basic NVC knowledge: without knowledge of the four steps, the physical navigation is meaningless."],"fokusfragen":["Which situation do you want to walk through the dance floor — what's the concrete triggering situation? (set the topic)","Where are you standing on the field right now — at observation, at feeling, at need, or at request? (physical positioning)","What changes when you physically step from one field into the next? (naming the physical experience)"],"mini_form":"Dance-floor demonstration (15 minutes): a volunteer takes a concrete topic, the facilitator guides them through the four fields (observation - feeling - need - request) with one question per field. The group observes silently.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","coaching"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1 active person + group as witnesses; group 5-20 people","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"harvard-konzept","name":"Harvard Concept (Principled Negotiation)","feld":"E","kurz":"Negotiate on the merits – hard on the issues, soft on the people, creating value for both sides.","schritte":["Separate people from problem: name relationship issues and address them separately","Ask for the interests behind the positions: Why does this matter to you?","Develop options for mutual gain – generate first, evaluate later","Agree on objective criteria for evaluation","Check your own BATNA and make a decision"],"zweck":"Negotiate on the merits – hard on the issues, soft on the people, creating value for both sides.","hinweise":"Clarify your BATNA before the negotiation, not during it. In purely distributive conflicts with a large power imbalance, the concept reaches its limits – then only your own alternative protects you.","phasen":["entscheiden","konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["entscheidung","klaerung"],"formate":["coaching","workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Program on Negotiation (Harvard) – Principled Negotiation","url":"https://www.pon.harvard.edu/daily/negotiation-skills-daily/principled-negotiation-focus-interests-create-value/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Roger Fisher / William Ury: Getting to Yes (1981; dt. Das Harvard-Konzept)"}],"wann_passt":["Negotiation with a clear substantive issue and at least two parties with differing interests: Harvard separates positions from interests, creating space for creative solutions that let both sides win.","Preparing for difficult contract negotiations: clarifying your BATNA, anticipating the other side's interests, and gathering criteria for fair solutions gives you confidence instead of reactivity.","Training for anyone who negotiates regularly (procurement, project management, collective bargaining): the four-principle model is pragmatic and transferable."],"wann_nicht":["In purely distributive conflicts with a massive power imbalance: if one side has no realistic BATNA, it can only protect its alternative – Harvard principles barely help then.","When the relationship level is so damaged that substantive negotiation is impossible: address NVC mediation or relationship clarification first, then Harvard.","In value conflicts without substantive content: Harvard resolves conflicts of interest, not fundamental differences in values."],"fokusfragen":["What is your position – and what is the interest behind it? (separating positions from interests)","What would be an objective criterion by which we could measure a fair solution? (developing objective criteria)","What is your best alternative if this negotiation fails – your BATNA? (realistically assessing negotiating power)"],"mini_form":"Interest mapping (10 minutes): Each party writes down its position and, underneath, three interests behind it. Then compare: are there overlapping interests that could enable a shared solution?","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2 parties + optional facilitation; for trainings up to 20 people","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"phasenmodell-mediation","name":"Phase Model of Mediation","feld":"E","kurz":"Guide conflict parties through a structured, all-party process toward an agreement they develop themselves.","schritte":["Introduction: clarify the working alliance, roles, ground rules, and voluntary participation","Gathering topics: hear perspectives, create a topic list, agree on order","Clarifying interests (the core): surface the interests, feelings, and needs behind the positions","Options: gather solution ideas creatively, then evaluate","Agreement: put a workable solution in writing, agree on implementation and review"],"zweck":"Guide conflict parties through a structured, all-party process toward an agreement they develop themselves.","hinweise":"The most common mistake is jumping from phase 2 straight to solutions – phase 3 carries the sustainability. When NOT to use: without voluntary participation of both sides, in cases of violence within the relationship, or once escalation is high (Glasl level 7+).","phasen":["konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["konflikt","klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":240,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":8,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Deutsche Stiftung Mediation – Phasen einer Mediation","url":"https://stiftung-mediation.de/phasen-einer-mediation/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Christoph Besemer: Mediation – Vermittlung in Konflikten (1993)"}],"wann_passt":["A structured mediation process between two or more parties seeking an agreement: the phase model (opening – narration – deepening – solution space – agreement) gives the process a clear, reassuring framework.","Training context for aspiring mediators: the phase model is the basic structure that integrates all other mediation techniques.","More complex multi-party mediations (e.g. neighborhood disputes, internal organizational conflict): the phases ensure the deepening phase (phase 3) isn't skipped."],"wann_nicht":["Without genuine voluntary participation of both sides: forced mediation doesn't produce sustainable agreements.","In cases of domestic violence or a massive power imbalance within the relationship: mediation requires parity of arms.","From Glasl level 7 upward: other processes apply there (arbitration, power intervention); mediation is no longer safely possible."],"fokusfragen":["What happened from your point of view – what is occupying you about this situation? (phase 2: narration, per party)","What was going on inside you when that happened – what did it do to you? (phase 3: deepening – don't skip this!)","What would you need from the other side so that you could leave this room saying: it was worth being here? (transition to phase 4)"],"mini_form":"Phase awareness as an intervention: during an ongoing mediation, pause briefly and make transparent which phase the process is in – 'We're now in the deepening phase, before we move to solutions. That's intentional.' Builds trust and slows the push toward solutions.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2-4 parties + mediator; up to 8 people in multi-party mediation","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"transformative-mediation","name":"Transformative Mediation (Bush/Folger)","feld":"E","kurz":"Use the conflict as an opportunity for parties to regain empowerment and recognition of the other.","schritte":["Set the frame: the parties determine topics, pace, and outcome – the mediator follows","Accompany the parties' conversation without structuring it","Support empowerment moments: when a party gains clarity, give it space","Support recognition moments: when a party begins to see the other, gently reinforce it","Agreement only if the parties want it – it is not the success criterion"],"zweck":"Use the conflict as an opportunity for parties to regain empowerment (self-efficacy) and recognition of the other.","hinweise":"Success here is not agreement but changed interaction – prepare clients for this in advance. When NOT to use: when a quick substantive solution is needed or parties expect clear procedural direction.","phasen":["konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["konflikt","selbstzugang"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung","coaching"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":6,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Beyond Intractability – Transformative Mediation","url":"https://www.beyondintractability.org/essay/transformative_mediation"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Robert Baruch Bush / Joseph Folger: The Promise of Mediation (1994)"}],"wann_passt":["Conflicts where the focus isn't primarily on reaching an agreement but on the quality of the relationship and the parties' sense of agency: transformative mediation pursues empowerment (strengthening one's own capacity to act) and recognition of the other as goals – not agreement.","Organizational conflicts where hierarchy dynamics and violations of dignity overshadow the substantive level: the format gives both sides room to strengthen their own position and truly hear the other side.","When classic mediation keeps producing agreements that don't hold: that shows the relationship itself is the real issue – transformative mediation addresses that."],"wann_nicht":["When a quick substantive solution is needed: transformative mediation is slow and relationship-oriented – the Harvard Concept is better suited to urgent substantive questions.","When clients (e.g. an HR department) set agreement as the success criterion: clarify beforehand that transformation is no guarantee of agreement.","When a party expects clear procedural direction from the facilitator: transformative mediation is less directive than classic mediation."],"fokusfragen":["What would be a sign for you that you achieved something important in this conversation – not as an agreement, but as an experience? (clarifying expectations)","What would you like to say to the other side now – in your own words? (empowerment: finding your own voice)","What did you hear when party B said that – what landed with you? (recognition: truly hearing the other side)"],"mini_form":"Empowerment pause (5 minutes): if a party blocks or falls silent during mediation, ask a brief empowerment question: What would you like to say in this moment – what matters to you right now? No pressure toward a solution, just space for their own voice.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","coaching","schwieriges_gespraech"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2 parties + mediator","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"restorative-justice","name":"Restorative Justice / Victim-Offender Mediation","feld":"E","kurz":"Respond to wrongdoing with repair, accountability, and relationship clarification instead of punishment alone.","schritte":["Separate preliminary talks: clarify voluntary participation, expectations, and safety for both sides","Encounter: the harmed person describes the act and its consequences","Taking accountability: the responsible person listens, responds, and takes responsibility","Clarifying needs: what is needed for repair – material and symbolic?","Reach an agreement","Follow up on fulfillment"],"zweck":"Respond to wrongdoing with repair, accountability, and relationship clarification instead of punishment alone.","hinweise":"Never bring both sides together without thorough preparation of each. When NOT to use: when the party responsible does not accept accountability, when there is risk of re-victimization, or when the harmed party participates only under pressure.","phasen":["konflikt"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","feld"],"modi":["konflikt","klaerung"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":10,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Servicebüro für Täter-Opfer-Ausgleich und Konfliktschlichtung","url":"https://www.toa-servicebuero.de/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Howard Zehr: The Little Book of Restorative Justice (2002)"}],"wann_passt":["Victim-offender mediation in a criminal-justice context: when a person wants to take responsibility for an act and the harmed person is willing to enter dialogue – with professional support and full voluntary participation on both sides.","School conflicts or internal organizational violations, where a harmed party wants to be heard and the responsible party can take accountability: restorative justice as an alternative to purely disciplinary measures.","Community processes after an incident affecting several people: circle-based RJ processes give the community a role, not just those directly involved."],"wann_nicht":["When the responsible person does not take accountability or denies what happened: RJ requires, at minimum, acknowledgment of the event.","When the harmed person participates only under social or institutional pressure: forced RJ processes re-traumatize.","When there is a risk of re-victimization (e.g. relationship violence, where the responsible person still holds power over the harmed person).","As a quick or mandatory procedure without preparation for both sides."],"fokusfragen":["What happened – from your point of view? (harmed party speaks first)","What did what happened mean for you – how has it affected your life? (impact of the act on the harmed party)","What do you need now for something to be repaired? (defining repair)"],"mini_form":"No meaningful mini format: restorative justice requires full preparation and support – a shortened procedure without a pre-circle and safety check can cause harm.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2-5 people directly involved + facilitator; community circles larger","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"oral-history","name":"Oral History","feld":"E","kurz":"Preserve lived memory as a source and honor people as witnesses of their own history.","schritte":["Choose the narrator and thematic focus","Clarify consent: purpose, recording, use, and right to withdraw","Conduct an open biographical interview – start chronologically, interrupt little, keep the narrative flow","Record (audio/video) and document key passages","Obtain the narrator's approval","Archive or share as agreed"],"zweck":"Preserve lived memory as a source and honor people as witnesses of their own history.","hinweise":"Data ownership stays with the narrators – consent for use is non-negotiable. When there are experiences of violence, interview in a trauma-sensitive way (no probing for details, offer pauses).","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["person","feld"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":3,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Oral History Association – Do Oral History","url":"https://oralhistory.org/about/do-oral-history/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Oral History Association - Trauma-Informed Interviewing","url":"https://oralhistory.org/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peacebuilding Practice (Woman PeaceMaker Program, 2023) – Chapter 3: Transitional Justice / Testimony"}],"wann_passt":["Contexts with suppressed or divided memory (post-conflict processing, transitional justice): oral history gives people the chance to tell their version of the story and thereby regain dignity — especially powerful with witnesses of human rights violations.","Community research as PAR (Participatory Action Research): when the community itself researches its own history, participants become researchers and break down the divide between knowers and non-knowers.","Intergenerational dialogue formats: older people tell their stories, younger people listen and document — the process itself builds bridges between generations."],"wann_nicht":["Without consent and data protection: oral history recordings can endanger people, especially in authoritarian contexts.","As an alibi process: if stories are collected but never reflected back to the community, extraction happens instead of empowerment."],"fokusfragen":["\"Tell me about [a certain time/event] — what did you experience, who was there, what changed afterward?\" (open narrative invitation)","\"What do you want the next generation to know about this time?\" (strengthening dignity and relevance)","\"If you had known back then what you know today — what would you have done differently?\" (opening a level of reflection)"],"mini_form":"15-minute mini-interview: pairs of two, one interviews, one answers exactly one question: 'Tell me about the moment that shaped you most in this work.' No interruption, no comments. Afterward: which single sentence from what you heard stays with you?","anlass_typen":["dialograum","lernformat","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-20 people, also works 1:1","stimmung_geeignet":["belastet","neugierig"]},{"id":"narrative-mediation","name":"Narrative Mediation (Winslade/Monk)","feld":"E","kurz":"Separate conflict parties from their conflict story and enable an alternative, shared narrative of the relationship.","schritte":["Hear both conflict stories in full – with double listening: also listening for what the conflict story doesn't capture","Externalize the conflict: name it as a separate third entity (the dispute, the mistrust)","Map its effects: what does the conflict do to each side?","Look for exceptions (unique outcomes): moments when the relationship was different","Build a counter-story of the relationship together from those exceptions"],"zweck":"Separate conflict parties from their conflict story and enable an alternative, shared narrative of the relationship.","hinweise":"Externalization is precision language work – sustain it consistently ('the conflict wants ...', never 'you do ...'). Works poorly when a party needs the conflict story as identity.","phasen":["konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["konflikt","klaerung"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung","coaching"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":8,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"UNM Ombuds – Narrative Mediation: Re-authoring Conflict Stories (PDF)","url":"https://ombudsfac.unm.edu/Article_Summaries/Narrative_Mediation.pdf"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"John Winslade / Gerald Monk: Narrative Mediation (2000)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Beyond Intractability - Narrative Mediation (Winslade/Monk)","url":"https://www.beyondintractability.org/bksum/winslade-narrative"}],"wann_passt":["Conflicts where both sides are strongly identified with their version of the story and positions act like identity armor: narrative mediation externalizes the conflict ('the conflict wants...' instead of 'you do...') and makes the story discussable without attacking the person.","Long-standing conflicts that keep recurring despite factual clarifications: this often shows that the conflict story itself is the problem, not just the substantive issues.","When a party carries the conflict story as identity: narrative mediation creates space for an alternative story of the relationship without denying the previous one."],"wann_nicht":["When a party needs the conflict story as identity and is not willing to develop an alternative narrative: the format only works if at least one side brings openness.","When a quick substantive solution is needed: narrative mediation is slow and linguistically precise – prefer other formats for urgent substantive conflicts.","Without the facilitator consistently using externalizing language: as soon as the facilitator slips back into 'you have' or 'she has', the mechanism breaks down."],"fokusfragen":["What would you call the conflict if it had its own personality – what would its character be? (introducing externalization)","When did the conflict have less power over your relationship – what was different in those moments? (unique outcomes / looking for exceptions)","What would a different story of your relationship sound like, one in which the conflict takes up less space? (developing the alternative story)"],"mini_form":"Externalization opener (5-10 minutes): have the conflict named – 'let's call it the old dispute' – and then ask: What does the old dispute want when it shows up – what does it gain? Creates distance from the story without denying it.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","coaching","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2 parties + mediator; rarely more than 4-5 people","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","belastet"]},{"id":"testimony-zeugenschaft","name":"Testimony / Bearing Witness","feld":"E","kurz":"Publicly bear witness to experienced injustice – combining personal honoring with societal recognition.","schritte":["Establish a safe frame and absolute voluntary participation, secure support","The person tells of the injustice they experienced – the account is documented verbatim","Joint editing: the raw text becomes a coherent statement authorized by the person","Honoring handover or reading aloud (often as a small ceremony with witnesses)","Use only with consent: advocacy, archive, public remembrance"],"zweck":"Publicly bear witness to experienced injustice – combining personal honoring with societal recognition.","hinweise":"Take the risk of re-traumatization seriously: only with a support structure and never under time pressure. When NOT to use: as an exercise simulated by uninvolved people, or without clarity about what happens to the testimony.","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["person","feld"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"MIT Press Reader – Of Trauma, Testimony, and the Power of Human Rights Voices","url":"https://thereader.mitpress.mit.edu/of-trauma-testimony-and-the-power-of-human-rights-voices/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Trauma-Informed Peacebuilding - PMC Review","url":"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12930582/"}],"wann_passt":["Public honoring of survivors: testimony as part of a commemoration format, an exhibition, or a reconciliation process – when the narrating person has decided themselves to speak and a support structure is in place.","Educational context with eyewitnesses: when survivors share their story in schools, universities, or trainings – with a clear frame, voluntary participation, and honoring by the listeners.","Truth commissions and institutional processes of reckoning: testimony as a formal act of societal recognition."],"wann_nicht":["As an exercise with uninvolved people pretending to have experienced something: this simulates dignity instead of establishing it – and can damage the format.","Without a clear structure for what happens to the testimony: narrators must know whether the testimony will be recorded, published, or kept confidential.","Under time pressure or as an item squeezed between other activities: testimony needs time before and after – for arrival and for aftercare.","In cases of acute, unprocessed trauma without a psychological support structure: without preparation and follow-up support, the risk of re-traumatization is considerable."],"fokusfragen":["What do you want the people in this room to take from your testimony – what is the message behind the story? (clarifying the narrator's intent)","What did you hear as a listener – what has found a place in you? (honoring by the group)","What remains – what does this testimony change for you? (impact of bearing witness)"],"mini_form":"No meaningful mini format: testimony needs a full frame (preparation, testimony, honoring, aftercare). A shortened format without these elements is not testimony.","anlass_typen":["dialograum","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1 witness + group; group of 10-100 depending on context","stimmung_geeignet":["belastet","neugierig"]},{"id":"storytelling-for-peace","name":"Storytelling for Peace","feld":"E","kurz":"Build empathy between hostile or estranged groups through personal stories.","schritte":["Create a safe frame: storytelling ground rules (first-person perspective, no debate, confidentiality)","Pose a guiding question that opens personal experience","Tell stories across the conflict line – alternating between both groups","Listen without comment, then a resonance round: what touched me?","Gather shared themes – where do the experiences resemble each other?"],"zweck":"Build empathy between hostile or estranged groups through personal stories.","hinweise":"Do not allow discussion about the truth of the stories – experience is not up for debate. Maintain balance between groups and speaking time. When NOT to use: in cases of acute violence between those present, or when one side would dominate the stage.","phasen":["oeffnen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["workshop","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Peace Insight – Storytelling for peace","url":"https://www.peaceinsight.org/en/articles/storytelling-peace/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Lederach - The Moral Imagination: Summary","url":"https://www.beyondintractability.org/bksum/lederach-imagination"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Epilog: Wissensmanagement als gemeinsames Lernen"}],"wann_passt":["A learning format or community process (10-40 people) where experiences of violence, loss, or injustice are to be shared without re-traumatizing — structured storytelling gives frame and safety.","Monitoring and evaluation as an MSC complement: stories of transformation (e.g. 'What has changed in your community?') make impact tangible in ways numbers cannot capture.","Network meetings with a heterogeneous group: when people from very different contexts come together, a structured story round ('Tell of a moment when you experienced peace') can connect people without relying on shared facts."],"wann_nicht":["Without a safety frame in groups with fresh trauma: stories of violence or loss need clear preparation, voluntary participation, and the facilitator's readiness to provide aftercare.","When storytelling is misused as a PR exercise: 'Share a success story with us' — that creates selection bias and no genuine picture of impact."],"fokusfragen":["\"Tell me about a specific moment — what did you see, hear, feel? When was that, where were you?\" (inviting concreteness, not abstraction)","\"What changed through this moment — in you, in your relationship, in your community?\" (connecting to transformation)","\"If you told this story to someone who has never heard of peacebuilding — what should they take from it?\" (distillation and transfer question)"],"mini_form":"2-minute story round as check-in: everyone shares in 2 minutes a situation where they experienced communication/dialogue changing something. No comments from others. Enough as an opener for a reflection format.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","dialograum","beteiligung","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-30 people","stimmung_geeignet":["belastet","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"perspektivuebernahme","name":"Perspective-Taking (Walk in My Shoes)","feld":"E","kurz":"Not just understand the other side's inner perspective, but try it on – empathy through embodiment.","schritte":["Form pairs across the line of difference/conflict","A shares a formative experience, B listens attentively","Perspective shift: B speaks in first person as A – introduces themselves or answers questions from A's point of view","A corrects and adds detail","Switch roles","Reflection: what has shifted in the view of the other person?"],"zweck":"Not just understand the other side's inner perspective, but try it on – empathy through embodiment.","hinweise":"High emotional intensity – clear de-roling at the end. Explicitly get permission for speaking on someone's behalf beforehand. When NOT to use: with fresh trauma, or when speaking on someone's behalf would be experienced as appropriation.","phasen":["vertiefen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","netzwerk"],"modi":["verbindung","selbstzugang"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Greater Good Science Center – Empathy: Definition & Practices","url":"https://greatergood.berkeley.edu/topic/empathy/definition"}],"wann_passt":["Empathy training for professionals who work with people in difficult situations (social workers, doctors, mediators): perspective-taking through role play or guided imagination creates an embodied understanding that goes beyond cognitive knowledge.","Conflict clarification as preparation: each party takes on the other's perspective before the actual conversation – this reduces defensiveness.","Dialogue programs with opposing groups: walk-in-my-shoes exercises as an opener, to try on the other side's inner perspective — not as agreement, but as comprehension."],"wann_nicht":["With fresh trauma, or when speaking on someone's behalf is experienced as appropriating their suffering: then the format is potentially re-traumatizing and disrespectful.","Without clear de-roling at the end: the intensity of perspective-taking needs a conscious exit – without it, the person stays stuck in the role.","When a group has not explicitly permitted speaking on its behalf: explicit consent from the represented group is a precondition."],"fokusfragen":["If you were [person/group X] – what would you feel in this situation, what would matter to you? (introducing perspective-taking)","What was surprising or unfamiliar about the perspective you took on? (de-roling and reflection)","What changes for you in your own point of view after taking on this perspective? (transfer)"],"mini_form":"3-minute perspective shift: Imagine you are the other side. What would you need right now in this room? – 1 minute of silent reflection, then share in pairs. No full role play needed.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","konfliktklaerung","dialograum"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"any size for imagination exercises; 6-20 for structured role play","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"empathic-deep-listening","name":"Empathic / Deep Listening","feld":"E","kurz":"Experience listening as an intervention in its own right – being heard changes speakers and listeners alike.","schritte":["Form pairs or small groups, agree on clear speaking times (3-5 min)","One person speaks, the other listens with full presence – without interrupting, without inwardly preparing a response","Consciously set aside your own frame of interpretation, tolerate silence","Reflect back what was heard – content and tone, not interpretation","Switch roles","Meta-reflection: what does this kind of listening do to the conversation?"],"zweck":"Experience listening as an intervention in its own right – being heard changes speakers and listeners alike.","hinweise":"The temptation to interpret or to help is the main pitfall. Quality drops sharply with fatigue – better short and focused than long.","phasen":["vertiefen","ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","coaching"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Beyond Intractability – Empathic Listening (Richard Salem)","url":"https://www.beyondintractability.org/essay/empathic_listening"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peacebuilding Practice (Woman PeaceMaker Program, 2023) – Chapter 13: Facilitative Listening Design"}],"wann_passt":["A dialogue space or mediation setting where one party first needs to truly be heard before solutions are discussed — deep listening creates the space that makes NVC-style communication possible in the first place.","Research and field work in conflict contexts: the Facilitative Listening Design (FLD) variant from Cambodia shows that structured listening (Be there / Listen carefully / Accept them / Stay with them / Trust them) can change perceptions of 'the other' — even without confrontation.","Check-in in strained groups: 3-5 minutes of genuine listening (no advice, no judgment) as the opening of a difficult meeting lowers defensiveness."],"wann_nicht":["When the listening person is themselves strongly emotionally activated — first do self-regulation (breathing exercise, short pause) before attempting deep listening.","As a technique without genuine interest: paraphrasing alone is not deep listening. If the listening person is already mentally at their response, the speaker feels it."],"fokusfragen":["\"What is it that you really want to say — behind the words?\" (inviting, not analytical)","\"What is the one thing you'd like me to really understand?\" (focuses on the essential)","\"I heard that... Is that what you mean?\" (paraphrase as a check for understanding, not as a summary)"],"beispiel":"FLD conversation opener: two people from hostile groups sit together. Listener begins: 'We want to understand what life is like here for you. Tell us — what is on your mind most right now in your community?' No comment, no counter-argument. If the person says something that sounds false or exaggerated: 'That sounds difficult. Did you experience that yourself?' — the question checks without confronting and often opens space for more nuanced perspectives.","mini_form":"10-minute listening round: pairs, 4 minutes each. Person A talks about something on their mind. Person B listens without speaking, no advice, and at the end says one sentence: 'What I heard is...' — no interpretation. Then switch. Reflection question: what was hard about listening?","anlass_typen":["dialograum","konfliktklaerung","lernformat","coaching"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"1:1 up to 20 (in pairs or small groups)","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"erzaehlcafe","name":"Story Café","feld":"E","kurz":"Combine biographical storytelling and communal listening – making life stories a shared richness.","schritte":["Choose a topic with biographical relevance","Create a café atmosphere: drinks, small rounds, low threshold","Facilitation invites storytelling – explicitly to tell, not to discuss","Storytelling rounds with gentle follow-up questions; everyone may, no one must","Honor communal listening, point out connections between the stories","Honoring closing"],"zweck":"Combine biographical storytelling and communal listening – making life stories a shared richness.","hinweise":"Facilitation protects against discussion and judgment – that's its main task. Choose a topic that all generations/groups can connect with.","phasen":["oeffnen","ankommen"],"ebenen":["netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["verbindung"],"formate":["grossgruppe","workshop"],"dauer_min":90,"dauer_max":150,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Netzwerk Erzählcafé – Leitfaden Erzählcafés veranstalten (PDF)","url":"https://netzwerk-erzaehlcafe.ch/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Leitfaden_zweite-Auflage_06_2019.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["Intergenerational encounters in communities, social institutions, or organizations: the story café gives people of different generations or backgrounds a dignified frame to share life memories – without judgment or discussion.","New groups or networks that don't yet know each other and want to build connection beyond the substantive topic: biographical storytelling around a shared theme builds connection and mutual understanding quickly.","Closing or transition ritual in communities: when something ends or changes – a story café that gathers the shared history."],"wann_nicht":["When facilitation does not clearly intervene as soon as discussion or judgment arises: the story café thrives on stories being allowed to stand side by side, without being compared or judged.","With a topic that structurally excludes certain groups (e.g. 'Tell us about your childhood in the countryside' when many city people are present).","As a quick format in a packed program: story cafés need atmosphere, leisure, and enough time – at least 60-90 minutes."],"fokusfragen":["Tell us about a moment when you truly experienced [topic] for the first time – concrete, personal. (thematic opener)","What was most important about this experience – what do you want others to know about it? (deepening)","What connects you to the stories you just heard? (bridge between narrators)"],"mini_form":"Mini story round (15 minutes): an object is placed in the middle (photo, everyday item). Each person tells a single sentence about it: This object reminds me of... No comment, no discussion. Let an atmosphere of shared remembering emerge.","anlass_typen":["dialograum","netzwerktreffen","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-20 ideal; with larger groups form subgroups and share highlights at the end","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","müde","belastet"]},{"id":"strukturaufstellungen","name":"Structural Constellations (Sparrer/Varga von Kibéd)","feld":"E","kurz":"Make the structure of a system visible and provisionally changeable – even covertly, without disclosing content.","schritte":["Clarify the concern in a preliminary conversation","Abstractly define relevant elements (focus, goal, obstacle, resource – no real people needed)","Choose representatives and place them intuitively in the room","Ask the representatives about their perceptions (representative perception)","Test interventions: repositioning, process words, resolving sentences","Anchor the solution image, careful de-roling"],"zweck":"Make the structure of a system visible and provisionally changeable – even covertly, without disclosing content.","hinweise":"Requires trained facilitation. Constellation images are hypotheses, not proof of truth – introduce them that way. When NOT to use: during acute psychological crises of participants, or as a spectacle without a mandate.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","selbstzugang"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["koerperlich","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"SySt-Institut München (Sparrer/Varga von Kibéd)","url":"https://www.syst.info/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Insa Sparrer / Matthias Varga von Kibéd: Ganz im Gegenteil (2000)"}],"wann_passt":["Coaching or consulting with someone who wants to understand a complex system (organization, network, family business) without disclosing all content: structural constellations (Sparrer/Varga von Kibéd) can work covertly – the representatives don't know the content.","Strategy processes with a small group that wants to make a systemic phenomenon visible: where are solutions hiding that haven't yet been thought of? The constellation gives the system a voice.","Training context for systemic work: structural constellations as a learning format to experience system dynamics physically."],"wann_nicht":["Without trained facilitation: the format produces intense experiences (physical resonance, representation phenomena) – without training, misinterpretation and harm are possible.","During acute psychological crises of participants: the format is contraindicated if someone in the room is in an acute unstable state.","As spectacle or entertainment without a clear mandate from the person setting up the constellation.","When constellation images are communicated as truth rather than hypothesis: this is the most common ethical overstep in practice."],"fokusfragen":["What is the question you want this constellation to clarify – what should become visible? (clarifying the mandate)","What do you sense in this position – what draws you, what pushes you away? (questioning the representative)","What changes when we move this element – what becomes easier or harder? (searching for solutions in the constellation)"],"mini_form":"Three-chairs constellation (10-15 minutes): three chairs represent, e.g., status quo, resistance, solution. The person doing the constellation sits on each in turn, senses into each position, and describes the perception. No representatives needed.","anlass_typen":["coaching","strategie","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1 person setting up the constellation + 3-10 representatives + observers; 5-20 total","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","angespannt"]},{"id":"soziometrie-aufstellung","name":"Sociometry / Spatial Positioning (Moreno)","feld":"E","kurz":"Quickly make differences, relationships, and distributions within the group physically visible.","schritte":["Choose a question or dimension (agreement, experience, background, closeness to the topic)","Define the space: line, scale, map, or circle","Everyone positions themselves at the same time","Interview individual positions: why are you standing here?","Optional second question or repositioning","Jointly evaluate the group structure that became visible"],"zweck":"Quickly make differences, relationships, and distributions within the group physically visible.","hinweise":"Choose questions carefully – positioning exposes people (avoid questions that single anyone out). Can be done online with whiteboard dots, but loses the physical dimension.","phasen":["ankommen","verstehen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["verbindung","energie"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":50,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Werner Stangl – Was ist Soziometrie?","url":"https://arbeitsblaetter.stangl-taller.at/FORSCHUNGSMETHODEN/Soziometrie.shtml"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"}],"wann_passt":["A group that doesn't yet know each other and should quickly get a physical picture of commonalities and differences: sociometry makes diversity visible without anyone needing to speak – movement is enough.","Check-in in large groups: instead of having everyone speak, everyone positions themselves – where in the room do I stand on this question? That's fast, inclusive, and generates energy.","Team day or kickoff: who has been here how long? Who comes from where? Who has what experience with the topic? Sociometry as a playful opener."],"wann_nicht":["With questions that could expose or embarrass individuals: 'Who has felt uncomfortable here in the past week?' visibly singles people out – that needs very high trust.","Online without an alternative tool (whiteboard, Mentimeter): the physical dimension is missing and the format loses its main advantage.","In highly escalated conflicts, where spatial positioning is experienced as forming camps."],"fokusfragen":["Position yourselves in the room according to: who has [trait/experience]? The more familiar you are with it, the further into this corner. (positioning invitation)","Look around – what do you see? What surprises you? (reflecting on the distribution)"],"mini_form":"Position check (5 minutes): one question, everyone lines up on an imaginary line (left = little, right = a lot). Look around the room. One person from each side says a sentence. Done.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","lernformat","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-50 people ideal; under 6 it loses impact","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","müde"]},{"id":"genogramm","name":"Genogram / Family Tree","feld":"E","kurz":"Make multigenerational patterns visible that continue to shape current behavior and concerns.","schritte":["Draw at least three generations using standard symbols","Add basic data: births, deaths, separations, occupations, formative events","Mark relationship qualities (close, conflictual, cut off)","Explore patterns: repetitions, ruptures, family legacies, taboos","Form hypotheses and connect them to the current concern"],"zweck":"Make multigenerational patterns visible that continue to shape current behavior and concerns.","hinweise":"Belongs in a protected counseling setting, not in a plenary. Respect the narrator's pace – behind every symbol is a story.","phasen":["verstehen"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["selbstzugang","klaerung"],"formate":["coaching"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":3,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"GenoPro – Introduction to the Genogram","url":"https://genopro.com/genogram/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection (Family Tree)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Monica McGoldrick / Randy Gerson: Genograms – Assessment and Intervention (1985)"}],"wann_passt":["Individual coaching or systemic counseling where patterns from the family of origin shape current behavior: the genogram makes multigenerational patterns visible that would otherwise be barely discussable.","Family counseling or therapy: a standard tool for mapping loyalties, losses, repeating patterns, and resources across generations.","Leadership development (a deep format, not standard coaching): when someone wants to understand which leadership images from their family of origin shape their own leadership behavior."],"wann_nicht":["In a plenary or in groups without an explicit therapeutic/counseling mandate: genograms touch very personal material – they belong in a protected individual or small-group format.","When the person has not explicitly consented to go deep biographically: respect the narrator's pace.","As a diagnostic instrument without systemic training: reading genograms requires context and training – otherwise patterns are misread."],"fokusfragen":["Who was especially important in your family – a person who strongly shaped you? (opening without pressure for completeness)","What theme or pattern keeps recurring in your family – across generations? (naming multigenerational patterns)","What did you take from these people that you still carry today – as a resource or as a burden? (mapping resources and burdens)"],"mini_form":"Genogram opener (15 minutes): sketch three generations (grandparents, parents, me). One question: Who in this map has shaped you most strongly – and how? Not a full genogram, but an entry point into multigenerational thinking.","anlass_typen":["coaching"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"Individual; in small groups (3-5) only with high trust","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"skulpturarbeit","name":"Sculpture Work (Satir)","feld":"E","kurz":"Condense relationship dynamics into a body image – communication patterns become felt, not just discussed.","schritte":["Clarify the concern and the system to be depicted","The presenting person physically arranges the members: posture, distance, gaze direction, gesture – without words","Freeze the sculpture, everyone senses into it","Ask for statements from the positions","Shape the change toward the desired sculpture","De-roling and joint reflection"],"zweck":"Condense relationship dynamics into a body image – communication patterns become felt, not just discussed.","hinweise":"The wordlessness is the mechanism of action – don't talk it apart along the way. Physical touch only with consent. Careful de-roling.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung","selbstzugang"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Systemisches Netzwerk – Methodensammlung: Skulpturarbeit","url":"https://systemischesnetzwerk.de/methodensammlung/skulpturarbeit/"}],"wann_passt":["Family counseling or individual/group therapy: sculpture work (Virginia Satir) makes communication patterns physically tangible – the stress postures (placater, blamer, super-reasonable, distracter) are immediately recognizable when embodied.","Training context for therapists, counselors, or mediators: getting to know one's own communication patterns through embodiment – lasting, because it's physical.","Team development format with a high level of trust: when a team is ready not just to discuss relationship dynamics but to make them physically visible."],"wann_nicht":["Without careful de-roling and a closing ritual: physically embodying roles needs a clear exit – otherwise the posture lingers.","When physical touch is not consensual: sculpture work often involves positioning people – only with explicit consent.","In teams without sufficient trust: the format makes vulnerability visible and needs a safe frame."],"fokusfragen":["What posture do you recognize in this sculpture – what does it show about the relationship? (letting the sculpture be interpreted)","What do you sense in this posture – what does your body tell you? (questioning the narrator within the sculpture)","What would the sculpture look like if the relationship were the way you wish it to be? (developing a solution image)"],"mini_form":"Posture demonstration (5 minutes): facilitation demonstrates a Satir stress posture (e.g. placater – body small, head lowered, hands open upward). Group observes. Question: When do you recognize this posture – in yourselves or others? No role play, just demonstration as an insight trigger.","anlass_typen":["coaching","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1-6 people active; group as witnesses up to 20","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"organisationsaufstellung","name":"Organizational Constellation","feld":"E","kurz":"Make hidden dynamics of an organization – loyalties, power, role conflicts – spatially tangible.","schritte":["Clarify the concern and determine relevant system elements (roles, departments, goals, customers)","Choose representatives and position them according to an inner image","Ask for perceptions","Develop hypotheses about loyalties, power, role clarity","Test interventions: repositioning, clarifying sentences","Transfer: what does this image mean for real decisions? De-roling"],"zweck":"Make hidden dynamics of an organization – loyalties, power, role conflicts – spatially tangible.","hinweise":"Clarify confidentiality when real colleagues are represented. Results are hypotheses. When NOT to use: for personnel evaluation or as a substitute for decisions; not with present parties to an escalated conflict without a protective frame.","phasen":["verstehen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["organisation"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["koerperlich","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"socialnet Lexikon – Aufstellung","url":"https://www.socialnet.de/lexikon/Aufstellung"}],"wann_passt":["Consulting a leader on a hidden system dynamic (loyalty conflicts, power questions, blind spots in the organization): the constellation gives the system a spatial voice that could not previously be articulated.","Team coaching for ongoing tensions that don't resolve despite conversations: when talking alone isn't enough, the constellation can show what is working structurally.","Organizational development during change processes: which forces work for and against the change? The constellation makes systemic forces visible before strategies are developed."],"wann_nicht":["For personnel evaluation or decisions about individuals: this would be an ethically unacceptable use of a projective format.","As a substitute for decisions: constellation images are hypotheses, not truths – treating the constellation as a basis for decisions crosses ethical boundaries.","With present parties to an escalated conflict without a protective frame and trained facilitation.","When confidentiality is not secured: real colleagues are represented – this needs a clear confidentiality frame."],"fokusfragen":["What is the concrete question you want the constellation to clarify – what should become visible? (clarifying the mandate)","What do you sense in this position – what pulls, what pushes, what is missing? (representative within the constellation)","What changes for the system when this person or element is positioned differently? (searching for solutions)"],"mini_form":"Symbol constellation (10 minutes): instead of people, objects (cups, cards, stones) are placed as representatives. The presenting person arranges the objects in the space and describes the relationships. A more affordable variant for coaching without a group.","anlass_typen":["coaching","strategie","konfliktklaerung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1 person setting up the constellation + 3-12 representatives; up to 20 people total","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"after-action-review","name":"After Action Review (AAR)","feld":"F","kurz":"Capture learning right after an action, while memory is fresh and implementation is close.","schritte":["Gather everyone involved promptly after the action","Question 1: What was supposed to happen? (reconstruct goal/plan)","Question 2: What actually happened? (facts, no blame)","Question 3: Why were there deviations? (causes, multiple perspectives)","Question 4: What are we learning – what will we do differently next time?","Capture insights and schedule them concretely"],"zweck":"Capture learning right after an action, while memory is fresh and implementation is close.","hinweise":"Blamelessness is the foundational premise – as soon as justifications dominate, sharpen the facilitation. Keep it short, routine beats perfection.","phasen":["reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["reflexion"],"formate":["meeting","workshop"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":15,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["reflexion","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"BetterEvaluation – After Action Review","url":"https://www.betterevaluation.org/methods-approaches/methods/after-action-review"},{"typ":"online","titel":"US Army AAR Guide – the original format","url":"https://www.aca.army.mil/Portals/119/AAR%20Guide.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["Right after a completed action, event, or critical decision – while memory and emotions are still fresh: project completion, event, difficult meeting.","As a short team ritual after every iteration, not only after failures: the AAR works best as a routine, not as an exception after crises.","When a team is under time pressure and a full retrospective isn't possible: a 15-minute AAR captures the essentials."],"wann_nicht":["When psychological safety is missing and the group expects blame rather than learning – sharpen the framing first before starting the AAR.","As a substitute for a deeper retrospective in a longer process: the AAR is close to the action, not team development.","In very hierarchical settings without explicit blame-free framing – facilitation must actively intervene if justification dominates."],"fokusfragen":["\"What was supposed to happen – what was the plan, the goal?\"","\"What actually happened – what do we observe, without judging?\"","\"Why were there deviations – what were the causes from different perspectives?\"","\"What are we taking with us – what will we concretely do differently next time?\""],"beispiel":"After a workshop: 15-minute AAR. Question 1: 'What did we plan for today?' (reconstructing the plan). Question 2: 'What actually happened – what felt different from the start?' (facts, no blame). Question 3: 'Why did the first block go better than the second?' (causes, multiple perspectives). Question 4: 'If we do this again tomorrow: what will we do differently?' (transfer, schedule immediately). Difference from a retrospective: the AAR focuses on a single action, is shorter, and the insights stay close to the action – no team-dynamics diagnosis.","mini_form":"Two-question blitz in 5 minutes: 'What went well today?' and 'What would we change tomorrow?' – written on post-its, then 3 mentions per question shared in plenary. Not a full AAR, but the learning is captured.","anlass_typen":["retro","regeltermin","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"3-12 people ideal; up to 15 with facilitation support","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"retrospektive","name":"Retrospective (Start/Stop/Continue, Sailboat, 4Ls)","feld":"F","kurz":"Regularly improve the how of collaboration – in small, actionable steps.","schritte":["Set the stage: check-in and clarify the focus of the retro","Gather data using a structure – e.g. sailboat (wind/anchor/rocks/island) or start/stop/continue, 4Ls","Work out patterns and insights together","Decide on a maximum of 2-3 concrete actions (owners, deadline)","Close the retro briefly (check-out, feedback on the retro)"],"zweck":"Regularly improve the how of collaboration – in small, actionable steps.","hinweise":"Fewer actions, but implemented ones. Rotate formats (Retromat), otherwise the ritual wears thin. Review old action items at the start.","phasen":["reflektieren"],"ebenen":["team"],"modi":["reflexion"],"formate":["meeting","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["reflexion","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Retromat – Retrospektive-Formate-Baukasten","url":"https://retromat.org/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"From the Impact Up method collection"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Esther Derby / Diana Larsen: Agile Retrospectives (2006)"}],"wann_passt":["At the end of a work phase, a sprint, or a project: when the team wants to improve the collaboration itself – not the content, but the how.","As a recurring ritual in the team's rhythm (monthly or quarterly): the retrospective needs continuity to develop trust and depth.","When concrete tensions in the collaboration are noticeable but no conflict format seems appropriate – a retro has a lower threshold than conflict clarification."],"wann_nicht":["After a single event where no team routine has been established yet: an AAR (closer to the action, more structured) fits better.","When the action items from the last retro were not implemented – check and make that transparent before gathering new ones.","When the hierarchy in the room is so strong that honest feedback isn't possible – build psychological safety first."],"fokusfragen":["\"[Start/Stop/Continue] What should we start, stop, keep doing?\"","\"[Sailboat] What is driving us forward (wind), what is holding us back (anchor), what threatens us (rocks), where do we want to go (island)?\"","\"[4Ls] What did we learn, like, lack, and long for?\""],"beispiel":"Difference between AAR and retrospective: the AAR asks about a single action (What was supposed to happen? What happened?), the retrospective asks about the how of collaboration over a period of time. AAR is shorter, closer to the action, without a team-development agenda. The retrospective has more structure (5 phases per Derby/Larsen: Set the Stage / Gather Data / Generate Insights / Decide What to Do / Close), always closes with concrete actions, and is designed for repetition. Sailboat format in 45 minutes: check-in (5 min) → category visualization on a flipchart → everyone writes post-its in silence (10 min) → cluster and discuss (15 min) → decide on max. 3 actions with owners and deadline (10 min) → check-out (5 min).","mini_form":"One-question retro in 10 minutes: a single question – e.g. 'What cost us the most energy this week?' – everyone writes an answer, 3 are shared, one action is named. Not a full format, but reflection happens.","anlass_typen":["retro","teamtag","regeltermin"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-12 people ideal; up to 15 with subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"kolb-learning-cycle","name":"Kolb Learning Cycle","feld":"F","kurz":"Design learning as a complete cycle – experience only becomes competence through reflection and application.","schritte":["Concrete experience: go through an exercise, simulation, or real task","Reflective observation: what happened, what did I perceive?","Abstract conceptualization: name patterns, connect them to models and concepts","Active experimentation: plan a concrete transfer and try it out next time"],"zweck":"Design learning as a complete cycle – experience only becomes competence through reflection and application.","hinweise":"Most trainings skip phase 2 or phase 4 – plan both in explicitly. Learners enter at different points, but the cycle still needs to be completed fully.","phasen":["reflektieren","planen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["reflexion"],"formate":["fortbildung","workshop"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["reflexion"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Simply Psychology – Kolb's Learning Styles and Experiential Learning Cycle","url":"https://www.simplypsychology.org/learning-kolb.html"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"David Kolb: Experiential Learning (1984)"}],"wann_passt":["In trainings or workshops where an exercise or simulation was done – Kolb structures the subsequent reflection so that experience becomes learning.","As a frame for the entire learning architecture of a day: experience (exercise) → reflection (AAR/retro elements) → conceptualization (input block) → transfer (what will I do next week?).","When a team wants to learn from experiences made, not just accumulate knowledge – Kolb makes the difference between knowledge transfer and competence development visible."],"wann_nicht":["When phase 2 (reflection) or phase 4 (transfer) get cut due to time pressure – better to run a smaller cycle consistently than to abandon a more complete method.","As an explanatory slide with no consequence for the design – the model needs to be visible in the flow, not just in the trainer's head.","When pure knowledge transfer is called for (rules, compliance) – the experiential cycle is oversized here."],"fokusfragen":["\"[Phase 2 – reflection] What did you perceive – what struck you, surprised you, moved you?\"","\"[Phase 3 – conceptualization] What pattern is behind this – how do you explain what happened?\"","\"[Phase 4 – transfer] What are you concretely taking with you – what will you do differently next time?\""],"beispiel":"Difference between Kolb and Gibbs: Kolb is a learning cycle (a design frame for trainers, a learning architecture for groups), Gibbs is a reflection format for individuals (written, 6 stages with explicit feeling and analysis phases). Kolb suits a group learning from a shared experience. Gibbs suits an individual working through a specific situation. Place the input block in Kolb's phase 3 (abstract conceptualization): the trainer offers the model after the group has named patterns itself – then the input has something to connect to.","mini_form":"Quick cycle in 15 minutes: after each exercise, ask 3 questions directly: 'What happened?' (experience) → 'What do you notice?' (reflection) → 'What will you take into your everyday life?' (transfer). Skip phase 3 (conceptualization) if needed – but never skip transfer.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","retro","teamtag"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"2-30 people; flexible","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"gibbs-reflective-cycle","name":"Gibbs Reflective Cycle","feld":"F","kurz":"Work through a single experience in writing, systematically, across six stages.","schritte":["Description: What happened? (facts only)","Feelings: What did I feel and think?","Evaluation: What was good, what was difficult?","Analysis: How do I make sense of this – what factors were at play?","Conclusion: What could I have done differently?","Action plan: What will I concretely do in a similar situation? – written individually, then optional exchange in pairs"],"zweck":"Work through a single experience in writing, systematically, across six stages.","hinweise":"Its strength is the forced separation of feeling, evaluation and analysis – don't let the stages blur together. Works well as a recurring learning-journal format.","phasen":["reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["reflexion","selbstzugang"],"formate":["coaching","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["schriftlich","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["reflexion"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"University of Edinburgh – Gibbs' Reflective Cycle (Reflection Toolkit)","url":"https://www.ed.ac.uk/reflection/reflectors-toolkit/reflecting-on-experience/gibbs-reflective-cycle"}],"wann_passt":["A person wants to systematically process a specific, emotionally charged situation – the forced separation of facts, feelings and analysis prevents everything from blending together.","In trainings where reflective competence is explicitly meant to be developed (teacher training, nursing education, OD training) – Gibbs provides a written learning-journal structure for this.","After a difficult facilitation or consulting situation: the 6 stages prevent premature judgments ('that was a mistake') and lead to more differentiated self-reflection."],"wann_nicht":["As a group format without written individual work: without the writing, the forced separation of stages is lost.","When the person is looking more for exchange than structured reflection – then Intervision or peer consultation is better.","For very brief events without emotional weight: the cycle is designed for significant, challenging experiences."],"fokusfragen":["\"[Stage 1 – Description] What exactly happened – who, what, when, how?\"","\"[Stage 2 – Feelings] What did I feel and think in that moment – honestly, without judgment?\"","\"[Stage 6 – Action plan] What will I concretely do in a similar situation – in one sentence, with a verb?\""],"beispiel":"Difference Gibbs vs. Kolb: Gibbs is an individual reflection format (written, 6 stages, focused on one specific experience, explicitly including feelings). Kolb is a learning cycle (groups or individuals, a design frame for trainings). Gibbs suits: 'I just had a difficult situation – I want to work through it.' Kolb suits: 'We just did an exercise – what do we learn from it as a group?' In practice: Gibbs as a learning-journal template after each consulting session in an OD training – stages as headings, 20 minutes of writing time, then optional exchange in pairs.","mini_form":"Three-stage flash version in 10 minutes: Only stage 1 (What happened?), stage 2 (What did I feel?) and stage 6 (What will I do next time?) – written, then optional exchange. Not a complete Gibbs, but the reflection pattern is activated.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","coaching","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–20 people; as individual work with pair exchange","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"double-loop-learning","name":"Double-Loop Learning (Argyris)","feld":"F","kurz":"Instead of correcting mistakes ever better, question the assumptions that produce them.","schritte":["Choose a recurring problem that keeps coming back despite corrections","Gather previous corrections – this is single-loop: adjust action, keep assumptions","Make the underlying assumptions, goals and values explicit","Question these assumptions themselves: are they still valid?","Formulate a new theory of action and agree on a test"],"zweck":"Instead of correcting mistakes ever better, question the assumptions that produce them.","hinweise":"This runs into defensive routines – people defend their core assumptions. Needs psychological safety and time. The guiding question 'What must not be questioned here?' often opens the door.","phasen":["reflektieren","verstehen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["reflexion","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern","reflexion"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"infed.org – Chris Argyris: Theories of Action, Double-Loop Learning and Organizational Learning","url":"https://infed.org/mobi/chris-argyris-theories-of-action-double-loop-learning-and-organizational-learning/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Chris Argyris / Donald Schön: Organizational Learning (1978)"}],"wann_passt":["A team is solving the same problem for the third time – the symptom keeps returning despite corrections: now it's worth questioning the underlying assumptions.","In a strategy retreat where past decisions are being reviewed: 'What assumptions guided our recent decisions – are they still valid?'","In OD accompaniment, when an organization has developed defensive routines: Double-Loop Learning creates language for this and opens up space for reflection."],"wann_nicht":["Without psychological safety: questioning core assumptions triggers defensive routines and needs sufficient trust.","For acute operational problems that need a quick fix – single-loop is enough here.","When the group doesn't yet understand what single-loop is: the difference first needs to be made experiential (e.g. through an exercise or an example)."],"fokusfragen":["\"What have we already tried – and why didn't it hold?\"","\"What assumptions lie behind our previous attempts at a solution – what did we take for granted?\"","\"What must not be questioned here – and what if that's exactly the crux of the matter?\""],"beispiel":"A team complains about poor communication for the third time. Single-loop answer: introduce a new communication format (didn't hold). Double-loop: 'What assumption underlies the idea that the problem lies in the form of communication – not in the relationship or the decision-making structure?' Question to the group: 'What must not be questioned here?' (Argyris's opening question). If someone says 'the hierarchy, that will never change' – that is exactly the assumption that needs examining. Follow-up question: 'If we set this assumption aside for a moment: what would we try then?'","mini_form":"Assumptions flash round in 10 minutes: Ask about a recurring problem: 'What assumptions have we made so far whenever we've tried to solve this problem?' (2 min silent notes, then share). Enough to switch on double-loop mode without introducing the full concept.","anlass_typen":["retro","strategie","lernformat"],"typ":"rahmenmodell","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–12 people; with a foundation of trust","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"intervision","name":"Intervision / Peer Consultation","feld":"F","kurz":"Systematically consult on professional cases within a peer group – without external authority, with distributed roles.","schritte":["Distribute roles: case presenter, facilitator, consultants","Case description (5–10 min), consultants listen","Case presenter formulates a key question","Choose a method for the consultation round (hypothesis round, resonance round, brainstorming)","Consultants advise – case presenter only listens","Case presenter reports back what was helpful; brief closing"],"zweck":"Systematically consult on professional cases within a peer group – without external authority, with distributed roles.","hinweise":"Keep the structure strictly – especially the listening-without-defending by the case-presenter – it's the safeguard against coffee-break randomness. A fixed group and rhythm increase depth.","phasen":["reflektieren","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["reflexion","klaerung"],"formate":["reflexionsrunde","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":9,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern","reflexion"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Kollegiale Beratung (Kim-Oliver Tietze)","url":"https://www.kollegiale-beratung.de/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO)"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Kim-Oliver Tietze: Kollegiale Beratung (2003)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Intervision – Methoden und Phasen (Socialnet)","url":"https://www.socialnet.de/lexikon/Intervision"}],"wann_passt":["A stable peer group of professionals (consultants, trainers, managers) meets regularly for mutual case consultation – Intervision needs an established group and a fixed rhythm.","As a professional reflection frame in an OD training, where learners bring real consulting situations – the phase model gives the conversation structure and prevents coffee-break randomness.","When external supervision is unavailable or too expensive: Intervision offers similar depth of reflection using available peer intelligence."],"wann_nicht":["For individuals without a fixed group – Intervision needs at least 4 stable members.","When the group doesn't yet share a common stance toward the format: without a clear role distribution (facilitator, case presenter) and structural discipline it becomes arbitrary.","For acute crises: Intervision is not a crisis-intervention format – case consultation is designed for distance and reflection."],"fokusfragen":["\"[Key question] What exactly does the case presenter want from the group – a hypothesis, a recommendation, resonance?\"","\"[Hypothesis round] What function might this behavior serve for the system being described?\"","\"[Closing] What from what you heard was most valuable to you – and what are you consciously leaving aside?\""],"beispiel":"Phase model of peer consultation (after Tietze): 1. Case description (5–7 min) – case presenter tells the story, group listens without interrupting. 2. Formulate key question (2–3 min) – case presenter states what they need from the group (hypotheses? recommendations? resonance?). 3. Choice of method (1 min) – facilitator picks a format: hypothesis round, brainstorming, role-play. 4. Consultation phase (15 min) – group advises, case presenter only listens, takes notes. 5. Case presenter reports back (3 min) – what was helpful, what wasn't. 6. Closing. Difference from Reflecting Team: in a Reflecting Team, part of the group comments on the others' observations (meta level), while in Intervision the roles are more fluid. Intervision/peer consultation has clearer phase discipline and is better suited to practice peer groups without facilitation experience.","mini_form":"Flash Intervision in 20 minutes: case description 5 min, key question 1 min, hypothesis round 10 min (case presenter stays silent), feedback 4 min. Not a complete format, but the core works.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","coaching","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–8 people ideal; 9 still manageable","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"johari-fenster","name":"Johari Window","feld":"F","kurz":"Make blind spots and hidden aspects visible – enlarge the area of shared knowledge between people.","schritte":["Explain the four windows: public, blind spot, façade (hidden), unknown","Gather self-image (e.g. adjective selection)","Gather others' image: colleagues choose adjectives for the person","Compare: feedback shrinks the blind spot, self-disclosure shrinks the façade","Exchange in pairs or small groups with feedback rules","Note down personal intentions"],"zweck":"Make blind spots and hidden aspects visible – enlarge the area of shared knowledge between people.","hinweise":"Establish feedback rules beforehand (concrete, appreciative, requested). Voluntary degree of disclosure. Do not use as an assessment tool.","phasen":["reflektieren","verstehen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","teamentwicklung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Communication Theory – The Johari Window Model","url":"https://www.communicationtheory.org/the-johari-window-model/"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Self-Reflection"}],"wann_passt":["In a team day or team development workshop where mutual understanding and a feedback culture are meant to be strengthened – Johari makes the concept of the blind spot experiential.","In a training on self-reflection and leadership: the model is easy to understand and has immediate practical consequences.","As an entry point into a feedback culture: before anonymous or formalized feedback processes are introduced, Johari creates a shared picture of why feedback is useful at all."],"wann_nicht":["When trust and psychological safety in the group are not yet sufficient – self-disclosure and feedback need a safe basis.","As a quick team warm-up: the format needs time and feedback rules, otherwise it produces surface instead of depth.","In very hierarchical contexts where feedback to superiors seems risky – choose other formats or ensure anonymity."],"fokusfragen":["\"What about me is visible to others – what do I consciously show?\"","\"What am I hearing today that surprises me – what wasn't I aware of about myself?\"","\"What would I like to move from the façade into the public space – what do I want to consciously show?\""],"beispiel":"Adjective-list variant in 45 minutes: everyone chooses 5–6 adjectives that apply to them from a list of 56 (open, patient, introverted …). At the same time, others choose 5–6 adjectives each for the person. Comparison: overlaps = public window. Adjectives only assigned by others = blind spot. Adjectives only chosen by the person themselves = façade. Exchange in pairs: 'What surprises you about your blind spot?' (5 min). Important: establish feedback rules beforehand – concrete, appreciative, descriptive (not evaluative).","mini_form":"Blind-spot question in 10 minutes: a single question to the group or in pairs: 'What is something others see in me that I often don't notice myself?' – share voluntarily. Opens the Johari dynamic without the full format.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat","coaching"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–12 people; split into pairs or trios","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"inneres-team","name":"Inner Team (Schulz von Thun)","feld":"F","kurz":"Externalize inner multivocality and develop a clarified, integrated stance out of inner confusion.","schritte":["Name the concern or decision situation","Gather and name the inner voices around it","Visualize the voices or arrange them with objects/cards","Let every voice speak – including the quiet and banished ones","Team conference: the head (the self) moderates the voices and seeks an integrated answer","Record the outcome"],"zweck":"Externalize inner multivocality and develop a clarified, integrated stance out of inner confusion.","hinweise":"Banished voices (voices in the basement) often carry the most important information. In groups, run this as guided individual work with voluntary exchange.","phasen":["reflektieren","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["person"],"modi":["selbstzugang","klaerung"],"formate":["coaching","workshop"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":12,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Schulz von Thun Institut – Das Innere Team","url":"https://www.schulz-von-thun.de/die-modelle/das-innere-team"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Training materials from the systemic OD training programme (WISPO) – Self-Reflection"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Friedemann Schulz von Thun: Miteinander reden 3 (1998)"}],"wann_passt":["A person is inwardly torn over an important decision – the Inner Team externalizes the different voices and makes them discussable.","In coaching, when someone keeps failing at the same inner contradictions ('I want X, but part of me …').","In trainings on communication and self-leadership: the model normalizes and makes manageable inner multivocality."],"wann_nicht":["Under acute psychological pressure or near trauma: the format leads deep inward and needs a clear basis of psychological safety.","As a short group exercise without enough time: the format needs 45–90 minutes for the banished voices to emerge.","When the person tends to approach a decision pragmatically and experiences inner multivocality as alien – choose other decision formats then."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which voices come up when you think about this situation – what does each one say?\"","\"Which voice rarely gets to speak – what if you gave it more space?\"","\"What would the head – your integrated self – decide once all voices have been heard?\""],"beispiel":"In coaching on a career-change decision: the person names inner voices: 'security seeker' (prefers to stay), 'adventurer' (wants to change), 'inner critic' (doesn't dare). Visualization: cards with names on the table. Let each voice speak: 'What does the security seeker want?' Then the banished voice: 'Is there a voice that hasn't spoken yet – maybe a quiet one you'd rather not hear?' Team conference: 'What would the head decide once all voices were allowed to say what they need?' Follow-up question: 'What does each voice need in order to support the decision?'","mini_form":"Voices flash round in 15 minutes: 'Name 3–4 inner voices about this decision – what does each say in one sentence?' Then: 'Which voice is usually overheard?' Not a full team conference, but the multivocality becomes visible.","anlass_typen":["coaching","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–3 people in coaching; as individual reflection in groups up to 12","stimmung_geeignet":["belastet","neugierig"]},{"id":"harvesting","name":"Harvesting (Art of Hosting)","feld":"F","kurz":"Harvest collective knowledge from large-group processes and make it usable beyond the event itself.","schritte":["Before the session: plan the harvest – which questions, which artifacts (cards, graphic recording, photos, quotes), for whom?","Document visibly during the session – the group sees its thinking take shape","Distill: name patterns and core insights together","Create an artifact that is understandable without having been present","Feedback loop: feed the harvest into the next process step"],"zweck":"Harvest collective knowledge from large-group processes and make it usable beyond the event itself.","hinweise":"The harvest is planned into the design, not improvised afterward. Artifact + feedback loop belong together – a nice record without further use is not a harvest.","phasen":["reflektieren","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["reflexion"],"formate":["grossgruppe","workshop"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["reflexion","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Chris Corrigan – The Art of Harvesting","url":"https://www.chriscorrigan.com/parkinglot/the-art-of-harvesting/"}],"wann_passt":["Large-group processes (Open Space, World Café, Future Search) where a lot of knowledge is generated that would otherwise be lost – Harvesting ensures insights remain usable beyond the event.","In longer accompanying processes (strategy development, OD process) where several sessions build on each other – Harvesting secures the flow of knowledge between phases.","When a group can't answer 'What did we actually learn?' after an intensive dialogue – a planned harvest prevents this 'plenary forgetting'."],"wann_nicht":["As an afterthought improvisation: Harvesting must be planned into the design – what should be harvested, how, for whom?","When no feedback loop is built into the process: a harvest artifact without further use is wasted energy.","For small meetings or short sessions: the effort of Harvesting is disproportionate – minutes are enough."],"fokusfragen":["\"What should be harvested – insights, energies, tensions, commitments?\"","\"Who is the harvest for – who needs the artifact, in what form?\"","\"How does the harvest flow back into the process – who decides based on the harvested insights?\""],"beispiel":"Harvesting in a two-day strategy process: before the event: a harvest plan (What? For whom? In what form?). During the sessions: a graphic facilitator visualizes live, facilitation cards are photographed, key quotes are collected. End of day 1: distillation round (15 min) – the group names 3 core insights that go onto a single page. End of day 2: harvest mirror-back – the distilled page is played back to the group: 'Is this what we decided?' Further use in the minutes and as a starting point in the next session.","mini_form":"Three-sentence harvest in 10 minutes: at the end of a session everyone writes a card: 'What am I taking away – in one sentence?' Read the cards aloud, cluster them, name 3 core insights. Not an elaborate artifact, but the essentials are captured.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"Not a classic group format – a planning tool for process design; works in groups of any size","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"most-significant-change","name":"Most Significant Change","feld":"F","kurz":"Capture impact through significant stories of change rather than only through predefined indicators.","schritte":["Ask the guiding question: What was, from your point of view, the most significant change in period X?","Collect stories – in writing or as short interviews, with a rationale for why they're significant","In groups, select the most significant story and document the selection criteria","Repeat the selection across several levels if needed (team → program → steering)","Feedback to the storytellers: which story was chosen and why?","Use the insights for steering"],"zweck":"Capture impact through significant stories of change rather than only through predefined indicators – including the values debate about what counts as significant.","hinweise":"The selection process with its discussion is the real learning gain – document the criteria. It systematically captures the striking, not the representative – combine it with other data.","phasen":["reflektieren","verstetigen"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","prozessbegleitung"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern","reflexion"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"BetterEvaluation – Most Significant Change","url":"https://www.betterevaluation.org/methods-approaches/approaches/most-significant-change"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"Rick Davies / Jess Dart: The Most Significant Change Technique – A Guide to Its Use (2005, frei verfügbar)"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Rick Davies & Jess Dart: The MSC Guide (2005, frei verfügbar)","url":"https://www.mande.co.uk/docs/MSCGuide.pdf"},{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Station 8: Evaluation / MSC"}],"wann_passt":["Program monitoring in contexts where quantitative indicators miss the real change – MSC collects stories of the 'most significant change' from participants themselves and then lets teams decide together which one is most relevant.","Evaluation phase with partner organizations (10–30 people): when the program had many unintended but important effects that no logframe can capture – MSC makes the unexpected visible.","Team reflection after a longer process: everyone shares the story of 'the most significant change I experienced in this project' – relieves reporting pressure and creates shared awareness of impact.","Participatory formats with communities: when the perspective of the people affected should become the main source for assessing impact, not the perspective of the program providers."],"wann_nicht":["As the sole monitoring instrument: MSC needs to be complemented by process indicators – it captures impact, but not whether the program was implemented as planned.","When funders demand exclusively aggregated quantitative data: MSC stories don't translate well into bar charts.","In groups with strong hierarchy, where participants only tell what leadership wants to hear – build psychological safety first."],"fokusfragen":["\"Over the past [3/6/12] months: what was the most significant change in your life/your community that you attribute to this program?\" (core MSC question)","\"Why was this particular change the most significant for you – what makes it more important than others?\" (forces justification and reveals values)","\"When you compare these stories: which one best represents what we wanted to achieve with this program – and why?\" (team selection round)"],"beispiel":"MSC round in a program review (15 people): everyone gets 5 minutes to write down a story. Then small groups of 4–5, each group selects the one story it considers most significant and justifies it. Plenary: each small group presents its choice. The facilitator notes the justifications – they are often more revealing than the stories themselves: they show what the group considers truly relevant.","mini_form":"Solo MSC in 10 minutes as a check-in: 'Write in 3 sentences: what is the one change in this project you'll never forget?' Share in the plenary without discussion – enough as a mood barometer and entry into a retro.","anlass_typen":["retro","lernformat","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–30 people, with enough time (at least 60 min for the full method)","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"mini-bodyscan-im-sitzen","name":"Mini Body Scan Seated","feld":"F","kurz":"A guided attention journey through the body (feet, legs, torso, shoulders, face) while seated on a chair. Brings the group out of their heads and into perception, and marks transitions between thinking blocks.","schritte":["Opening line: \"Before we move into the next block, three minutes of concentration reset. Sit comfortably, feet on the floor. Eyes can be open or closed.\"","Guide slowly through the body: feet – seat – back – shoulders ('can they drop a little?') – face. About 20–30 seconds per station, calm everyday voice.","Closing: \"Take one deep breath in, breathe out – and arrive back here in the room.\""],"zweck":"Focus attention, release tension, mark the transition between thinking blocks physically.","hinweise":"Frame it secularly as a 'concentration reset.' Trauma-sensitive: eyes open is fine, only name body regions, offer an opt-out. Good after lunch break or heated discussions; for the very first exercise with skeptical groups, better start with stretching or breathing.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","coaching","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":3,"dauer_max":7,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Body Scan Meditation – Greater Good in Action (UC Berkeley)","url":"https://ggia.berkeley.edu/practice/body_scan_meditation"}],"wann_passt":["After lunch break or after a long block of thinking work: attention is brought out of the 'post-lunch dip' without over-activating.","As a transition between two content blocks that differ in topic: the body scan marks the shift physically and gives the brain a sorting pause.","When the group needs to come down after a heated discussion, before starting a new topic."],"wann_nicht":["As the very first exercise with a group that doesn't know each other yet or is skeptical of methods: a body scan feels odd with an unfamiliar group – better to start with stretching or a breathing exercise.","When the group urgently needs activating (after long sitting, early morning): a movement exercise is better then.","Online, when camera expectations inhibit participants: announcing 'cameras off is fine' helps, but still use cautiously with difficult groups."],"beispiel":"Opening line for a skeptical group: 'Before we move into the next block, let's do a 3-minute concentration reset – this isn't meditation, it's a deliberate direction of attention that comes from neuroscience. Eyes open or closed, doesn't matter. I'll guide briefly.' Then name the body stations: feet → seat → back → shoulders → face, about 20–30 sec each, calm voice. Closing: 'Take one deep breath in and out, and we're back.'","mini_form":"Shoulders-face reset in 2 minutes: only two stations – shoulders ('can they drop a little?') and face ('jaw loose, tongue off the roof of the mouth'). Enough as a short return of attention.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","teamtag","regeltermin"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–100 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"physiological-sigh","name":"Physiological Sigh","feld":"F","kurz":"Inhale twice in a row through the nose (deep, then a short top-up), then exhale slowly through the mouth. The fastest known single technique against acute tension – works after just 1–3 repetitions.","schritte":["Opening line: \"A quick trick from Stanford stress research – this is what the body does automatically during a sob, just applied deliberately.\"","Demonstrate: inhale deeply through the nose, take a short second sip of air at the top, then exhale slowly and fully through the mouth.","3 rounds together, then have a brief check-in: \"Does anyone notice a difference in their shoulders?\""],"zweck":"Physiologically down-regulate acute stress response (heart and breathing rate) – in under a minute.","hinweise":"Ideal before difficult conversations, after moments of conflict, before presentations. Secular framing built in: explicitly physiological, no breathing tradition – the Stanford study (Balban et al. 2023) convinces skeptical groups. If prone to dizziness while seated, breathe less deeply. Offer an opt-out.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","coaching","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":5,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Cyclic sighing can help breathe away anxiety – Stanford Medicine","url":"https://med.stanford.edu/news/insights/2023/02/cyclic-sighing-can-help-breathe-away-anxiety.html"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Balban et al. 2023 – Cell Reports Medicine (Originalstudie)","url":"https://www.cell.com/cell-reports-medicine/fulltext/S2666-3791(22)00474-8"}],"wann_passt":["Right before a difficult decision or a conflict conversation: the acute stress response is physiologically down-regulated in under a minute.","After a moment of conflict or emotional escalation: as an immediate reset before the conversation continues.","In very skeptical groups (military, fire service, administration) that don't want to do relaxation exercises: the Stanford study and its Navy SEAL association open the door."],"wann_nicht":["As the only breathing technique in the repertoire: the Physiological Sigh calms acutely but isn't suited for focus work or endurance – use Box Breathing for that.","For people with anxiety or panic experience without a prior opt-out announcement: the short top-up breath can feel uncomfortable.","As an extended exercise (over 5 rounds): a few repetitions are enough – more causes dizziness."],"beispiel":"Opening line for a skeptical group: 'A quick trick from Stanford stress research – this is what the body does automatically during a sob, just applied deliberately. Two seconds.' Demonstrate: inhale deeply through the nose, take a short top-up breath, then exhale slowly through the mouth. 3 rounds together. Afterward: 'Does anyone notice a difference in their shoulders?' – the question makes the effect conscious and retroactively legitimizes the format.","mini_form":"A single Physiological Sigh as an instant reset: in a moment of tension (your own or the group's) do one single round – inhale, top up, exhale. Works after just one repetition.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech","entscheidungstreffen","krisensitzung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–200 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"box-breathing","name":"Box Breathing (4-4-4-4)","feld":"F","kurz":"Breathing in a square: 4 seconds inhale, 4 hold, 4 exhale, 4 hold. Known as a Navy SEALs training method – which makes it instantly relatable for method-skeptical professional groups.","schritte":["Opening line: \"One minute focus technique – used by emergency responders and surgeons to stay calm before difficult situations.\"","Announce the rhythm or draw a square in the air with your hand: inhale (4) – hold (4) – exhale (4) – hold (4).","4–6 rounds together, then let everyone return to normal breathing."],"zweck":"Calm the nervous system while sharpening concentration at the same time – focus rather than relaxation as the frame.","hinweise":"Good before decision- and negotiation situations and as a calm opening. Secular framing via its origin (tactical breathing) – disarms 'eso-allergy.' Holding the breath can feel uncomfortable for people with anxiety/panic experience: offer an alternative without holding – that's the opt-out.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","coaching","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":4,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"How Box Breathing Can Help You Destress – Cleveland Clinic","url":"https://health.clevelandclinic.org/box-breathing-benefits"}],"wann_passt":["Before a decision- or negotiation situation: Box Breathing sharpens focus and regulates the nervous system at the same time – the frame is performance, not relaxation.","As a calm opening on the morning of an intensive day (retreat, kick-off): sets the tone for concentrated work.","With method-skeptical, performance-oriented groups: its origin (Navy SEALs, surgery) makes the format relatable."],"wann_nicht":["For people with anxiety or panic experience without an opt-out: holding the breath can feel uncomfortable – offer an alternative without holding.","When the group needs acute calming (after conflict, escalation): use 4-6 breathing or the Physiological Sigh instead – Box Breathing focuses, calms less strongly.","More than 6–8 rounds without a break: risk of hyperventilation, especially for beginners."],"beispiel":"Opening line for performance-oriented groups: 'One minute focus technique – used by emergency responders and surgeons to stay calm and focused before difficult situations. Four seconds inhale, four hold, four exhale, four hold. I'll trace the square, you follow with your breath.' Draw a square in the air with your hand, announce the rhythm. 4–6 rounds, then: 'Back to normal breathing.' No comment needed afterward – move straight into the next block.","mini_form":"Two-round focus reset: just 2 complete boxes (2 × 16 seconds) as an individual short break – for individuals before difficult conversations, without a group. Works solo too.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","konfliktklaerung","kickoff"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–200 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"vier-sechs-atmung","name":"4-6 Breathing (Extended Exhale)","feld":"F","kurz":"Inhale for 4 seconds, exhale for 6 – the extended exhale activates the parasympathetic nervous system. The simplest breathing technique there is: no holding, no counting acrobatics.","schritte":["Opening line: \"The principle is simple: exhaling calms you. When the exhale is longer than the inhale, the body measurably shifts down a gear.\"","5–8 breaths together: inhale for 4, exhale for 6 (count aloud or silently).","Optionally increase to 4-8. Closing: return to normal breathing, brief check-in."],"zweck":"Lower the group's arousal level – after conflicts, before delicate agenda items, at the end of the day.","hinweise":"The lowest-threshold breathing exercise, works even in passing. Secular framing via physiology. The Stanford comparative study found exhale-focused breathing more effective than meditation – a good argument for skeptics. Offer an opt-out; no contraindications at a moderate pace.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","coaching","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":5,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Cyclic sighing tops other breathing methods for calming down – Stanford Medicine Magazine","url":"https://stanmed.stanford.edu/cyclic-sighing-stress-relief/"}],"wann_passt":["At the end of the day after intensive work or as a transition out of an emotional block: the extended exhale reliably activates the parasympathetic nervous system.","After a moment of conflict, when the group needs to come down before a new topic begins – lower threshold than other breathing techniques.","As the very first breathing exercise with a group that has no experience with body practices yet: no holding phase, no counting acrobatics, no esoteric flair."],"wann_nicht":["When activation is needed: the extended exhale calms rather than focuses – use the Physiological Sigh or Box Breathing instead.","When the group is at an energy low and needs to become active again – use a movement exercise first.","As focus preparation before a demanding task: Box Breathing is better suited for that."],"beispiel":"Opening line for skeptics: 'The principle is simple: exhaling calms you. When the exhale is longer than the inhale, the body measurably shifts down a gear – the Stanford data shows this too. We'll do 5 breaths: inhale for 4, exhale for 6. I'll count aloud.' Count aloud or tap fingers on the table. Closing: 'Back to normal breathing, brief check-in.' No fuss – move straight on.","mini_form":"Three-breath reset: just 3 extended exhales (4 in, 6 out) – as a silent individual break between two stressful situations. Physiologically enough as an instant regulator.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–200 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"schulter-nacken-reset","name":"Shoulder-Neck Reset at the Desk","feld":"F","kurz":"Three short release moves for shoulders, neck and wrists – seated, without standing up. The go-to format for online meetings and sitting-heavy work sessions.","schritte":["Opening line: \"90 minutes of screen time – the neck has earned a break. Join in as far as feels comfortable for you.\"","Announce the sequence and join in: raise shoulders, hold 3 sec., let them drop (3×) – tilt head to each side 10 sec. – circle shoulders backward (5×) – shake out hands.","Closing: one deep breath, then continue with the program."],"zweck":"Release tension from long sitting phases and refresh attention, without leaving work mode.","hinweise":"Universally usable, even in the most conservative contexts – this is ergonomics, not a method. Especially valuable online (camera can stay off for this). Announce: only stretch as far as feels comfortable; small movements for neck issues.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","coaching","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":4,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":500,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Desk stretches: Video collection – Mayo Clinic","url":"https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/adult-health/in-depth/office-stretches/art-20046041"}],"wann_passt":["After 90+ minutes of screen work or sitting in a meeting: a short ritual to release tension without leaving work mode.","In online meetings where the group has been sitting for hours – especially valuable because movement is harder to trigger on screen than in a room.","In the most conservative group and the most formal context: this is ergonomics, not a method – no pre-explanation needed."],"wann_nicht":["When neck complaints are known in the group: then explicitly announce 'only as far as feels comfortable' and recommend small movements.","As an activation format: the reset calms and releases tension but doesn't energize – for energy lows, prefer standing up and stretching.","When it gets misused as a break to stall content work – then better a direct block change without a body unit."],"beispiel":"Universal opening line: '90 minutes of screen time – the neck has earned a break. Join in as far as feels comfortable for you.' Then announce and join in: raise shoulders → hold → let drop (3×) → tilt head to the side (left/right, 10 sec.) → circle shoulders backward (5×) → shake out hands. Closing: 'One deep breath.' No comment needed – move straight on with the program.","mini_form":"60-second shoulder reset: just shoulders up-hold-drop (3×) and shoulder circles (5×) backward. Can be done invisibly even in a meeting – as a silent individual break.","anlass_typen":["regeltermin","lernformat","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–500 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","angespannt","frisch"]},{"id":"aufstehen-und-strecken","name":"Stand Up & Stretch Between Blocks","feld":"F","kurz":"Everyone stands up, stretches upward, to the side, lets their arms drop – 2 minutes of standing stretch as a fixed block-change marker.","schritte":["Opening line: \"Block change – everyone stand up once, the brain thanks us for it.\"","Announce and demonstrate: stretch arms overhead (yawning allowed) – side bend left/right 10 sec. each – roll shoulders – hang forward, slowly roll back up.","Optional: bounce on tiptoes 10× in place. Then go straight into the next block."],"zweck":"Activate circulation, interrupt sitting fatigue, physically mark transitions in the day's schedule.","hinweise":"Works in any group; the more matter-of-fact and short the announcement, the higher the participation. Announce it as a recurring ritual, then the threshold drops from round two onward. Always offer the seated variant (opt-out for limited mobility). Escalation: Shake Down.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":3,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":500,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["energizer"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Desk stretches: Video collection – Mayo Clinic","url":"https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/adult-health/in-depth/office-stretches/art-20046041"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Shake Down – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/shake-down"}],"wann_passt":["As a fixed block-change marker after 60–90 minutes of sitting: the body movement marks the transition and activates circulation.","In full-day workshops or retreats where energy management matters – as a recurring ritual, the threshold drops sharply from the second round on.","As an explicitly inclusive energizer: always offer the seated variant too – 'or stay seated and stretch your arms overhead.'"],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for a real break: if the group is physically and mentally exhausted, 2 minutes of stretching isn't enough – schedule a real break instead.","In very formal contexts (a conference with external stakeholders, a hearing) where standing up would seem out of place – prefer the seated Shoulder-Neck Reset instead.","When accessibility hasn't been considered: always offer a seated alternative."],"beispiel":"Keep the opening line matter-of-fact: 'Block change – everyone stand up once, the brain thanks us for it.' Join in immediately: stretch arms overhead (yawning allowed) → side bend left/right (10 sec.) → roll shoulders → hang forward and slowly roll back up. Optional: bounce on tiptoes 10×. Then go straight into the next block – no softening, no long announcement.","mini_form":"Stretch-and-yawn in 60 seconds: stretch arms, yawning allowed, roll shoulders – done. As a mini ritual after every block.","anlass_typen":["lernformat","teamtag","regeltermin"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2–500 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","frisch"]},{"id":"walk-and-talk","name":"Walk & Talk (Walking as a Thinking Break)","feld":"F","kurz":"Pair conversations while walking instead of at the table – 10–15 minutes outside or in the hallway, with a clear guiding question. Walking demonstrably boosts divergent thinking (about 60% more creative answers, Stanford study).","schritte":["Make the guiding question visible (flipchart/chat), e.g. \"What would be the boldest next step for our project?\"","Opening line: \"For the next round you'll think while walking – in pairs, 15 minutes. Stanford research is clear: we come up with more and more original ideas while walking.\"","Form pairs ('find someone you haven't spoken with much today'), state the return time.","Back in the room: each pair shares the one most important insight in plenary."],"zweck":"Produce ideas and build informal relationships at the same time – movement plus a one-on-one setting lowers conversational barriers.","hinweise":"Suited to idea, strategy and reflection questions; unsuited when notes or materials are needed. Check the weather and walking route beforehand; offer a seated pair conversation by the window as an equal option (inclusion). Online variant: actually walk while on the phone.","phasen":["verstehen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","energie"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":20,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":60,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Stanford study finds walking improves creativity (Oppezzo & Schwartz 2014) – Stanford Report","url":"https://news.stanford.edu/stories/2014/04/walking-vs-sitting-042414"}],"wann_passt":["When an open strategy or reflection question needs more and more original ideas than sitting produces – walking demonstrably boosts divergent thinking (Stanford study: ~60% more creative answers).","In intermediate phases of a workshop, when informal connection and relationship building are desired: pair conversations while walking lower conversational barriers.","In trainings or retreats when a real movement break is needed after many hours of sitting, but one that's still used productively."],"wann_nicht":["When notes, materials or visual work are needed – Walk & Talk suits questions that can be worked through mentally.","In bad weather without a workable alternative: always offer a seated variant by the window or in the hallway as an equal option.","Online: only possible if the person actually walks while on the phone – can be an explicit instruction, but not a group-synchronous format."],"fokusfragen":["\"What would be the boldest next step for our project – what do you dare to think while walking that you wouldn't say while sitting?\"","\"What moves you about this process – what haven't you said out loud yet?\""],"beispiel":"Make the guiding question visible (flipchart/chat), then: 'For the next round you'll think while walking – in pairs, 15 minutes. Find someone you haven't spoken with much today.' State the return time. Back in the room: each pair shares one insight in plenary (max. 2 minutes). Then close with a scaling question: 'What of what you heard surprises you the most?'","mini_form":"5-minute pair walk: a single question, 5 minutes of walking in pairs, one insight shared back. Enough as a thinking break and a relationship moment.","anlass_typen":["strategie","teamtag","lernformat","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4–60 people (pairs or trios); useful from 4 people upward","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"erdung-5-4-3-2-1","name":"5-4-3-2-1 Grounding Exercise (Sensory Anchor)","feld":"F","kurz":"Name in sequence: 5 things I see – 4 I feel – 3 I hear – 2 I smell – 1 I taste. A standard technique to move out of rumination or agitation into the here and now.","schritte":["Opening line: \"Before we go into the difficult topic, one minute of arriving through the senses – this reliably brings attention into this room.\"","Let people go through it silently, facilitator gives the steps: \"Find 5 things you see … 4 you feel on your body … 3 sounds … 2 smells … 1 taste.\"","Brief closing: \"Take one breath – let's start.\" No debrief round needed."],"zweck":"Self-regulation before stressful or conflict-laden conversations; shift attention from within (circling thoughts) to outside (sensory perception).","hinweise":"Proven before conflict resolution, difficult feedback rounds, after unsettling content. Can be phrased entirely secularly (directing attention, no introspection). Well-suited precisely because it's trauma-sensitive: it leads outward rather than inward. Smell/taste can be dropped (then 5-4-3).","phasen":["ankommen","konflikt"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","coaching","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":2,"dauer_max":4,"gruppe_min":1,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"The 5-4-3-2-1 Grounding Technique for Anxiety – Healthline","url":"https://www.healthline.com/health/anxiety/5-4-3-2-1-grounding-technique-for-anxiety"}],"wann_passt":["Right before a conflict-resolution conversation or a difficult feedback conversation: the exercise reliably brings attention out of circling thoughts and into sensory perception of the room.","After unsettling input or an emotional account: as a brief anchor before the conversation continues.","In groups close to trauma or with burden-heavy topics (social work, healthcare): the exercise leads outward rather than inward – this is trauma-sensitive and avoids overwhelm."],"wann_nicht":["As a general warm-up exercise without a concrete occasion: the exercise has its strongest effect when it matches a moment of tension or agitation.","In very short transitions under 2 minutes: without enough time for all 5 stages it feels rushed.","As a substitute for psychological safety: the exercise regulates but doesn't resolve structural conflicts or trust deficits."],"beispiel":"Opening line before a conflict conversation: 'Before we go into the difficult topic, one minute of arriving through the senses – this reliably brings attention into this room.' Let people go through it silently: 'Find 5 things you see – 4 you feel on your body – 3 sounds – 2 smells – 1 taste.' Closing: 'Take one breath – let's start.' No debrief round needed – go straight into the topic.","mini_form":"5-4-3 short version in 90 seconds: only seeing (5), feeling (4), hearing (3) – smell and taste are dropped. Enough as an anchor.","anlass_typen":["konfliktklaerung","schwieriges_gespraech","coaching"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"1–100 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet"]},{"id":"stille-mit-atem-anker","name":"Brief Silence with a Breath Anchor","feld":"F","kurz":"One to three minutes of shared silence; those who want to can use their own breath as an attention anchor. The most minimalist of all practices – and often the most effective one before decisions.","schritte":["Opening line: \"Before we decide, two minutes of silence – everyone sorts for themselves. If thoughts jump around, it helps to listen to your own breath. I'll let you know when the time is up.\"","Stop the clock, sit calmly yourself – the facilitator holds the silence by holding it out themselves.","End in a calm voice: \"Thank you. Who'd like to start?\""],"zweck":"Take the pace out, prevent impulsive decisions, give quiet voices preparation time.","hinweise":"Suited before decisions, after emotional contributions, as a closing moment. For inexperienced groups, start with 60 seconds and reliably announce the end. Secular framing: \"thinking pause\" or \"sorting minute.\" Trauma-sensitive: eyes open is fine; no one is called on.","phasen":["ankommen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["selbstzugang"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","coaching","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":1,"dauer_max":3,"gruppe_min":2,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["uebergang"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Mindful Breathing – Greater Good in Action (UC Berkeley)","url":"https://ggia.berkeley.edu/practice/mindful_breathing"}],"wann_passt":["Before an important decision: the silence prevents impulsive decisions and gives quiet voices preparation time.","After emotional contributions or an escalation: as a moment of processing before the conversation continues.","As a closing moment at the end of an intensive day or session: the silence rounds things off and allows inner sorting."],"wann_nicht":["As the first exercise with a group that has no experience with silence yet: use 60 seconds to start – a reliable time announcement is decisive, otherwise the silence becomes uncomfortable.","When acute action is called for (crisis meeting, escalation without a pause): do a breathing exercise first, then silence.","In very large groups without a clear facilitation presence: the facilitator holds the silence by holding it out themselves – anyone who gets nervous disrupts it."],"beispiel":"Opening line before a decision: 'Before we decide, two minutes of silence – everyone sorts for themselves. If thoughts jump around, it helps to listen to your own breath. I'll let you know when the time is up.' Stop the clock, sit calmly yourself. End: 'Thank you. Who'd like to start?' – no debrief round, go straight into the decision. The silence has spoken.","mini_form":"60-second sorting minute: 'A moment of silence – sort yourselves.' No breath cue, no explanation. The shortest variant of the silence practice.","anlass_typen":["entscheidungstreffen","konfliktklaerung","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"2–200 people; universal","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","belastet","muede"]},{"id":"paarinterview-mit-vorstellung","name":"Pair Interview with Introduction","feld":"C","kurz":"Two people interview each other (5 min per direction) and then introduce their partner in plenary. A classic for getting acquainted with built-in listening practice.","schritte":["Form pairs, mix deliberately: 'someone you don't know yet.'","Opening line: \"You each have 5 minutes to get to know your counterpart – then you'll introduce each other. Three guiding questions are on the flipchart, feel free to go beyond them.\"","Choose low-threshold guiding questions (career path, current project, 'what could you talk about for hours?'). Announce the switch after 5 minutes.","Plenary: each person introduces their partner in 1 minute."],"zweck":"Create contact and bring all voices into the room early; being introduced by someone else lowers self-presentation pressure and trains listening.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: none – works with complete strangers. With large groups, do the plenary introduction in groups of four instead of the full circle (time). Guiding questions steer the depth of openness: work-related = low, biographical = medium. Each person decides for themselves what gets shared.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":40,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"67 engaging icebreakers (Abschnitt Interview-Icebreaker) – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/blog/icebreaker-games/"}],"wann_passt":["A retreat or workshop where people from different contexts come together and should really get to know each other – being introduced by another person produces a quality of listening that self-introduction doesn't achieve.","Start of a training: the format immediately makes clear that listening and engaging with one another is expected here.","Networking meetings with a desire for genuine connection rather than a speed-networking feel."],"wann_nicht":["When the group already knows each other very well – then the exercise is redundant.","Over 40 people without adaptation: plenary introductions of everyone take too long; do introductions in groups of four instead.","When preparation time is lacking or content needs to start immediately."],"fokusfragen":["\"Here are three guiding questions: Who are you, what's moving you right now, and what wouldn't people guess about you?\" (interview invitation)","\"What surprised you most about your counterpart?\" (plenary opener)"],"mini_form":"One-question interview (10 min): 3 min per direction with a single question ('What really brings you here?'), introduction in one sentence. Enough for a first contact.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","netzwerktreffen","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6–30; over 30 do the plenary introduction in subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch"]},{"id":"appreciative-interviews","name":"Appreciative Interviews (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"Pair interviews about a concrete success story; in groups of four, each person's partner's story is retold and searched for the conditions of success.","schritte":["Opening line: \"We start with what's working: tell your counterpart about a concrete situation in which you succeeded at something here – and what made it possible.\"","Pairs: 7–10 min interview per direction.","Groups of four: each person retells their partner's story; the group notes recurring conditions for success.","Plenary: collect patterns – \"What shows up across several stories?\""],"zweck":"Build trust through positive shared storytelling while surfacing usable knowledge about conditions for success.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: low – the success framing protects, no one has to show weakness. Announce the retelling beforehand ('say if something should stay between the pair'). Very good as an opener for strategy or team processes; unsuited in the middle of acute conflicts (comes across as glossing over things then).","phasen":["ankommen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":40,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Appreciative Interviews (AI) – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/5-appreciative-interviews-ai/"}],"wann_passt":["A team day or retreat where the group needs energy and direction and doesn't want another problem-solving meeting – Appreciative Interviews start with what's working and build trust through positive shared stories.","A strategy kick-off for an organization: the discovery step from Appreciative Inquiry as a standalone building block – surfaces what's already working before planning the future.","A network meeting with participants from different organizations who need to become productive together – retelling the other person's story creates a shift in perspective."],"wann_nicht":["In the middle of an acute conflict – comes across as glossing over things and loses credibility.","When the group is so burdened that there are no positive stories, or they'd feel dishonest – then an NVC approach or conflict resolution comes first.","As a superficial energy booster without real listening – if the retelling phase is skipped, it's just a nice conversation."],"fokusfragen":["\"Tell me about a moment when our collaboration was really good – what was different from usual?\" (core interview question)","\"What was the decisive condition in this story – what made it possible?\" (surfacing conditions for success)"],"mini_form":"Solo interview in threes (15 min): A interviews B (7 min), C listens and notes key words. Then: C recalls what C heard. Without the retelling round in groups of four, but the trio dynamic works well.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8–80; scales via small groups","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"impromptu-networking","name":"Impromptu Networking (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"Three quick pair conversations of 4–5 minutes each around a double question, with a partner switch after each round. Everyone talks to three people within the first 15 minutes.","schritte":["Make the double question visible and tailor it to the session topic, e.g. \"What brings you here? What are you hoping for – and what do you bring?\"","Opening line: \"Three short conversations, 4 minutes each in pairs – both get a turn. When the gong sounds: new partner.\"","Run three rounds, keep time tight.","Optional brief plenary harvest: \"What surprised you?\""],"zweck":"Lay a relationship network over the whole group within minutes and make everyone's expectations audible – the basis for everything that follows.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: none. Works regardless of hierarchy or personality, because the structure treats everyone equally. Allow a group of three if the number of people is odd. Online with random pair breakouts across three rounds.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team","netzwerk"],"modi":["verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":20,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Impromptu Networking – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/impromptu-networking"}],"wann_passt":["The start of an event with a group that doesn't know each other yet – three quick conversations with three different people lay a relationship network over the whole group within 15 minutes.","When everyone's expectations and contributions should become visible before the program starts – the double question ('What are you hoping for, what do you bring?') gives the facilitator a real picture.","As a quick transition after a long talk or presentation, to wake the energy back up."],"wann_nicht":["When the group already knows each other well and the questions feel too familiar – then choose stronger questions or a different structure.","When the question doesn't fit the double structure – Impromptu Networking thrives on a good invitation question that addresses both contributing and hoping.","In very small groups (under 8): three rounds with the same people become odd."],"fokusfragen":["\"What really brings you here – and what are you hoping to get out of this day for yourself?\" (double-question invitation formula)","\"What surprised you in these three conversations?\" (optional plenary harvest after three rounds)"],"mini_form":"Two rounds instead of three (10 min): enough for a first contact, saves 5 minutes.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","netzwerktreffen","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"10–200; from 30 people upward definitely use a gong/signal for switching","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch","muede"]},{"id":"drei-dinge-gemeinsam","name":"Three Things in Common","feld":"C","kurz":"Pairs or small groups have 3-5 minutes to find three surprising things they have in common - the obvious ones like \"we both work here\" don't count.","schritte":["Framing: \"Find three things you have in common as a pair - things people can't tell just by looking at you. The more surprising, the better.\"","Give them 3-5 minutes to search.","Plenary or neighboring group: share the most surprising commonality.","Optional second round with new pairs or as a foursome (\"find one thing all four of you have in common\")."],"zweck":"Similarity creates sympathy and trust - the exercise systematically produces experiences of commonality across department and status boundaries.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: none. Pairs regulate the depth of disclosure themselves (hobby vs. biography). Competitive variant for energy: \"Which pair can find the most things in common in 3 minutes?\" Combines well with a sociometric exercise as a follow-up.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":5,"dauer_max":15,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","energizer"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Three Things in Common Game – icebreaker-games.org","url":"https://icebreaker-games.org/three-things-in-common"}],"wann_passt":["First joint meeting of groups with very different backgrounds (age, professional field, organization) - the exercise reliably breaks through silo perception.","Tight time (5-10 min) for a get-to-know-you opener: Three Things in Common is the most efficient format for minimal time and maximum connection effect.","As an energizer after a quiet block - the active search and delight over surprising commonalities lifts the mood quickly."],"wann_nicht":["When the group already knows each other very well - the commonalities are no longer surprising.","In cultural contexts where personal disclosures (hobbies, biography) aren't customary or don't feel safe.","As a substitute for real getting-to-know-you on sensitive topics - the method opens things up on the surface, not in depth."],"fokusfragen":["\"Find three things you have in common - but nothing obvious. The more surprising, the better.\" (task instruction)","\"What was the most surprising thing in common that you found?\" (plenary close)"],"mini_form":"Is itself a minimal format (5 min). Even shorter: One commonality in 2 minutes. Good as a 60-second session opener.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","netzwerktreffen","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-60; over 60 only with random pairings","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","skeptisch","muede"]},{"id":"low-tech-social-network","name":"Low-Tech Social Network","feld":"C","kurz":"Everyone draws themselves as an \"avatar\" on a card, sticks it to the wall, and draws connecting lines to people they know - an analog network map of the group emerges.","schritte":["Prepare materials: facilitation cards, pens, tape/pinboard.","Framing: \"We're building our own social network - no server required. Draw yourself as a simple portrait, add your name, and 'upload' yourself: stick the card on the wall.\"","Draw connections: lines to people you know, labeled (\"studies\", \"project X\").","Look at it together: Where are the clusters? Who connects groups? Where are there few lines - and who do I want to meet today?"],"zweck":"Makes existing relationships visible and marks gaps in the network as an invitation - especially valuable at network meetings and in multidisciplinary groups.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: none. Keep the self-portrait low-threshold (\"stick figures explicitly welcome\"). Leave the map hanging - it keeps growing throughout the event. Online substitute: shared whiteboard (Miro/Mural) with photo or emoji avatars.","phasen":["ankommen"],"ebenen":["person","team","netzwerk"],"modi":["verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":40,"gruppe_min":10,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["spielerisch","schriftlich","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Low-Tech Social Network – Gamestorming","url":"https://gamestorming.com/low-tech-social-network/"}],"wann_passt":["Network meeting or conference with participants from different organizations who want to find out who knows whom and where connections are missing - the analog network map makes this visible without software.","Workshop start where networking itself is a goal (e.g. community building, regional networks) - the map stays up and grows throughout the day.","When the abstract 'we are a network' should become a visible experience."],"wann_nicht":["Online without a very good whiteboard tool - the physical analogy (pinning a card, drawing a line) loses impact digitally.","When there's no room for a pinboard, or the map can't stay up for the whole event - then the effort isn't worth it.","In time-critical settings without 20-30 minutes available."],"fokusfragen":["\"Look at the map: who do you know - and who do you really want to meet today?\" (invitation to look)","\"What connections do you see that haven't been drawn yet - and that would matter?\" (strategic network reflection)"],"mini_form":"Just hang name cards without connecting lines (5 min): everyone sticks up their card, sees who's here. Connecting lines can be added voluntarily throughout the day.","anlass_typen":["netzwerktreffen","kickoff","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"12-60; above 60 the map becomes unreadable","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"blind-fuehren-trust-walk","name":"Trust Walk (Leading Blind)","feld":"C","kurz":"One person closes their eyes, their partner leads them safely through the room - first by hand, then by voice only. Trust becomes a physical experience: giving up control, taking on responsibility.","schritte":["Framing with explicit opt-out: \"This exercise requires giving up control - that's its core. If you don't want to do that today, you can observe and join the debrief.\"","Safety rules: leaders are 100% responsible; slow pace; no obstacle pranks.","Round 1 (3 min): leading with hand contact. Round 2 (3 min): voice only. Then switch roles.","Debrief in pairs, then plenary: \"What was easier - leading or being led? What built trust, what did it cost?\""],"zweck":"Trust and responsibility as a physical experience rather than a concept; yields rich debriefing on leadership, communication, and giving up control.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: established - never use as an opening exercise with strangers. Trauma-sensitive: closing eyes, touch, loss of control - a triple imposition; face-saving opt-out, blindfold never mandatory, pairs choose themselves. Not suitable during acute conflict or strong hierarchy.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["vertrauen"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"nein","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["koerperlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Facilitation Tools (Trust-Building Games) – Seeds for Change","url":"https://www.seedsforchange.org.uk/tools"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Tools for Meetings and Workshops (PDF) – Seeds for Change","url":"https://www.seedsforchange.org.uk/downloads/tools.pdf"}],"wann_passt":["Team retreat after at least one shared day, where trust and leadership are being worked on as explicit topics - the Trust Walk delivers the lived experience that can then be discussed conceptually.","Training on leadership, communication, or trust: the debrief ('What built trust, what did it cost?') translates directly to organizational questions.","When a group wants to talk about giving up control and taking on responsibility and abstract discussions have run their course."],"wann_nicht":["Early in a process or with unfamiliar groups - closing your eyes plus physical contact plus loss of control is a triple imposition; a failed exercise causes lasting damage.","With a strong hierarchy gap: a boss and staff leading each other blind doesn't create a symmetrical trust experience.","Without an explicit trauma-sensitive clearing phase: loss of control and physical contact can be triggering.","Online - not feasible."],"fokusfragen":["\"What was easier - leading or being led - and what does that tell you about yourself?\" (debrief after role switch)","\"What in this exercise built trust - and what of that can you carry into your collaboration?\""],"mini_form":"Back-to-back instead of leading blind (5 min): pairs sit back to back, feel the connection, breathe in sync. No need to close eyes, no movement space needed. The gentlest form of physical connectedness.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-24; always in pairs","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"human-knot","name":"Human Knot","feld":"C","kurz":"The group stands in a circle, everyone reaches across and grabs two strangers' hands - then the group untangles itself back into a circle without letting go. A cooperation task with no materials at all.","schritte":["Form groups of 7-10 people.","Framing: \"Reach both hands into the middle and grab two different hands - not your neighbors'. Task: untangle yourselves into a circle without letting go. Repositioning your grip is allowed.\"","Give them 5-10 minutes; if stuck, offer a hint (\"stepping over and ducking under is allowed\").","Short debrief: \"Who coordinated? What helped - talking, trying things out, listening?\" Variant: second round done silently, or with a 'manager' outside the circle."],"zweck":"Makes cooperation, communication, and self-organization tangible as a physical experience - the shared success bonds the group.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: first shared hours together - because of physical contact, not for the very first minute with strangers. Announce the physical contact, offer an opt-out (observer role). Respect cultural norms around touch. Above 12 people per circle it's often unsolvable - better to form two circles.","phasen":["ankommen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["vertrauen","energie"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":20,"gruppe_min":7,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"nein","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["energizer","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Human Knot – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/human-knot-zmabvk"}],"wann_passt":["First or second shared hour of a new group, after a simple get-to-know-you has already happened - the knot quickly creates a shared cooperation experience and laughter with no content link.","Energizer after a long sitting session, when the group needs physical activation - Human Knot works better than Warp Speed when physical contact is already comfortable in the group.","Team-building day as a low-threshold cooperation starter before more demanding tasks."],"wann_nicht":["At the very first encounter with complete strangers - physical contact (holding hands across the circle) needs a minimum of warm-up first.","Above 12 people per circle: the task becomes geometrically unsolvable; better to form two circles.","When cultural norms forbid or limit physical contact between strangers.","Online - not possible."],"fokusfragen":["\"Who coordinated - explicitly or implicitly? Who was heard, who got overlooked?\" (debriefing core)","\"What did you try that didn't work - and what made you switch strategy?\""],"mini_form":"Silent round (10 min): Human Knot without talking. Creates a more intense cooperation experience and a stronger debrief: 'How did you communicate without words?'","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"7-12 per circle is ideal; above 12, split into subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","muede"]},{"id":"marshmallow-challenge","name":"Marshmallow Challenge (short tower-building variant)","feld":"C","kurz":"Teams of 4 build the tallest freestanding tower in 18 minutes out of 20 spaghetti, 1m of tape, 1m of string - the marshmallow must sit on top. A cooperation and prototyping classic (Skillman/Wujec).","schritte":["Set out materials for each team. Everyday variant with no shopping needed: 20 sheets of paper + 1m of tape, goal: tallest freestanding paper tower in 10 min.","Framing: \"18 minutes, tallest freestanding tower, marshmallow on top - it's heavier than it looks. Go.\"","Count down time out loud (12 - 9 - 5 - 2 - 1 min). Measure, applaud.","Debrief: \"Who tested early, who planned until minute 17?\" - punch line: kindergartners beat MBA teams because they prototype iteratively instead of planning at length."],"zweck":"Makes collaboration under time pressure tangible; iteration over perfection-planning as a shared learning point.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: none - the competition plus task shields against the personal, making it ideal for skeptical, task-oriented groups. Mix teams across hierarchies. The debrief carries the real impact - plan 10 minutes for it. Online only as an individual or household variant.","phasen":["ankommen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","energie"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":60,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["spielerisch","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["energizer","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Marshmallow Challenge – Tom Wujec","url":"https://www.tomwujec.com/marshmallow-challenge"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Marshmallow Challenge with Debriefing – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/marshmallow-challenge-with-debriefing"}],"wann_passt":["A group with a task-oriented or skeptical attitude toward team-building - the competitive logic and clear task bypass resistance and create a real cooperation experience.","Workshop on innovation, prototyping, or agility: the debrief punch line (kindergartners beat MBA teams because they iterate instead of planning) is direct and memorable.","Kickoff of a new project team: the challenge reveals more about team dynamics in 30 minutes than half a day of assessment."],"wann_nicht":["Online without a household variant: the original task needs physical materials; digital simulations lose the crucial 'the marshmallow is heavier than it looks' surprise effect.","In very small groups (under 8): too few teams for the competitive effect.","As a closing energizer without a debrief - without debriefing it's just fun."],"fokusfragen":["\"When did you test for the first time - at the start, in the middle, or at the end? What did that reveal about your approach?\" (debriefing core)","\"What from this experience do you carry into your current project - where do you build too long before you test?\""],"mini_form":"Paper towers in 10 minutes (groups of 3, 10 sheets of paper): no spaghetti, no shopping needed. Same dynamic, immediately doable in any office.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-40 ideal; teams of 4-5 people","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"lebenslinien-sharing-triaden","name":"Life-Line Sharing in Triads (Life Map)","feld":"C","kurz":"Each person draws their life or career path as a line with highs and lows and shares it in a group of three; the others listen without commenting or advising.","schritte":["Individual work (10 min): \"Draw your line - stations, turning points, highs and lows. You decide what goes on it; a purely career line is just as valid as a life line.\"","Triads: each person tells their story for 7-10 min; listeners only ask clarifying questions (\"questions of understanding yes, advice no\").","Short close in the triad: \"What touched or surprised me most?\"","Plenary only at the meta level (\"How was the format?\"), content stays in the triad."],"zweck":"Builds deep mutual understanding and resilient trust - makes the people behind the roles visible.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: established - multi-day format or team retreat. Explicitly agree on confidentiality. Offer self-directed depth of disclosure (a career line as a face-saving opt-out). Trauma-sensitive: never probe further into low points; let triads form themselves.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["vertrauen","selbstzugang"],"formate":["klausur","teamentwicklung","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":40,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"hoch","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Life map – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/life-map"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Life maps (Variante) – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/methods/life-maps"}],"wann_passt":["Multi-day team retreat or training where real depth and trust are meant to emerge - life lines build more connection in one hour than many superficial get-to-know-you rounds.","A group that has already had some shared hours together and is ready to look behind the role - not for complete strangers.","Supervision group or learning group that wants to consciously shape a new phase of its collaboration."],"wann_nicht":["Early in a process without warmed-up trust - life lines need safety that can't be forced.","When the format isn't explicitly voluntary: no one should feel pressured to share their biography.","In groups with acute conflict - the format opens people up emotionally; in charged situations this can destabilize.","Online without a separate breakout and enough time - the format needs calm and confidentiality that's hard to get in large video calls."],"fokusfragen":["\"Draw your life or career path as a line - highs and lows, turning points. You decide what goes on it.\" (individual work invitation)","\"What in the stories you heard touched or surprised you most?\" (triad close)"],"mini_form":"Career lines (30 min): just the career path, no life line - clearly lowers the depth of disclosure. Each person tells their story for 5 min, others just listen. No plenary. Good as an entry point into longer processes.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","lernformat","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-24; always in triads","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"pecha-kucha-ueber-mich","name":"Pecha Kucha About Me","feld":"C","kurz":"Short presentation in PechaKucha style about yourself: images advance automatically while the person talks along. Compact format: 10 images x 20 seconds instead of the classic 20x20.","schritte":["Advance task (or 20 min prep): \"Choose 10 images that say something about you - places, projects, people, objects. 20 seconds per image, slides advance automatically.\"","Draw order, 3:20 min per person plus brief applause.","After every 3-4 presentations, a short buzz round: \"What am I newly taking away about these colleagues?\""],"zweck":"Personal getting-to-know-you with clear form - the fixed pace protects against a self-promotion marathon and makes listening easy.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: first shared hours; image choice governs the depth of disclosure. Good for new teams, onboarding, network retreats; needs tech (projector/screen share) and preparation time - announce in advance. Variant for skeptical groups: \"My work year in 10 images\".","phasen":["ankommen","oeffnen"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["klausur","teamentwicklung","workshop","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":25,"dauer_max":80,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":16,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Our 20x20 Format – PechaKucha","url":"https://pechakucha.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/4408778681485-Our-20x20-Format"}],"wann_passt":["A new team in onboarding or after a reorganization that really wants to get to know each other - Pecha Kucha About Me gives personality a stage that verbal introduction rounds don't.","Training or retreat with a group known in advance: as an opener that automatically creates personal depth through image choice.","Network retreats with people who only know each other professionally and want to see more of one another."],"wann_nicht":["Without advance-communicated preparation - gathering and assembling 10 images takes time that isn't there in the meeting.","For very large groups (>16) without adaptation: all the presentations back-to-back take too long.","When the tech (projector, screen share, auto-advancing slides) isn't reliable - the format collapses if slides don't change automatically."],"fokusfragen":["\"Choose 10 images that say something about you - places, people, objects, moments. Things people can't tell just by looking at you.\" (advance task)","\"What did you learn about this person through the images that you wouldn't have learned through conversation?\" (buzz round after every 3-4 presentations)"],"mini_form":"Three-image introduction (5 min per person): instead of 10 slides, just 3 images, 1 min each, no automatic switching needed. A smartphone is enough. Good as an unprepared variant ('show three pictures from your phone').","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-16; above 16, split into subgroups","stimmung_geeignet":["frisch","neugierig"]},{"id":"appreciation-runde","name":"Appreciation Round (Closing)","feld":"C","kurz":"A structured closing round in which participants voice concrete appreciation to one another - e.g. as a sentence starter \"What I appreciated about your contribution today...\".","schritte":["Framing: \"To close, a round of appreciation - concrete and about today, no generalities. Format: 'What I appreciated about you today is...'\"","Choose a format: a) circle - each person appreciates the person to their left; b) popcorn - whoever wants speaks, until everyone has been mentioned; c) written - everyone writes to everyone.","Recipients respond only with \"thank you\" - no deflecting."],"zweck":"A positive relational signal at the close; being seen for concrete behavior strengthens psychological safety more lastingly than general praise.","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: one shared workday is enough. With popcorn-style sharing, make sure no one is left out - for insecure groups use a circle or written variant. \"Just say thank you\" removes the awkwardness. Sober framing: \"Feedback: what worked - about a person\".","phasen":["reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["vertrauen","verbindung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","reflexionsrunde","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":25,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":25,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Appreciation Workshop Activities (Sammlung) – SessionLab","url":"https://www.sessionlab.com/library/appreciation"}],"wann_passt":["Close of a shared workday or project: appreciation for concrete behavior ('what you did today') is the most effective signal for psychological safety.","A team stuck chronically in problem-solving that has lost sight of what's going well - the round reorients without discussion.","Multi-day training on the last evening: as a closing ritual that honors the shared story."],"wann_nicht":["When relationships are so strained that appreciation feels fake or gets received cynically - clarify first.","In very large groups without structure: the popcorn variant easily leads to some people never being mentioned.","When praise is used to steer performance - the appreciation round loses its power if leadership stages it as a motivation tool."],"fokusfragen":["\"What I appreciated about you today - concrete and about today.\" (sentence starter for everyone)","\"What impressed me most about this group's work - a moment, a behavior.\" (group variant)"],"mini_form":"Written variant (10 min): everyone writes everyone else one sentence on a card - then the cards are handed out. Everyone reads silently. No reading aloud, no awkwardness. Especially effective in groups that find verbal appreciation difficult.","anlass_typen":["teamtag","retro","lernformat"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-20 ideal; above 25, use written variant","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","belastet","neugierig","frisch"]},{"id":"soziometrische-aufstellung-spectogram","name":"Sociometric Positioning / Spectrogram","feld":"C","kurz":"The room becomes a scale or map: participants position themselves physically in response to statements (agreement, places of origin, years in the field) and get talking through their position.","schritte":["Explain the axis: \"This wall means 'fully agree', the opposite one means 'not at all'. I'll read out a statement - stand where you stand. There's no right answer.\"","Warm up with harmless questions (travel distance, coffee/tea), then raise the stakes thematically (\"I believe our network knows its impact\").","For each positioning, interview 2-3 voices from different positions: \"What do you see from where you're standing?\"","Neighbor buzz: 2 minutes with the person next to you. Several rounds; gather observations at the end."],"zweck":"Makes differences and commonalities visible and discussable, gets everyone moving and talking - builds trust through the visible act of \"I show where I stand\".","hinweise":"Minimum trust level: none for factual questions, established for sensitive ones - the choice of question determines the risk. No one has to explain their position (opt-out; those who don't want to stand can show a hand signal or card instead). Online as a spectrogram: scale on the whiteboard, stamps or a number 1-10 in the chat.","phasen":["ankommen","verstehen"],"ebenen":["person","team","netzwerk"],"modi":["verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","prozessbegleitung","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":10,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":true,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["koerperlich","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["einstieg","energizer","kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"10 Ways to Use A Spectogram Online – Training for Change","url":"https://www.trainingforchange.org/training_tools/spectograms-online/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Tool-Bibliothek – Training for Change","url":"https://www.trainingforchange.org/tools/"}],"wann_passt":["At the start of a workshop or network meeting as a physical opener: everyone moves, positions themselves, starts talking - better than any icebreaker that keeps people seated.","When diversity of opinion needs to become visible without one side dominating - body position makes all positions visible at once and gives quiet voices visibility.","Diagnosis at the start of a team development day: 'How comfortable do you feel in our team?' on the scale shows the picture immediately, without lengthy discussion."],"wann_nicht":["For sensitive questions without established trust: 'Do I trust my manager?' as a first question can destroy trust rather than build it.","In cramped rooms without room to really position yourself - the physical dimension is the core of it.","When participants have physical limitations, without having offered an alternative option (hand signal, card)."],"fokusfragen":["\"This wall means 'fully agree', the opposite one means 'don't agree at all'. Stand where you stand - there's no right answer.\" (opening phrasing)","\"What do you see from where you're standing - what can't you see from over there?\" (position interview, 2-3 people from different positions)"],"mini_form":"Hand-signal spectrogram (5 min): everyone shows 1-5 fingers at once instead of positioning themselves. No room needed, works online. Loses the physical dimension, keeps the visibility of opinions.","anlass_typen":["kickoff","teamtag","beteiligung","retro"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-60 ideal; above 100 only for factual questions with simple positions","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","neugierig","frisch","muede"]},{"id":"troika-consulting","name":"Troika Consulting (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"Three people rotate as client and consultants: one person brings a real question, turns away, the other two consult out loud - then the person turns back around and hears what came through.","schritte":["Form groups of three. Person A states their real question or challenge (2 min).","A turns away or closes their eyes - B and C consult out loud, as if A weren't there (4-5 min).","A turns back around, shares what they heard - what was new, what they're taking away (2 min).","Switch roles: B brings their question, C and A consult. Then C."],"zweck":"Peer consulting on real questions without the pressure to justify yourself; turning away interrupts loops of explaining and defending and produces surprisingly precise outside perspectives.","hinweise":"The real question must be set in advance - allow time to formulate it. Turning away is the mechanism that makes it work, don't skip it. Works online via mute plus a turned-away camera image, or in breakouts.","phasen":["vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung","teamentwicklung","coaching"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":40,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":60,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Troika Consulting – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/8-troika-consulting/"}],"wann_passt":["Leadership or OD training where everyone comes with real practice questions - Troika Consulting gives everyone three outside perspectives in 40 minutes on what really occupies them.","A team that keeps circling the same question without progress - turning away interrupts loops of justification and brings fresh phrasing.","Intervision format: as a standard structure for peer consulting, better than free conversation because the roles are clearly separated."],"wann_nicht":["With very sensitive or personal questions in groups without established trust - being consulted about as a pair, without being addressed directly, can feel depersonalizing.","When everyone has the same question - then Troika Consulting is too elaborate; 1-2-4-All is enough.","Under 6 people: a full rotation isn't possible."],"fokusfragen":["\"What is the one question that's really occupying you right now - concrete and yours, not your organization's question?\" (formulating the question, prep)","\"What did you hear that was new - and what are you taking away?\" (return step after turning away)"],"beispiel":"Person A asks: 'How can I motivate my team for change without applying pressure?' A turns away. B to C: 'I wonder whether A even knows what's really holding the team back - has A asked people directly?' C: 'Maybe the problem isn't motivation but clarity about the goal.' A turns back around: 'I heard that I should ask first instead of explaining - and that the goal might not be clear enough. That was new to me.'","mini_form":"Two-round Troika (25 min): only two of the three people bring a question. Saves one round, keeps the effect.","anlass_typen":["coaching","lernformat","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"9-30 ideal (groups of three)","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","muede","skeptisch"]},{"id":"triz-ls","name":"TRIZ (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"The group first asks how it could guarantee the opposite of what's wanted - then they reverse the answers and uncover blocked improvements that direct questions wouldn't have surfaced.","schritte":["Ask the counterfactual question: 'What would we have to do to make absolutely sure we prevent X / guarantee the opposite of Y?' (5 min, note silently)","In pairs or groups of four: gather ideas freely and without self-censorship (5 min).","Plenary: make all ideas visible - which of these do we already do, unconsciously or out of habit?","Reverse: derive the positive opposite from each problematic practice - what would help instead?","Prioritize: which one or two reversals have the highest leverage potential?"],"zweck":"Makes blockages and counterproductive habits visible by first deliberately amplifying them - the reversal then produces unusually honest improvement ideas.","hinweise":"The trick lies in the provocative opening question; it must be phrased boldly ('How do we guarantee that our strategy meeting changes nothing?'). A half-hearted TRIZ produces arbitrary results.","phasen":["vertiefen","reflektieren","planen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation"],"modi":["reflexion","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":8,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","spielerisch","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"TRIZ – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/6-making-space-with-triz/"}],"wann_passt":["A retro or strategy day where the group never really voices uncomfortable truths - TRIZ makes this safer through humor and exaggeration, without prettifying the truths.","A workshop where the group knows what isn't working but doesn't name it directly - TRIZ gives a language for the unspoken elephants in the room.","An organizational review meant to surface real dysfunctions: 'What do we do to prevent cooperation?' produces more honest answers than 'What's stopping us from cooperating?'"],"wann_nicht":["In groups without psychological safety: TRIZ requires the willingness to name your own dysfunctions - risky under leadership's observation.","As a fun format without real consequence: if the reversals aren't taken seriously, TRIZ is just entertainment.","With groups that don't yet share enough history to know their counterproductive patterns."],"fokusfragen":["\"What would we have to do to make sure nothing changes in our team?\" (TRIZ opening question - example)","\"Which of these do we already do - consciously or unconsciously?\" (the sharpest step in TRIZ)"],"beispiel":"In a team retro: 'What would we have to do to make sure our meetings achieve nothing?' Answers: 'Always the same agenda, never record decisions, the manager talks 80% of the time.' Facilitator: 'Which of these sounds familiar?' Silence, then laughter, then conversation. Reversal: 'What's the opposite of each point?' - produces a concrete list of measures.","mini_form":"Solo TRIZ (10 min): just the counterfactual question, noted silently, then shared in pairs. No plenary, no plenary reversal - take impulses away and invert them privately.","anlass_typen":["retro","teamtag","strategie"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-40; above 40 in small groups with a shared harvest","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","muede","neugierig"]},{"id":"15percent-solutions","name":"15% Solutions (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"Everyone identifies the room to act they already have right now - without permission, budget, or outside help. 15% is the share that everyone controls, even within constrained systems.","schritte":["Ask the question: 'What is your 15% - what can you already do now without permission or extra resources?' (2 min, note silently)","Pairs (7 min): share answers, ask follow-up questions for specifics: 'What exactly, when, with whom?'","Groups of four (5 min): share patterns and surprises.","Plenary: whoever wants to, states one concrete 15% commitment."],"zweck":"Activates agency by shifting attention away from obstacles and toward existing room to maneuver - an antidote to collective paralysis and waiting for permission.","hinweise":"The trick is the modesty of the question - 'not 100%, just 15%' lowers the activation threshold considerably. Getting concrete in the pair conversation is crucial: vague 15% answers don't help.","phasen":["planen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["klaerung","energie"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","fortbildung"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":30,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend"],"blocktyp":["kern","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"15% Solutions – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/7-15-solutions/"}],"wann_passt":["After a long block of strategy or problem analysis, when the group is at risk of tipping into paralysis or helplessness - 15% Solutions breaks the spell and produces immediate action impulses.","Closing a workshop that had lots of diagnosis and little decision-making: what are you specifically taking away - and what will you do next week?","A team strongly fixated on external obstacles ('we can't, because...'): the question redirects attention to what's actually possible."],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for real structural change: 15% Solutions creates agency but doesn't solve systemic problems - don't use it as a comforting patch.","When actual room to act is very small and the question feels cynical ('what am I supposed to do when everything's already decided?') - clarify the framing conditions first.","For complex decisions with many dependencies - 15% is for individually-controllable actions, not collective decisions."],"fokusfragen":["\"What can you do within your own sphere of influence - without permission, without budget, without help from above?\" (core question)","\"What would you specifically do by when - and with whom?\" (follow-up specifics question in pairs)"],"beispiel":"After a strategy workshop that produced many insights but no decisions: '2 minutes of silence: what is your 15% - what can you do in your area of responsibility next week?' Person A: 'I can update my team weekly for 10 minutes on the strategy process.' Person B: 'I can build the connection to Team C, which we've been avoiding so far.' - concrete action steps that need no approval.","mini_form":"Solo note (5 min): note silently, stick the card with your 15% commitment on the door on your way out. Commitment visible without the pressure of sharing.","anlass_typen":["strategie","retro","lernformat","entscheidungstreffen","krisensitzung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"6-200; scales to any size","stimmung_geeignet":["muede","belastet","skeptisch"]},{"id":"what-so-what-now-what","name":"What? So What? Now What? (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"Three-phase reflection: What happened? (observation) - What does it mean? (interpretation) - What do we do now? (consequence). Separates perception, interpretation, and action in guided sequences.","schritte":["What? (observation level, 5 min): 'What did you observe, hear, do - without judgment?' In pairs or small groups, then plenary.","So What? (meaning level, 5 min): 'What does that mean - for us, our project, our collaboration?' Name patterns.","Now What? (action level, 5 min): 'What follows from that - what do we do, who does what by when?' Concrete commitments."],"zweck":"Structures learning from experience and ensures that observation, interpretation, and consequence aren't blended together - a standard error in debriefs.","hinweise":"Separating the three levels is the mechanism at work: don't move into 'So What' before 'What' has been sufficiently filled in. Judgments during the 'What' phase should be interrupted and redirected to the next level.","phasen":["reflektieren","planen"],"ebenen":["person","team","organisation"],"modi":["reflexion","klaerung"],"formate":["meeting","workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":15,"dauer_max":45,"gruppe_min":3,"gruppe_max":100,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["reflexion","abschluss"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"What, So What, Now What? – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/9-what-so-what-now-what-w/"}],"wann_passt":["Debrief after an experience (exercise, simulation, project phase): What? So What? Now What? gives reflection structure and prevents drifting in vague impressions.","A retro with a group that always jumps straight to 'what do we do better?' without observing first - separating observation from interpretation is often surprisingly sharpening.","Learning format after fieldwork or an outside deployment: what did you observe, what do you conclude from it, what do you do?"],"wann_nicht":["As a substitute for a deep retro with explicit methods (four-quadrant, timeline, etc.) - What/So What/Now What is good for quick reflection, not deep evaluation.","When the group has no shared experience to refer to - the question 'what did you observe?' then has no common anchor.","When the 'Now What' phase isn't taken seriously - then better to choose a method that ends with consequences rather than starting there."],"fokusfragen":["\"What did you specifically observe, hear, do - without judgment, just facts?\" (What phase)","\"What does that mean - for you, for the group, for the project?\" (So What phase)","\"What are you doing now, specifically - who, what, by when?\" (Now What phase)"],"beispiel":"After an exercise on communication in conflicts: What: 'A interrupted B, C went quiet.' So What: 'Interruption created silence - we lose voices when we don't actively listen.' Now What: 'In our next meeting we'll experiment with an interruption rule - whoever interrupts notices it themselves and hands back the floor.' A concrete learning cycle in 15 minutes.","mini_form":"Writing sprint (10 min): all three questions on one sheet, 3 min per question writing silently, then keep the card at hand. No sharing needed.","anlass_typen":["retro","lernformat","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"4-40; above 40 in small groups with a plenary harvest","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","muede","frisch"]},{"id":"25-10-crowd-sourcing","name":"25/10 Crowd Sourcing (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"Everyone writes their boldest idea on a card, then swaps blind five times, reads and rates each card (1-5) - after five rounds, the highest ratings reveal the collectively favored ideas.","schritte":["Formulate the invitation question: 'What would be your boldest idea that would really move X forward?' (2 min writing silently, one card per person)","Blind swap: everyone walks around, swaps cards with strangers five times - each person reads the card they're holding and gives it a rating of 1-5 (written at the top of the card).","After five rounds: add up the numbers on the card. Whoever holds a card with a high total reads it out.","Review the top ideas and prioritize them together."],"zweck":"Condenses many ideas in large groups into a collective ranking quickly - without domination by loud voices or a halo effect from authorship.","hinweise":"Blind swapping is essential - rating happens without knowing whose idea it is. Especially effective from 20 people upward; below that the effort-to-impact ratio isn't optimal.","phasen":["vertiefen","entscheiden"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung","entscheidung"],"formate":["workshop","grossgruppe","klausur"],"dauer_min":20,"dauer_max":35,"gruppe_min":20,"gruppe_max":200,"online":"eingeschraenkt","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["strukturiert","beteiligend","spielerisch"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"25/10 Crowd Sourcing – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/12-2510-crowd-sourcing/"}],"wann_passt":["Large group (30-200) after an ideation block with many ideas in the room that need prioritizing - without a show-of-hands vote, which is influenced by social pressure.","An open strategy process where genuinely bold ideas are wanted that wouldn't be voiced in normal hierarchies - anonymity of authorship protects.","A network meeting with a large group and a wish for collective expression: 'What is the one idea that would really move our network forward?'"],"wann_nicht":["Under 15 people: too little blind-swap effect, better to prioritize directly.","Online without a shared whiteboard with sticky-note functionality - the physical card swap is hard to replicate digitally.","When ideas are complex and need context - only one concise idea fits on a card."],"fokusfragen":["\"What would be your boldest idea that would really move X forward - one idea, one card.\" (invitation formula)","\"The cards with the highest ratings: what do they tell us about what this group really wants?\" (harvest opener)"],"beispiel":"","mini_form":"Three swap rounds instead of five (15 min): sufficient for 15-30 people; ranking validity drops, speed increases.","anlass_typen":["beteiligung","strategie","netzwerktreffen"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"20-150; not useful under 15","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"]},{"id":"wise-crowds","name":"Wise Crowds (Liberating Structures)","feld":"C","kurz":"One person sits as a 'client' in front of four or more 'consultants': they explain their challenge, turn away - the group consults out loud. Then they turn back and hear the essence. Troika Consulting at larger scale, scaled up further with simultaneous parallel rounds.","schritte":["Form groups of 5-6: one client, 4-5 consultants.","Client explains their challenge (2-3 min), turns away.","Consulting group discusses out loud (5-7 min), without addressing the client directly.","Client turns back around, shares what came through (2 min).","Switch roles - depending on time, 2-3 people act as client per group."],"zweck":"Scales peer consulting: many clients get outside perspectives at the same time in parallel small groups - more efficient than sequential consulting rounds.","hinweise":"Difference from Troika: a larger group (5-6) instead of three, more diversity of perspective; difference from classic supervision: no facilitation, the group carries itself. Turning away is mandatory.","phasen":["vertiefen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["person","team"],"modi":["klaerung","reflexion"],"formate":["workshop","fortbildung","teamentwicklung"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":10,"gruppe_max":60,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Wise Crowds – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/13-wise-crowds/"}],"wann_passt":["A learning group or supervision with 10-40 people who should all get peer consulting - Wise Crowds gives everyone at least one consulting round in 45 minutes.","A leadership workshop where everyone comes with real challenges and doesn't just want to listen - the simultaneous rounds give everyone time for their own question.","When Troika Consulting yields too few perspectives: 5 consultants see more than 2."],"wann_nicht":["Under 10 people: Troika Consulting is more efficient then.","When confidentiality of content is critical - in parallel groups, many people share challenges that may overlap.","Online without good breakout organization: simultaneous groups need clear room logistics."],"fokusfragen":["\"What is your real challenge - phrased as a question you genuinely want answered?\" (client prep)","\"What of what you heard was new - and what are you taking away?\" (client return)"],"beispiel":"","mini_form":"One-round Wise Crowds (20 min): only one person per group is the client - everyone else consults. No role switch. Good as a quick demo, or when only one person urgently needs consulting.","anlass_typen":["coaching","lernformat","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"10-40; groups of 5-6 people","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","muede","skeptisch"]},{"id":"conversation-cafe","name":"Conversation Café (Liberating Structures / Viant)","feld":"C","kurz":"Facilitated table conversation with clear roles and two conversation rounds: round 1 everyone goes in turn, round 2 open - a talking object passes the floor, no one gets interrupted.","schritte":["Group of 5-8 at one table; talking object (cup, stone) in the middle.","Formulate and share the question: an open, personal invitation to reflect.","Round 1: in turn, each person holds the talking object and speaks without interruption (2-3 min); the others just listen.","Round 2: open conversation - whoever wants to speak takes the talking object; no one without the object in hand speaks.","Closing round: one sentence each on what everyone is taking away."],"zweck":"Enables deep conversation on a meaningful topic in which everyone gets a voice and no one dominates - quality over quantity of contributions.","hinweise":"The talking object is the protective mechanism - hold to it consistently. Questions must be personal and open: no yes/no questions, no factual debates. Well suited to controversial topics when the aim is mutual understanding rather than persuasion.","phasen":["oeffnen","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["person","team","netzwerk"],"modi":["verbindung","reflexion","klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","teamentwicklung","fortbildung","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":60,"gruppe_min":5,"gruppe_max":60,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"beruhigend","stil":["gespraechsnah","strukturiert"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"online","titel":"Conversation Café – Liberating Structures","url":"https://www.liberatingstructures.com/17-conversation-cafe/"},{"typ":"online","titel":"Conversation Café – conversationcafe.org","url":"https://www.conversationcafe.org/"}],"wann_passt":["A network meeting or conference where a controversial topic needs to be understood rather than debated - Conversation Café is the format for understanding rather than a battle of opinions.","A workshop with a heterogeneous group (different backgrounds, opinions) where everyone should get a voice without a facilitator acting as referee.","When World Café involves too many rotations and a question deserves an hour of deep engagement."],"wann_nicht":["For decision-making - Conversation Café produces understanding, not decisions.","With groups that don't take the talking object seriously or undermine the turn-taking rule - the format then collapses.","Online without a strong facilitator signal for the talking object (e.g. an unmuted mic as the talking object): interruptions are harder to prevent."],"fokusfragen":["\"What draws you to this topic - what worries you, what are you hoping for?\" (round 1 question, phrased personally)","\"What did you hear today that surprised or touched you?\" (closing round)"],"beispiel":"","mini_form":"Round 1 only (20 min, 5-7 people): everyone in turn with the talking object, no open round. Gives everyone a voice without the risks of the open round. Good as a check-in variant for sensitive topics.","anlass_typen":["dialograum","netzwerktreffen","teamtag"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-8 per table; parallel tables for larger groups","stimmung_geeignet":["angespannt","skeptisch","neugierig","belastet"]},{"id":"rpp-matrix","wann_passt":["Strategic planning for peace and development programs (5-15 people), to check whether activities really contribute to peace - the RPP Matrix (Reflecting on Peace Practice) sets up four quadrants: many people/individual (A), key people/individual (B), many people/socio-political (C), key people/socio-political (D) - and asks whether the program is represented in all four fields.","A mandatory instrument for ZFD/CPS projects (GIZ Civil Peace Service): every project must show its connection to the five RPP effectiveness criteria - the RPP Matrix makes this connection visible and communicable.","Reflection after program phases (8-20 people): which quadrant have we mainly worked in - and what have we neglected? Strategic blind spots become visible."],"wann_nicht":["As a bureaucratic form without genuine reflection: the matrix lives on honestly engaging with whether the program really has impact across several quadrants - not just the easiest one.","In early contact phases, before a conflict analysis exists: the matrix assumes it's already clear who the key actors are and which socio-political structures are meant to change."],"fokusfragen":["\"Which of the four RPP quadrants (A/B/C/D) do we work in most - and why?\" (current-state analysis)","\"Which of the five effectiveness criteria do our activities address directly - and which not at all?\" (gap analysis)","\"Who are the key actors in this context that we'd need to win over for a strategic connection - and how do we reach them?\" (quadrant B/D)"],"beispiel":"RPP Matrix in a program reflection: the team enters all current activities into the four quadrants. Result: 80% in quadrant A (many people / individual - e.g. trainings, workshops). Quadrant D (key people / socio-political) is empty. The question 'do we have access to political decision-makers or local authorities - and if not, who could build that bridge?' opens up the strategic discussion. That's the core of the RPP's 'Strategic Connection Principle'.","mini_form":"Quick mapping in 10 minutes: four quadrants on a flipchart. Everyone sticks post-its with the main activities in the quadrant where they think they have impact. Then: where's the clustering? What's missing? Enough as an impulse opener for a strategy reflection.","anlass_typen":["strategie","lernformat","retro"],"typ":"werkzeug","gruppen_sweetspot":"5-15 people, program team or field staff","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","skeptisch"],"name":"RPP Matrix (Reflecting on Peace Practice)","feld":"A","kurz":"A strategy check for peace and change programs: all activities get placed in four quadrants (many people vs. key people x individual vs. socio-political change). Reveals where the program has impact - and which field remains empty.","schritte":["Draw the matrix: x-axis \"many people <-> key people\", y-axis \"individual <-> socio-political change\" (quadrants A-D).","Write all ongoing activities on cards and hang them jointly in the quadrants.","Read the pattern: where does the work pile up? Which quadrant is empty - and is that a conscious decision?","Check the strategic connection: what connection leads from individual change to the socio-political level (and from many people to key people)?","Record 1-2 strategic consequences: what do we expand, what do we newly connect?"],"zweck":"Makes a program's strategic blind spots visible and communicable in 60 minutes - grounded in the five RPP effectiveness criteria.","hinweise":"Lives on honest self-criticism, not on filling in boxes. Clarify beforehand who counts as a key actor in the context - otherwise quadrants B/D stay speculative.","phasen":["planen","verstehen","reflektieren"],"ebenen":["organisation","netzwerk"],"modi":["klaerung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","reflexionsrunde"],"dauer_min":45,"dauer_max":120,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":20,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"niedrig","energie":"neutral","stil":["strukturiert","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Station 6: RPP Matrix"},{"typ":"online","titel":"CDA: Reflecting on Peace Practice (RPP) Basics – Resource Manual","url":"https://www.cdacollaborative.org/publication/reflecting-on-peace-practice-rpp-basics-a-resource-manual/"}]},{"id":"zukunftsvision-filmskript","wann_passt":["A strategy process for peace programs or community projects (8-20 people), when a shared vision of the desired state of peace is missing - the method uses narrative future description ('Imagine three years have passed and peace has arrived: what do you see, what do you hear, who's there?') to make the vision concrete and sensory.","A kickoff or relaunch process, when a group needs to re-calibrate its values and direction: the film-script format (miracle-question logic: what if the problem were solved?) creates positive energy and orientation without blanking out reality.","In parallel with conflict analysis (PME stations 1+2): conflict analysis shows WHERE the problem lies. Future vision shows WHERE we want to go - together they create the tension that motivates action."],"wann_nicht":["As an escape from analysis: future vision without conflict analysis can lead to naive planning - the reality of the context must be understood first.","When the group doesn't yet have a shared problem framing - then do conflict analysis/connectors-dividers first.","In groups in acute distress who first need to clarify their immediate needs - future visions then come across as cynical."],"fokusfragen":["\"Imagine three years have passed. The conflict hasn't simply vanished, but it's playing out differently. What do you see when you look out the window - what has changed?\" (sensory future invitation)","\"Who is present in this future place who isn't there today - and what is that person doing?\" (actors of transformation)","\"What was the first small step that made this change possible - what was the turning point?\" (working backward from the goal to the present)"],"beispiel":"Film-script round in a strategy workshop: the facilitator invites: 'Close your eyes. It's three years from now. The program has had its impact. You're walking through your target community - what do you see? What do you hear? Who's talking to each other who didn't talk before?' 5 minutes of writing. Then share in small groups: what comes up? Collect patterns. Result: the group jointly distills the image it's working toward. This image becomes the reference point for the Theory of Change.","mini_form":"Miracle question in 10 minutes: 'Imagine a miracle happens tonight, and tomorrow morning you wake up and the conflict/problem is solved - what would be the first thing you'd notice? What would be different?' Each person answers in 2-3 sentences. Share in the round. Enough as a vision check-in.","anlass_typen":["strategie","kickoff","dialograum"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"8-25 people","stimmung_geeignet":["neugierig","frisch","muede"],"name":"Future Vision as Film Script","feld":"A","kurz":"Narrative visioning work: the group describes the desired state in three years as a sensory scene (\"What do you see, what do you hear, who's there?\") instead of a list of goals. Miracle-question logic for strategy and kickoff processes.","schritte":["Invitation: \"Three years have passed, our work has had impact. You're walking through the place where it happened - what do you see, what do you hear, who's talking to whom?\"","5-10 minutes of silent writing: each person notes their own scene like a short film script.","Read aloud and listen in pairs or triads - still without judgment.","Harvest patterns: which images come up repeatedly? What's surprising?","Distill a shared future image (3-5 core sentences) - a reference point for Theory of Change or planning.","Ask backward: \"What was the first small step that made this possible?\""],"zweck":"Creates a shared, concrete image of the future and motivation - the productive tension between analysis (where we stand) and vision (where we want to go).","hinweise":"Needs a prior analysis, otherwise it becomes naive. In acutely distressed groups, clarify basic needs first - otherwise the vision comes across as cynical.","phasen":["planen","oeffnen","ankommen"],"ebenen":["team","organisation","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["klaerung","energie","verbindung"],"formate":["workshop","klausur","grossgruppe"],"dauer_min":30,"dauer_max":90,"gruppe_min":4,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":false,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"aktivierend","stil":["gespraechsnah","schriftlich"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"buch","titel":"PME Guidelines for Projects and Programmes of GIZ Civil Peace Service – Station 2: Vision for Peace / Film Script"}]},{"id":"facilitative-listening-design","wann_passt":["Contexts with negative stereotypes between groups (ethnic tensions, generational conflicts, conflict between institutions and civil society): FLD (Facilitative Listening Design) brings members of both groups together as researchers who interview the other group - the act of researching itself produces a shift in perspective without confrontation.","Community peacebuilding programs aiming for lasting relationship change rather than one-off workshops: FLD processes over several months produce, according to evidence from Cambodia, durable attitude change.","PAR-based (participatory action research) accompaniment of conflicts, where outside experts aren't the main source of knowledge but the community itself produces knowledge."],"wann_nicht":["As a one-off event: FLD needs multiple rounds (interview -> analysis -> exchange between groups -> iteration) - as a workshop module without follow-up it loses its effect.","When one of the groups isn't ready to listen - participation must be voluntary and intrinsically motivated.","In acute violence contexts where physical safety isn't guaranteed."],"fokusfragen":["\"What's occupying people in your community most right now - what are the most pressing issues?\" (open conversation opener without steering toward conflict)","\"Did you experience this yourself, or did you hear about it?\" (gentle check without confrontation - often opens more nuanced answers)","\"What do you wish for the relationship between the groups - what would be a first small step?\" (future orientation at the end)"],"beispiel":"FLD mini-round: two teams of 3 people from different groups become researchers. Each team interviews members of the other group with three open questions (without confronting negative stereotypes). After the interview: teams exchange findings, not opinions. What did we hear? What surprises us? - the basis for real dialogue.","mini_form":"Listening pair in 20 minutes: two people from different 'camps'. Person A asks Person B three open questions about their life, their worries, their hopes. Person B asks the same questions of A. At the end, one sentence each: 'I wouldn't have expected that...'","anlass_typen":["dialograum","konfliktklaerung","lernformat","beteiligung"],"typ":"methode","gruppen_sweetspot":"10-30 people in two or more groups","stimmung_geeignet":["skeptisch","angespannt","neugierig"],"name":"Facilitative Listening Design (FLD)","feld":"E","kurz":"Listening as a bridge between groups with reservations about each other: members of both sides become researchers who interview the other group with open questions. Perspective change arises from the researching itself - without confrontation.","schritte":["Form two (or more) teams from the groups involved - participation voluntary.","Jointly develop 3 open interview questions (life, worries, hopes - no conflict confrontation).","Teams interview members of the other group and note what they hear.","Exchange findings rather than opinions: what did we hear? What surprises us?","Jointly develop the next questions or steps - FLD works across multiple rounds."],"zweck":"Changes attitudes between groups lastingly, because people encounter each other as a source of knowledge rather than as opponents (participatory action research).","hinweise":"Not a one-off event - without follow-up rounds the effect fades. Voluntary participation is a condition; in acute violence contexts, clarify safety first.","phasen":["verstehen","konflikt","vertiefen"],"ebenen":["team","netzwerk","feld"],"modi":["konflikt","verbindung","vertrauen"],"formate":["prozessbegleitung","workshop"],"dauer_min":60,"dauer_max":180,"gruppe_min":6,"gruppe_max":30,"online":"ja","braucht_raum":false,"vertrauensbildend":true,"selbstoeffnung":"mittel","energie":"neutral","stil":["gespraechsnah"],"blocktyp":["kern"],"quellen":[{"typ":"buch","titel":"Peacebuilding Practice (Woman PeaceMaker Program, 2023) – Chapter 13"},{"typ":"online","titel":"FLD Handbook – Women Peace Makers Cambodia","url":"https://wpmcambodia.org/project/the-fld-handbook/"}]}];